<SLUG> BC-DIRT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRTY JOB WORTH BIG MONEY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. TimesNews Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dirt is a hot commodity in Phoenixs booming construction
market.
</P>
<P>
   Those who don't have it want it so they can build homes,
offices, shopping centers and highways, and those who have too much
of it need to get rid of it to clear sites and finish developments.
</P>
<P>
   The gritty stuff people wipe off their shoes is big business
here. Companies are selling it, trucking it and grading it. More
than 10 million cubic yards of earth was moved around the Valley
last year.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about 10 truckloads of dirt to carve out a hole for the
typical swimming pool, about 75 cubic yards of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 21,000 truckloads have come out of the ground in the
middle of downtown Phoenix where the office, hotel and shopping
complex Collier Center is going up.
</P>
<P>
   But where does it all go? Wherever a dirt broker can find a home
for it.
</P>
<P>
   These middlemen work with contractors to find dirt for projects
that need it and haul it away from land that has too much of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real commodity,'' said Mike Markham, president of
Markham Contracting of Phoenix. ``If you need it, dirt's expensive.
If you need to get rid of it, it's expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   It costs from $30 to $50 to move an average truckload several
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors use dirt to raise foundations, fill in ravines,
solidify hillsides and support parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes builders even have to outbid each other for good soil
close by so they can finish projects on time and on budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirt really has no value. It all comes down to the cost of
moving it,'' said Jim Padavano of Canyon Country Contracting. He
was one of the first dirt brokers in the Valley, starting in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Padavano, who is constantly tracking developments across the
Phoenix area to find dirt and builders who want it, estimated soil
is worth about $3 to $5 a cubic yard.
</P>
<P>
   That's why dirt is rarely moved more than five miles to another
site, because longer treks turn into money losers. Dirt brokers say
that's why Valley dirt never goes as far as Tucson or out of state.
</P>
<P>
   To keep costs down, most trucking companies move it at night,
something traffic engineers appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lund, a senior project manager with Opus West
Construction, is in charge of the Collier Center project, and said
hauling the 281,000 cubic yards of dirt out of that project's
basement was no easy feat.
</P>
<P>
   He explained the trucks had to maneuver around crowds of people
in downtown Phoenix at night for baseball, basketball and hockey
games and concerts.
</P>
<P>
   If a contractor can find someone to buy the dirt, then the cost
is usually split between the two projects. However, if no one wants
the earth, then a builder has to assume the cost of hauling it to
the dump to get it out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The dirt in your front yard could be from the nearest freeway,
shopping center or office building.
</P>
<P>
   Earth and cobble rock that came out of the Collier Center went
to Phoenix's Sky Harbor International Airport, the nearby Salt
River bed and to a crusher where some is being turned into
Ready-mix concrete.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the 10,000 truckloads of dirt that came out of the hole
for the Nordstrom department store built last year at Scottsdale
Fashion Square ended up as part of the new Pima Freeway a few miles
away to the east, Padavano said.
</P>
<P>
   Freeways are huge dirt users and movers. The ``bridges to
nowhere'' on the Pima Indian Reservation on the fringe of east
Scottsdale were built when the Arizona Department of Transportation
had extra dirt, say dirt brokers.
</P>
<P>
   But not all dirt is the same. Some is bad and can be used for
little else than infill at the dump. Good dirt usually has a slew
of takers.
</P>
<P>
   Dirt brokers and contractors shy away from soil in Gilbert,
southwest Phoenix and along parts of the Superstition Freeway in
the East Valley because it's packed with clay, which makes it
porous causing it to expand under projects, eventually cracking
foundations and walls.
</P>
<P>
   Soil from the base of mountains fresh with silt is the best,
they say. That's what makes north Scottsdale dirt, Mesa soil from
the Superstition Mountains and land along the Camelback Corridor
fronting Camelback Mountain hot commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Location is important, but dirt is key to most projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a developer picks a site, the next thing they do is test
the soil,'' Lund said. ``To know what you can build and how much it
costs, you have to know what kind of dirt is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, if the dirt beneath a building site had too
much clay, was contaminated or too rocky, the contractor would just
find another site. They can't be as picky today since the Valley
doesn't have many big empty parcels.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, more than 36,000 new homes were built, at least
15 neighbhorhood shopping centers went up, more than a dozen office
buildings were developed and miles of roadways completed.
</P>
<P>
   All the construction translates to millions of cubic yards of
dirt to dig, load and move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting good dirt cheap has become so important for projects
that construction will be speeded up or slowed down depending on
when it's available,'' Markham said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
