A1105 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BLACKS-YOUTH-BALL     05-02 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BLACKS-YOUTH-BALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER PLAYING THE GAME  
 BLACK PARTICIPATION FALLING, FROM COL LEGE TO LITTLE LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When draft pick Curtis Johnson chose to play college
baseball, no one warned him about the isolation he would feel as an
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to deal with when you look around and don't see any
others,'' said the University of California outfielder, who was
drafted by the Diamondbacks out of high school in 1996. ``You can't
help but look. It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The decline of African-American participation in baseball
extends far beyond the major leagues. One need only look in Arizona
to see the problem has permeated every level:
</P>
<P>
   The baseball rosters at Arizona and Arizona State have a
combined two Black athletes out of 80 players.
</P>
<P>
   Only one athlete on South Mountain High School's baseball team
is Black despite an African-American enrollment at the school of
more than 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Little League programs that serve African-American communities
in metropolitan Phoenix report a steady decline in Black
participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, when I took over the baseball program at South
Mountain, I thought I'd attract a lot of African-American kids,''
said Coach Derrick Gray, who is Black. ``Now, I stop kids all the
time and ask them `Why?' I hear, `It's not my sport,' or `I don't
know how to play.' How did this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   That's what many are asking 52 years after Jackson Robinson
broke Major League Baseball's color barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Each level of play seems to have its own problems.
</P>
<P>
   Only 6.5 percent of baseball student-athletes in Division I are
Black, according to Northeastern University's Center for the Study
of Sport in Society, and less than 4 percent &QL; 
of Pac-10 players are Black.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Johnson's African-American peers in Oakland chose to
sign professional contracts right out of high school for economic
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that instant gratification,'' he said. ``They see money
right now, so they go after that. And maybe their family needed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, I think education hasn't been emphasized enough in many
Black communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Rafell Jones, the only African-American on the
University of Arizona's baseball team, said that basketball and
football are marketed to the Black communities as more glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a lot of negative thinking about baseball,''
he said. `` `The game's too slow.' `It takes too many hours of
preparation.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The issue troubles ASU Coach Pat Murphy, who this season went as
far as scheduling a three-game series with Howard University, a
predominantly Black college in Washington, D.C., to help increase
awareness of African-Americans in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to reach out to an all-Black school and say,
`Look, come in, we'll pay you a great package, have a great trip
and experience and maybe we can encourage more Blacks to go to
college,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general feeling, certainly not mine, that all the
really good Black players are going to sign (out of high school)
and so maybe some schools lay off. It's a gross generalization and
an unfair one.''
</P>
<P>
   Many are concerned that there soon won't be enough Black talent
available at the high school level. Gray's challenges at South
Mountain magnify the problem. If a school with one of the largest
populations of Black students in the Valley can't find
African-American players, what does that say about the state of the
sport?
</P>
<P>
   Duane Nelson, field manager for the Boys and Girls Clubs of
Metropolitan Phoenix, said many of the youth that come to his
clubs, which attract predominantly Blacks and Hispanics, have
limited, if any, experience with the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most of our kids, it's all new,'' he said. ``Most of them
don't own gloves, high quality baseball bats, or good equipment.
Many are more familiar with basketball and other sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Most agree that baseball's relationship with children has
changed. Gone are the days when kids found the nearest sandlot and
played for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, we played every day, with one baseball until
the cover fell off, or it disintegrated or we lost it,'' said
Murphy, who is from New York. ``Everybody used the same bat, and if
it was too big, you choked up, and if it was cracked, you nailed
it. That's all we wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The decreasing number of young African-Americans playing the
game reflects a recent indifference toward youth baseball overall.
Since 1995, national Little League enrollment has tapered off and
participation in 1998 was down 33,300 players from '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole syndrome of yelling parents has hurt youth
leagues,'' Murphy said. ``But I think the biggest reason (for the
decline) is that there is a lot of failure in Little League, and I
don't think parents are ready to let their kids deal with failure.
Striking out is perceived as failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other sports, like soccer, the failure (is more disguised).
But I think a lot of us have learned that failure makes us
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boys and Girls Clubs of Metropolitan Phoenix is
participating with the Diamondbacks in a national program called
RBI, Reviving Baseball in Inner Cities, whose objective ``is to
reintroduce baseball to some good athletes that may not have the
opportunity to play baseball,'' said Craig Pletenik, the
Diamondbacks' director of community affairs.
</P>
<P>
   RBI is one of several programs the Diamondbacks are involved in
to help bring back the game to minority and underprivileged youth.
</P>
<P>
   They have run clinics throughout the Valley and are helping to
refurbish fields. They provided $8,000 worth of equipment to the
Boys and Girls Clubs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is excited about the RBI program but hopes he can find
players to commit to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a problem with getting kids to come back week after
week with our clubs because we have such a transient population,''
he said. ``They have no commitment. And the parents of a lot of our
kids don't care what their kids are doing. We can't say to them,
`Can you get Johnny to the game tonight?'
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, we're going to houses, picking up kids and
getting them out of bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is hopeful African-American interest in the game will
improve. He wants to field an all-Black Connie Mack team this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he has always had a dream of coaching an all-Black
baseball team and taking it to the College World Series in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's kind of a ``White Shadow'' thing, I don't know,''
he said,smiling. ``I just think it would be a way for Black players
to see there are advantages to coming to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something needs to be done.'' &QL; 
Paola Boivin can be reached at (602) 444-8956 or at
paola.boivin(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
