A1109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-ELECTION-NYT &LR;      05-02 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 REPUBLICANS IN RUNOFF FOR LIVINGSTON'S SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   METAIRIE, La. _ Former Gov. David Treen and state Rep. David
Vitter finished atop the nine-person field vying to succeed Bob
Livingston as the congressman from Louisiana's 1st District
Saturday night, and advanced to a runoff scheduled for May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Both are Republicans, ensuring that the party will maintain its
11-seat majority in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   David Duke, a former Ku Klux Klan leader and a self-described
advocate for the civil rights of white people, finished in third
place and close enough to the two leaders to make the night an
anxious one for Republican leaders in both Louisiana and
Washington. Establishment Republicans feared that if Duke won the
race, or even made the runoff, Democrats would attempt to make him
a national Republican symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Duke had moved into second place with just under half of the
precincts reporting, and he lingered close to Treen and Vitter well
into the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we were sweating bullets,'' said Ken Johnson, an
aide to Rep. W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, the Republican dean of
Louisiana's congressional delegation and an outspoken critic of
Duke. ``Having David Duke in the runoff would have been a nightmare
come true for Louisiana.''
</P>
<P>
   With 97 percent of the precincts reporting, Treen had 25 percent
of the vote in Saturday's special election, followed by Vitter with
22 percent and Duke with 19 percent. Monica L. Monica, an
opthamologist with a timely name, finished a disappointing fourth
with 16 percent of the vote despite vastly outspending her
opponents. Dr. Monica spent at least $1 million of her own money on
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana has an unusual open primary system that allows
Republicans and Democrats to run against each other in a first
primary. If no candidate wins a majority, the top two finishers
move on to a runoff, regardless of their party.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, a Republican who had represented the district for 21
years, announced his resignation late last year when Hustler
magazine threatened to expose his extramarital affairs. He had been
slated to become speaker of the House, succeeding Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The 1st District, which begins in the northern New Orleans
suburbs and stretches across the 24-mile bridge over Lake
Ponchartrain to the Mississippi border, is considered the most
conservative and the most reliably Republican district in the
state. Eighty-five percent of the registered voters in the district
are white, and many of them have fled what they consider to be high
crime rates and unacceptable schools in the majority black city of
New Orleans. President Clinton lost badly here in both 1992 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The runoff will pit one of this state's Republican warhorses
against one of its youngest Turks. Treen, 70, was the first
Republican since Reconstruction to represent this state in Congress
and then also became the first to serve as governor. Vitter, a
37-year-old lawyer, Harvard graduate and Rhodes Scholar, has served
for eight years in the state legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Treen enjoys the support of Livingston, Tauzin, and Sen. Trent
Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader. He maintains that he
still has relationships with leading congressional Republicans that
will help the district compensate for the loss of Livingston's
seniority and influence. But Vitter counters that Treen's age may
limit his ability to accumulate power in the House and suggests
that the district would be better served by a younger
representative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
