<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-OFFENDER-AZR &LR;      05-02 3113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-OFFENDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONWIDE CRACKDOWN PUTS PRESSURE ON SEX OFFENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Brad Farabough sends a birthday card to a niece or nephew,
he's a step closer to going back to jail.
</P>
<P>
   If he opens the door to neighborhood kids, he could be back
behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   As a registered sex offender, he isn't allowed the remotest
contact with children.
</P>
<P>
   Farabough, who pleaded no contest to felony charges, must follow
a long list of rules. He keeps the sheriff informed of his latest
address. When he moved into an apartment in Mesa, the police passed
around fliers to alert the neighborhood. He's on intense probation
for life, and next year, his name and photo will be on a new state
Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Farabough is feeling the full weight of a national push to keep
closer tabs on at least 200,000 registered sex offenders who are
out in the community. The aim isn't punishment _ they've already
served their sentences _ but to prevent them from striking again.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the pressure is a shocking crime: In New Jersey,
7-year-old Megan Kanka was raped and strangled in 1994 by a
convicted sex offender living across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Now Congress has lighted a fire under states to adopt minimum
standards for monitoring sex offenders, with the threat of losing
some federal funding if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, sex offenders are in the spotlight. Alarmed
neighbors worry about letting their children play outside. In
Maricopa County, surveillance officers are shadowing 700 men and
women offenders for life.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows whether all this time, effort and money will pay
off. There's little consistency among states monitoring sex
offenders and scant data yet to show whether the public will be
safer. A few programs, such as Maricopa County's intense lifetime
probation, show promising results.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that it will take more and more dollars and
people to keep these systems running. Consider Maricopa County,
where the number of sex offenders on probation is rising 11 percent
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Another certainty is the depth of pain that victims suffer,
especially children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a sex offender abuses a child, he murders that child, he
takes away her childhood,'' said Karie Farrally, who volunteers at
the Center Against Sexual Abuse in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Farrally speaks from her own harrowing experience. She was
abused for years as a teenager by a man who was never prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where the most elaborate system of monitoring
registered sex offenders falls short.
</P>
<P>
   While society is keeping an eye on the known predators, a huge
number of criminals haven't yet come into the sights of
prosecutors. More than three-quarters of state prison inmates
serving time for rape or sexual assault in 1994 had no previous
convictions for sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The files at the Phoenix Police Department give a vivid picture
of the challenge ahead for local governments. The city has 4,000
registered sex offenders. Their records fill nine tall file
cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, the papers were in something of a jumble, a low
priority in a busy urban police department. But a series of federal
laws is forcing sex offenders to the top of the to-do list.
</P>
<P>
   States risk losing 10 percent of their federal anti-crime
funding if they don't set up systems for registering sex offenders,
regularly verify the addresses of registered offenders, and warn
the community of sexual predators in its midst. The deadline for
complying is September.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Farabough knows the system from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he pleaded no contest to charges of attempted
molestation involving minors. Farabough, 37, maintains he's
innocent but couldn't afford an adequate defense.
</P>
<P>
   People don't know what they're facing when they make a plea
agreement on a sex charge, he says, and ``I had no idea what it
entailed.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst possibility: getting out of prison and suddenly being
assessed as a sexually violent predator, to be confined in the
state mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   It's a controversial strategy used by some states to keep the
most dangerous offenders off the street.
</P>
<P>
   And it's just what happened to Farabough, who was detained in
the hospital for eight months before the state found ``no
reasonable cause'' for commitment and released him in July. He then
faced Arizona's multipronged strategy for keeping watch on sex
offenders after they finish their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The state took a DNA sample to compare with blood or semen found
at future crimes. Next Farabough had to register under one of the
broadest laws in the country. Arizona requires lifetime
registration for virtually every sex-related crime except
first-time indecent exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, on the other hand, limit registration to 10 years
for all but the most violent sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Does Arizona cast the net too wide?
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Ronald Reinstein supports
lifetime registration, but worries about cases like the two teenage
boys who were goofing around in a store, exposing themselves to
each other. A young boy saw them, a guard was called and the teens
were arrested for indecent exposure.
</P>
<P>
   With that one incident, ``they were looking at lifetime
registration,'' Reinstein said. They got off only after the court
ordered an assessment of whether they were really risks to the
community.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has one of the nation's oldest registration laws, dating
to 1951. Sex offenders must tell the sheriff where they're living,
but until recently, there was little effort to verify addresses.
After a Mesa girl vanished in January, police in neighboring
Chandler hurried to check on their registered sex offenders _ and
discovered 40 percent of the addresses were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Arizona Department of Public Safety finally
began sifting through the state's nearly 10,000 registered
offenders. It's expected to take a year to check just those
registered since June 1, 1996, who are subject to tougher laws.
</P>
<P>
   And it's easy to lose track of sex offenders if they move or
travel to another state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Tyson's a perfect example,'' said Barbara Broderick,
director of adult services at the state Administrative Office of
the Court. The boxer, a registered sex offender for a hotel-room
rape in Indianapolis in 1991, came to Phoenix on a travel permit
but failed to register when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona authorities picked up on it only because it's a
high-profile case and Tyson was training just down the block.
</P>
<P>
   At his apartment complex in Mesa, Farabough has kept a low
profile. ``I've lived here since December and never spoke a word to
anybody,'' he said. ``I fear the way they're going to perceive
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew the police would soon do a sex-offender notification _
warning schools, putting a bulletin on the community-TV channel and
plastering the area with fliers giving his name, photo, address.
</P>
<P>
   It all stems from ``Megan's Law,'' adopted in various versions
by Congress and many states, which requires authorities to alert
the public to registered sex offenders. The law is named for Megan
Kanka, whose gruesome murder was committed by a twice-convicted
molester. Neighbors knew nothing of his criminal background _ nor
of two sex offenders who were his roommates.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a right to know who's threatening their kids in
their neighborhoods,'' said Marc Klaas, who began speaking out
after his 12-year-old daughter, Polly, was abducted at knifepoint
from their California home.
</P>
<P>
   As with registration, states take widely differing approaches.
In Washington, which had the country's first community-notification
law, police typically hold forums and distribute fliers.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum are states like West Virginia,
which notifies only a few government agencies and youth groups that
sign a non-disclosure agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is among a dozen states that try to avoid a
one-size-fits-all approach by rating offenders _ from 1 to 3 _ on
how likely they are to repeat their crimes. Notification is
required for Level 3, the most risky, and optional for Level 2.
</P>
<P>
   But each city and county typically does its own evaluation, with
inconsistent results.
</P>
<P>
   One man who had molested his daughter was rated a low-risk Level
1 by the state when released from prison. But when he moved to
Gilbert, police considered him a Level 2 and prepared to hand out
warning fliers. The panicked landlord canceled the offender's lease
and offered him $1,000 to move out. The man ended up in Phoenix,
which ranked him Level 1.
</P>
<P>
   There's no appeal in Arizona, although at least 11 other states
allow offenders to contest being subject to community notification.
</P>
<P>
   Reinstein fears that the inconsistency and lack of an appeals
process could be grounds for challenging Arizona's notification
system as unconstitutional. ``You have the danger of losing the law
altogether,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Chandler Detective Velma Anderjeski, that would mean losing
a powerful crime-fighting tool. When neighbors are alerted to sex
offenders, she said, ``they become an extra set of eyes for us, and
it's been very beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Citizens tipped her off that a convicted sex offender had
slipped back into Chandler after being deported and was hanging
around an elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   But as someone who has been through notification, Farabough says
it ``puts more of a panic and hyperawareness in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, harassment isn't common. It's occurred in fewer
than 4 percent of notifications in Washington state. Most were
minor, although in one case, the house where an offender planned to
live was burned down.
</P>
<P>
   But statistics also show that sex offenders aren't any less
likely to repeat their crimes just because their neighbors are on
the alert. A Washington study found that recidivism was the same
for offenders who were subject to notification and those who
weren't _ although the former were caught sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Notification leads to ``a false sense of security,'' said
Eleanor Eisenberg, executive director of the Arizona branch of the
American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   And she argues that it adds one more barrier to turning
offenders into productive citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of notification can actually make sex offenders try
to hide their whereabouts, a reaction known as ``Megan's flight.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Phoenix police geared up to distribute fliers on one
sex offender, and he moved the night before. It's happened more
than once.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them: Every time you move, we have to re-flier you,''
said Sgt. Gail Kavanagh, head of sex-crimes notification for
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The community may hope offenders will move out; the police hope
they stay put.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is high-tech: The Internet. In January, Arizona
will join 15 other states with Web sites listing sex offenders.
Chandler, Tempe, Tucson and Yuma already have their own electronic
lists, and Phoenix is considering one.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County is trying a lifetime leash for sex offenders _
putting them on permanent probation with strict rules, surprise
visits by a surveillance officer, therapy and periodic lie-detector
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Scott, supervisor of adult probation, points to the
numbers: Since 1993, fewer than 2 percent of those under Maricopa
County's intense supervision have committed another sex offense.
</P>
<P>
   The program, chosen as a national model for the U.S. Justice
Department project, gives the probation department veto power over
almost every part of an offender's life: from roommates to
recreation. An offender may be forbidden to drink alcohol, own a
computer or be around children.
</P>
<P>
   You may not be able to cure sex offenders, Scott said, but you
can help them manage their lives so they're less likely to molest
or rape again.
</P>
<P>
   The rules go too far, argued Farabough, a trim man with blue
eyes and a handlebar mustache. As he settled onto the sofa in his
apartment, furnished with dream catchers and other Southwestern
touches, there was a soft knock at the front door. Farabough peeked
out the curtain and shook his head. ``I'm not allowed to answer the
door because it's a kid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The knocking got louder and louder, an insistent drill that went
on and on, but Farabough ignored it. He can't have any contact with
minors, even sending cards to nephews and nieces across the
country, a restriction he calls ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Probation supervisor Scott says it's too risky to allow any
communication until a sex offender has gone through treatment. ``We
need to know that he's not being manipulative or `grooming' these
children in any way,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Lie-detector tests are used to check whether sex offenders are
following all the rules. Professionals say they're the only way to
cut through evasions and falsehoods.
</P>
<P>
   But Farabough says therapists are trying to force him to admit
guilt in a case in which he pleaded otherwise _ and if the
polygraphs support him, they say he's in denial.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, in an odd twist, Arizona's most dangerous
offenders have been the least likely to be under such intense
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Violent sex offenders who served their full sentences would come
out of prison with no strings attached to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors now try to convict them on at least two counts, with
sentences that combine prison and lifetime probation.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their effectiveness, all these strategies for
monitoring sex offenders carry a cost that's likely to keep rising.
Arizona has six people working full time to verify the addresses of
registered sex offenders. Once they get through the list, it will
be time to start checking again.
</P>
<P>
   And the list keeps growing. Arizona has 800 more registered sex
offenders every year, and with lifetime registration, few names
drop off.
</P>
<P>
   Val Biebrich, who coordinates registration, predicts the job
will get easier, because ``as time goes on, people are going to
keep current.'' And sex offenders are required to get special
one-year driver's licenses, so the state can cross-check addresses
with the Motor Vehicle Division.
</P>
<P>
   There's a stick, too: Failure to register is a felony in
Arizona, with mandatory prison time.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Biebrich realizes that ``staffing needs will grow
down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same story in Phoenix. The city now has six detectives
whose sole job is to keep track of offenders and do notifications.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kavanagh, who supervises them, predicts, ``We're going to
have to grow dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller jurisdictions are feeling the pinch, too.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale is proposing a position devoted to registration and
notification instead of a system spreading the work among officers
busy with other duties.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County's intense monitoring program, on the other hand,
gets much of its budget from the sex offenders themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, they pay the standard monthly probation fee of $40,
plus $25 a week for group therapy and $180 apiece for lie-detector
tests, required once or twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to taxpayers is $3.81 a day per offender. That's a
bargain, supporters say, if it heads off the cost of sending
someone to prison for $50.25 a day. But the overall caseload is
rising _ up 11 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County just added two officers to sex-offender
probation, bringing the total to 29, with another hire planned.
</P>
<P>
   It adds up to a lot of dollars, but Biebrich argues, ``If it
prevents one additional child from being molested or one additional
person from being sexually assaulted, it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a taxpayer and a registered sex offender, Farabough says
there are better ways to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want these people to have treatment so bad, why don't
they offer it in prison?'' he wonders.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona prisons, only 50 to 75 sex offenders a year have been
getting treatment _ although officials say there hasn't been a
waiting list, either.
</P>
<P>
   The state is trying a new four-phase program, beginning with
mandatory orientation.
</P>
<P>
   But Pamela McCauley, mental-health manager for the Department of
Corrections, said, ``There is not a lot of motivation for most sex
offenders to participate in treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont is one place that has moved more aggressively, with
special units for treating sex offenders in prison and intensive
treatment programs once they're released.
</P>
<P>
   The track record of treating sex offenders is mixed, but
research on offenders in the Vermont program showed lower
recidivism rates than those with other programs or no treatment.
</P>
<P>
   While the community is devoting so much money and energy to
watching known criminals, many sex offenders had no criminal
history at the time of their arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Karie Farrally was molested by someone close to the family for
five years, beginning in seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   Her abuser was never arrested or prosecuted, and she didn't have
the strength to confront him until she was in her 30s.
</P>
<P>
   She persuaded him to come to a therapy session, where she said
he admitted his actions. Far from the tearful confessions of
television tell-all shows, she said, ``it was a very chilling
experience to have him sit there and be so calm, cool and collected
with all these rationalizations, no remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   A Phoenix consultant with her own business, Farrally decided to
speak publicly about her experiences for the first time to help
push for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Registration, community notification, intensive therapy and
stringent restrictions all make sense to her for convicted
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their life should not be easy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But that wouldn't have spared her.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to prevent more victims, she said, is education.
</P>
<P>
   More than the ``stranger danger'' that parents and schools are
used to teaching, children should be told what type of behavior is
inappropriate, assured that it's not their fault and urged not to
keep secrets but to tell a trusted adult.
</P>
<P>
   Farrally was paralyzed by shame, guilt, the threats of her
abuser and the fear that she would be blamed rather than believed.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, teachers and youth-group leaders can be trained to
recognize the techniques of sex offenders: an adult befriending a
child, making him or her ``special,'' separating the child from
other children, developing an exclusive relationship.
</P>
<P>
   An alert adult might have picked up on her own behavior as a
girl. ``I stuttered when this person was around,'' Farrally said.
``I had hellacious nightmares and chronic stomachaches.''
</P>
<P>
   But the best way to protect children from sex offenders is one
she can just dream of: ``Send them to Jupiter and leave them
there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
