<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-650&AMP;     05-02 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS COAST AS CONE IS NEARLY PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hitting against David Cone these days is like
trying to guess the winner in a 19-horse field. Opposing batters
don't know if he is going to take them inside, if he is going
outside, if he will stalk them with his slider late in the count or
go to the whip with a high fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing his different pitches for strikes, Saturday night Cone
allowed just two hits over seven scoreless innings against the
Kansas City Royals, and the New York Yankees went on to win, 8-4,
with Chuck Knoblauch getting three hits and improving his batting
average to .381.
</P>
<P>
   Cone (4-0) struck out seven and walked three, and in 33 innings
this season he has allowed just 11 hits; opponents are batting just
.101 against him, easily the best in the big leagues. His earned
run average is a league-leading 0.82. ``I don't think he can pitch
any better than he has in this stretch,'' said Don Zimmer, the
Yankees' interim manager. ``He's just in a tremendous streak right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi, the Yankees' catcher, said: ``It would be hard to
improve on what he's doing, other than to throw no-hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone's performance Saturday night was unique in that his style
was ill-suited to the strike zone being called by the home plate
umpire, Rick Reed. Cone often picks at the fringes of the strike
zone, like a kid who only likes frosting, and if the home plate
umpire is calling strikes on pitches just off the edges, then Cone
is so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed called the rule book strike zone: If Cone threw the
ball an eighth of an inch off the edge, Reed called a ball. If Cone
grazed the strike zone just a bit inside, or low, or high, Reed
called a ball. Cone received no special consideration for his
control, for his veteran status and sometimes he did a double-take
or snapped at the return throw from the catcher Joe Girardi after
Reed didn't give him a certain pitch.
</P>
<P>
   So Cone earned everything he got, with perhaps his best outing
since sometime last summer; he cannot remember throwing this well
since 1988, the year he went 20-3 for the Mets. ``I really like my
style,'' Cone said. ``I like the way I pitch now, even more than
when I was more of a power pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in 1998, when Cone closed on 20 victories, he would have
days when he would have to win with only his breaking stuff, or
only his fastball, and a bit of good fortune. Right now, Cone is
throwing four pitches effectively _ a fastball that he is zipping
past hitters high in the strike zone, his slider, his
split-fingered fastball and a slow curveball Cone has refined this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   He is throwing them all for strikes, with different speeds and
from different angles, making it difficult for hitters to look for
a specific pitch to hit in a specific situation. On four of Kansas
City's seven strikeouts, the Royals' hitters were caught looking, a
strong indication they were fooled completely. Carlos Febles stared
at a strike-three slider in the second inning and another in the
seventh, Joe Randa watched a fastball dissect the outside corner in
the third and a curveball mesmerized Larry Sutton in the fourth.
Cone loves to use his curveball against left-handed hitters,
starting it outside the zone and then bending it back in. It is so
different than anything else he throws that hitters almost always
take it, rather than swinging.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Royals did hit the ball, their swings were so
ill-timed _ again, Cone changed speeds exceptionally _ that the
contact was imperfect. The Royals didn't have a hit until the
fourth inning, when Mike Sweeney lined a double to left-center.
``Sweeney was the only guy to hit a ball hard off him the whole
night,'' said Johnny Damon, the Kansas City left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only runs the Royals scored came in the eighth, when
Larry Sutton hit a grand slam off Tony Fossas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cone was in trouble only one time the whole night, with the
Yankees leading by 5-0 in the fifth. He walked Febles leading off,
twice staring at Reed about pitches Cone thought were strikes,
before Rey Sanchez dumped a single into center. Two on, nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Chewing his gum ferociously until pausing to look in for the
sign, Cone attacked the next hitter, Carlos Beltran, with
split-fingered fastballs, getting ahead in the count and then
striking him out with a fastball. Cone then made one of his few
mistakes, hanging a splitter, and Joe Randa lifted a drive deep to
left field. It looked as if the ball might drift into the stands
for a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   But Ricky Ledee, the Yankees' left fielder, caught the ball so
close to the wall that the stadium lights projected his shadow
against the fence, and after Johnny Damon rolled out weakly to
first to end the inning, the Yankees' first baseman Tino Martinez
ran past Cone on his way to the dugout and tapped the pitcher on
the side. Nice going. The Royals were 0-for-9 with runners in
scoring position; opposing batters are 2-for-29 (.069) with runners
in scoring position against Cone this year.
</P>
<P>
   Cone assumes nothing about the weeks and months to come. He has
broken down before, ``and there is a long way to go,'' he said. But
Girardi shook his head slightly in amazement at what Cone is
accomplishing. ``I think he's getting wiser with age,'' said
Girardi. ``And he'll get better as long as he keeps getting older,
I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1119 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-MONITOR-AZR &LR;      05-02 1887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-MONITOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX OFFENDERS FACE AROUND-THE-CLOCK INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Sitnek thunders his fist on the door of the local sex
offender. The well-practiced knock is calibrated to overpower the
loudest TV or stereo. The surveillance officer will do it a dozen
times tonight as he makes the rounds checking up on registered sex
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   He pops into people's lives unpredictably with a simple goal:
``The feeling that someone's watching might make them hesitate if
they were thinking of re-offending.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek opens closets, looks at mail, scours videotape
collections for pornography, conducts searches without needing a
warrant. He may tail an offender for a few hours or drop by a house
at 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Close surveillance is a key part of Maricopa County's intensive
probation program for sex offenders. It includes strict rules,
group therapy and periodic lie-detector tests.
</P>
<P>
   As the country struggles to find the best way to protect the
public from rape, molestation and other sex offenses, this is
viewed by many as a model.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Sex Offender Management, a national project
supported by the U.S. Justice Department, chose Maricopa County as
one of 11 sites with the most promising and innovative programs for
dealing with sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lifetime supervision is one of the best things we can do,''
said Lori Scott, supervisor of adult probation.
</P>
<P>
   The county has supervised 1,845 sex offenders since 1983. Many
have violated their probation or committed other kinds of crimes _
263 had their probation revoked and were put behind bars _ but only
1.6 percent have committed new sex offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek's knocking finally gets an answer from a squat
middle-aged man who flings the door open, flicks his cigarette to
the ground and motions Sitnek into a tiny unit in a
down-at-the-heels apartment complex in central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek chats and scans the room, glancing at magazines, videos,
books for any sign of kiddie porn _ the type of material that got
this man into trouble. He downloaded child pornography from the
Internet and sold it to an undercover officer at a swap meet.
</P>
<P>
   Casually dressed, with an engaging smile and blond hair pulled
back in a short ponytail, Sitnek looks a lot like a refugee surfer.
When he showed up at one sex offender's door for the first time,
the startled man insisted on seeing his badge.
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek is one of 10 surveillance officers and 19 probation
officers who oversee the 1,007 sex offenders on intensive probation
in Maricopa County.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent are on lifetime probation.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Sitnek is making the rounds in central Phoenix and
Tempe. His next visit is to a thin, grizzled man in his 60s, socks
pulled up to protect the sores on his legs. Last year, the man
finished 10 years in prison for molesting his daughter and
stepdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to see his grandson, he complains. But he's not
allowed any contact with his family. It's a common restriction.
Nearly two-thirds of the county's sex offenders have committed
crimes, often incest, against children.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new resident in the crowded trailer: a brown and white
puppy. Scratching behind its floppy ears, Sitnek wonders what breed
it is. A pit bullterrier mix. Sitnek nods doubtfully. He could
forbid a sex offender to keep a dog if he thought it might lure
children.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Eisenberg, executive director of the Arizona affiliate
of the American Civil Liberties Union, questions making all sex
offenders follow such strict rules, especially when they accept
lifetime probation as part of a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people always understand and are psychologically
prepared to have their lives so controlled and to give up so many
of the basic human decision-making powers that we value so much,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek makes a quick stop at a tiny trailer parked behind a
hamburger joint, where he touches base with a round, balding man
who has progressed to ``maintenance'' probation, with less
intensive therapy and monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Checking up on sex offenders means dropping by million-dollar
homes, the homeless shelter and everywhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek moves on to an upscale adult mobile home community, with
a tidy, well-landscaped patch in front of each residence.
</P>
<P>
   A trim, 70-year-old man with curly steel-gray hair, wearing only
Bermuda shorts, answers the door.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting Sitnek, he ducks back inside, anticipating the order,
``Put a shirt on.'' Being completely dressed is part of the drill.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested for molesting three children. How many kids did
he actually abuse over the years? The man answers 13. Later, when
he's out of earshot, Sitnek scoffs, ``It has to be at least three
times that number.''
</P>
<P>
   The man gestures to a tape recorder on the coffee table next to
the couch. He bought it as a shortcut for all the writing the
therapist makes him do. He doesn't like the way the therapist is
insisting that he write about molesting incidents again and again,
so he doesn't leave out any detail about how he groomed victims,
preyed on their friendliness and abused them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like wallowing in a cesspool,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Therapy is a crucial prong of Maricopa's sex-offender probation
program.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix psychologist Tom Selby, a contractor to treat
probationers, says the focus is less on cure and more on
management: recognizing the triggers for deviant behavior and
learning to handle them in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   As a reality check, there are lie-detector tests every six to 12
months. Offenders may have to undergo testing with a
plethysmograph, a device attached to the penis, to gauge whether
they're aroused by inappropriate images or suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Some question whether the probation department goes overboard.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Leone Hamm, director of an inmate advocacy group called
Middle Ground Prison Reform, argues for closer scrutiny of how well
treatment is working and whether it should be continued.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the probation requirements can become a gravy train
for therapists and polygraphers. ``You're guaranteeing them
success,'' she says, ``because if the guy drops out of the program,
he'll go to prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Another controversial point is that probationers must waive the
usual patient-doctor confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   To the probation department's Scott, it's critical to have ``a
very structured program with no secrets'' to keep tabs on what
stresses offenders are experiencing and how well they're moving
through the steps of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the therapy is typically coming clean about past sex
offenses. If the information is shared with authorities, it could
lead to future prosecution or to commitment in the Arizona State
Hospital as a sexual predator.
</P>
<P>
   Law Professor Michael Gordon, currently at Arizona State
University, contends that the government should offer some sort of
immunity if the therapy sessions aren't confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek heads into a neighborhood of modest ranch houses, where a
shy, unassuming man in his mid-30s ushers Sitnek into the living
room. ``You like the picture?'' he asks, gesturing to a large
framed photo from his wedding a year ago. Hearing voices, his wife
comes out and plops onto the couch beside him.
</P>
<P>
   Before they could get married, she had to go through the partner
program, a series of counseling sessions. Her husband molested his
10-year-old stepdaughter and spent a year behind bars before going
on probation in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The couple will have to think carefully about having children.
Depending on a sex offender's restrictions, the probation
department can make the father move out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Female offenders, who make up barely 1 percent of Maricopa
County's caseload, may lose custody if they give birth. One woman,
arrested for molesting the boys she was baby-sitting, has had two
babies since going on probation. Both were placed with relatives.
She's not allowed to see them.
</P>
<P>
   The public's picture of a child molester is a dirty old man
lurking in the shadows ready to grab a child.
</P>
<P>
   But in Maricopa County's program, only 12 percent of the sex
offenders preyed on strangers, while 51 percent molested family
members and 37 percent victimized acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   The next apartment is a shrine to Elvis. There are pictures of
The King, magnets, a calendar, framed records, even an Elvis clock.
``I'm an Elvis impersonator,'' the 25-year-old sex offender
confides. Short and rotund, he doesn't look at all like his idol,
but he breaks into a passable imitation of Elvis' tremulous voice.
</P>
<P>
   He's ``low functioning.'' The probation department has had to
set up special slow-learner therapy classes for people like him.
</P>
<P>
   Secondhand smoke is a hazard of the job for Sitnek, and it hangs
heavy at his next stop. The 22-year-old sex offender shows off his
new haircut: shaved around the lower edges, long and dyed red on
top.
</P>
<P>
   He served six months in jail for molesting a girl _ in an odd
twist, the victim was the daughter of another sex offender in
Sitnek's crew. He's taking Lithium to deal with a bipolar disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a job is a problem, he complains. (``That haircut
couldn't help,'' Sitnek comments later.) But he needs the money to
pay for therapy and testing.
</P>
<P>
   Offenders must foot part of the probation bill whenever
possible, which helps hold the cost of the county's program to
$3.81 per person per day. A similar program in Pima County runs
$9.85 because it has fewer offenders per officer.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County officials would like to lower the ratios of
offenders to officers, especially for surveillance. Many other
Arizona counties lack the resources for any special probation
program for sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Supreme Court has been lobbying the state
Legislature for several years to put more money into managing sex
offenders. Lawmakers haven't anted up, but this year they did give
the court some flexibility to move existing funding into such
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek makes his last visit at a tumbledown trailer court. He
opens a rickety wood gate, fends off a pair of large dogs and
ambles over to a decrepit Volkswagen, almost vibrating from the
radio turned full-blast inside.
</P>
<P>
   A boyish girl with short hair climbs out of the car as her
boyfriend, a registered sex offender, steps out of a ramshackle
trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Obscene rap talk booms from the VW. Sitnek asks her to turn the
music down; it will disturb the neighbors. Their lights are on, she
points out. Yes, he answers, but they have two little kids who are
probably in bed and could hear the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dilemma for probation: The kind of cheap housing that
will accept sex offenders is likely to attract financially strapped
families and single mothers whose children may not get much
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   This offender got a 13-year-old drunk and had sex with her. His
girlfriend may be wild _ Sitnek recently confiscated a knife with
brass knuckles from her _ but the offender has been following all
the terms of his probation.
</P>
<P>
   Sitnek pokes around outside for a while and calls it a night.
</P>
<P>
   He's done his part to keep some sex offenders on the straight
and narrow. ``If there are a few kids who don't get molested,'' he
says, ``we've done something right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
