</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COYOTES02-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHABIBULIN NEARS PAY DIRT  
 1 MORE WIN WOULD ELEVATE CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS - It's a win-win situation that Nikolai Khabibulin
faces.
</P>
<P>
   There's an old bromide in hockey that the greatness of a goalie
is not decided by regular-season performance, but by how far he can
carry his team in the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If Khabibulin can win today's Game 6 of the Coyotes' Western
Conference quarterfinal series against St. Louis, he will have
carried his mates into the second round for the first time in his
career after a season in which he statistically finished among the
NHL's top five goalies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Niki is our man,'' Coyotes left wing Keith Tkachuk said. ``He
wins games for us. He might be underrated by some around the
league, but that's fine. All he does is stop goals and win. That's
good enough for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gaining the recognition is fine, but there's an even bigger
 &UR; plus: financial reward.
</P>
<P>
   If Khabibulin, a restricted Group II free agent at season's end,
closes out the Blues today or, failing that, on Tuesday at home if
a seventh game is necessary, he figures to become a much wealthier
man next season.
</P>
<P>
   His Group II status means other NHL teams can tender an offer
and the Coyotes can either match it, or, if not, receive
compensation in the form of first-round draft picks according to
his salary status. In his case, probably three choices.
</P>
<P>
   But Khabibulin, who's earning $1.7 million this season, is only
26 and a proven, battle-tested product playing a position that
takes years to develop. A top-five NHL goalie earns in the $3
million-$5 million range in today's market. He will receive offers.
He's also a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked about it yet,'' Coyotes General Manager
Bobby Smith said. ``I don't think (during the playoffs) is the
proper time to even discuss it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Smith, a stubborn negotiator, anticipate having problems
re-signing Khabibulin?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll have our differences, but it will get done,''
he said, confidently.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Khabibulin agrees with the boss and prefers to
focus his thoughts on beating the Blues and advancing far into the
playoffs to worrying about contract issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked about it at all,'' he said. ``I haven't even
talked about it with my agent. It's not the time to talk about it.
I haven't forgotten it, but I don't really care. There's only so
much time left in the season and I've waited seven months. I can
wait another couple.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting salary issues aside, he entered this playoff series with
a career postseason record of 7-9 and a 2.91 goals-against average.
He's 3-2 with a 2.30 GAA in this series and, if one conducted a
poll of his teammates they would likely name him the team's most
valuable player in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he will tell you differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have probably played better in this series,'' he said
before Friday's 2-1 overtime loss. ``There's no particular area,
just better overall. If I would have played better, we probably
would have finished playing this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, to make a name for oneself in the NHL, one must close the
deal and advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to think of those things,'' Khabibulin said.
``I don't want to put any more pressure on myself . . . I don't
need that. So I don't think about what people are going to think
about me if we lose. I just go out there and try to do what I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   What strange logic there is in hockey. This man basically owns
every franchise goaltending record. He had a 32-win season, eight
shutouts, shattered his own franchise goals-against record (2.74)
at 2.13 this season, and it means little if he doesn't win in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the NHL is measured on playoff performance,''
Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``Teams are, franchises are,
individual players and goaltenders are; it's the same for everyone.
You become a household name by being on one of the two teams left
playing for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who likes hockey is focused on that series, whether
they're from the cities involved or not. There are a lot of
variables to consider. Nik's performance has been tremendous in
this series and we're still in the mix. But you don't evaluate
anyone until it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   In leading Phoenix to back-to-back wins in St. Louis last week,
he was forced to stop 17 third-period shots in Game 3 for a 5-4 win
(all four Blues' goals came with a man advantage), then backed it
up with a 27-save effort in 2-1 win in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the chance to seal the deal with a win Friday, he
played brilliantly and stopped 40 of 42 shots, allowing only an Al
MacInnis' power-play goal until Scott Young's shot in overtime left
him frustrated and the Coyotes with a 2-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nik played it well,'' Schoenfeld said of Young's game-winner.
``He was well out of the net. He has his angle, but it was a
perfect shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfectly frustrating, eh Nikolai?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you win; sometimes you lose,'' he said in his normal
stoic manner. ``I tried hard but we didn't win. There's nothing we
can do about it right now. We just have to win today. I played
pretty good and I'm confident. I'll try to do the same thing
today.''
</P>
<P>
   With a better result. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
