<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTLEY'S EXILE ENDS IN GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, KY. - He searched for the words. When he felt them,
lodged in his throat, he smiled. His pale blue eyes welled with
tears.
</P>
<P>
   How could he say this?
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to oblige those who stood around him, looking down at
him, asking how he felt. He wanted to shout it to the world. But
how could he put into words how special this day was for him, from
the moment a pari-mutuel choir of 140,000 voices sang that sweet
old song to the thrilling finish when the colt he was riding, a
30-to-1 longshot named Charismatic, charged from behind and won the
Kentucky Derby, the greatest horse race of them all?
</P>
<P>
   The Derby is called a ``mile and a quarter without any water.''
It's about courage and stamina and sacrifice, not only for the
winner but also the little man aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Antley, a longshot himself, can tell you about sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Antley had to give up racing horses last year. Discouraged, he
moved back home to Columbia, S.C. His weight was the problem. One
day he stepped on the scales. His heart sank. ``147'' pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Antley had faced a career crisis before. In 1988 he tested
positive for cocaine and lost his jockey's license. He beat his
addiction and three years later won the Derby aboard Strike the
Gold.
</P>
<P>
   Now he faced a battle he feared he couldn't win no matter how
hard he tried. Antley had to lose weight _ lots of weight _ if he
hoped to race again.
</P>
<P>
   He began running. He dieted. ``Every diet you could think of.''
He took water pills. Over time, he dropped 22 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Antley grew weak. Light-headed. He shed a few more pounds but
couldn't keep the weight off. He was stuck at 125.
</P>
<P>
   Les Antley's heart went out to his son. He urged him to give up
this torturous regimen. ``Chris, you're killing yourself. Forget
being a'' ``jockey. It's dangerous. You're 33. Why don't you try
something else''?``''
</P>
<P>
   At times Antley wanted to quit. It was hard. ``So'' hard. Too
hard. Hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   But Antley persevered. He began to run longer distances. People
in town became accustomed to seeing the 5-foot-3 figure jogging for
hours at a time. ``I got up to 25 miles,'' Antley said. Marathon
distance. Folks nicknamed him Forest Gump.
</P>
<P>
   Antley remembers the wishful conversation he had in December.
``Dad, the Derby is coming up soon. Wouldn't it be great if I made
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would say to his father now, Antley paused. Eyes
shining, the miniature figure wearing green and gold silks drew
himself up to his full height and said triumphantly, all 114
pounds, ``I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   He was everywhere Saturday. Sitting atop a determined horse that
caught Cat Thief and Worldly Manner down the stretch and held off
Menifee near the wire. Standing alongside Hall of Fame trainer D.
Wayne Lukas, who became a four-time Derby winner. Shaking hands and
accepting congratulations from many of the 18 other jockeys who
wished they could trade places with him.
</P>
<P>
   What was it Lukas called winning the Derby? ``A chance of a
lifetime in a lifetime of chances .''
</P>
<P>
   Antley felt as if that poetic sentiment had been penned just for
him. The winning jockey didn't know until a few weeks ago if he
ever would get another chance to be back in the saddle, doing what
he loves.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on the day, the ride itself was easy compared with
what was required of him afterward. All the questions about what it
felt like coming down the stretch. Crossing the finish line and
pointing to the sky. Looking into the sweeping grandstands at the
sea of faces, men dressed in their silk neckties and matching
pocket squares; women in their fashionable finest, smiling out from
beneath the wide brims of their Derby Day hats.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes words seem inadequate. This was one of those days for
the small goggled figure who appeared bobbing down the sandy loam
headed for home _ ``in the midst of a miracle''_ feeling reborn,
weightless with joy, light as air. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
