<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1128 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DBACKS-BREWERS-AZ     05-02 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DBACKS-BREWERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE WAS MORE THAN OL SON TO D BACKS' VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Closer Gregg Olson was officially credited with the
save Saturday, but there were plenty of others who saved the
Diamondbacks in their 5-3 victory over the Milwaukee Brewers at
County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There was starter Todd Stottlemyre, working 6 strong innings and
drawing a pivotal walk with two out in the sixth to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   There was center fielder Steve Finley, who, after begging
Manager Buck Showalter to play two hours before the game, delivered
with a two-run single after Stottlemyre walked.
</P>
<P>
   There was set-up man Greg Swindell, getting out of impending
doom in the seventh with runners on base and working a perfect
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   There was left fielder Luis Gonzalez, who has been on such a
roll of late that he even won the clubhouse Kentucky Derby pool,
collecting two more hits to extend his franchise-record streak to
15 games and raising his team-best batting average to .392.
</P>
<P>
   There was second baseman Jay Bell, making a mad dash into right
field in the ninth to rob Brian Banks of a leadoff hit with an
over-the-shoulder catch.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Olson, exorcising early April demons by picking up
his fourth save, third on this trip and second in less than 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owed Oly one,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   With Olson on the mound and the Diamondbacks in the lead April
11 in Atlanta, Bell dropped a leadoff soft liner in the ninth
inning that led to a Braves' victory and Olson's third blown save
in the first week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big catch,'' Olson said. ``If that drops in, it
could end up being demoralizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell said the wind slowed the ball just enough for him to get to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had an angle on it,'' said Bell, who had three hits,
including his eighth home run in the fifth. ``I basically turned
around, hoping I wouldn't get hammered by one of the outfielders.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory gives the Diamondbacks (14-11) a 5-4 record on this
13-game trip and a second straight win over the Brewers, who lost
their fifth straight and ninth of 11 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre (3-1) was sharp. He got ahead on most batters and
was in control until the seventh when he walked left fielder Geoff
Jenkins to start the inning, leading, 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Banks then singled. Leadoff batter Fernando Vina and Mark
Loretta both went after first pitches and fouled out to catcher
Kelly Stinnett. Jeff Cirillo singled up the middle to score Jenkins
and, with Showalter making his way to the mound, Stottlemyre kicked
the dirt in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out there in the seventh inning and walk the leadoff
guy with a 5-1 lead, that's not real good pitching,'' Stottlemyre
said. ``I felt I had better command of my fastball today. I just
missed there on Jenkins.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the bullpen has performed lately, Stottlemyre wasn't too
worried about handing Showalter the ball to give to Swindell.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up a double to Jeromy Burnitz that cut the score to
5-3, Swindell, with runners on second and third, got Sean Berry to
hit a soft liner into left, where Gonzalez charged in to make the
catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job of the middle reliever is tough,'' Swindell said. ``He
can make or break a game. We made it out and I didn't break it.
That means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who has struggled at the plate, was grateful he didn't
break a bat for a change.
</P>
<P>
   He had two broken-bat outs Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've broken enough bats to build a house,'' said Finley, who
is hitting .228. ``I'd say I was due for a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he didn't break any bats but perhaps the Brewers'
spirit with his two-run single in the sixth that gave Arizona a 5-1
lead and sent starter Jim Abbott to the showers.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter came to the stadium, seriously contemplating giving
the left-handed Finley a day off against left-handed Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of begged to play,'' Finley said. ``I don't care if I'm
swinging the bat bad or swinging it good. Sometimes, it's good to
have a day off. But I just felt I really needed to be out there. I
had my mind set to face this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter is glad he heeded his center fielder's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big knock,'' Showalter said. ``And what can I say
about Jay? He's played as good as anyone has played. That was a
great play (in the ninth). That stopped their momentum.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
