<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1136 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-FERGUSON-AZ     05-02 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-FERGUSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERGUSON GETS JOB AS CARDINALS' GM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, Bill Bidwill's friends around the NFL advised him,
urged him, to hire a real football man and give him control of the
Bidwill family business, the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   And for years, Bidwill, the Cardinals owner, resisted. The
result was a consistently downward spiral in every aspect of the
team. Along the way, the title of general manager was given to
various men, but none had the power that it suggested.
</P>
<P>
   And when Bidwill finally did relent and give control to one man,
he gave it to the wrong one, Buddy Ryan, who held the dual role of
coach and general manager for two years until 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The team since has been in the hands of a committee with no
clearly defined leader until Bidwill on Saturday confirmed a Friday
report in ``The Arizona Republic'' and handed the reins to Bob
Ferguson, who was promoted to general manager.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, Ferguson, 48, has been vice president
for player personnel. He was assistant to the president for one
year before that. Ferguson now has authority over football
philosophy, player personnel, the coaching staff, pro and college
scouting, the draft and free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Ryan has Bidwill entrusted someone outside his family
with such power. It is a move that, to the credit of Bidwill,
continues a wave of recent momentum for the team that it hopes
helps carry an election in two weeks on the Rio Salado Crossing, a
proposed Mesa convention and exposition center that would include a
retractable-roof stadium where the Cardinals would play.
</P>
<P>
   The outgoing Ferguson has been the antithesis of the
tight-vested, bumbling image of the team during its first decade in
the Valley. He has become a favorite of fans because he is
accessible and straight-shooting. His deft player transactions and
drafts lifted the Cardinals to their first winning record since
1983, their first playoff berth since 1974 and their first playoff
win since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am outspoken,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   With Ferguson running football and a Bidwill son, Michael, in
charge of non-football matters that include liaison to the Rio
Salado Crossing, the Cardinals have what Bidwill Sr. called a
leadership team ``to take us where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said having Bidwill entrust him with his team ``is
pretty special when the family believes in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two months ago Ferguson was uncertain he would be with the
Cardinals beyond the expiration of his contract later this month,
not knowing whether Bidwill wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm staying here and that's important to me,'' Ferguson said.
``I want to help us build a championship team and build a new home
in the East Valley. I'm grateful I've been part of what we've begun
here the last couple of years. Now we hope to finish it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an affirmation of what we all have been doing here
together. Now we need to learn how to play against a championship
schedule every year . . . to prove to everybody that we are
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, who received a multiyear contract, will direct a front
office staff that includes Rod Graves, who continues as assistant
to the president and serves as the team's primary contract
negotiator; Bill Bidwill Jr., who had done considerable contract
negotiation but who now will provide strategic financial planning
on salary-cap issues in his role as vice president; and Jay
Nienkark, player personnel administrator who serves as daily
salary-cap administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill Jr. had served as one of the top committeemen in the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fergie has earned the right to be the Cardinals' senior
football executive,'' Bidwill Sr. said. ``He has proven to be one
of the game's most astute evaluators of college and professional
talent. He is an excellent communicator and his expertise on draft
day is undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope his guidance will help take us where we want to go.
Our team has made great strides in the years he has been with our
organization and he deserves his fair share of the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson has held executive postions in the NFL for 22 years
with Seattle, Buffalo, Dallas, San Francisco and Denver. All but
Seattle went to the Super Bowl with players he landed.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion of Ferguson might have a profound impact on the
team's negotiations with free agent linebacker Jamir Miller.
Ferguson has said that he is a fan of Miller, an outside linebacker
who led the team with 150 tackles last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that I like Jamir, I want him here, but
now we have made other moves that make it tough under the salary
cap to get anything done,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cardinals are strapped under the cap, Ferguson now has
authority to tinker and open enough room to entice Miller into a
one-year offering, enough to get him back in the fold with the
opportunity to reach for more as a free agent again next year.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Miller nor his new agent, Leigh Steinberg, could be
reached Saturday for comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
