</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CAL500-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON ON THE POLE FOR CAL 500
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ If history is to repeat itself today at the California
Speedway, the winner of the California 500 will start from the
third position in the 43-car field. That scenario would return Mark
Martin to the winner's circle at the end of the 250-lap contest.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who dominated the second running of the NASCAR Winston
Cup Series event over the two-mile track last year, is in the third
starting spot not because he qualified there, but because that's
where he stands in the points race.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's rain, which seemed like such a distant memory during
Saturday's two practice sessions, washed out qualifying. Thus the
field for today's race, the 10th of 34 in the series, was set by
points and entry postmarks. The last Winston Cup race started by
points was the inaugural Texas event in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That means Jeff Burton will be on the pole alongside fellow Ford
driver Dale Jarrett. Joining Martin in the second row will be Bobby
Labonte, with Jeff Gordon and Rusty Wallace in the third row.
Gordon won the inaugural race in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Of the front six, only Jarrett and Labonte have yet to win a
race this year. Burton and Gordon have each won twice, and Martin
and Wallace have also triumphed.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a race track like this, it really doesn't matter where you
start,'' said Burton, who has finished 30th and 10th in his two
starts on the Fontana track. ``You could start 10th, 20th or
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was the fastest during Saturday's final practice, dubbed
``Happy Hour'' by tour regulars. Gordon, the two-time defending
Winston Cup champion, toured the oval in 40.198 seconds, a speed of
179.113, in his famed No.24 DuPont Chevrolet. Jeremy Mayfield,
sporting a paint scheme that commemorated Saturday's 125th running
of the Kentucky Derby on his Mobil 1 Ford Taurus, was second
fastest at 40.257, followed by Burton's 40.383. Jarrett was
fifth-fastest in the hour-long session, followed by Labonte and
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was also fastest in the morning session, turning in a
39.699. He won the pole in 1998 with a run of 39.610. What does
that say for the lack of time on the track Friday?
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually I think qualifying really mixes up the field,'' said
Burton. ``I'm glad we're starting by points. All the cars that run
good are high in the points. ``I think it may make it safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach said the 2{ hours of practice were enough to
get ready for today's race. Dallenbach, a Rick Hendrick teammate to
Gordon and Terry Labonte in his No.25 Budweiser Chevrolet, will
start 22nd but had the 16th best time in the final practice
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we might have had a top 10 car here,'' Dallenbach
said. ``But we had plenty of time to work on the race setup.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Schrader is in total agreement. ``We got more practice
time than we usually get,'' said Schrader, who has won two of four
Winston West races held at the speedway but only finished as high
as 15th in Cup competition. ``We don't learn anything on Friday. I
think it's a complete waste of time. ``Everybody is about as good
as they're going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton doesn't believe the field will allow him to go around the
first time without a challenge. ``Everybody wants to lead a lap,
especially those in the top five,'' said Burton, who has scored 40
bonus points thus far, tops in the circuit. Drivers gain five bonus
points for leading a lap and the one with the most laps led for
each race collects an additional five.
</P>
<P>
   At Fontana, only Gordon, Terry Labonte and Ricky Rudd have
completed every lap in Cup competition. However, Martin has led the
most laps in that same time span, 176, thanks to his dominating
effort last year when he paced the field 160 times. Martin, who has
seven top-10 finishes in his last eight races, will be making his
400th career start.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's Valvoline-sponsored Ford is one of five owner Jack
Roush will field today. That includes Burton, who has driven the
Exide Batteries car to 11th or better in eight of the nine races.
He saw enough during practice to say that the expected crowd of
115,000 will see some spirited racing today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be a lot of two-wide racing,'' said Burton,
who got extra seat time Saturday by finishing second in the Busch
Grand National Auto Club 300. ``I think you saw some of that in
practice. The bottom (groove) is still best, but the top is good
enough to slow the bottom down.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race track is a little bit different in that you know
you're gonna have a lot of close racing,'' said Jarrett, whose
No.88 Quality Care is one of two cars in the field owned by Robert
Yates. ``It's extremely fast, but there are a couple of grooves
here. You go in knowing it's a wide track that's gonna let you have
fun racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Martin used different strategies for their wins at
Fontana. Gordon won on fuel mileage, cutting it so close that he
coasted into the winner's circle, a development that many won't
forget. Martin was a runaway winner on power.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to start thinking fuel mileage-pit strategy as soon
as the race starts,'' said Larry McReynolds, crew chief for the
No.31 Lowe's Chevrolet driven by Mike Skinner. ``(The track) has
that characteristic, that possibility that it could be a full
green-flag race. There's lots of racing room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
