A1147 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-MU-AZR &LR;      05-02 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-MU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHANTOM MENACE SOUNDTRACK ANOTHER WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To fans of John Williams' music for the ``Star Wars'' movies,
each score has the significance of a numbered symphony by a major
composer.
</P>
<P>
   There was the first, original ``Star Wars,'' with its screaming
fanfare of an opening and moments of mysterious quiet for young
Luke. There was the second, ``The Empire Strikes Back,'' with that
maniacally mechanical ``Empire March'' so compelling in its evil it
made you want to join the dark side. And there was the third,
``Return of the Jedi,'' in which the themes of good and evil _
musical as well as cinematic _ came into collision and resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But now, at last, we can say:
</P>
<P>
   May the fourth be with you.
</P>
<P>
   The Original Motion Picture Soundtrack of ``Star Wars: Episode
I, The Phantom Menace,'' due in stores Tuesday, shows once again
that composer John Williams has a great deal in common with Franz
Liszt, the famously devilish 19th century pianist-composer. Liszt
and Williams, whose ubiquitous music makes him the writer of the
soundtracks to our fantasies, are masters of the same genre:
melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred and fifty years ago, ``melodrama'' referred to a
dramatic reading accompanied by music. The reading told the
audience what was happening, and the music _ usually played at the
piano _ told them what to feel. Liszt wrote many scores for such
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Williams in his best movie scores tells the audience what
to feel while the visuals tell it what's going on. Different
technologies, same idea.
</P>
<P>
   On Sony Classical, reuniting Williams with the London Symphony
Orchestra, ``Phantom Menace'' contains much that is expected, and a
great deal that's new. After the main title, which is exactly the
same as that for the 1977 ``Star Wars,'' the old themes show up
only in fragments, woven into or popping out of the texture of new
music. The movie is a prequel, after all, and these themes haven't
``happened'' yet.
</P>
<P>
   The most effective use of an old theme in the new context is in
a track titled ``He Is the Chosen One.'' It starts out with the
yearning ``Force'' theme (think of Luke beneath the double moons in
``Star Wars)'' but quickly morphs into a distortion of the theme,
auguring some dangerous misuse of the sacred Force. The most
immediately striking of the new music is the second track on the
compact disc, ``Duel of the Fates,'' a choral incantation
reminiscent of Carl Orff, underpinned by a scurrying, insistent
rhythmic figure that will show up again. Less gripping viscerally
but perhaps even better as feeling-painting is the third track,
``Anakin's Theme,'' a serenely haunting melody and possibly the
finest single thing Williams has penned for the series. At the end,
it eerily but aptly changes into a slow version of the ``Empire
March.''
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of melodrama is signaling, a semaphore of pitch and
pace. Williams is without peer at this. In all four ``Star Wars''
soundtracks, the semaphore vocabulary is clear and exactly right.
Pyramiding brass signal danger. Trumpet fanfares on repeated notes
indicate battle. Percussion _ of which there is a great deal more
in ``Phantom Menace'' than in the earlier three _ points to
something strange, new and possibly illusory.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of hymnlike writing. The sole and soulful
sort, and the kind reserved for moments of public, civil order,
such as the curtain-call medal-hanging scene at the end of ``Star
Wars.'' Both kinds are put to use in ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Star Wars'' and ``Return of the Jedi,'' there is a track
of quasi-pop music. In ``Star Wars'' this was the silly Cantina
Band number, and in ``Jedi'' it was the rather flimsy chanting song
of the Ewoks. ``Phantom Menace'' has ``Augie's Great Municipal
Band,'' a short, Caribbean-flavored dance tune.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' ``Star Wars'' scores are entertainment music at its
best and most honest. They do not pretend to be more than they are,
but they are not shy to exploit everything they truly are. &QL; 
Kenneth LaFave can be reached at (602) 444-8927 and can be e-mailed
at ken.lafave &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
