<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAVEN WINS WINSTON WEST RACE
</HEADLINE>
 WEST-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ Ricky Craven is starting 41st in today's NASCAR
Winston Cup California 500 at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's Winston West California 200, the NASCAR veteran
would rather be starting his Winston West Ford Taurus than his
Winston Cup Ford. Craven ran away from his competition to win the
100-lap, 200-mile Winston West race before approximately 40,000
fans Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably a better car than the one we're going to race
tomorrow, said Craven, who raced in a Winston West event at Las
Vegas Motor Speedway, but did not finish because of engine trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The car was purchased to race in last year's Winston West
exhibition in Motegi, Japan from Winston Cup owner Jack Roush, who
employed Craven until he sat aside because of injuries and was not
re-offered a job back last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be one of the best cars I've ever had, Craven said.
``Either we had 10 more horsepower than they did or they had 10
horsepower less.
</P>
<P>
   The race, a postlude to the Busch Grand National Auto Club 300,
was dominated by drivers who compete in other series. Kenny
Schrader, who is 13th in Winston Cup points, finished second.
Schrader had won this race the previous two years. Craftsman Truck
driver Rick Carelli finished in third place.
</P>
<P>
   The race was marred by a spectacular crash, although no driver
was seriously injured. Brendan Gaughan was tapped from behind in
Turn 4, spun into the wall and slid to the bottom of the track.
Gary Smith, already spinning backward, hit Gaughan in the rear,
causing a large explosion. The fire did not spread and was quickly
extinguished. Gaughan complained of only being singed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get it turned (back) around, Gaughan said. I lost
the brake lines when I hit the wall. I started to go down and I saw
the No. 7 car coming, but I couldn't stop.
</P>
<P>
   Craven took the lead for good on Lap 73. When the sixth, and
final, yellow flag went out two laps later, Schrader, who had been
swapping the lead with Craven for nearly the entire race, went into
the pits to change all four tires. The pit stop put him at the back
of the lead lap, in 15th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed our sequence, Schrader said. ``We knew we were not
going to get around (Craven) without a change.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Schrader passed Carelli to take second with two laps
to go, Craven was four seconds in front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought our only chance was to get fresh tires, make a run
for second and then hope we catch a yellow, Schrader said.
</P>
<P>
   Polesitter Austin Cameron went out of the race on Lap 58 when
battling Schrader for the lead. He bumped John Metcalf and went
into the wall in Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a very good driver, but he's got to learn how
to finish a race, Schrader said. ``He has to figure out what he has
to do, but it's hard to tell someone that. We've all had to learn
that.
</P>
<P>
   Winston West will race at Irwindale Speedway on June 19 and Aug.
21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
