A1149 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-GORDON-AZR     05-02 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-GORDON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCKLESS GORDON HAVING HEADACHE OF A SEASON  
 BUT 3 DNFS IN 9 STARTS ARE `NO REASON TO PANIC' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ So this is what it's like.
</P>
<P>
   Rotten luck. Lousy finishes. Headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, boy, the headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon always knew it could happen. He knew because it's
happened so many times before.
</P>
<P>
   But it's always happened to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Except now.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gordon is the snake-bit driver, the one racer seemingly
unable to buy a stinking break.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of luck, kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Crew chief, confidant, soulmate) Ray Evernham reminded me we
won 10 races after last year's Coca Cola 600 in May,'' Gordon said.
``There's no reason to panic. It's still early.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's early.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're a two-time defending NASCAR Winston Cup driving
champion, winner of a whopping 40 races the past four seasons, and
someone used to going home late because you're too busy supplying
sound bites and quotes for an inquiring media, it's never too early
to talk about being late at the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   And in nine starts this season entering Sunday's California 500
at pristine California Speedway, Gordon has been so late in three
races, he hasn't shown up at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having one of those years that everybody has been
waiting for,'' said Gordon, whose statistical ledger this season
includes three DNFs (39th, 43rd and 38th). ``But it's not because
we're not running good. We're running real good. We're just not
having the good fortune that we've had in the past, and that's what
it takes to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a year like we had last year (13 wins, 26
top-five and 28 top-10 finishes in 33 starts), a third driving
title in the past four seasons, and enough race winnings and
endorsement bucks to purchase an island somewhere near, oh,
Jamaica, it's real easy to look at this season and say we're having
a real bad year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we've had three wrecks and three bad finishes, but we're
still fifth in points. Actually, I feel fortunate that I can sit
here and say, `How in the heck are we fifth in points?' ''
</P>
<P>
   How indeed. Maybe things aren't so bad.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Gordon is fifth in the drivers standings, which is
exactly where he was at this juncture a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, Gordon has the same amount of wins (two), one more
top-five (five) and an additional top-10 (six) finish than last
season after nine races.
</P>
<P>
   But a year ago, Gordon trailed the series leader by 73 points.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the deficit separating leader Jeff Burton and
Gordon is 210 points.
</P>
<P>
   And, then, there's those DNFs. That doesn't happen to Gordon. At
least, not to the point where it creates a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard someone say that they weren't sure they could make up
that point differential,'' Dale Jarrett said. ``You have to laugh a
little bit at that. He's (Gordon) still very much within striking
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon isn't laughing. But he also hasn't locked himself in a
closet, either.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is Gordon, Evernham and the Rainbow Warriors
we're talking about. If anyone is capable of putting together
another remarkable stretch (10 wins, 17 top-five and 20 top-10
finishes in final 20 races of last season), it's you know who.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team is too good and Gordon is too good a driver to stay
down for long,'' Rusty Wallace said. ``They'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Burton senses a Gordon surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it appears as if (Gordon) is having some
troubles,'' Burton said. ``I don't think that's happened to them
that early in the season before.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think championships are won on luck. They're won
on preparation. That team knows how to prepare and how to keep
themselves out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   True.
</P>
<P>
   But all good things eventually come to an end, don't they?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, isn't it healthy for NASCAR to have so many different
front-runners (seven different winners this season) instead of a
constant Gordon-Mark Martin and vice-versa one-two finish every
week, which is what happened so many times in 1998?
</P>
<P>
   ``All sports have teams or someone that stands out,'' Burton
said. ``Baseball has the Yankees, the Bulls with Michael Jordan,
the 49ers (a few years ago) in football. It benefits the sort. It
gives others something to shoot at, the way everyone is shooting at
the 24 team (Gordon).
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had 30 races and 30 different winners, it might be
parity, but what fun would it be?''
</P>
<P>
   Not much for Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gordon is going to mirror last season and the season
before, he will need a jump start soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need things to happen like what happened last week to
(Burton),'' Gordon said. ``It looked like (his car) was going to
blow up on the starting line, but he comes back and everything is
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of luck we've had. It's been unbelievable at
times, the last three or four years. I'm more surprised at that
than anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we can still have a great season, even greater
than it's already been after winning (the Daytona 500). We have a
competitive team, as competitive as we've had in a long time. We
can't put pressure on ourselves and feel like we have to win every
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's what we all want to do _ win. I guess that's me just
wanting to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfectly content. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
