<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-BUSCH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT NOW 0 FOR 10 BUT KEEPS POINTS LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Still no checkered flag for  &UR; Dale Earnhardt
 &UR; Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, whose sensational debut last season resulted in seven
wins and the NASCAR Busch Series championship, can't seem to find
the entrance into victory lane this year.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt finished third Saturday behind winner  &UR; Matt Kenseth
and runner-up  &UR; Jeff Burton in the Auto Club 300 at California
Speedway, leaving him 0 for 10 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have the points lead than win races,'' Earnhardt
said Friday on the eve of the race. ``But I look forward to
hopefully changing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt almost did 24 hours later. He led 81 laps, nearly
three times as many as Kenseth. But Earnhardt made a daring move
underneath a slower car on Lap 121 while running sixth and wound up
spinning and losing a lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty spectacular to see someone spin like that at 185
miles per hour and not hit anything,'' Kenseth said. ``(Earnhardt)
is a great driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt unlapped himself on Lap 128, and when a three-car
crash produced the sixth of eight caution flags on Lap 129, he was
able to move to the tail end of the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   By Lap 138, Earnhardt was up to third from 14th. There was
another caution on Lap 140, and Earnhardt momentarily dropped to
fifth following the restart on Lap 145 because his Chevy Monte
Carlo was without third gear.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt mounted another charge and was significantly closing
the gap on the two front-runners when Todd Bodine crashed on Lap
149, forcing the race to end under caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to see that (Lap 140 caution),'' Kenseth said.
``Seeing all those cars on your bumper makes me nervous. But as
long as I kept my position, I felt like I could hold them off.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was Kenseth's second of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, despite no wins, remained atop the drivers standings,
95 points ahead of Kenseth. &QL; 
Notes &QL; 
McDonald's and car owner  &UR; Cal  &UR; Wells III have agreed to a
sponsorship agreement to field a NASCAR Busch Series car next
season. The arrangement eventually will lead to a Winston Cup team.
Although McDonald's will continue to be car owner/driver  &UR; Bill
Elliott's major sponsor through 2000, the relationship will end
following next season. Elliott last won in 1994, when he drove for
 &UR; Junior Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bobby Labonte will not drive in any more Busch races this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Thompson of Scottsdale finished 10th in the NASCAR Winston
West California 200 on Saturday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
