<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Raul Mondesi was dropped from fourth to fifth in
the Dodgers' batting order, had a bit of a tizzy and now thinks
life is grand.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson did it to spark the offense, and
also catch Mondesi's attention.
</P>
<P>
   It's working.
</P>
<P>
   The lackluster offense the Dodgers took to Milwaukee is
disappearing as they deliver clutch hits and piece together big
innings. The latest piling on came Saturday as the Dodgers beat the
Philadelphia Phillies 12-6 at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' highest run output of the season pushed their
winning streak to five _ the longest string since August 1997. In
the last three games the Dodgers have scored 26 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's doing well the last five games,'' said Mondesi,
the Dodgers' right fielder. ``Last week I said we weren't going to
be struggling on offense. We're starting to hit better and our
pitching is doing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi led a 12-hit attack with a three-run homer in the first
inning off long-forgotten left-hander Paul Spoljaric (0-3). His
ninth homer in 24 games gave the Dodgers a 3-0 lead and served as a
precursor to a five-run second inning that made life on the mound
easier for starter Darren Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   Since being moved in the lineup five games ago Mondesi has a
pair of homers, six RBI and is hitting .353.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad the first day, but after that I don't think about
it,'' said Mondesi, who leads the Dodgers with 20 RBI. ``I was mad,
but after that what are you going to do? After that, I have to do
the best I can. I go out there every day and I play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Eric Karros, who swapped places with Mondesi, showed
signs of breaking out of a 1 for 16 skid with a pair of hits,
including the back-breaking one in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield's RBI single knocked Spoljaric (0-3) out with one
out in the second and kept the bases loaded. Karros then hit
reliever Mike Grace's first pitch into left field to score two runs
and give the Dodgers an 8-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to do a few things offensively, (but) some guys
are trying to do too much,'' Johnson said. ``Mondesi is hitting the
ball well. I guess he's still made at me for dropping him to
fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all Dreifort (4-1) needed. He gave up 10 hits and three
runs in six innings, but that hardly mattered. Once the huge lead
was provided, he altered his pitching plan. Many of his 106 pitches
were fastballs, though he did have a wicked slider working.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other starts in which Dreifort was wild, he was able
to throw strikes. He walked a season-low one and had five
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it was an `I come straight after them' approach,''
Dreifort said of pitching with the big lead. ``It's the game (Paul)
LoDuca called and I pitched it. I still gave up 10 hits, but only
three scored. I was just throwing it so they could hit it. I'm not
a guy who's going to nibble around. Even when I gave up 10 hits
tonight, most of the time I was behind in the count.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was still able to give the Dodgers a solid outing,
something the Dodgers starters did during the winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   But the once-stagnant offense is alive and producing runs, which
lessen the burden on the pitchers. The Dodgers were averaging 4.7
runs while limping to a 9-10 mark before the road trip. They were
hitting .255.
</P>
<P>
   However, since arriving in Milwaukee for a three-game set
Tuesday, the Dodgers are averaging 6.4 runs and they're hitting
.284.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we're doing anything better. We're just getting
hits now,'' Karros said. ``It's a much more balanced lineup. When
(Todd) Hundley's catching, (Adrian) Beltre's hitting eighth, and
he's batting .350, so we're in good shape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
