<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-JOHNSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS ROOKIE RISES FROM THE ASHES  
 LIFE'S STRUGGLES BRING SAFETY JOHNSON TO NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals rookie safety Paris Johnson was 14 the day his mother
was taken away because of a crack cocaine problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody called the authorities and said she was unfit,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He was made a ward of the state of Illinois. His two younger
sisters and brother were placed in different foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see them,'' he said. ``I call them. I talk to them. But it
hurts so bad to see my brothers and sisters struggle like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the lucky one. He was placed in the custody of his
aunt, who tried to shield him from the life of drugs and gangs on
the streets of Chicago's mean West Side.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't always work. At times, he was so wild, his aunt,
Paulette Thompson, locked him out of her house.
</P>
<P>
   He still roamed the streets. One night, he was out celebrating
his acceptance to a junior college to play football when a gang
pulled its guns on him and his cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life flashed in front of me,'' said Johnson, a fifth-round
pick earlier this month from Miami of Ohio. ``I made up of my mind
I didn't want to live that way, constantly watching my back,
constantly worried I was going to jail.'' &QL; 
Chapter and verse &QL; 
Miami Coach Terry Hoeppner likes to tell people that Johnson is an
``incredible story who just keeps writing new chapters to the
book.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest chapter happened April 18, when Johnson was playing
Monopoly with friends and his girlfriend, Monica Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my turn to roll the dice,'' he said. ``I let the dice
go, and all of sudden, I see, `Paris Johnson, Arizona Cardinals' on
TV. My mouth just dropped. I said, `Yes!' ''
</P>
<P>
   That was a long way from the day he watched his mother, Darlene
Johnson, leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I stayed in that situation, I would have ended up in
jail,'' Johnson said. ``Or dead. Or on the wrong side of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   His dad, who fathered 16 children with seven different women,
was long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got addicted to drugs,'' Johnson said. ``It took a toll on
her life and our whole quality of life. But it motivated me that I
didn't want to go down that path, the way she led her life. I never
wanted to end up like that.''
</P>
<P>
   His aunt took him in, even though she already was raising three
kids and a grandchild. Then she lost her job at the post office,
and money was tight.
</P>
<P>
   That's why she served chicken nearly every night _ fried
chicken, baked chicken, broiled chicken, chicken and rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though she lost her job, we stuck together,'' Johnson
said. ``It made me learn what true hard work was. She worked late
hours, would come back in the middle of the night exhausted. But
she still made sure I got my homework done.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wasn't an angel, which is why he sometimes got locked
out of the house. He didn't get arrested, just hung around the
wrong people and got involved with gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was ready to spread my wings and see the world the
way it was, and basically, I wasn't ready,'' he said. ``I was being
stubborn.''
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson was a senior in high school, he was out on his own
again. He switched from a high school in a rough neighborhood,
Proviso West, to one in more of a middle class neighborhood, Oak
Park River Forest.
</P>
<P>
   But to play at Oak Park, he had to live alone in a state-funded
apartment as part of the government's New Direction program. He'd
awake at 5:30 a.m., iron his clothes, pack himself a lunch and then
go off to school.
</P>
<P>
   Every couple of weeks, government workers interviewed Oak Park's
coaches to make sure Johnson was behaving himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't let anyone down,'' he said. ``I had a
responsibility to uphold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on my own was another blessing. Another door opened. It
allowed me to see what life was all about. It gave me an
opportunity to be a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Football gave Johnson another opportunity. His grades kept him
from going to a Division I school. So he went to North Iowa Area
Community College instead.
</P>
<P>
   It was there he met Lindsay, who later transferred to Miami. She
was the one who told a Miami assistant about him.
</P>
<P>
   The RedHawks invited Johnson for a visit. During that visit, he
told then-head coach Randy Walker, ``I want to play for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker's response was, ``OK. Who are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he found out Johnson's amazing life story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing he knew about me was what he saw on the (junior
college) highlight tape,'' Johnson said. ``It was a homemade tape.
It wasn't clear. Still, he took a chance on me. All my life, I've
been associated with people who took a chance on me.'' &QL; 
Another risk taker &QL; 
The Cardinals took a chance on Johnson, 6 foot 2, 213 pounds, even
though he missed six of his final seven games last season because
of a bruised knee.
</P>
<P>
   They liked his hitting ability, even though he lacked coverage
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the thing that jumped off the film,'' Cardinals
secondary coach Larry Marmie said. ``He played the game with an
attitude. We knew he was going to be very physical in his style of
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked with his college coach (Walker) at North Carolina,
and he told me the guy had some real strong resolve. He said, `You
talk about liking somebody, you're going to like this guy.' Some
people can overcome a lot of things if they want to. He must have a
great amount of personal pride and will to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's mother remains in jail. He hasn't talked to her in
months.
</P>
<P>
   When he signs his first contract, Johnson wants to spend the
money to help his brother and sister, teenagers who remain in
foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to raise them like I always wanted to be raised,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The low part of my life is every time I think about them. Now
that I'm here, I just hope to God I can make it, so I can give them
the quality of life they always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibility keeps building. I'm in too deep to fall
down.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
