r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFE     05-02 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALAAM FIGURES HE IS DUE FOR BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cheekbone under his left eye is swollen and scarred _ not
the result of a fight but a car accident _ which has left Chicago
Bears running back  &UR; Rashaan Salaam trying to put his NFL career
back together at a fitness center in the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   His broken leg has healed, his knee and hamstring problems
appear over. So why is the former Heisman Trophy winner out of a
job?
</P>
<P>
   ``The day before I was supposed to go the (Oakland) Raiders, I
got into a wreck,'' he said of the March 28 accident in San Diego
in which he also injured his back. ``The timing was unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years, I've had a lot of downs. I guess it was my
turn to go through tribulations, just the course my life has taken,
because before that, my life had gone real smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Salaam was a first-round draft pick of the Bears in 1995 after
rushing for 2,055 yards and 24 touchdowns his junior season at
Colorado, earning him the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   He had an impressive rookie season, gaining 1,074 yards and 10
touchdowns despite missing four weeks of training camp because of a
contract holdout. But he also had fumbling problems that season.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, he missed the first three games because of an
injured right knee and hamstring. ``I got hurt in the last
preseason game, but the Bears didn't give me a chance (to recover)
from that,'' he said. ``They wanted me out there. I came back too
quickly and was playing on one leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the season, he reinjured his knee, and he finished with
only 496 yards and three scores.
</P>
<P>
   In the third game of the 1997 season, he suffered a broken leg.
A rod was put in the leg, and he was in a walking cast for 13
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He was traded to the Miami Dolphins last off-season, thinking he
had a chance to rebuild his career. ``I was ecstatic,'' he said.
``I was joining a new team with (Coach)  &UR; Jimmy Johnson, who loves
to run the ball. I thought it was the perfect place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But he failed his physical examination with the Dolphins, who
thought the broken leg made him too much of a health risk. He was
released by the Bears and was out of football last season.
</P>
<P>
   Salaam, only 24, was ready to make his comeback until the car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a month ago, he was reading a magazine about NFL prospects
who visit training centers before the league's scouting combine to
enhance their draft status. One of those centers is run by  &UR; Warren
Anderson in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great,'' said Salaam, 6 feet 1, 224 pounds. ``I work
out five days a week, four to five hours a day. I want to be
looking great by July 1 so I can go to (training) camp. I want to
go to Oakland. That's always been a dream of mine. I used to wear
nothing but Raiders gear. But I have to be honest: I'd go
anywhere.'' &QL; 
New favorites &QL; 
With Denver Broncos quarterback  &UR; John Elway retiring, the Minnesota
Vikings are the favorites among oddsmakers to win Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have been established as 4-1 favorites.
</P>
<P>
   In the AFC, many are picking the New York Jets, losers to Denver
in last year's AFC title game. The Jets led the Broncos, 10-0,
early in the third quarter of that game, but Elway ralled his team
to a 23-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Jets quarterback  &UR; Vinny Testaverde says, ``I like our
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Jets Coach  &UR; Bill Parcells hasn't jumped on the title bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to be an easy task for us,'' Parcells said.
``I don't care about perceptions. I learned a long time ago that
last year's performance isn't an indication of this year's
performance. (The balance of power) changes every year. Things do
change. The landscape changes regardless of whether John (Elway)
plays. I think this does give other teams a chance, but it will be
very competitive.'' &QL; 
Next in line? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miami quarterback  &UR; Dan Marino, the last member of the 1983
quarterback class, isn't planning to join Elway in retirement soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that (retirement) enters your mind sometimes,
but I feel pretty good about what I'm doing,'' Marino said. ``If I
was on a team that I didn't think had a chance to win, then maybe I
would think about it a lot more seriously. But right now I feel
good. I'm throwing the ball great. I don't see any reason to think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino, one of six quarterbacks taken in the first round in '83,
said it's hard to believe Elway won't be playing anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I kind of had a feeling after winning two championships in
a row, it probably would be time for him to spend more time with
his family,'' Marino said. ``He's a close friend. He's been a
friend for a long time, and I admire him as a person and also as
the great quarterback that he is. I think we'll all miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino still thinks the Broncos, back-to-back Super Bowl
champions, can win the crown with Elway gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver's got a real good team, and until someone beats them,
they're the world champions,'' Marino said. ``I think we're getting
better, though. We're going to have a chance, a real chance. I'm
looking forward to it. I really am.'' &QL; 
Off color &QL; 
Baltimore Ravens executive  &UR; David Modell, son of owner  &UR; Art Modell,
didn't appreciate former Ravens offensive tackle  &UR; Orlando Brown
saying recently that he hated wearing the team's purple uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Brown signed with Cleveland, Baltimore's big rival and former
home of the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my butt was that big, I wouldn't like wearing purple
either,'' Modell said. &QL; 
Dollar signs &QL; 
The Green Bay Packers, the NFL's only publicly owned team, are
thinking of charging the 47,000 people on their season ticket
waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   Each would be charged $20, earning the club about $940,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns are the only other team to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about doing it because other clubs have done
it,'' Packers President  &UR; Bob Harlan said. ``The reason they do it
is to find out if the waiting list is really legitimate or if it's
watered down. You always wonder: Are there truly 47,000 people, or
is that misleading?'' &QL; 
Steve Schoenfeld can be reached at (602) 444-8334 or at
steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
