<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERSATILITY PUTS DUNCAN AT MVP LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the regular season winding down and the playoffs set to
begin Saturday, here's one man's ballot for the NBA's annual
awards: &QL; 
Most Valuable Player &QL; 
Leading candidates: Utah's  &UR; Karl Malone, Miami's  &UR; Alonzo Mourning,
the Suns'  &UR; Jason Kidd, Seattle's  &UR; Gary Payton, San Antonio's  &UR; Tim
Duncan and &UR; Shaquille O'Neal of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Malone probably is the favorite. His team looks to be headed for
the league's best record, and Malone ranks high among the league
leaders in scoring and rebounding. But Malone's scoring average
(23.7) is his lowest since 1986-87, and his rebounding average
(9.3) is his lowest since 1985-86, his rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning, however, will get a lot of votes in the East. He's not
far from Malone in scoring and rebounding and has far greater
impact on the defensive end. His team could emerge with the best
record in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd is having his best season as a pro and, with seven
triple-doubles, is going to get a lot of votes. He would get this
one, too, if the Suns had won 30 games or more. Winning has to be
part of the equation. Some, including ESPN.com expert Kevin
Loughery, have endorsed Kidd despite his club's record.
</P>
<P>
   Payton has a similar problem. His team's record is even worse,
and his tirade in the locker room after another loss this week will
cost him votes. O'Neal carried the Lakers early and showed signs of
exerting himself as a leader. But the Lakers have slipped, and so
have his chances.
</P>
<P>
   The vote goes to Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs overcame a very slow start to make a run at the
league's best record. Duncan, like Malone, is among the scoring and
rebounding leaders. He's also a candidate for the All-Defensive
team who is high on the list of shot blockers, and he shoots a high
percentage. Mourning is a close second, followed by Kidd, Malone
and Payton. &QL; 
Coach of the Year &QL; 
Leading candidates: Utah's  &UR; Jerry Sloan, Miami's  &UR; Pat Riley,
Toronto's &UR; Butch Carter, Portland's  &UR; Mike Dunleavy, Philadelphia's
 &UR; Larry Brown, Charlotte's  &UR; Paul Silas and Orlando's  &UR; Chuck Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations always hurt Sloan and Riley in these contests. The
award almost always goes to a team that overachieves, in which case
Brown and Carter will get a lot of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Daly also will benefit from taking a team that was considered a
playoff club but not a championship contender and making a run for
the Eastern Conference's best record.
</P>
<P>
   Silas did a terrific job as an interim, turning his club around
after a 4-11 start and the resignation of  &UR; Dave Cowens. But Silas
also benefited from the trade that sent  &UR; Eddie Jones and  &UR; Elden
Campbell from the Lakers to the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   The vote goes to Dunleavy.
</P>
<P>
   How he managed to keep all of those egos _ especially  &UR; Isaiah
Rider's _ going in the same direction is a mystery. Virtually
everybody expected the Blazers to come back to reality after a
torrid start, but they never did.
</P>
<P>
   And Dunleavy won a lot of games by playing veteran  &UR; Greg Anthony
at the point during fourth quarters instead of the club's highly
paid star,  &UR; Damon Stoudamire, who had suffered through a bad
shooting season. &QL; 
Rookie of the Year &QL; 
Leading candidates:  &UR; Vince Carter of Toronto,  &UR; Jason Williams of
Sacramento,  &UR; Paul Pierce of Boston and  &UR; Mike Bibby of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   This looked like a wide open contest at the start of the season.
Pierce had a terrific first month in Boston. Williams was a regular
on the highlights in Sacramento and Carter was wowing fans in
Toronto. Denver's  &UR; Raef LaFrentz was right in it, too, until a
season-ending knee injury. Bibby got better as the season
progressed, but his team didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The vote goes to Carter, who ran away with this contest in the
season's second half. &QL; 
Defensive Player of Year &QL; 
Leading candidates: Seattle's Payton, Atlanta's  &UR; Dikembe Mutombo,
Miami's Mourning and the Suns'  &UR; Clifford Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson probably won't get as many votes as he deserves,
although he should end up on one of the league's All-Defensive
teams. He guarded point guards to centers and did it well. He
finished among the league leaders in steals and led the club in
blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Payton will get a lot of votes but didn't have anywhere near his
usual season. Mutombo is another who will get as many votes from
reputation as achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The vote goes to Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   He anchored the league's best defensive team and was averaging
more than four shot blocks a game. For perspective, 7-foot-6
Mavericks center  &UR; Shawn Bradley was a distant second with 3.2
blocks a game. &QL; 
Sixth Man award &QL; 
Leading candidates:  &UR; Darrell Armstrong of Orlando,  &UR; Jalen Rose of
Indiana and  &UR; Rasheed Wallace of Portland. &QL; 
Wallace gets some credit for volunteering to come off the bench on
a talent-laden roster. Rose had a solid year that went largely
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   The vote goes to Armstrong, even though he started most of the
season's second half. Any player who came off the bench more than
he started is eligible. &QL; 
Most Improved Player &QL; 
Leading candidates: Utah's  &UR; Bryon Russell, Orlando's Armstrong,
Philadelphia's  &UR; Allen Iverson, Milwaukee's  &UR; Haywoode Workman and
Minnesota's  &UR; Joe Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, this award finds its way into the hands of a player
who has simply gotten more of an opportunity than in the past.
Armstrong fits that category and is the favorite to win it. Iverson
and Smith are the opposite. They came into the league as starters
but have had to grow into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The vote goes to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   All-NBA teams &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First team: Kidd and Payton at guard; Mourning at center; Malone
and Duncan at forwards.
</P>
<P>
   Second team: Iverson and  &UR; Penny Hardaway of Orlando at guards;
O'Neal at center;  &UR; Antonio McDyess and  &UR; Kevin Garnett at forward.
</P>
<P>
   Third team:  &UR; Tim Hardaway of Miami and  &UR; John Stockton of Utah at
guards;  &UR; Hakeem Olajuwon at center;  &UR; Shareef Abdur-Rahim and
 &UR; Grant Hill at forwards. &QL; 
Bob Young can be reached at (602) 444-8271 or at
bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
