<HEADLINE>
SULLIVAN LIKELY TO PLAY; BRIERE, WAITE RECALLED FROM MINORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Defensive specialist  &UR; Mike Sullivan likely will be
in the lineup today when the Coyotes meet the St. Louis Blues in
Game 6 of their Western Conference first-round series. But
second-line left wing  &UR; Greg Adams' availability won't be decided
until game time.
</P>
<P>
   As insurance, the team recalled forwards  &UR; Daniel Briere and
 &UR; Tavis Hansen from Springfield of the American Hockey League, along
with goalie  &UR; Jimmy Waite, after the Falcons were knocked out of the
playoffs by Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan got hit in the leg with a slap shot from Blues
defenseman  &UR; Al MacInnis in the third period of Friday's 2-1
overtime loss to the Blues in Game 5. He left the game but returned
and didn't miss a shift. Earlier this season, a MacInnis shot broke
one of Sullivan's big toes.
</P>
<P>
   Adams has missed three games in the series, which Phoenix leads,
3-2, because of a pulled groin muscle he suffered late in Game 1.
He came back and scored one of the Coyotes' two goals during their
2-1 victory in Game 4, but the injury flared up and he missed Game
5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell how it is because it doesn't hurt me just
sitting around,'' Adams said. ``It's more when I'm exerting myself.
I don't know if I'll test it in the morning or not. I've got to
talk to our trainer and the doctors first.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Adams play if this was Game 7? He'd probably try, but the
team wants to be careful about a possible long-term problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of factors you take into consideration,'' Adams
said. ``I've got to sit down with them and find out exactly what's
at risk and take it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith said there's a small chance
either Briere or Hansen could see action today. He added that the
call-up of Waite, whom the Coyotes gave up on when he struggled to
an 0-5-2 mark after a torrid 6-0-2 start, is simply an insurance
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to have a third goalie, eh?'' Smith said. ``If  &UR; (Nikolai)
 &UR; Khabibulin gets hurt (today), you've got  &UR; (Mikhail) Shtalenkov in
net and no backup.'' &QL; 
Melting ice time &QL; 
After averaging more than 20 minutes per game in the first four
games, defenseman  &UR; Oleg Tverdovsky played only 7:01 Friday night.
The biggest reason for that was that Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld moved
him to a wing position with the return of blue liner  &UR; Gerald Diduck
from a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   Playing mostly on the fourth line, Tverdovsky recorded no shots
and seldom left the bench after the second period. He is a plus 3
in the series, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if (playing wing) is what I have to do, if the coaches
see me there, that's all there is to it,'' said Tverdovsky, who has
shyed away from changing positions in the past. ``I'll do whatever
it takes.'' &QL; 
Slap shots &QL; 
As bad as the Phoenix power play has looked at times in the series,
the unit has produced one man-advantage goal in each of the past
four games. The Coyotes were on the power play early in overtime
Friday but couldn't connect for the 29th time in 33 chances.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rick Tocchet, who scored 26 goals during the regular season,
has taken seven shots but has no goals in the series. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
