<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG PICKED GOOD TIME FOR 1ST GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _  &UR; Scott Young's first job involved working with
explosives, so it was fitting that the St. Louis right wing was the
one creating the fireworks in Game 5 of the playoff series against
the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Young took  &UR; Chris Pronger's lead pass on the right wing and
fired a wrist shot over  &UR; Nikolai Khabibulin's glove hand 5:43 into
overtime Friday night. It kept the Blues alive in the postseason
and moved the series to St. Louis for Game 6 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw it and went after it,'' Young said. ``It was just
reaction. I went as hard as I could toward the puck and took a hard
shot, and it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Young's first goal in the playoffs and one that his
teammates said afterward that they sensed was coming. In four
regular season games against the Coyotes, Young posted two goals
and two assists. He finished the regular season third on the team
in goals with 24. He was due.
</P>
<P>
   The way he did it, with a rocket of a wrist shot, was vintage
Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect shot,'' Coyotes Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld said.
``He is one of the few guys who could take a wrist shot like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said, ``I'm just glad it went in. I guess it was a good
time to get the first (playoff goal).'' &QL; 
History matters &QL; 
Five Blues players have a combined 10 Stanley Cup rings, and if you
look at who owns them, it says something about the benefit of
championship experience.
</P>
<P>
   Five belong to goalie  &UR; Grant Fuhr, who secured all of them
during his career with the Edmonton Oilers. With the exception of
Game 3, when the Coyotes scored five goals on him, the 35-year-old
Fuhr has been a key factor in keeping these games close.
</P>
<P>
   Young won titles with Pittsburgh in 1991 and Colorado in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Al MacInnis, the most dominating player in this
series with three goals and six assists, was a member of the
1988-89 Stanley Cup champion Calgary Flames and was the leading
scorer during those playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Wing  &UR; Geoff Courtnall, who has three points in this series,
played for the champion Oilers in 1988, and defenseman  &UR; Chris
McAlpine's first NHL season was with the 1995 Stanley Cup champion
New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience is always going to help,'' said Blues Coach
 &UR; Joel
 &UR; Quenneville, who won a ring as an assistant with Colorado. ``And
those things will reveal themselves in positive ways.'' &QL; 
Turning point &QL; 
There were several key moments in Friday's game, but Quenneville
said the biggest came in the third period, when Fuhr made a key
stop on a &UR; Keith Tkachuk breakaway. It was't much later that
MacInnis scored his score-tying goal on a power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That to me was the turning point,'' Quenneville said. ``It was
a big play by Grant. I thought the first two periods weren't great,
but I thought the third period we played like we wanted to win. We
seemed to play our best when the game was on the line.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
