<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITEOUT: SOMETHING JUST ISN'T WORKING HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS - The Whiteout in Phoenix is pretty cool. Pretty to
look at.
</P>
<P>
   And pretty much a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Whiteout is no longer intimidating. Not when the
home team wins four times in nine playoff starts at America West
Arena. Not when the Coyotes have gone 2-5 since uncorking the
tradition with a pair of victories against the Mighty Ducks. Not
when the building is 0-2 in potentially series-clinching games.
</P>
<P>
   Not when Grant Fuhr says it actually helps him see the puck.
</P>
<P>
   For a visual blizzard, the Whiteout is a big-time dud, yielding
results better suited for its cousin, the correctional fluid.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the reason for the lack of home ice advantage,
especially with all the attention given to the pomp and
circumstance?
</P>
<P>
   And just who are you, Arizona sports fan?
</P>
<P>
   You might not want to hear this, but you are becoming a national
curiosity. Across the country, people noticed that Randy Johnson
pitched before a sparse house in his first start at BOB. People
heard about Thom Brennaman's public scolding of Diamondbacks fans
during a recent telecast, a night when Brennaman was distraught
over fans leaving in the seventh inning of a nip-and-tuck affair.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be a big-time city, he said, you stay until the
end of the game.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be a big-time city, he said, you'd better start
acting like one.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is any great news flash. The Suns following is a
running joke in this city, a muted gaggle of gray-haired geese. The
Cardinals can't sell out Sun Devil Stadium unless they're in the
closing weeks of a playoff chase. Wells Fargo Arena is a morgue.
</P>
<P>
   And now it appears _ I can't believe I'm typing this _ that
every following needs a crash course in fanaticism from the
Rattlers backers and Mercury militia.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the Whiteout isn't loud. Rather, it underachieves.
It isn't rabid. It doesn't blow the roof off the building. It's not
what it could be.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, this might be a case of what comes first. Too often,
the Coyotes fall behind at home in a playoff game. Too often, they
fail to jump on an opponent. Too often, they take their own crowd
out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no denying this: On Friday night, there were
instances where the crowd could've been the lift the hockey team
needed. It could've been the sixth skater. And it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, Nikolai Khabibulin was pitching a shutout
and strung together an array of outstanding saves. A genuine hockey
town would've given a standing ovation after any one of those. In
overtime, the crowd was silent with dread. The crowd does fine with
scoreboard prompts, but not so well on instinct and initiative.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dilemma you might want to ponder if the Coyotes get
pummeled by the Blues this afternoon and come home with their tails
between their legs, forced to win Game 7 at home or watch the
entire organization blow up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's understood that on occasion, they fill you with
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Take the power play, please. It's so awful that people are
wondering why the coach can't fix it, and on Friday, it hit a new
low. The guys playing catch on the point were as far apart as they
could be, and the passes literally took seconds to arrive at the
other stick. The spacing was ridiculous, and let's hope it didn't
look that way on the Schoenfeld drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is, the owner is wondering about that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, a few Coyotes need to step up. Rick Tocchet is playing
like a warrior, but he is not looking like a premier player. For
the most part, this is not his fault. His line has been
unpredictable. Greg Adams has been injured. Robert Reichel has been
invisible, living up to his playoff reputation. And down below, Bob
Corkum has been winning faceoffs, but not much else.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the Whiteout isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   Next time it is called the most intimidating spectacle in
hockey, feel free to laugh. Or better yet, look in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Have they let you down once too often?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it the other way around? &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
