<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1168 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-     05-02 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOVE SEASON PERFECTLY FINE AS IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Just when things are running smoothly, someone always
thinks they could be better.
</P>
<P>
   This year's dove season is one of those things.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Game and Fish Commission instructed department
biologists to analyze possibilities for changing the season,
including full-day hunts in the second half of the first season.
Currently, the entire two weeks of the early season is composed of
half-day hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Tice Supplee, chief of the Game Branch, warned commissioners
that full-day hunts in the early season could result in an
additional dove harvest that could have an adverse effect in a
number of areas, including seasons in later years.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the dove population in Arizona was declining,
causing fewer hunters. Half-day hunts were instituted in 1989 to
spread the kill. After 10 years of half-day seasons, the dove and
hunter numbers have increased.
</P>
<P>
   States with full-day hunts in the early season are experiencing
dove population declines and may face restructuring their seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Since doves are migratory birds, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service sets the framework for dove seasons. The states develop
their seasons under that framework.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Shroufe, department director, told commissioners that a
decline of dove populations in this state for whatever reason could
cause Fish and Wildlife to restrict Arizona's options.
</P>
<P>
   Supplee said the numbers of dove hunters in the late '80s was
declining about 10,000 a year. The low was 48,000 in '88. After the
half-day regulation became effective in '89 and more doves were
available, she said, hunter numbers grew, too.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the number of hunters afield rose to 56,000. The dove
harvest in 1989 was about 570,000 mourning doves during the early
season but rose to more than 870,000 in 1996. The figure went from
170,000 in the second season of '89 to 610,000 in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' Supplee said, ``is that what Arizona
implements as a dove season structure will impact Arizona's dove
population and dove hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting on the direction of the commission, biologists cameup
with alternatives for the commission to review in June:
</P>
<P>
   Creating a juniors-only afternoon dove hunt statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Instituting afternoon-only hunts in specific units and areas
under a permit-like system.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing all-day hunts in Pinal County.
</P>
<P>
   Restructuring the early dove hunt statewide and allowing
half-day hunts during the first week of the season and full-day
during the second week.
</P>
<P>
   Junior hunters would be allowed to hunt doves in the mornings
under regular regulations. Then they could hunt the rest of the day
on the juniors-only provision.
</P>
<P>
   That way, they could hunt after school with parental
supervision. Supplee said that wouldn't likely decrease the
populations of doves by more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The commission obviously is attempting to raise recreational
opportunities for hunters while raising more revenue for the
department.
</P>
<P>
   The juniors-only rule may be OK. Who can resist a kid? But this
juniors-only hunting stuff is beginning to reach levels of
diminishing returns.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of hunters who made use of afternoon hunts in the
first season was low (about 20 percent). But that would mean a
substantial loss of doves that wouldn't have been taken with
morning-only hunts. Besides, there was no way to regulate hunter
activities in the afternoon. Then, too, research on these
alternatives would cost about $200,000 a year for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The old bromide, ``if it works, don't fix it,'' is completely
applicable.
</P>
<P>
   Why tweak something that's working well? Dove numbers have
increased, and so have dove hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Just leave a good thing alone. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com. via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
