<HEADLINE>
PINCH-HITTING IRKS JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Diamondbacks ace  &UR; Randy Johnson will spend extra
time in the batting cage, so he can finish the job on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   The big left-hander said he was disappointed Friday after being
lifted in the eighth inning for a pinch-hitter with the bases
loaded and two outs and the score tied at 2 against the Milwaukee
Brewers at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson left the clubhouse without talking to reporters. It was
his second straight strong effort, but a second straight
no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like ages since I got a win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When told it's only been a couple starts, Johnson repeated, ``It
feels like ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Saturday he wanted to talk to Manager  &UR; Buck
Showalter about the disappointment he felt of coming out for a
pinch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've got to get used to in this league,'' said
Johnson, who spent most of his career in the American League, where
a pitcher doesn't have to worry about coming out because he's not
producing at the plate. ``If I can help myself by hitting or
bunting, I'm out there still.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is 0 for 17.  &UR; Hanley Frias came in to hit for Johnson
and flied out. The Diamondbacks still won, 3-2, with a run in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he didn't like getting pinch-hit for, ``but that's
just me and my competitive nature, not wanting to come out of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want him any other way,'' Showalter said. ``Any
time you take Randy out of the game, it's tough. You have a better
chance winning a game with him pitching.'' &QL; 
Against odds &QL; 
With the Diamondbacks' facing left-handers the past few days,
left-handed hitting outfielder  &UR; Luis Gonzalez put his franchise
record 14-game hit streak on hold the past two games. He was back
in the lineup Saturday against a left-hander,  &UR; Jim Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is I don't want Gonzo to sit around for four
days,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who came in with a team-high .391 batting average, has
been platooning with  &UR; Bernard Gilkey, a right-handed hitter.
Showalter doesn't feel locked into that mind-set, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are very capable of hitting left- and right-handed
pitchers,'' Showalter said. &QL; 
Rooter buses &QL; 
Catcher  &UR; Damian Miller said he anticipated about 200 family members
and friends to arrive in ``bus loads'' for Saturday's game. Miller
grew up on the west side of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bona fide cheesehead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller tried to leave 12 tickets just for family Friday, but it
was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came early and already bought them,'' he said. &QL; 
Snake bits &QL; 
Right fielder  &UR; Tony Womack was a last-minute scratch from the
lineup Saturday. With an afternoon game and no clouds, Showalter
hinted that the sun could pose a problem for Womack, who, as he
says, is still learning on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks either set or tied 42 team records through the
first 24 games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
