A1173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      05-02 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets try to focus on here and now to get on track
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Hakeem Olajuwon has a suggestion, perhaps even a solution. But it
does not involve improving defense, or changing the offense. It's
not really about problems or such details, or what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   OlajuwonIt is, in fact, about nothing. Forget the playoffs, he
said. Forget the Lakers and home-court advantage. At this point,
after losses in five of the Rockets' past six games, he said their
only means to make the long climb back is moment by moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all we can think about now,'' Olajuwon said. ``The next
game, the next play.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult to argue. If the Rockets sent themselves
into this slide at the most inopportune time, just three
regular-season games before the start of the playoffs, with their
inability to prepare for the games considered beneath them, it
would seem no game is beneath them.
</P>
<P>
   This must include tonight's game against the Clippers, one of
the teams to have taken a win against the Rockets since the
collapse began. The way things are, there is little reason to
consider the playoffs such a happy thought to spend time thinking
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do is keep playing,'' Charles Barkley said.
``Hopefully things will turn around. I'm always confident. I don't
think you want to go into the playoffs struggling. I want to finish
up strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will tell you the truth, but I will. We have played
terrible. That's it. We played hard. We don't play smart. There's a
difference between playing hard and playing smart. We're not
playing very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Games like tonight's derailed the Rockets. But if the loss in
Los Angeles and two home losses to the Mavericks were embarrassing,
Friday's defeat to the Jazz, without the explanation of a lack of
motivation, seemed to show how far the Rockets are from
playoff-ready.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems suddenly seem too numerous to consider a quick
refresher course on everything a solution at hand. The slide might
have begun with lackadaisical defense, but it has included poor
shooting and sloppy execution on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rudy Tomjanovich laments the lack of execution in special
situations such as jump balls or last-second shots as a sign of
sporadic concentration. Barkley points toward inconsistent
production.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than try to fix everything, Tomjanovich considered
Olajuwon's proposal perhaps the best first step. He will address
the problems. But to get the concentration to where they can expect
to consistently improve in so many areas, Tomjanovich agreed a
renewed sense of urgency and immediacy might be needed most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it is. Here's the now,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I'm out
here. I have to play against this guy on this play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing about this deal is you have to get it done
now. While you're playing, this is it. This is why you get
trophies. Here's the play. Here it comes. I get it stopped. Or
here's the shot. Make it. That's why you get the trophies. It comes
down to basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   But lately, the Rockets have been putting out one fire, only to
have to move on to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make general statements (about what is wrong),''
Tomjanovich said. ``Early in the game (Friday's loss to the Jazz),
we came out frantic. We came down and flung up the first shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called timeout and let them know we didn't really come to
play. `We're not into the meat of the game. Let's trust each other.
Be a team.' And then we did. We played defense and tied the score.
Then we didn't play smart basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those things have to be corrected to be good in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   But before then the Rockets might have to play well tonight. If
each loss has sent them further from playoff form with the playoffs
fast approaching, a home loss to the Clippers would seem even more
devastating than even the losses that have brought the Rockets to
this point.
</P>
<P>
   But with a team meeting Friday and Saturday's practice, the
Rockets have at least decided they can turn their season back
around, unless they turn on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much have to forget about everything and worry about
my own game,'' Barkley said. ``I know what I have to do and I have
to do it. I can't worry about everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody spends so much time worrying about everybody else,
nobody says, `You know what, I stink.' I'm willing to say it.
Nobody else around here is willing to say it. Coach addressed that.
Everybody always blames somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   And since the Rockets still believe they can solve their
problems and become a playoff force despite the losses of the past
two weeks, they certainly would be ready to believe it should they
finish the season with wins over the Clippers, Timberwolves and
Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy always says we have to stick together and believe as a
team,'' guard Brent Price said. ``The only way to get it back is to
start doing it on the court. We can talk about it, point to the
problems and try to change things, but until we start playing and
doing it on the court, it wouldn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't take long, either. A game or two to start doing it
on the court and everybody starts feeling it again. Definitely we
can turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   If that faith has not been lost by now, it might be unshakable _
if things change fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe,'' forward Scottie Pippen said. ``I think we
have what it takes with a whole-hearted effort. We have to have
everyone dedicated to this team to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be willing to do what it takes, whether it's diving
on the floor for a loose ball or taking a hard foul. We've got to
show we want this team to succeed. And if it all fails, then hey,
we gave it the best we had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
