<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE IN THE NEST  
 ORIOLES TRADE ANGRY WORDS WITH MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mess keeps getting worse with each passing day in Baltimore
and no end seems in sight. Manager Ray Miller's team meeting to
clear the air on Tuesday lasted 35 minutes and turned into a
free-for-all in which manager, coaches and players all made
critical statements about each other.
</P>
<P>
   It came one day after Miller went into a post-game tirade
against the players while reporters were in his office. That night,
Miller severely bruised his hand by slamming his fist into a brick
wall. He then went on to rip the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention was to unload my feelings and see what feelings I
got back,'' Miller said of the meeting. ``I certainly did not
apologize for what I said. It was about being accountable. I've got
to sit here every day and be accountable, and I'll do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also as a player, I think you have to do the same thing. We
had a very good meeting, a very responsible meeting. Everybody had
their say, and hopefully it will do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Most players agreed with Miller's assessment. Owner Peter
Angelos, who picked Miller as his manager after letting Davey
Johnson walk away, has remained silent on the matter. Rookie
General Manager Frank Wren wants to make a managerial change,
several sources said, but there is a question as to how well
Angelos and Wren are getting along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the mistakes that have been made so far are by the
players,'' Orioles designated hitter Harold Baines said in a rare
moment of expression from one of the quietest human beings on the
planet. ``But you don't single out any one player, and we haven't.
You lose as a team and you win as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray can only do so much. It's up to us. It starts with every
individual going out to do his best job, and being prepared for
each game. I'm not saying we weren't prepared, but when you're
losing, every little thing gets magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   Some believe Angelos is simply waiting until after Monday's
exhibition game against Cuba to drop the hatchet on Miller, who has
gained respect by becoming so defiant in the wake of an obvious
firing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ownership that we have here knows he can do anything any
time he wants,'' Miller said. ``I expect him to. But as long as I'm
here, I expect to manage the club and do my job right. I'm not
happy about (our record), but if I'd had it, I wouldn't be here.
I'm certainly financially set. If I didn't want to be here, I
wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   One other side note. Cal Ripken Jr.'s back condition has not
improved and he may be thinking about surgery. The 19-year veteran
needs 117 hits to reach 3,000, which is 162 more than Lou Gehrig
wound up with. Ripken has not ruled out retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still gathering information, so I can't even say what I'm
trying to decide,'' said Ripken, who must know by the All-Star
break whether the Orioles are picking up the $6.3 million option on
his 2000 season or buying it out for $2.5 million. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
Name the pitcher with the lowest winning percentage in major league
history? Note: A minimum of 275 career decisions is needed to make
this list. &QL; 
Plenty of seats available &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in baseball are franchises suffering more at the gate
than in Oakland, Montreal and Chicago's south side, where the White
Sox have the worst average attendance of the 30 big league clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox are projected to draw fewer than 1.3 million fans
this season. This is a club that watched 2.6 million file into the
new Comiskey Park as recently as 1993. The plight of the White Sox
was evidenced last week, when a total of 36,471 watched three ames
against Detroit while the Cubs drew 39,265 for their Sunday game
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hit bottom,'' White Sox vice president of marketing Rob
Gallas said. ``But I've been here 10 years and this is as positive
an atmosphere as I've seen (because of the young players). We look
at this as a process that's going to take time.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Montreal, there is a strong belief that the Expos
are playing their final season in Canada, probably headed to
Washington, D.C., next year and eventually to a new stadium in
northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   On the other coast in Oakland, a franchise that drew more than 2
million fans from 1988 to '93, is at a point where midweek crowds
are consistently under 10,000 and the players are getting angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sucks,'' Athletics first baseman Jason Giambi said. ``It's
kind of depressing. We're out here playing hard. And it's not like
we're a bad team. It's sad we can't get more people out here. This
team and this organization have done everything from commercials to
community service, every angle that you could possibly have to get
people in the seats. And it still doesn't work.'' &QL; 
Childish behavior &QL; 
Pittsburgh pitcher Jason Schmidt and outfielder Turner Ward could
find themselves in serious trouble if major league baseball
security director Kevin Hallinan is true to his word.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Hallinan said baseball ``will prosecute users of
laser pointers (because) those things are dangerous for fans and
players.''
</P>
<P>
   They're also dangerous for a photographer with a camera, which
is exactly where Schmidt and Ward had their pointers fixed during a
game, San Diego Padres team photographer Joel Zwink said.
</P>
<P>
   Zwink said the two Pirates had their lasers pointed directly
into his camera lens. The 44-year-old photographer experienced
blurry vision and immediately left the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still blurry,'' Zwink said days later. ``I saw Schmidt do
it. Others saw Ward. I just want to get my eyes straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, who last year sent an e-mail bomb to a reporter that
dropped 500 pieces of junk mail in an electronic mailbox, and Ward
have refused to comment on the allegation. The National League has
not taken any action. One only wonders what the league would have
done if a fan were guilty of the same actions. &QL; 
Making it count &QL; 
Texas shortstop Royce Clayton not only talks the talk, but he also
walks the walk. Rather than simply prattle about what an important
person Jackie Robinson was, Clayton is backing it up with a
concrete move.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley resident donated $100,000 for an endowed scholarship
to the Jackie Robinson Foundation. A Chicago resident attending
Washington University in St. Louis is the first recipient of
Clayton's goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what Jackie Robinson stood for,'' said Clayton, who is
no publicity-seeker and genuinely wants to help. ``He created an
opportunity for me. I feel it's an obligation for me to keep it
going. Hopefully, other (players) will follow. I'm sure my peers
will follow suit.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As of today, it's a virtual dead heat between the former
Washington Senator Pedro Ramos and current Texas Ranger Mike
Morgan. Ramos was 117-160 during his career, giving him a winning
percentage of .42238. Morgan is 125-171 in his career, which
translates into a .42229 percentage and gives him the current
ranking of biggest loser in the game. Of course, a victory in
Morgan's next start will push Ramos back to the top _ or bottom,
depending on how it's viewed _ of this list. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
The new city of brotherly love: The Cleveland Indians were 8-0
entering the weekend when the Alomar brothers, Roberto and Sandy,
each had a hit in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   The X-Cub factor at work?: The last time the Chicago Cubs had
six pitchers on the disabled list at one time, they finished 23{
games out of first place in 1985, one season after they advanced to
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Flashback: Don Money.
</P>
<P>
   What did you expect, sugary marshmallows?: Baltimore right
fielder Albert Belle will begin marketing his own cereal flakes.
Coming with no surprise whatsoever, the flakes are plain. Just like
Belle himself, there will be no frills.
</P>
<P>
   He can't be slipping this much this quickly, can he?: Cleveland
shortstop Omar Vizquel, a six-time Gold Glove winner, already has
committed five errors, the same number he had in 151 games last
season.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of staying put for a while?: For the first time in the 14
seasons Toronto's Jim Fregosi has been a major league manager, he
is not renting and has purchased a home in the city in which he
works. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Brian Bohanon, acquired as a free agent over the winter, is the
first Colorado Rockies pitcher to start a season with a 4-0 record.
Bohanon and Darryl Kile were the only Rockies starters to have a
victory entering the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Harold Baines was a designated hitter for the
1,428th game in his career Friday night, surpassing Hal McRae for
the major league record. Even at 40, Baines is batting near .300.
</P>
<P>
   Florida reliever Archie Corbin managed to etch his way into the
record book when he became the 30th pitcher to have four strikeouts
in one inning. Corbin had the chance for a fourth strikeout after
Cubs catcher Tyler Houston reached base after swinging at a wild
pitch on a third strike.
</P>
<P>
   After last week's trade between Cleveland and San Francisco that
netted the Giants reliever Jerry Spradlin, it can be noted that San
Francisco has traded with Cleveland for six relievers in the past
four years. The others: Julian Tavarez, Joe Roa, Jose Mesa, Jim
Poole, and Al Morman. Also, the Giants have Alan Embree, another
former Indians reliever, whom they acquired from the Diamondbacks
over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City outfielder Johnny Damon's consecutive games streak,
which was in jeopardy because of his wife's impending birth of
twins, remains intact after she delivered the boy and girl during a
day off last week. Entering Saturday's game, Damon had played in
180 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins trailed in 54 consecutive innings before
Torii Hunter belted a grand slam in the fourth inning of Monday's
victory over Boston. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
The Diamondbacks are not that interested in trading Brian Anderson.
Several general managers who have inquired about Anderson have been
told the price is high because Arizona is holding on to Anderson as
insurance against Armando Reynoso, who struggled badly in his last
outing and twice has been moved in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Brian Hunter has been traded to Seattle, Detroit
Manager Larry Parrish is strongly considering moving right fielder
Bobby Higginson into the leadoff spot. The only time Higginson held
down the leadoff spot, in 1996, he hit .421 (53 for 126) with 13
home runs, 34 RBI and a .500 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's arrival in Seattle has created a problem in the
outfield that can only be solved by getting rid of one of the other
three on the roster _ Butch Huskey, John Mabry or Matt Mieske. Look
for one of those to be traded, released, waived or sold soon.
Hunter is the 63rd left fielder to play alongside Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is quietly shopping Tavarez. The Giants called
Anaheim last week and have made similar calls to a handful of other
clubs. Tavarez has lost his role as San Francisco's primary setup
man to closer Robb Nen.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Reggie Jefferson has returned from the disabled list
and Boston's $26 million investment, Jose Offerman, has moved to
second base, Jeff Frye is wondering what will become of him? Frye
is not above asking to be traded, a point he may make very soon.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets are looking to add a starting pitcher. The
addition of Rick Reed once his foot heals will force Mets Manager
Bobby Valentine to choose between Masato Yoshii and Allen Watson as
the fifth starter. Neither one excites the Mets very much. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandPlayed in front of its 300th consecutive home sellout.
 &QL; 
2. NY YankeesJoe Torre is on his way back and the Yanks couldn't be
playing better.  &QL; 
3. San FranciscoEntered the weekend with an 8-4 record since Barry
Bonds' injury.  &QL; 
4. AtlantaHas won three when trailing in the ninth; had two such
wins last year.  &QL; 
5. HoustonShowed D-Backs they still have a ways to go before
entering elite status.  &QL; 
6. NY MetsWithout question, the best bullpen in baseball.  &QL; 
7. TexasStill trying to catch up to its nemesis, the Yankees.  &QL; 
8. St. LouisDid not lose consecutive games until Wednesday and
Thursday.  &QL; 
9. Los AngelesRaul Mondesi is in a fit about being dropped in the
lineup. BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. BaltimoreWhatever happened to the Oriole Way of pitching and
defense?  &QL; 
29. FloridaEntered the weekend without posting back-to-back wins
this season.  &QL; 
28. MontrealThe 2-11 start at home is the worst in the franchise's
31-year history.  &QL; 
27. OaklandIf a game is lost but no one shows up to watch, did the
A's really lose?  &QL; 
26. MinnesotaRookie pitchers are finding life is not so easy in the
majors.  &QL; 
25. Kansas CityPitcher Kevin Appier is grumbling louder about
wanting out.  &QL; 
24. MilwaukeeSlumping Marquis Grissom was dropped from No. 2 to No.
6 in lineup.  &QL; 
23. DetroitIs center fielder Gabe Kapler the next budding
superstar?  &QL; 
22. San DiegoLost a ninth-inning lead for the first time since July
1996. ON THE RISE &QL; 
Chicago White Sox: These White Sox seem intent on showing they are
not the dregs they are supposed to be, at least not at this stage
of the season. Rookie pitcher John Snyder has a 1.88 ERA and young
outfielder Magglio Ordonez seems to be living up to the advance
billing he received two years ago. Leading the early resurgence is
Frank Thomas, who not only was batting .381 before this weekend's
series at Anaheim but also seemed reinvigorated with what's going
on. ``This a young club now, but I'm having fun with these guys.
I've been on a lot better teams talentwise. Twenty games do not
make a season, but I think we've got something going.'' &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
Boston Red Sox: After starting the season 6-1, the Red Sox have
been in an offensive funk that has led to a slide in the standings.
Boston entered the weekend series 5-9 since the hot start. The Red
Sox went through a skid of scoring two or fewer runs in seven of
eight games. Boston had only 15 home runs before the weekend
series, six of those came from Troy O'Leary. Without offense, all
that great pitching is going to waste. Winning two of three from
Cleveland was erased after losing two of three to Minnesota before
this weekend's series at Oakland. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
WSB-AM (Atlanta) radio engineer Dave Baker describing the
slow-footed Greg Maddux's first career triple in a game last
weekend: ``It replaced the Kentucky Derby as the most exciting two
minutes in sports.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
San Francisco rookie Joe Nathan has made quite an impression since
making his big league debut on April 21, a game in which he threw
seven scoreless innings in a 4-0 victory over Florida. ``Best debut
I've seen since Fernando (Valenzuela),'' Giants pitching coach Ron
Perranoski said. Nathan's name came up throughout spring training
when opposing managers were left scratching their heads wondering
where this kid with a 97-mph fastball came from. He is 2-0 with a
1.20 ERA in his first two starts. Nathan, who started only 33 minor
league games before his promotion, did not start pitching until
1997. ``I caught Kerry Wood's first outing,'' said former Cubs
catcher Scott Servais, now with the Giants, ``and obviously, Joe's
results were better than Kerry's.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
