<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1183 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-GRIZZLIES-AZ     05-02 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-GRIZZLIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOPSIDED WIN CLINCHES PLAYOFF BERTH FOR SUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Suns came to America West Arena Saturday night
looking to clinch their 11th consecutive playoff berth with a
victory over the Vancouver Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   For most of three quarters, however, it appeared the only thing
clinched might be the Suns' throats by the team with the league's
worst record. In the end, though, it was the Grizzlies who were
throttled, 107-77.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns used a torrid 35-5 fourth-quarter blitz to bury the
Grizzlies and wrap up a playoff berth. With two games remaining,
including one tonight in Sacramento, the Suns could still finish
anywhere from sixth to eighth in the Western Conference race. And
whichever of those positions they finish in, they could play either
Utah, Portland or San Antonio in a five-game, first-round playoff
series.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Suns Coach Danny Ainge said he would try to
win the last two games and finish sixth but also hoped to find some
rest for some of his key players _ particularly point guard Jason
Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have the No. 6 seed,'' Ainge said. ``We want to
play as well as we can in the last two, but at the same time, my
No. 1 priority is to make sure we're going to be healthy and fresh
_ but not rusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said his regulars still would play substantial minutes,
but he would cut them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want somebody to shoot me if Jason Kidd plays 45 minutes,''
Ainge said, then added, ``unless we're in a double-overtime or
something. I've got to cut myself a little slack.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge hopes to get Tom Gugliotta completely healthy from a sore
knee and calf, Luc Longley healed from a hyperextended knee, Rex
Chapman rested and healed from a fractured eye socket and _ most
important _ Kidd rested from sore knees and a sprained wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're going to try to win the last two games,''
said Gugliotta, who led the Suns with 24 points and 12 rebounds.
``Jason has been playing 48 minutes a game all season. Cliff
(Robinson) has been playing a lot of minutes. But we just need to
play better so nobody has to play 45 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Good point. The Suns could have gotten a lot of rest Saturday
night had they played a lot more efficiently in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   They jumped out to a 19-10 lead, and maybe it just came too
easily. Because as quickly as the Suns built it, they let it slip
away.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's Shareef Abdur-Rahim hit an 18-foot jump shot to
start a 12-2 Grizzlies run, and the game was on.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns sputtered in the second quarter and trailed at the
half, 42-40, despite shooting 54 percent while yielding just 41
percent shooting to the Grizzlies. The equalizer was 12 Phoenix
turnovers that led to 14 points for the Grizzlies and the halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies hung close through the third quarter and trailed
by only four points going to the fourth. But a team that loses 40
games in a 50-game season is never far from collapse.
</P>
<P>
   And the Grizzlies went quietly into that good night, escorted by
Suns' sharpshooter George McCloud, who hit back-to-back three-point
shots to start the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm supposed to do, right?'' McCloud said,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   That pushed the Phoenix lead to 10 points, and the Grizzlies
were convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened it up, went up by 10 and the more we opened it up,
you could just see with every shot we hit that they lost a little
more,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a nice way of saying the Grizzlies called it a night.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns outscored 35-5 before the reserves came off the bench
to finish off a 38-12 quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And although it wasn't their best performance, there were things
to like about it.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman played with goggles to protect his injured eye, hated
them but scored 20 points on six of 11 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awkward,'' Chapman said of the goggles. ``It seemed
like, peripherally, I couldn't see very well. And I threw a couple
of passes into the bleachers.''
</P>
<P>
   McCloud scored 14 points off the bench, hitting three of seven
three-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   And Kidd had 14 points and 13 rebounds despite the sore wrist,
which was apparently injured in a fall at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough season for us,'' Kidd said. ``We're in the
playoffs now, but we can't come out and play these last two games
like it's spring break.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
