r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-MALONE-AZR &LR;      05-02 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-MALONE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA: MALONE MEANT NO HARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The blows have been delivered and the surgeons have
completed the stitching, but the words still flow like bad blood.
</P>
<P>
   Charge, countercharge and questions about the NBA's role remain
in the wake of a collision Monday night in which Utah forward Karl
Malone left Suns center Joe Kleine badly bloodied.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Thorn, NBA vice president of operations, said Saturday that
his office decided to take no action against Malone because there
was no evidence of intent.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn said he reviewed the tape several times and also spoke to
Malone and Kleine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malone had both hands on the ball and when he turned to shoot,
Joe was there,'' Thorn said at halftime of the Suns-Vancouver game
Saturday at America West Arena. ``Obviously, from Joe's standpoint,
he thought (Malone) led with his elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Suns Coach Danny Ainge said the NBA should have punished Malone,
who was shoved by Kleine as the Suns backup center left the floor
and headed for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty stitches were needed to sew together gaping wounds in the
face and mouth of Kleine, who has declined comment for the print
media. However, Kleine has ripped Malone on Phoenix radio shows.
Apparently, he doesn't want the printed word to reach Malone and
provide him with bulletin board motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge also said the NBA is practicing a double standard. Last
year, Malone was fined $5,000 for throwing an elbow that knocked
out Spurs center David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   In the Robinson knockout, videotape clearly shows Malone
swinging his elbows from side to side. The same thing is not
evident in tapes of the Malone-Kleine incident.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was the league's Most Valuable Player in 1995. He's a
star; Kleine is a journeyman. If Malone had bloodied an established
star instead of Kleine on Monday, would the NBA have penalized him?
</P>
<P>
   Thorn said no.
</P>
<P>
   He said the NBA treats each incident independently. He pointed
out that New York Knicks center Patrick Ewing, also an acknowledged
star, was suspended for Game 7 of an Eastern Conference playoff
series against the Miami Heat two years ago. Ewing was involved in
a brawl in Game 5 of the series, which the Knicks lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you might imagine, that was extremely controversial in New
York,'' said Thorn, who was at America West Arena to present the
Gold Whistle, an officiating award, to longtime NBA referee and
Phoenix native Tommy Nunez.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn said he shares Ainge's concern about Malone's evident lack
of remorse for several collisions that have resulted in injuries to
opposing players. Suns center Luc Longley suffered a hyperextended
knee earlier this season. Several years ago, Eliott Perry, then a
Suns guard, was knocked unconscious by a Malone elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me, yes,'' Thorn said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the NBA has no rules prohibiting bad manners.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Malone ripped Ainge Friday night before a Utah
victory in Houston. He referred to an infamous moment in Ainge's
playing days in Boston when he was bitten by Atlanta's Wayne
``Tree'' Rollins. But Malone misplaced the bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I didn't bite anybody _ like him,'' Malone told the
``Salt Lake Tribune.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone went on to compare Ainge to beavers that populate creeks
near his home in Summerfield, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both use their teeth the same way _ to chew things up,''
Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge countered with a reference to Sybil. A couple of days ago,
he said Malone was as undependable as the character with many
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was weak,'' Ainge said. ``Come on, Sybil.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
