<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1186 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POW-RAMIREZ-1stld-wri     05-02 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POW-RAMIREZ-1stld-writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POW'S MOTHER ANTICIPATES TEARFUL REUNION WITH SON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Updating with confirmation of release.) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hailing the Rev. Jesse Jackson as a hero, Vivian
Ramirez glowed with hope as she thanked Jackson for securing the
release of her son, Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, from his Serbian
captors.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson announced Saturday that he had successfully brokered the
release of Ramirez, 24, of East Los Angeles, Spc. Steven M.
Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, and Staff Sgt. Christopher J.
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., who were captured a month ago
while patrolling the Yugoslavia-Macedonia border.
</P>
<P>
   Following Jackson's announcement, the Pentagon confirmed that
the three POWs are expected to be released. At about 10:50 p.m.
Pacific Daylight Time the three men were released to Jackson by the
Serb government of Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lifesaver,'' Vivian Ramirez said during a press
conference held outside the police headquarters in the eastern
suburb of Baldwin Park on Saturday afternoon. ``He will be my hero
when he brings my !italics!mijo!end italics! home and I thank
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez received a call at about noon Saturday from the U.S.
Army confirming Jackson's successful mission. Her ``little Andy''
was finally coming home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy now,'' said Ramirez, sporting a T-shirt
emblazoned with her son's image and pinned with a yellow ribbon.
``It seems like this time we're really going to go (to Germany).''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, of Baldwin Park, spent the evening awaiting the green
light from the U.S. Army to fly to Germany where she planned to
reunite with her son at a military base. She was to be accompanied
by her son Steven Ramirez, a Los Angeles police detective, her
former husband, Andrew M. Ramirez, her daughter Nadine Ramirez, and
Nadine Ramirez's 5-month-old daughter, Vanessa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we see him that's when it will really hit us,'' Nadine
Ramirez said as she cradled her daughter. ``Right now we're just
hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   In the East Los Angeles neighborhood where Andrew Ramirez was
raised, a fresh wave of well-wishers sporting yellow ribbons showed
up throughout the morning with candles and letters to place outside
his home. Friends and relatives remained cautiously hopeful, but
thankful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable. We really can't express our happy
emotions,'' said Maria Rios, 39, a childhood friend of Andrew
Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very uplifting, it was positive,'' said Robert Carcano,
who is Andrew Ramirez's second cousin. ``Until the official word
comes out, obviously there will be cause for celebration. I'm sure
there will be one heck of a block party.''
</P>
<P>
   The serviceman's father declined to comment but spent part of
Saturday on his front porch with his sisters and cousins arranging
yellow ribbons and POW buttons in plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Andrew M. Ramirez) feels that until he receives official word
from the government that his son has been released into the arms of
the United States, then he'll be satisfied,'' said Carcano, 42, a
police officer.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Vivian Ramirez said she would do when she saw
her son is cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll hug him and I will not let go and tell him how much I
love him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When she first heard of Jackson's breakthrough, Ramirez couldn't
believe it and said it didn't seem real until she received
confirmation from Maj. Don Dunne, an Army reservist based in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know that maybe it's definite,'' she said. ``I pray that
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said she hadn't planned to pack her bags until she
received word Saturday because she didn't want to get her hopes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would have been depressed looking at my bag,'' she
said. ``Today I will pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the media frenzy that has surrounded the capture of the
three American soldiers, Ramirez said she didn't think her son
would view himself as a celebrity, describing him as shy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a home-cooked meal, the first thing she would
probably do for her son when he arrives home is take him to his
favorite fast-food hamburger joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``His favorite is In-N-Out. He'll say, Forget your dinner,'' she
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Though the past month has been filled with anguish, Ramirez said
she took each day one step at a time.
</P>
<P>
   When she saw her son in a CNN-televised interview shown Friday
from Yugoslavia, Ramirez said she was encouraged. Her son looked
thinner but healthy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and son wrote to each other in the past month. In a
letter she told him how his neighborhood was pulling for him, how
Los Angeles residents had strung yellow ribbons across the city,
how letters poured in from all over the world encouraging Vivian
Ramirez to remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ramirez in turn told his mother that he was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he's doing a lot of praying, (that) he misses us, he
loves us and he can hardly wait to come home and see us,'' Vivian
Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Once her son returns, Ramirez said she was unsure what his plans
would be. Next May, Andrew Ramirez will have completed his
commitment to the army. He originally was supposed to serve two
years, but will have served a total of seven years in the army,
Vivian Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to him, he only has a few more months,'' she said,
adding that his goal is to join the Los Angeles Police Department.
``He wants to be an officer like his brother.''
</P>
<P>
   When Andrew Ramirez arrives home to Los Angeles he'll find the
messages of people like Sandra Dominguez nearby Downey who wrote a
special note for him and hand-delivered it to his father's home
Saturday by placing it under a candle outside the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome home, Andy. So glad you're coming home. Our prayers
have been with you,'' read the letter, which Dominguez said she
wrote on behalf of her sister, a Navy reservist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit close to home when it happened,'' said Dominguez, 24,
accompanied by her parents, Armando and Rose Menchaca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully they will all be coming home safe,'' Armando
Menchaca said. ``That's what we're all hoping will be the bottom
line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
