favorite fast-food hamburger joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``His favorite is In-N-Out. He'll say, Forget your dinner,'' she
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Though the past month has been filled with anguish, Ramirez said
she took each day one step at a time.
</P>
<P>
   When she saw her son in a CNN-televised interview shown Friday
from Yugoslavia, Ramirez said she was encouraged. Her son looked
thinner but healthy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and son wrote to each other in the past month. In a
letter she told him how his neighborhood was pulling for him, how
Los Angeles residents had strung yellow ribbons across the city,
how letters poured in from all over the world encouraging Vivian
Ramirez to remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ramirez in turn told his mother that he was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he's doing a lot of praying, (that) he misses us, he
loves us and he can hardly wait to come home and see us,'' Vivian
Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Once her son returns, Ramirez said she was unsure what his plans
would be. Next May, Andrew Ramirez will have completed his
commitment to the army. He originally was supposed to serve two
years, but will have served a total of seven years in the army,
Vivian Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to him, he only has a few more months,'' she said,
adding that his goal is to join the Los Angeles Police Department.
``He wants to be an officer like his brother.''
</P>
<P>
   When Andrew Ramirez arrives home to Los Angeles he'll find the
messages of people like Sandra Dominguez nearby Downey who wrote a
special note for him and hand-delivered it to his father's home
Saturday by placing it under a candle outside the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome home, Andy. So glad you're coming home. Our prayers
have been with you,'' read the letter, which Dominguez said she
wrote on behalf of her sister, a Navy reservist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit close to home when it happened,'' said Dominguez, 24,
accompanied by her parents, Armando and Rose Menchaca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully they will all be coming home safe,'' Armando
Menchaca said. ``That's what we're all hoping will be the bottom
line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
