A1192 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     05-02 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERCIVAL LETS ONE GET AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Troy Percival pitching the ninth inning with a lead.
The Angels' chances of extending their winning streak to four games
looked pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of preserving the victory for Chuck Finley on
Saturday night, Percival was rocked for two homers and five runs in
an 8-5 loss to the Chicago White Sox in front of 35,296 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Percival, one of the game's premier closers, had not blown a
save opportunity this season, but his 95-mph fastball has been
missing since opening night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no excuses,'' he said. ``I didn't put the ball where
I want it. I always want the ball in that spot. I want to be back
out there tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   In Percival's third game in four nights, Greg Norton opened the
ninth by pulling a 2-1 fastball into the right-field stands. Five
batters later, Ray Durham drove a three-run homer to right. The
winning streak and Percival were done. The five runs were the most
he has allowed in one outing in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``A game like this happens to every closer,'' manager Terry
Collins said. ``From the side where I sit, you can't tell what he
has. But he has been throwing great. He is our guy in that spot.
Once in a while it doesn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival, who earned a save in Friday's 3-1 victory over
Chicago, spoiled Finley's performance, which at the time was the
game's highlight. The left-hander went seven innings and gave the
Angels the kind of performance they'll need if they want to win the
American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted that game for Chuck,'' Collins said. ``He
missed most of spring training (tendinitis), but now he is rounding
into form. We wanted to go seven and he did that. We wanted about
110 pitches from him and we got that (106).''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt the team will hit, even without injured Jim
Edmonds for the next three months. Even when Mo Vaughn goes 0 for 4
with two strikeouts as he did Saturday. But an erratic starting
rotation has been a trouble spot and Finley's 6.85 ERA coming in
was part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Against Chicago, he allowed eight hits and three runs as the
Angels were chasing White Sox starter James Baldwin. Shigetoshi
Hasegawa pitched a scoreless eighth and began an inning-ending
double play after Durham bounced sharply back to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   But then came Percival.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was quick to point out the fly-ball single by Darrin
Jackson that Tim Salmon did not pick up in right. Pinch-hitter Jeff
Liefer also drove in a run with a broken-bat bloop-single to left.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no denying the ball Durham drove into the
right-field stands on an 0-1 count.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad pitch,'' Percival said. ``I have to make
that pitch, not put it right over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last six games, Durham has four home runs and 11 RBI. His
five RBI was a career high and made a winner out of David Lundquist
(1-0). Bob Howry pitched the ninth for his seventh save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the same pitch on the first one and I should have hit it
out then,'' Durham said. ``I was just trying to stay out of the
double play that would have ended the game.''
</P>
<P>
   During the feel-good portion of the game, Garret Anderson had
three hits and Randy Velarde had a home run and RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Troy Glaus had two hits and ignited a critical
two-run rally in the fifth against Baldwin. Glaus, who is batting
.345, had two doubles and still has not gone more than a game
without a hit this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
