A1257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTON-ACCORDS03-COX     05-02 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTON-ACCORDS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Word 'Dayton' is reinvented yet again
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It seems like ever since war broke out between
NATO and Yugoslavia, the reputation of the Dayton Peace Accords has
deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas once the word ``Dayton'' was most typically a positive
one in the context of international relations, it now often has a
negative vibe. Whereas once it was a symbol of peace and successful
diplomacy, now it is a symbol of failed hopes, of how not to do
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Repeat Dayton's Mistakes in Kosovo'' was the headline on
an opinion piece in The Wall Street Journal. That complaint is from
the Bosnian ambassador to the United Nations, who _ in the last
paragraph of the piece _ embraces ``the spirit and letter'' of
``Dayton,'' but laments lack of enforcement of its provision for
resettlement of war refugees, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Other people worry that the United States is heading toward
another expensive, endless commitment in Kosovo just like the one
in Bosnia resulting from ``Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   And some (including the Bosnian ambassador), complain that
``Dayton'' legitimized the rule of Yugoslavian president/war
criminal Slobodan Milosevic by allowing him to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Still others complain that ``Dayton'' is a failure because the
people of Bosnia have not really reconciled; bitter divisions
prevail, along with political instability. Critics say this
situation should not be called peace.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's another group _ apolitical people who can't cite
any of the specifics of ``Dayton'' _ for whom the word represents
failure because it was supposed to have resolved the problems of
the former Yugoslavia, and yet here we are.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is pretty strange. After all, the Dayton peace talks
were (ITAL) not (END ITAL) supposed to solve the problems of the
former Yugoslavia. The talks were limited to Bosnia; the accords
never mention Kosovo. Everybody at the talks knew the Kosovo issue
was looming.
</P>
<P>
   But just bringing peace to Bosnia seemed a mightily ambitious
undertaking at the time. It was a three-sided war that had gone on
for years without a winner. Each side was claiming territory deep
within territories generally held by another side. Myriad peace
initiatives had flopped miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Yet peace, defined as an end to the fighting (a pretty good
definition), was achieved. And it has been sustained. To point out
that the animosities still prevail is to make all the more clear
what a remarkable achievement ``Dayton'' was. What would be the big
deal about making peace where brotherly love prevails?
</P>
<P>
   As for President Milosevic, what was the alternative to dealing
with him? The leaders of the Bosnian Serbs _ that is, the leaders
of the Serb side within Bosnia _ were formally indicted war
criminals. And, anyway, he was essentially their boss. How peace
would have been achieved without him is hard to see.
</P>
<P>
   As for the expense to the West of keeping the peace, it is not
oppressive. The United States has about 8,000 troops there. It used
to have 300,000 in Germany; 50,000 in Korea. For decades.
</P>
<P>
   The community of Dayton has a certain interest in ``Dayton's''
standing in the world. Obviously, being part of the international
vocabulary for good is better than being part of it for bad
(Munich).
</P>
<P>
   But the fate of any of the 2 million people of Kosovo is more
important than the aura surrounding the word ``Dayton.'' What's
important about the currently fashionable bashing of ``Dayton'' is
this: If, somehow, achieving an unlikely peace through tough
negotiations and the commitment of an affordable number of
peacekeeping troops has become a bad thing because the negotiations
left problems unsolved, the future of peace is not good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
