A1258 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX     05-02 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voucher support in Texas has spooky quality to it
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Lt. Gov. Rick Perry is beyond the pale. A pet
project for which he yanked every chain appears to be dead and
beyond his incantation.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe in mediums and channeling, maybe you can still
conjure a chance for school vouchers in this session. Anything's
possible. But it's very unlikely, and for a good reason: Genuine
support for vouchers, touted to be miles wide, proves to be less
than a thousandth of a milimeter thick. Indeed, it's so filmy as to
exist largely in a spirit world, in the specter of James Leininger.
</P>
<P>
   Leininger is the San Antonio physician who made millions
developing hospital beds and whose interests last year pumped
millions of dollars to candidates supporting vouchers, including a
$1 million loan to Perry for crucial ads in the closing days of his
neck-and-neck race with Democrat John Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Leininger founded an organization that went right after a public
school district, Edgewood ISD in San Antonio, offering $4,000
vouchers to 13,000 students. Of those, 835 accepted and left.
(Forty-one later would return.) The rest said ``keep your money.''
</P>
<P>
   One Waco voucher supporter who's worked with Leininger asserts
that commentators have demonized a mild-mannered and decent man.
Voucher foes beg dispensation for angry words, pointing out that no
one has done more than Leininger and his mass mailings to demonize
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Though vouchers appear dead this session, Leininger's money
walks the Capitol with the sound of clinking bones.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of an ethereal being, I do believe that's what Rick
Perry became when the issue of vouchers was raised on the campaign
trail. He wanted to downplay the subject, sort of like George Bush
and abortion. He said, ``I won't do anything to hurt public
schools,'' and then would shift the conversation to reading
teachers or some such.
</P>
<P>
   Perry didn't conceal his support for vouchers. He just slipped
on the soft shoes. Last week reports had Perry changing from soft
to steel-toed. A Senate coalition had the votes to prevent the
two-thirds support needed to bring Sen. Teel Bivins' voucher bill
to the floor. Bivins retreated from a pilot project involving the
state's six largest metropolitan school districts. He scaled it
down to involve two school districts chosen by the state education
commissioner. Opponents wouldn't budge. It wasn't the project's
size they opposed. It was vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Strategy next shifted to an effort, reportedly led by Perry, to
attach a voucher amendment to the school funding bill, which
included pay raises for teachers. Would Senate voucher foes cave if
teacher pay was at stake? Absolutely not. Not only that, but the
state's two largest teachers associations said they'd prefer
spiking the pay-raise bill if it were contaminated by a voucher
pilot. The legisation was approved without a voucher amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Should we be amazed that an issue Perry soft-pedaled on the
campaign trail assumed hard-ball significance to him in office? No.
It was that way all along. That's why Leininger put his money on
the man. Perry knew the volatility of the school voucher issue and
didn't want to belabor it. He would settle the matter in the
confines of the Capitol, away from the glare of the people who
believe that vouchers would hurt public schools. Opposition also
formed among conservatives who didn't like the idea of religious
schools getting sucked into something with strings-attached
government money. The voucher movement also is undermined by better
test scores by low-achieving students, repudiating assertions that
public schools are beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   So we had groups such as the Texas PTA and League of Women
Voters dead-set against vouchers despite the tweak-and-tinker
crowd's battle cry, ``We just want to see if vouchers work.''
</P>
<P>
   This session shows support for vouchers to be ghostly
transparent, and now lawmakers know how deeply support runs for
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
