bid to lure working-class voters away from Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu took a hit on Sunday after an actress supporting Barak
called them rabble. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PROTEST (Beijing) _ Police were out in force in several
Chinese cities this weekend, seeking to head off rumored plans for
new demonstrations by a spiritual cult that staged a giant vigil in
Beijing last Sunday. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-MUSLIMS (Istanbul) _ A newly elected deputy of Turkey's
parliament insists she will take her oath while wearing her Muslim
head scarf. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-CORSICA (Paris)_ Bombs and fires have long been common
tools for Corsica's separatists, but a recent explosion at a beach
restaurant appears to have been the work of the very crack police
squad that was created to stem the guerrilla violence. By Marlise
Simons.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-PADRE-PIO (Rome) _ The beatification of Padre Pio, an
enigmatic friar and mystic who has a vast following in Italy and
throughout the world, unleashed long-awaited rejoicing for 270,000
devotees who flooded into Rome for the ceremony. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR; (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-INTERNET (Undated) _ The Littleton, Colo., massacre
has heightened parental concerns over the influence of the Internet
and computer games. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBS-POLITICS (Undated) _ Fifty years ago fewer than a
quarter of Americans lived in the suburbs. By early next century
more than half of Americans will live there. Every ten years,
another 10 congressional districts become suburban. As the battles
for the presidency and control of Congress get under way, these
growth patterns are already having a profound effect on the
language and policy proposals of the two parties. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ARK-BOAT-SINKS (Hot Springs, Ark.) _ Death toll at 13 tourists
in sinking of amphibious boat in this resort town. At the scene,
however, it's like nothing happened. By David Firetone.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-BALL-PROFILE (Washington) _ Profile of Robert Ball, old
lion and voice of traditionalism in the Social Security debate. By
Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-POLITICS (Metairie, La.) _ Republicans breathe a sigh
of relief after David Duke comes close to making the runoff in the
election for Robert Livingston's seat. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-WORKERS (Washington) _ A study shows that low-wage
workers at companies with many high-wage workers are more likely to
have employer-provided health insurance than low-wage workers at
companies with few high-wage workers. That is, it's better to flip
hamburgers in the General Motors cafeteria than at McDonalds. By
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   CORRESPONDENTS-DINNER (Washington) _ Magazines like George and
Vanity Fair dominate the annual White House Correspondents
Association dinner. The event is too much for some to swallow. By
Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
