<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEYMOUR-HERSH-NYT &LR;      05-02 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEYMOUR-HERSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAUD CASE PUTS INVESTIGATIVE REPORTER'S METHODS UNDER SCRUTINY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seymour M. Hersh, a relentless digger and
interrogator, has long been considered a premier investigative
reporter. His work on the My Lai massacre won him the Pulitzer
Prize in 1970 and was followed by newspaper, magazine and book
exposes on such subjects as Henry A. Kissinger, Richard M. Nixon
and the Central Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   But when Hersh was called to testify as a government witness in
a recent criminal trial in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, the
renowned journalist found himself facing stiff cross-examination by
a defense attorney determined to expose any contradiction in his
story. In three hours on the witness stand, Hersh fielded more than
500 questions about his dealings with the defendant, a man who had
claimed to have explosive documents about President John F.
Kennedy. Hersh's account became an intriguing subtext in the trial,
offering a glimpse into how one of the nation's most accomplished,
and at times controversial, reporters practices his craft.
</P>
<P>
   The man on trial was Lawrence X. Cusack III, 48, a former
paralegal who was convicted on Friday of defrauding more than 100
investors of about $7 million in a scheme to sell the documents. He
had said he found the material in the files of his late father, a
prominent lawyer in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Cusack's documents were said to link Kennedy to Marilyn
Monroe and Sam Giancana, the legendary Chicago mobster, and that is
what had drawn Hersh to him.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh, who first learned of the papers in 1994, saw them as
possibly laying the basis for his next big scoop, as big as My Lai,
he suggested in court. He said he immediately set out to obtain
their exclusive use for a book he was writing on Kennedy that was
ultimately published as ``The Dark Side of Camelot'' (Little,
Brown, 1997). His wooing of Cusack included a barrage of letters.
Hersh testified that he wanted ``first crack'' at making the
documents public.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters hungry for scoops romance sources all the time,
although they do not always leave paper trials as detailed as
Hersh's.
</P>
<P>
   In his letters, he flattered Cusack, cajoled him and implored
him _ all tried and true methods in journalism of getting people to
act for the journalist, whether it is in their interest or not.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview last week, Hersh, who worked for The
New York Times in the 1970s after winning the Pulitzer, defended
his approach in seeking access to the papers before he learned they
were fraudulent. ``Was I romancing them?'' he said. ``Yes. Should I
say otherwise? Of course I wanted those papers.'' But he added:
``Did I cross the boundary? I certainly don't think so. I don't
think I came close.''
</P>
<P>
   His first move was to fly to Atlanta, where he was shown copies
of the materials by an associate of Cusack's. According to a court
transcript of his testimony, one document that caught Hersh's eye
purported to be a contract between Kennedy and Monroe in which the
president agreed to pay the actress money for her silence about
their affair.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh said his reaction to the papers was ``gaga.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a tip, they were incredible,'' he said. ``It's like
somebody calling me up and saying, `I know about a mass murder in
Vietnam.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh first met Cusack in April 1995, at Smith &AMP; Wollensky, the
steak house on Manhattan's East Side. There, he listened as Cusack
regaled him with childhood stories of seeing his father, Lawrence
X. Cusack Jr., leave for the Kennedy compound at Hyannisport,
Mass., with golf clubs or of his mother's chats with Rose Kennedy
about making sweet potato pie.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack also indicated to Hersh that he had once served in
Vietnam, carrying out special operations.
</P>
<P>
   The delicate dance between reporter and source had begun,
although Hersh did not realize for more than a year that he was
being tricked, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   He began his letter-writing campaign immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marilyn contracts are obvious dynamite,'' he wrote on
April 14, 1995. So was another document, which supposedly linked
Kennedy to Giancana.
</P>
<P>
   Showing some fraternity, he added: ``We got along so well at
that dinner Tuesday night because, I like to think, we are all what
we seem to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Six letters followed over the next two months. Hersh promised to
write the truth and to use the papers ``accurately, fairly and
appropriately.'' He said he would not dishonor the memory of
Cusack's father, who, his research showed, was every bit as eminent
and distinguished as Cusack had told him.
</P>
<P>
   He also reminded Cusack that he would not buy access. ``We must
be holier than the pope _ and that means we cannot, simply cannot,
pay for any information,'' Hersh wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But he also pointed out that if Cusack allowed him to use the
materials as the basis for further reporting, he would be able to
put the papers into the proper historical context, which in turn
could lead to greater financial rewards for Cusack.
</P>
<P>
   Putting ``history before personal profit,'' Hersh wrote, would
``maximize the value of the papers and the value of your story in
finding them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called having your cake and eating it, too,'' Hersh
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   By early May, Cusack was still demurring, leaving Hersh
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sitting here, frankly, scratching at the door like a
Chihuahua trying to get in,'' he told the jury about his feelings
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack finally relented, Hersh said, giving him the access he
wanted. Then in a letter dated June 22, Hersh elaborated on his
plans for the papers.
</P>
<P>
   It was an assertion in that letter that became a source of
contention at the trial. The defense accused Hersh of crossing the
line of journalistic ethics by declaring to Cusack, who is known as
Lex, that he had been able to confirm that Cusack's father had
known Kennedy, based on an interview Hersh had had with Kennedy's
secretary, Evelyn Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, I have independently confirmed not only the fact
of your father's relationship with the president'' through Ms.
Lincoln, he wrote, adding that he had also ``independently
confirmed some of the most interesting materials'' in Cusack's
father's papers.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh later acknowledged in court that this was not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is where I absolutely misstated things,'' Hersh
testified. He explained that Ms. Lincoln had initially confirmed
knowing Cusack's father but later recanted that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wrote this letter,'' Hersh testified, ``I selectively
recollected the good and didn't remember the bad.'' He added: ``I
simply misspoke to Cusack.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
