<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERSH-2NDTAKE-NYT     05-02 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERSH-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: misspoke to Cusack.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cusack's lawyer, Robert F. Katzberg, accused Hersh of misleading
Cusack, perhaps even lying to him. Even the prosecutor, Paul A.
Engelmayer, an assistant U.S. attorney, told the jury on Wednesday:
``Sure, Seymour Hersh played a little fast and loose with the
facts,'' but he added, ``None of this has anything to do with Lex
Cusack's guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh said by phone after the verdict on Friday, ``There is
nothing in my testimony that would suggest I was playing fast and
loose with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked at the trial about the Lincoln statement, Hersh
denied that he had lied to Cusack but did admit to ``romancing
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a newspaper man,'' he told the jury. ``You go after
stories. That's a great story.''
</P>
<P>
   He also testified that he never intended to mislead Cusack: ``I
believe it's very important to be as straight as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of investigation, testimony showed, Hersh
and several associates working on an ABC documentary came to
question the papers' authenticity and Cusack's credibility. Their
doubts eventually helped lead to the unraveling of the fraud
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh testified, for example, that he had asked an informant in
the intelligence community to check ``the very secret covert files
of American government'' and that no evidence was found that Cusack
had ever served in the military or any classified job.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh never used the documents in his book. But in court, his
reporting techniques were thrown back at him. Cusack's lawyer,
Katzberg, practically scoffed to the jury as he cited Hersh's
explanation for why he had not lied to Cusack, only erred.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were a Pulitzer Prize for backtracking and eating
one's words,'' Katzberg said, ``I think he could add it to his
trophy chest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Could those words be any clearer?'' Katzberg said, adding,
``Hersh is telling us in effect that he wrote these words with
disappearing ink.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh said in the interview last week that Katzberg's tactics
did not surprise him. ``He's doing what lawyers do,'' Hersh said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he should have been more careful in his letter to
Cusack: ``There's absolutely no question that had I been careful I
would have said in that letter Evelyn Lincoln `at one time
initially said' instead of `said.'''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Engelmayer, who criticized Hersh in his
summation for his handling of the facts, nevertheless attached yet
a different meaning to the journalism debate that had occurred in
the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Engelmayer, who himself spent about a year as a reporter for The
Wall Street Journal, told the jury: ``What the Seymour Hersh
episode does confirm for you is just how good a fraudster Lex
Cusack was in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a pretty good liar to fake out an investigative
reporter like Seymour Hersh,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
