<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KINGSLEY-PROFILE-ART-     05-02 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGSLEY-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PUBLICITY AGENT WHO HAS CHANGED THE RULES FOR ACCESS TO THE
STARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Pat Kingsley tends to minimize her role in
Hollywood. But no one else does.
</P>
<P>
   Not Tom Cruise, nor a host of other stars: Courtney Love, Arnold
Schwarzenegger, Nicole Kidman, Jodie Foster, Al Pacino, to name a
few. As a founder of PMK, the most powerful public relations
company in entertainment, she ranks as the doyenne of Hollywood
publicity and an extraordinarily potent force in the movie
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley, 66, counts Cruise and company among her clients.
The stars, often difficult, spoiled, volcanic and surprisingly
insecure, find a strong-willed rudder in Ms. Kingsley: smart,
tight-lipped and fiercely loyal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they can trust her,'' said Sherry Lansing, chairman
of Paramount Pictures, who has worked with Ms. Kingsley for years.
``She brings a sense of perspective to their careers. She has an
extraordinary instinct about what's right and not right for her
clients and for the movies she works on.''
</P>
<P>
   Her control of access to her roster at a time when the nation's
obsession with celebrity keeps growing has helped her reshape not
only stars' images but also entertainment journalism. Tall,
attentive and publicly anonymous in the company of her clients, she
has used her position as no one else has.
</P>
<P>
   She shrewdly manipulates and cajoles magazine editors and
television executives, and often demands outright that for profiles
of her clients they use preferred interviewers (usually ones who
are in awe of stars and will ask soft questions) as well as glossy
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Because an exclusive cover picture of Cruise, for one, can
increase newsstand sales by the thousands, magazine editors, as
well as their television equivalents, are often willing to agree to
Ms. Kingsley's requirements, even though by doing so they are
giving up significant traditional controls over their articles and
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day Ms. Kingsley canceled a ``Today'' appearance
by her client Calista Flockhart because the producers would not
agree to Ms. Kingsley's insistence that the show's interviewer not
ask any questions about the actress' bone-thin appearance.
</P>
<P>
   About Ms. Kingsley, Tom Goldstein, dean of the Columbia
University Graduate School of Journalism, said: ``She's changed the
rules. And although it may be to her credit as a publicist, it is
not to the general well-being of journalism as a field and those
who are consumers of journalism. There's a feeling that favorable
coverage is traded in some fashion, but what the audience isn't let
in on is the secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley, seated in a conference room at her office in a low
Italianate building on a quiet Los Angeles street, is direct about
her mission. ``Yes, we try to control,'' she said. ``We try to
control whether or not it's a cover. We cop to that. We ask who the
writer is. If it's somebody that either we or the client has had a
bad experience with, we say, well, that's not going to work. They
either will come back with another writer or won't do the story.
The same can be said with photographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an actor reaches a certain station, there's a prestige
that they have: They should either get the cover or they shouldn't
do the interview. A magazine editor told me he didn't understand my
reasoning. His magazine had a circulation of six million, and we
were offered an inside story on one of our clients. We turned it
down for a cover story in Details, which had a fraction of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That's right.' Basically, a lot of people don't read
these articles, but they do see the covers. They see them on the
newsstands. And when a person gets to a certain stage, they should
have that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Ms. Kingsley's most discussed triumphs was placing her
client Matthew McConaughey on the cover of Vanity Fair at a time
when he was almost unknown. The August 1996 article hailed him as a
major new star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we look for a puff piece,'' Ms. Kingsley said,
maintaining that she just wanted the journalist and the star to
``mesh.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Ms. Kingsley and others in public relations filled
the void left by the collapse of the old studio system. From the
1940s and through the mid-'60s studios not only controlled the
public appearances of actors but also created fictions about their
personal lives, including in some cases their sexual orientations
to make them palatable to the public. At the same time Hollywood
journalists, like those in Washington, often avoided publishing
what they knew about the personal lives of the people they covered.
By contrast, some of today's stars proclaim their sexual
identities, like Ellen DeGeneres, a PMK client.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley moved to Los Angeles in 1959, got her first movie
job as secretary to the press agent Warren Cowan, was steadily
promoted and wound up handling stars like Natalie Wood, Doris Day
and Samantha Eggar. One potential public relations challenge was
Ms. Wood, who had had several affairs. ``They would speculate who
she was going out with, but it was all very tastefully done,'' she
said. ``Today there'd be somebody in the bushes trying to get a
photograph.''
</P>
<P>
   PMK was formed in 1980 when Ms. Kingsley's former company merged
with two rivals. After deaths and departures, she emerged on top
and was later joined by her New York-based partners, Leslee Dart
and Lois Smith. Clients pay an estimated fee of $3,500 a month.
Studios pay about $10,000 a month for help with a film's release.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago PMK, a nearly $10-million-a-year business with 40
employees, was acquired for an undisclosed sum by the
McCann-Erickson World Group, the advertising agency, which itself
is a unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ms. Kingsley in her workday tends to say no more than yes,
often to people who don't hear no very often, she has stirred a
certain enmity, especially among studio executives who want her
clients to help promote their movies.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KINGSLEY-PROFILE-2NDT     05-02 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGSLEY-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
 
HOLLYWOOD: their movies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley herself takes strong exception to a view expressed
by one top producer that when it comes to encouraging clients to do
interviews, ``as far as studios go, it's mostly no, no, no with
Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``We prefer to be buffers,'' alluding to her role as
the gatekeeper limiting access to the stars. ``You know, the bigger
the stars, the studios really don't have much to complain about.
I've never had much complaint about Tom Cruise or Jodie Foster or a
lot of people who really feel the responsibility of their work.
They don't feel that their job ends once they wrap.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Kingsley, selection of writers and photographers is very
much a bargaining chip. Especially photographers. She was the first
publicity agent who demanded magazine covers for many of her
clients, a demand that is now commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Cable Neuhaus, Los Angeles bureau chief of Entertainment Weekly,
said the magazine's relationship with Ms. Kingsley had been
erratic. ``When we first began, she blew us off with impunity,'' he
said. ``Then we had our exclusive story about Julia Roberts calling
off her wedding to Kiefer Sutherland. Pat called. She said we had
turned the corner. She said, `Congratulations, you're one of the
big boys now.' '' The exclusive had turned the magazine into a must
read for entertainment industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Neuhaus said that Ms. Kingsley could be stern and intimidating.
Several years ago, he recalled, the magazine's plans for a cover
article on Ms. Foster fell through because of a late-breaking
report. Ms. Kingsley was furious that the article ran in a later
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat called and said: `As far as you're concerned, I'm dead.
Don't bother calling me back,' '' Neuhaus recalled. ``The truth is,
she continued to deal with us in a very professional and collegial
way. Subsequently our relationship has been totally civil.''
</P>
<P>
   From the client's point of view, Ms. Kingsley's approach, and
that of her PMK colleagues, is worth whatever they pay. ``If you
have a hint of a Newsweek cover or a little interest from Time,
they know exactly how to navigate the clients in a way that doesn't
seem desperate or lame,'' said Scott Rudin, one of the most
prolific producers, who employs the company on his films. ``They
have the ability to promise: `We'll give you a big Jim Carrey
piece, if you do Diane Keaton. We'll give you `Ransom' if you do
`Marvin's Room.'''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways Ms. Kingsley's partners have equally formidable
client lists. Ms. Dart's includes Tom Hanks, Woody Allen, Matt
Damon, Jennifer Lopez, Mariah Carey, Conan O'Brien and Mike
Nichols. Ms. Smith represents Robert Redford, Meryl Streep,
Michelle Pfeiffer, Rosie O'Donnell, Dustin Hoffman and others.
</P>
<P>
   Graydon Carter, managing editor of Vanity Fair, which is a prime
focus of PMK, said that Hollywood demographics had worked to
strengthen his hand and those of other editors in their dealings
with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five or six years ago every magazine was fighting over a small
number of movie stars,'' Carter said. ``PMK was very powerful. They
did a great job. But now there's an explosion of younger talent,
and it's put power back in the editors' hands. Half our staff
doesn't know why we choose some of the people we put on our
covers.''
</P>
<P>
   (Although PMK counts young stars among its clients, including
Ms. Flockhart, Johnny Depp, Neve Campbell and Lisa Kudrow, the
agency's rivals include two companies that are especially popular
with younger stars. One of the companies is Baker-Winokaur-Ryder,
whose clients include Leonardo DiCaprio, Brad Pitt, Sarah Michelle
Gellar, Rosie Perez and Ben Affleck. The other is
Huvane-Baum-Halls, with clients like Gwyneth Paltrow, Helen Hunt
and Jennifer Aniston.)
</P>
<P>
   For someone who spends so much time with so many high-profile
clients, Ms. Kingsley, who has held onto her North Carolina accent,
lives a surprisingly low-key life. She has in a relatively small
home in Pacific Palisades, Calif. She said she divided her time
among her office, a gym and the premieres she must attend with her
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she finds herself in a situation where no amount of
spin can save a client. In the early 80s she received a call from
the tennis player Billie Jean King, who said that because of a
lawsuit, the news was about to break that she had had an affair
with a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so difficult; it was at the end of her career on the
courts, and it was going to ruin her ability to make money,'' Ms.
Kingsley said. ``She didn't feel she could lie about what happened.
She wanted to deal with it in an aggressive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Let's do it here in Los Angeles.' So she gave her
statement at this hotel down near the airport. And it was terribly
difficult. Her mother and father were there, her family. And it was
painful not knowing what the consequences would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the things that she had signed up to represent went away.
And they never came back to this day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
