<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANGEROUS-BOOK-REVIEW     05-02 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANGEROUS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A DANGEROUS FRIEND:' HIGH IDEALS, ON THE EVE OF DESTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think that the Vietnam War has been milked dry as a
subject for fiction, this impression will be reinforced at the
opening of Ward Just's extraordinary new novel, ``A Dangerous
Friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Here the nameless narrator declares: ``I will insist at the
beginning that this is not a war story. There have been plenty of
those and will be many more, appalling stories of 19-year-olds
breaking down, frightened out of their wits, or engaging in acts of
unimaginable gallantry; and often all three at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   No, he continues, ``this is a different cut of history, a
civilian cut, without feats of arms or battlefield chaos. If love
depends on faith, think of my narrative as a kind of romance, the
story of one man with a bad conscience and another with no
conscience and the Frenchman and his wife who lived in the parallel
world, the one we thought was a mirage from the century before, a
bankrupt colonial milieu that offered _ so many possibilities, as
Dicky Rostok said.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the story still seems familiar, what with the man of bad
conscience, Sydney Parade, going to work in 1965 for the man with
no conscience, Dicky Rostok, leader of the so-called Llewellyn
Group, ``a team outside the normal chain of command, not for
intelligence or counter-insurgency _ the CIA already had more
people than the embassy, and its plate was full _ but for research
and rapid reaction when the usual channels broke down.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the story you learn that Rostok wants Parade to use his
family's connections to befriend and get information from a
Frenchman and his American wife who run a rubber plantation in Xuan
Loc.
</P>
<P>
   You know from the wearily disillusioned tone of the narrative
that things will end badly and that Parade will turn out to be the
dangerous friend of the title.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the shape of the story is predictable, Just more than
justifies its telling with the evocative detail he brings to it.
Not only has he used his experience reporting the war in the 1960s
(for Newsweek and The Washington Post) to bring the terrain and
weather and atmosphere of Vietnam alive, he also fashions a series
of eloquent symbols.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Parade first arrives in Vietnam he finds on
his desk an oblong carton from home that he thinks must contain his
father's prized shotguns, ``the twin Brownings he had won in a
poker game at the club,'' but that when opened yields ``not
firearms at all but two intricately carved boxes, each 10 inches by
14 inches, one marked IN and the other marked OUT in deep curving
script.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrative continues: ``The old man could be very droll. He
knew that the IN and OUT boxes were the maneuver battalions of
bureaucratic existence, now forward, now back, now concealed, now
full, now empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Just seems incomparably at home in his story. Gone is
the teasing obliqueness, the air of empty mystification that so
often marks his fiction (``The Congressman Who Loved Flaubert,''
``Nicholson at Large,'' ``Jack Gance'' and ``Echo House,'' among
his 14 previous novels and story collections). Instead his subtle
allusiveness is perfectly controlled, allowing the silences between
the lines to speak out loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   Finally he has invented an action involving a captured airborne
officer (``Saving Captain Smalley,'' you might call it) that neatly
sums up the frustration of the war from the American point of view,
the impossibility of penetrating the parallel world of residual
colonialism without destroying even what is worth preserving in it.
</P>
<P>
   One hesitates to call ``A Dangerous Friend'' brilliantly
Conradian, knowing how offensive it is to serious writers to be
defined in terms of other writers. But Just begs the comparison
himself by making Conrad a favorite of Rostok's, ``not the Conrad
of the African jungles but the Conrad of the open Asian seas, the
coming-of-age Conrad who was always conscious of the shadow line
between youth and maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end, after the final collapse of Parade's illusions,
Rostok sums up what they have been through together in Conradian
terms, perfectly misreading both Conrad and what they have been
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conrad has no patience with illusions,'' he tells Parade.
``There's something of the manifest destiny in Joseph Conrad, don't
you think? And he's relevant in these times, because he hated the
Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Parade looks hard at Rostok. ``Speechless was not the word.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally Parade and Rostok stand shoulder to shoulder on a wharf,
watching stevedores unload a freighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were offloading America, the arsenal of democracy, its
knowledge and its wealth, its optimism and industrial might.
Typewriters, blackboards, two cases of thesauruses and three of
dictionaries, cartons of envelopes and note pads, pencils, paper
clips, gum erasers and ballpoint pens, account ledgers, file
folders, coffee mugs, paperweights and insect repellent and
scissors and pictures frames and desk lamps. Television sets were
followed by transistor radios, then telephones, movie projectors,
intercom systems, lecterns with microphones attached, and case
after case of plastic rulers. An American stood to one side with a
checklist on a clipboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Just's novel makes you want to run screaming into the street to
protest retrospectively the war he has so movingly recreated.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A DANGEROUS FRIEND'
</P>
<P>
   By Ward Just
</P>
<P>
   256 pages. A Peter Davison Book. Houghton Mifflin Co. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
