<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-MEDIA-ART     05-02 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFLED AS EVERYONE ELSE, NETWORK TV WAS DRAWN TO THE LITTLETON
SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Ark., Tex.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the first frightening images flashed onto television
screens from Littleton, Colo., on Tuesday afternoon, April 20, it
was clearly a major story, one the cable news networks would cover
around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   But soon the three major broadcast networks were covering it
almost the same way, devoting far more time to this massacre, on
their evening and morning news programs and prime-time news
magazines, than they had ever allocated to any similar shooting
rampage.
</P>
<P>
   They devoted so much time to the event that the first week's
coverage was called ``unprecedented and disproportionate'' by
Andrew Tyndall, a longtime industry consultant who tracks the
amount of coverage the weeknight news broadcasts give to various
stories. He noted that the 6:30 p.m. newscasts on ABC, CBS and NBC
together spent 144 minutes on the Littleton tragedy over four days
_ more than twice as much as the 65 minutes spent on the Jonesboro,
Ark., school killings a year earlier. Those shootings also occurred
on a Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The coverage was far greater than that given to the 1997
Paducah, Ky., high school shooting, which left three dead (40
minutes over 5 days), and the 1991 cafeteria shooting in Killeen,
Tex., which killed 23 (27 minutes, 3 days).
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested a reason, and it had to do with race and
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have thought Jonesboro would be more horrifying because
it was children doing it,'' Tyndall said of the 11- and 13-year-old
boys who killed a teacher and four young girls in March 1998. ``Two
18-year-olds with guns who get angry and shoot people _ in Brooklyn
it wouldn't get much attention. The fact that this was an
upper-class suburb, and white upper-middle-class kids doing it, I
think influenced the coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh B. Price, president of the National Urban League, agreed,
to a point. ``We seem be a little more immune to and oblivious to
violence in urban areas,'' he said. ``We assume it goes with the
territory. In the eyes of many white Americans, people of color are
not quite whole people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he added: ``The gun violence that occurs in
black neighborhoods isn't like this. I can't recall an instance
where urban kids have gone in to blow things up. It may be some
gang stuff, or to settle some drug business. It's callous, but not
calculated, like what happened in Littleton. How do you find
Hitler? Why do kids like these even look for Hitler? This is beyond
the Ku Klux Klan even. I don't know what this is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans share Price's bafflement, which is a primary
reason television journalists give for the abundant Littleton
coverage _ coverage they insist was not excessive, given the many
factors involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story was bigger because the scope was bigger,'' said
Neal Shapiro, executive producer of NBC's ``Dateline.'' ``There
were more dead students.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dateline'' devoted a full hour to the Littleton tragedy each
night Tuesday, Wednesday, Friday and Sunday of the first week, and
most of its hourlong program the following Monday, Tuesday and
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro and others said that if two black 18-year-olds in an
urban school had killed 12 classmates and a teacher in the same
stylized way, and had placed bombs to blow up the school, the
networks would have covered it the same way. Others said,
privately, that they might not have.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was the worst shooting in any high school in the United
States ever, it would have gotten the same amount of coverage,''
Shapiro said, although the angles explored might have been
different.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that most school shootings have taken place in suburban
or rural areas, Paul Friedman, the executive producer of ABC's
``World News Tonight,'' said, ``I think the most surprising part
would be if it did take place in a major city.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that, along with the sheer horror of what happened in
Littleton, the incident was disturbing because it raised ``all the
questions we all have about raising children and getting along with
adolescents and understanding adolescents, as parents and authority
figures trying to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Ortiz, executive producer of ``CBS Evening News,'' said he,
his family and neighbors all felt ``forced to re-examine what our
kids are up to, what we knew about them, what video games they're
playing and what they are exposed to,'' because the killers in
Littleton appeared to be ``normal'' teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   But Ortiz also pointed out another reason the Littleton tragedy
got so much broadcast air time _ the agonizing way the story played
out, with mesmerizing live video. The first reports told of
hostages and gunfire, but not casualties. Slowly, over hours, came
reports of bombs and of bodies that could not be moved for fear of
booby traps.
</P>
<P>
   ``As every hour went by, the pictures that poured in were so
dramatic,'' Ortiz said. ``Kids running away, SWAT teams moving
around, shooting victims lying out in the open. It was obvious
there was something bigger than usual playing out. Then you heard
they were seemingly bright kids, and you heard about this trench
coat mafia, and as the hours went by it became curiouser and
curiouser.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of bewilderment made another difference, some
journalists said: People in Littleton did not shun the press, as
townspeople did after several other school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed an outlet,'' Susan Zirinsky, executive producer of
CBS' ``48 Hours,'' said of the teen-agers and parents. ``They
didn't understand what had happened, it was the most intense crisis
any of them had ever dealt with, and both the print and television
press became a vehicle for a cathartic experience for everyone
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Greenfield, the CNN commentator, who led CNN's ``town
meeting'' on the subject, said Littleton was different from other
school shooting stories because with the others, there seemed to be
some explanation for the violent acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This had such emotional resonance,'' he said of the Littleton
story. ``And the news magazine shows, the prime-time shows, have
all bought into the idea that in order to make a mark in prime
time, a story needs to have a big emotional wallop. This story had
it in hearts and spades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was every parent's nightmare,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
