<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VITAMIN-FORTIFIED AIR 
PROTECTING GOLFERS FROM THE SUN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   (mk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cereal makers, milk producers and skin-care cosmetic companies
put vitamins in their products and call them vitamin fortified,
making consumers feel better about what they are ingesting or
rubbing on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, would people feel if air was vitamin fortified?
</P>
<P>
   Leo Mettler, an inventor from Rancho Cordova, Calif., thinks
vitamin-fortified air is a good way to deliver vitamins
effortlessly. So he designed an air freshener and room deodorizer
that releases vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who need vitamin supplements take them in tablets or
capsules. A few years ago, spray vitamins that can be spritzed into
the mouth became popular as a method to deliver the vitamins more
quickly to the blood. Mettler, who holds several patents for air
fresheners and deodorizers, has adopted the kind of spray that can
used for those products for his ``vitaminized'' system. His latest
patent adds soluble vitamins like ascorbic acid (vitamin C), beta
carotene (vitamin A) or vitamin E to a formula that includes
fragrance oil and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The vitamins make up 1 percent to 12 percent of the mixture. The
fragrances, like those in conventional air fresheners, can be
derived from pine, fruit or flower oils. A propellant like
isobutane makes it possible to spray the freshener. Thus, Mettler
said, the air in a room can be vitamin fortified with isolated
sprays from a can. Or the vitamins can be dispersed using devices
covered in some of Mettler's older patents. One describes a
battery-operated air-freshening and deodorizing dispenser patented
in 1976. An electronic timer ejects doses of vitamins A, C and E at
intervals ranging from 5 seconds to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to control the frequency of emission of a constant
quantity of the composition permits the user to compensate for the
size of the room, the airflow and the number of occupants as may be
desired,'' Mettler said in the patent filing.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to get vitamins into the air, he said, is ``to load
these vitaminized mixtures onto compressed fiber pads through which
air can be forced via a fan blowing air on the pad.'' Mettler
patented such a device in 1981. Either way is more efficient than
expecting people to carry around their own inhalers or other
individual vitamin spray canisters, Mettler said.
</P>
<P>
   In his patent, he writes that his ``intent is to provide an
improved room deodorizer that benefits anyone and everyone who
enters the room, by permitting those people to gain the benefits of
propellant-delivered vitamins present in the mist or discrete
droplets of the air of a nicely smelling room.''
</P>
<P>
   He also believes that inhaling vitamins is superior to
swallowing them in pill form.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cell systems of the nasal cavity have been found to absorb
certain vitamins rapidly and efficiently,'' Mettler said in his
patent. ``One thereby avoids degradation of the vitamin by stomach
acid, and the inhibition of delivery of the benefits due to the
presence of food in stomach or intestine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mettler received patent 5,891,427.
</P>
<P>
   How to Save Golfers a Lot of Sun Block
</P>
<P>
   Golf is a game often played in sunny climates, which means that
a lot of golfers are exposed to the sun's damaging ultraviolet rays
for the many hours it takes to play a round.
</P>
<P>
   Most golf carts have canopies to shield players, but sometimes
that protective covering is deliberately eliminated. Ron Sanders,
an inventor and golfer, once played a course in Maine where the
carts did not have tops so that players could enjoy the spectacular
scenery. The view was beautiful, but the hot ride made him
uncomfortable. It also gave him the idea for a transparent,
ultraviolet-proof golf cart roof.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who founded a company in Great Neck, N.Y., called
Polymer Innovations Corp., has won a patent for the cart roof he
calls Sky-Vu. He says it fits the golf carts produced by three
leading manufacturers. He also cites research from the National
Golf Foundation showing that golf cart rentals account for more
than $2 billion in annual revenue, that 1.5 million golf carts are
in use and that 40,000 of those will need new tops each year.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' canopy is made of a thin sheet of transparent plastic
like polyethylene terephthalate-glycol. A chemical additive that
blocks ultraviolet rays can either be affixed to the plastic sheet
with adhesive or impregnated into the sheet itself, according to
the patent filing.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' invention can also be used for boat tops.
</P>
<P>
   He received patent 5,843,548.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
