<HEADER>
A1369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWAN-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT     05-02 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWAN-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRACEFULLY RUFFLING FEATHERS WITH A PROVOCATIVE ESTHETIC
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Love it or hate it, the first full-evening production
of ``Swan Lake'' at the New York City Ballet is already the talk of
the town.
</P>
<P>
   Passions run high among aficionados when rules are broken. Peter
Martins' staging of the standard four-act ``Swan Lake'' is not as
extreme as Robert Wilson's experiment with light in ``Lohengrin''
at the Metropolitan Opera. But it is bold and provocative in its
own right, with Martins' dazzling new choreography successfully
complementing a radical stage design.
</P>
<P>
   The decor by Per Kirkeby, a Danish painter, comes as a shock. No
fairy tale festivities or magic woodland enter into his highly
abstract landscapes and austere interiors. This is a Nordic clime
into which color, when it does light up the stage, plays an
important psychological role.
</P>
<P>
   Color theory and changing spatial composition tell the story
here as much as the 19th-century mime that Martins has, for the
most part, discarded.
</P>
<P>
   At its New York City Ballet premiere on Thursday night at the
New York State Theater, this $1.5 million ``Swan Lake'' was more
fascinating than moving. The deeply lyrical and elegiac quality of
the lakeside scenes seemed sacrificed to a perfect neo-classicism,
expressed in patterns and steps, as derived from George
Balanchine's one-act ``Swan Lake,'' which will also remain in the
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   But when led by the right Swan Queen and her prince, there is
still room even in this streamlined, modernized and swiftly paced
``Swan Lake'' for the emotional resonance that should be at its
core. Sadly, Darci Kistler and Damian Woetzel were deficient in
this respect at a gala on Thursday. But three other casts over the
weekend pointed in the right direction: Kyra Nichols and Philip
Neal on Friday, and on Saturday, Monique Meunier and Jock Soto
(matinee) and Miranda Weese and Peter Boal (evening).
</P>
<P>
   Soto and Ms. Meunier, with her wonderful amplitude of shape and
flow, knew best how to infuse drama and rapport into the encounters
between Prince Siegfried and Odette, the Swan Queen, and Odile, her
evil double.
</P>
<P>
   For although the choreography here tends toward the formal,
patterns and steps can be expressive in themselves. Contrary to
expectations, the production is not a pure-dance accident waiting
to happen. Martins follows the structure of the standard 1895
``Swan Lake'' by Marius Petipa and Lev Ivanov. The emphasis is on
dancing rather than characterization. But here as in Martins'
splendid 1991 ``Sleeping Beauty,'' the reason for bringing dance
into relief is found in the company's esthetics.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Balanchine why he did not choreograph a
full-evening ``Swan Lake,'' he replied that Tchaikovsky, in his
ballet score, had essentially written a suite of dances and that
the story was unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   The City Ballet performs here in its usual neo-classical style,
chest pulled up and energetic in its attack. This does not mean
that these qualities cannot be used to dramatic effect. There is a
wonderful moment when Martins has the swan maidens attack the
hunters in the first lakeside scene.
</P>
<P>
   Martins has compressed four acts into two with one intermission
and the mood of each act is definitely influenced by the decor,
with important contributions from Mark Stanley, the lighting
designer. Martins originally presented this ``Swan Lake'' at the
Royal Danish Ballet in October 1996, and it has been restaged for
the U.S. premiere with the aid of Colleen Neary, a former City
Ballet principal who lives in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   The front curtain is already a clue that realism will not run
through the production. Realism is reserved for the oppressive
world in which the Prince lives. Jackson Pollock might come to mind
when looking at the flowing paint on the first curtain; these veins
and roots, or scribbles, are echoed in many of the costumes,
including Odette's and Siegfried's.
</P>
<P>
   The two front curtains and lakeside backdrops are highly
effective; they are stunning as abstractions of nature and the
seasons. Branches, roots and ice come to mind in the first drop;
slate in the other. A splash of blue suggests a lake elsewhere. Act
I is more of a shock, with its no-frills courtyard surrounded by
ochre walls and arches below an abstraction of foliage.
</P>
<P>
   The Prince in blue stands out in the spare setting. Eight women
in green with eight men in red, yellow and orange fill the huge
space with a swirl of color in the highly musical and exciting
waltz choreographed by Martins. Tiny girls and their boy escorts
weave through the waltz and when they end in tribute to the Prince
on his birthday, the audience applauds rightly.
</P>
<P>
   Martins has kept set pieces such as the adagio solo and Dance of
the Cygnets in the traditional second act. The standard Black Swan
pas de deux in the ballroom scene is included. In a few cases he
expands upon the original steps with new patterns as Balanchine did
with Ivanov's swan maidens. He does the same for Petipa's pas de
trois in Act I. As in other productions, there is totally new
choreography. The Prince gets a solo in the first lakeside scene,
danced to the music of the big swans. The Jester, derived from
Soviet productions, is no fool; he is a virtuoso. Benjamin Bowman,
Tom Gold and Adam Hendrickson were all outstanding on different
days.
</P>
<P>
   The character dances, on toe or in heels, have a hit in a sexy
harem number, especially as fabulously performance by Charles
Askegard and Maria Kowroski. Their music is the Russian Dance, and
it is odd in this context to hear the Russian melodies of the
violin solo, although the choreography is highly musical.
</P>
<P>
   Siegfried's adagio with Odette is danced in a spotlight in the
usual Second Act, surrounded by a swan corps in blue light. Martins
uses the image of the deep curtsy that begins the adagio as a theme
for the corps, especially in Act IV, in which a huge circle of swan
maidens on the floor await Siegfried after he has betrayed Odette.
</P>
<P>
   He does so in an airless paneled room that resembles a courtroom
more than a ballroom. The courtiers are in Elizabethan dress, like
the Queen Mother, who has told the Prince to marry. The Jester,
aided by three little boys, ushers in the divertissement. This
section includes Martins' intricate neo-classical pas de quatre
from four years ago and standard character dances (Hungarian and
Spanish). There is a weak Neapolitan dance with the women on toe.
The six fiancees waltz on toe and Odile seduces the Prince as usual
in the traditional pas de deux, directed by Rothbart the magician,
who has a flair for flinging an orange cape.
</P>
<P>
   The mazurka is not part of the divertissement as usual; it
becomes suddenly a ghostly background, danced by courtiers, for a
new drama. Siegfried, who has sworn his love to Odette, is ready to
swear to Odile, but Rothbart violently stops him, gesturing as if
to ask him if he is sure.
</P>
<P>
   When the fatal second vow is taken, the Prince in this version
is doomed to remain alone. Odette, betrayed, exits, supposedly to
revert to swanhood. Rothbart dives into the wings leaving his cape
behind: an unsatisfactory touch.
</P>
<P>
   The production, dedicated to the memory of Lincoln Kirstein, a
co-founder of the City Ballet with Balanchine, has a sophistication
that other companies might envy. One looks forward to all the casts
later this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
