<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a busy Friday for DDB Needham Worldwide Communications
Group in New York, a unit of Omnicom Group, which changed its name,
designated the next generation of leadership and landed a large
account.
</P>
<P>
   DDB Needham is dropping the ``Needham'' from its name, which
dates to 1986 when Doyle Dane Bernbach and Needham Harper Worldwide
merged to form the agency. Keith Reinhard, chairman and chief
executive, said the decision to ``simplify our branding'' was
spurred by the coming 50th anniversary of the founding of Doyle
Dane.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhard, 64, is forming a worldwide operating committee
composed of executives who are likely to be top managers in the
next century. Ken Kaess, 44, president for North America, takes the
additional post of chairman of the committee, which formally
identifies him as Reinhard's eventual successor. Kaess will also
become a member of the agency's executive committee, along with a
creative executive, Nizan Guanaes, 40, president at DM9 DDB Brazil
in Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   And Dairy Management Inc. in Rosemont, Ill., which conducts
advertising and promotional programs for the American Dairy
Association and the National Dairy Council, named DDB Chicago to
handle the creative portion of its cheese account, with billings
estimated at $29 million. Those duties had been handled by Leo
Burnett Co. in Chicago until that agency and Dairy Management
agreed to part ways in January.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a two-month review that had been
narrowed to DDB Chicago and one other finalist, Goodby, Silverstein
&AMP; Partners in San Francisco, also owned by Omnicom. TN Media in New
York, a unit of True North Communications, continues to handle
media duties.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Ad Revenue Surging, Report Says
</P>
<P>
   Internet advertising more than doubled during 1998, according to
a report for the Internet Advertising Bureau in New York prepared
by the New Media Group of PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   Internet ad revenue reached a record $1.92 billion last year,
the report said, up 111.8 percent from $906.5 million in 1997. For
the fourth quarter of 1998, ad revenue totaled $655.6 million, the
report said, an increase of 33.6 percent from $490.6 million in the
corresponding period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of the Internet to blend ``traditional brand
building, retail sales and customer service in one place'' is the
reason that ad revenue ``has grown so quickly,'' Rich LeFurgy,
chairman at the bureau, said. ``And we're expecting continued
strong growth as traditional advertisers still sitting on the
sidelines start to come on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   _ Cambridge Soundworks Inc., Newton, Mass., a unit of Creative
Technology Ltd., to Ingalls, Boston, as the first agency to handle
branding duties for the designer of speakers. Billings were
estimated at $6 million to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   People
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Clark, executive vice president for account management,
was named executive vice president and director for business
development at Bates North America, New York, part of the Bates
Worldwide unit of Cordiant Communications Group PLC. He succeeds
John Marchese, president for integrated communications, who was
named chairman at 141 Integrated Communications, a division of
Bates North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
