<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG GONE, BUT NOT TO YARD IN SKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Grega owns what sound like perfect dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Dartanian, part malamute and part shepherd, and Alyosha, a
Samoyed, don't climb on the furniture. Barking is not a problem.
Cleanup is non-existent, and the dogs never threaten the postman.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they're dead.
</P>
<P>
   Which cuts down on their usefulness as guard dogs considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Grega had both dogs preserved; they lie, seemingly asleep, in a
bedroom of his New York apartment. Forever.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else, Fido, too, must shuffle off this canine
coil. But even the most devoted pet lover might wonder: What's the
point of keeping him around after he's gone?
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few years, it has alleviated the pain of losing
those animals,'' explained Grega, who works at a software company.
``I see them every day. . . . It's not like they're in the ground
decomposing. I can touch them. My kid actually likes to pet them.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. Four-year-old Dion doesn't think all dogs lie stone
still.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets along well with live dogs,'' Grega said, laughing.
``He'll even tell me we have two dogs, and they're both dead.'' &QL; 
`After-death pet care'
</P>
<P>
   Grega had his dogs preserved in Phoenix at Pet &AMP; Animal Lovers
Service, or PALS. The company specializes in after-death pet care.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting more emotionally attached to pets,'' said
Katherine Heuerman, PALS founder. ``Everyone's going to (the option
of) getting their pets back.''
</P>
<P>
   Often in the form of ashes: Cremations make up the bulk of her
business, Heuerman said. PALS cremates 60 to 65 animals a week (the
crematoriums are open for pet owners to inspect).
</P>
<P>
   But preservation is growing; one or two people a month now
request it.
</P>
<P>
   Preservation is a form of taxidermy, Heuerman explained, only
more detailed. You didn't gurgle baby talk for 10 years to the
white-tailed buck mounted above the mantel, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fox or deer is wildlife,'' Heuerman said. ``People see them
once, they shoot them, they kill them. There is no emotional
attachment. We have to capture the personality.''
</P>
<P>
   So PALS requires at least three photos of the pet. Preservation
is not cheap; it starts at about $500. (Cremations start at $100,
and burials run $750 to $1,000, Heuerman said.) It's also slow,
taking six to 12 months. But to some, it's worth it. &QL; 
Peanut's place
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said to Peanut, `You'll never leave me,' '' said
Sandra Wade of Scottsdale. And so he hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut, a chocolate-brown poodle no longer among the living,
lies atop a red satin pillow in a cherry-wood bed on top of the
entertainment center in Wade's bedroom. He's encased in a
custom-made glass case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to keep him with me,'' Wade said. ``I didn't want to
cremate him, and I didn't want him rotting in the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Peanut soon will be joined by Buddy, a white bichon frise, who
died in March and is being preserved, and, eventually, by her seven
other dogs. ``It's well worth the investment,'' Wade said.
``(Preserving Peanut) helped me. I cried when I saw him, but it was
happy. I feel very comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't. A dead pet sitting on a shelf staring back at me
sounds creepy.
</P>
<P>
   Grega understands that, noting that if he didn't know and love
Dartanian and Alyosha, he might find their presence weird, too. But
he did, so he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like they're asleep,'' he said. ``They're where
they've always been. They slept in these poses when they were
alive. If you imagine hard enough, you can imagine them sleeping
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He even talks to them, saying things like ``I miss you guys''
and ``I wish you were alive'' and ``I'm glad you're here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of unusual things going on in this world,''
Grega said. ``While that probably is unusual, there are a lot of
things going on you could look at a lot more cross-eyed than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. I'm willing to let eternally sleeping dogs lie.
Someone else's dogs, that is. In someone else's house. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VARIETY-REPORTER-ART-     05-02 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VARIETY-REPORTER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPERS BATTLE TO CONTROL HOLLYWOOD'S BUZZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Every weekday morning Hollywood awakens to ``the
trades,'' Daily Variety and The Hollywood Reporter, which talk
about the deals, the rumors and the announcements that spin out of
film studios and cable and television networks.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Variety dominated the daily agenda, with The
Hollywood Reporter trying to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after The Hollywood Reporter handed over the top
editor's job to Anita M. Busch, a strong-willed and aggressive
former top reporter at Variety, the competition has intensified as
Ms. Busch has challenged her former employer in the hard-fought
battle for readers and advertisers in the insular world of
Hollywood. In the process, the 37-year-old editor, who as a
reporter was as feared by executives as she was relentless, has
stirred the attention of a town that enjoys watching a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're killing them with exclusives,'' Ms. Busch said tartly of
her competitor in an interview the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Though such a comment may be an overstatement, it angers Peter
Bart, the editor in chief of Variety who is a former studio
executive and former journalist for The Wall Street Journal and The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody reading these papers day by day can draw their own
conclusions,'' Bart said. ``Our competition is not The Hollywood
Reporter but The Wall Street Journal, The New York Times and The
L.A. Times. The Reporter hasn't been competition for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``trades'' are the first papers read in offices throughout
Hollywood. Not only do Variety and The Hollywood Reporter set the
agenda, but they mirror the agendas of studios and talent agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't read the trades for information as much as the
spin,'' said Jeremy Zimmer, a partner at the United Talent Agency.
``The trades are like a bulletin board that people use. People
spin. People announce a slate of films that you know won't get
made. People announce a director is coming onto a project, when you
know there's not even a script ready. Some of it is wishful
thinking _ if you're trying to make a client appear hot then you
suggest that some director is pursuing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information travels so quickly now,'' Zimmer went on. ``People
in the information flow generally know what's going on before they
read the trades. We say at staff meetings, `If we have to read it
in the trades we're in trouble.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to assess the impact of Ms. Busch on circulation
or advertising. But the constituency for the trade papers _ studio
executives, talent agents and producers _ say that, by the nature
of her reputation and personality, Ms. Busch has sharpened the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty lopsided race before Anita, but now it's much
closer,'' said Mark Gill, president of the Los Angeles office of
Miramax, the studio owned by the Walt Disney Co. ``Anita has bought
an increased sense of urgency and a really aggressive style, an
amazing set of contacts and a pretty good nose for news.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wiatt, co-chairman of International Creative Management, a
top talent agency, said: ``Anita's an unbelievably competitive
person. Her relationships at every level of the business are
superb. It's a more level playing field now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Busch herself is widely feared in Hollywood and disliked by
plenty of people, too, partly because as a journalist and editor,
she seems indifferent to head-on collisions with moguls as well as
her former bosses, like Bart.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Ms. Busch wrote an article that angered
Michael Ovitz, then the head of the Creative Artists Agency.
Knowing that Ms. Busch had a serious allergy to monosodium
glutamate, or MSG, the powder that is used in foods as a flavor
intensifier, Ovitz sent her a bottle of it with a one-word note:
``Enjoy!''
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought it was a joke,'' Ms. Busch said. ``I tried to take
it like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Covering agents is the worst,'' she added. ``They're the most
thin-skinned.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point The Hollywood Reporter needs all the help it can
get, even with the arrival of Ms. Busch and several highly skilled
reporters covering films and television. Robert J. Dowling, the
editor in chief and publisher since 1988, said that over the last
10 years, The Hollywood Reporter had increased its reporting staff,
added numerous calendars, guides and features, started a Web site
and added advertising revenue through special sections.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who now believes The Hollywood Reporter is No. 2 to
Variety ``hasn't done any homework,'' he said. Referring to
Variety, he said, ``They are the No. 2 paper in town.''
</P>
<P>
   The figures don't quite attest to that _ and neither do the
comments heard about both newspapers across Hollywood, where
Variety is still the dominant trade paper. That The Hollywood
Reporter is the size of a magazine while Variety is larger and
easier to read does not help the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   Started 95 years ago as publication for the vaudeville business,
Variety is owned by Cahners, a division of the international media
conglomerate Reed Elsevier Inc., and has a daily circulation of
30,406, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations. Gerry Byrne,
the publisher of Variety, said the newspaper now has a daily
circulation of 37,899, which includes the West Coast and the
``Gotham'' edition in New York, which was started last year.
</P>
<P>
   The circulation of the weekly edition of Variety, which is
available Sunday or Monday, is 35,012. The household income of the
average Variety reader is an extraordinary $450,000 a year, Byrne
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for The Hollywood Reporter, its daily circulation as of Sept.
30, 1998, was 24,203, the last figure available from the audit
bureau. The circulation of the newspaper's weekly edition, which is
published on Tuesday, is 35,564. The Hollywood Reporter is owned by
Billboard Publications Inc., a subsidiary of VNU, a Dutch company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Busch started out in Los Angeles as a reporter for The
Hollywood Reporter, then was lured to Variety and has now returned
to The Hollywood Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in Granite City, Ill., the daughter of a
businessman, and worked as a business journalist for Crain
Communications in Chicago before moving to Los Angeles in 1990 to
cover marketing for The Hollywood Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that struck me as strange was people hanging
up on me,'' Ms. Busch recalled. She said one top studio marketing
executive told her: ``We don't talk about marketing. We're going to
have a very short relationship. Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   She said: ``He hung up in my ear. It was so unprofessional.'' In
her previous job, she said, ``I had been talking to people like
Malcolm Forbes and heads of companies. The behavior was so
different here.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Ms. Busch said she learned the Hollywood way of
dealing with the trade press. She once had an exclusive story about
Kevin Costner, for example, but before she could publish it a
publicist leaked it to Variety to curry favor with the larger
paper.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She also said she was often inundated with gifts. A Tiffany
apple from the movie executive Peter Guber was so expensive, she
said, that ``I sent it back.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she refused to negotiate with agents who were willing
to leak stories about their star clients only if Ms. Busch
guaranteed that a photo of the star would be on the front page and
that the agent's name would be conspicuously high in the article.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Busch quickly distinguished herself with numerous exclusive
articles on film and television deals. She was soon hired away by
Variety, where she tangled not only with agents and studio
executives but also with Bart, her editor.
</P>
<P>
   Bart, who has transformed Variety since he took over the weekly,
and later the daily, more than 10 years ago, recalled: ``When I
came here there was really a rather elderly staff, manual
typewriters, eyeshades. a lot of problems with alcohol,
particularly after lunch. Culturally and politically we were worlds
apart from what we are today. Variety hated rock-and-roll. There
were demonstrations by gay groups. And the reasoning in some ways
was, if it was not good for the industry, don't publish it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Busch, Bart said that she was a good reporter but
that ``she consistently did not get along with the editors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Busch said she tangled with Bart over the way her articles
were edited, especially those that involved the editor's friends,
like Guber, Ovitz, the producer Arnon Milchan, Joe Roth, the Disney
studio chairman, and Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax. Bart
denies any such favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   But the breaking point, about two years ago, was a front-page
article in Variety disclosing that a top executive at
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer was being dismissed by his boss, Frank Mancuso,
who ran the studio until he stepped down last week. The executive
first heard about his ouster when an agent-friend called him on the
morning that Variety ran the article and asked him, ``What are you
going to do now?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Busch, who did not write the article but left Variety soon
after it appeared, said she was appalled that no one at Variety had
called the executive for comment. She said it was part of an
arrangement between Bart and Mancuso. Bart insisted that Ms.
Busch's version was untrue and that he had instructed reporters to
call the executive the night before publication so the news would
not leak to other papers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Busch is consumed with work. She lives in an apartment a few
blocks from the offices of The Hollywood Reporter, in the
mid-Wilshire district of Los Angeles, and usually works six days a
week, if not seven. Her struggle to alter the culture of the trade
paper is difficult because she is also seeking to alter the way
Hollywood views the trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling everybody, `no trade-offs for story placement,' ''
Ms. Busch said. ``We don't publish one story so they can give us a
bigger story; we don't negotiate through all the spinning. I'm
telling people: `You can't lie to us. If you lie you're going to
have a credibility problem.' And I'm telling people to lighten up;
we're not dealing with national security here.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, Ms. Busch, who calls her sources for
stories, helped come up with a front-page article for the trade
paper: that Anthony Hopkins had been signed to co-star in the Tom
Cruise film ``Mission Impossible: 2.'' She tried to find out what
role Hopkins would play, but met with tight secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally called someone and found out,'' Ms. Busch said.
``But I thought: This is just a movie. What's the big deal? What
does it really matter? It's not Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
