<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-AD-COL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON AND KIRSHENBAUM BOND ARE FORMING UNITS TO FOCUS ON
ENTERTAINMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two agencies are joining the growing chorus along
Madison Avenue singing ``That's Entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   At J. Walter Thompson New York, an executive from the William
Morris Agency, Marina Hahn, is arriving in the new post of
executive vice president for strategy and entertainment.
Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP; Partners in New York is forming a division to
specialize in film, television and theatrical accounts. The
division, named KBE, opens with assignments that have billings
estimated at $15 million to $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   The moves are indicative of the increasing attempts by agencies
to broaden their missions beyond conventional advertising and enter
fields that are fresher and faster-growing. The enormous
opportunities presented by what Michael J. Wolf, in his new book,
``The Entertainment Economy,'' calls ``the E-factor'' _ the
voracious appetite among Americans to be amused _ are too
potentially lucrative to ignore, particularly after Hollywood
talent agencies have sought to muscle in on the tasks that agencies
have long performed for marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agencies can't just develop 30-second TV spots anymore,'' said
Bob Jeffrey, president at Thompson New York, part of the J. Walter
Thompson unit of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this big responsibility to form marketing partnerships
with clients in more aggressive ways and grow brands with the total
spectrum of communications,'' he said. ``Entertainment is global,
ubiquitous, contemporary and sets trends.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hahn, 40, had been vice president and head of the East Coast
corporate advisory group at the New York office of William Morris.
She has also worked for the Sony Corp. of America, the Pepsi-Cola
Co. unit of Pepsico Inc. and what is now DDB Worldwide in New York,
a unit of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about using entertainment as a strategic tool,'' Ms.
Hahn said, ``combining the creativity and clout of the
entertainment industry with the resources of corporate America and
figuring out how to build brands in innovative ways.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than creating the next sponsorship or product
placement or hiring the next celebrity endorser,'' she added. ``You
have to think about the experiences, not just the brands.'' Among
marketers praised by Ms. Hahn and Jeffrey were the Walt Disney Co.;
the Tommy Hilfiger Corp.; Nike Inc., for the Niketown retail
stores, and the Starbucks Coffee Co..
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hahn will form and lead a group at Thompson New York that
will combine what had been separate operations handling account
planning and media planning with a new entertainment unit, which,
like KBE, will seek clients in Hollywood, book publishing, music
and theater. Another goal is to use entertainment expertise to sell
the packaged goods of clients of Thompson New York and other
Thompson offices.
</P>
<P>
   At KBE, one initial assignment comes from a partnership between
the Columbia Tristar Television Group, a division of Sony Pictures
Entertainment, and Children's Television Workshop, the nonprofit
company that developed ``Sesame Street.'' KBE is working on
projects for ``Sesame Street'' and will provide services including
advertising, interactive marketing and promotions for ``Dragon
Tales,'' a new animated series aimed at preschool children that is
to be broadcast by PBS in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about developing a brand, not just a successful
show,'' said Sherrie Rollins Westin, executive vice president for
marketing, communications and research at the workshop in New York.
``The launch of KBE speaks to bringing brand-building sensibilities
to entertainment and media.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dragon Tales,'' featuring cartoon characters with names like
Cassie, Ord, Quetzal and the two-headed Zak &AMP; Wheelie, is being
produced by a new group at Sony Pictures Entertainment in Culver
City, Calif., devoted to television shows, movies and videos for
children and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the continuing fragmentation of the marketplace,
producers will have to take on more responsibility to supplement
the networks' efforts with their own show promotion,'' said Sander
Schwartz, president of the new group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The folks at Kirshenbaum Bond have shown an ability to
distinguish products of clients from the clutter and the
competition,'' he added, referring to work for Snapple and Target.
``I'm excited about them doing the same for `Dragon Tales.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another initial assignment for KBE comes from Radio City
Entertainment in New York, part of the Madison Square Garden
division of Cablevision Systems; Kirshenbaum Bond has handled
assignments for the company's Broadway musical, ``The Scarlet
Pimpernel.'' KBE's work will include campaigns for productions of
``The Wizard of Oz'' and ``A Christmas Carol'' and a Halloween
attraction with the entertaining name of Madison Scare Garden.
</P>
<P>
   KBE begins with about 10 employees under the direction of Jeff
Peters, 39, vice president and account director, and James
Hitchcock, 35, vice president and creative director. Peters joined
from (coincidentally) Thompson New York, where he had been a vice
president and marketing manager. Hitchcock had been a vice
president and associate creative director at Kirshenbaum Bond on
accounts like Target.
</P>
<P>
   Peters and Hitchcock will report to Jonathan Bond and Richard
Kirshenbaum, the co-chairmen at Kirshenbaum Bond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
