<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     05-02 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TWO GUYS FROM VERONA: A NOVEL OF SUBURBIA. &LR;  By James Kaplan.
Grove, $13. Set in an affluent New Jersey suburb in the very near
future, this bittersweet novel focuses on two middle-aged buddies _
one a prosperous businessman, the other a slacker _ whose lives are
shaken up when they attend their 25th high school reunion. The
result is ``a complex and often moving meditation on the passage of
time,'' Tom Perrotta wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERRA INCOGNITA: TRAVELS IN ANTARCTICA. &LR;  By Sara Wheeler.
Modern Library, $12.95. In this irreverent travelogue, a British
journalist describes her love affair with a continent, its history
and the people who are drawn to a place that spends half the year
in darkness. Last year our reviewer, Michael Parfit, praised the
author's ``gifts of observation and language'' and her
``straightforward narrative of characters, landscape and personal
change.'' The same publisher has reissued  &UR; OUTSIDE PASSAGE: A
MEMOIR OF AN ALASKAN CHILDHOOD &LR; , by Julia Scully ($12.95), an
account of the author's hardscrabble youth, which led her from
Depression-era San Francisco to Alaska, where she lived with her
mother and sister in Nome during the winter and a remote mining
district during the summer. In this ``plain but lovely'' memoir,
``the subdued rhetoric of directness has a grace equal to a more
heightened rhetoric,'' Verlyn Klinkenborg wrote in these pages in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DAMASCUS GATE. &LR;  By Robert Stone. Scribner, $14. The hero of
this complex novel is a skeptical American journalist living in
Israel who stumbles onto a plot by various fanatical groups to blow
up the Temple Mount, thus paving the way for the Second Coming.
Last year our reviewer, Jonathan Rosen, said Stone ``has faced his
novel with the literary equivalent of Jerusalem stone, the luminous
chiseled rock that lends authenticity to almost every building in
Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEAST IN THE NURSERY: ON CURIOSITY AND OTHER THOUGHTS. &LR;  By
Adam Phillips. Vintage, $12. A British therapist argues that the
essential mission of psychoanalysis is to explore and treat
curiosity disorders and thereby enable suffering adults to witness
the world again with a child's blissfully wide-open eyes. Last year
our reviewer, Stephen Greenblatt, called this a ``lively and
intelligent book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNION STREET &AMP; BLOW YOUR HOUSE DOWN. &LR;  By Pat Barker. Picador
USA, $15. The British author's first two novels have been reissued
in a single volume. ``Union Street'' portrays the bleak lives of
seven working-class women struggling to get by in an unnamed city
in England's industrial north. In 1983 in the Book Review, Ivan
Gold called this ``a first-rate first novel'' marked by ``pungent,
raunchy, North Country dialogue'' and ``passages of fine
understated wit.'' ``Blow Your House Down'' explores the lives of
women in a similar grim urban setting, but this time they are
prostitutes being stalked by a serial killer. ``Barker is able to
make us see her characters from within, as they see themselves,''
Katha Pollitt wrote in 1984, calling the novel ``swift, spare and
utterly absorbing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO TIME TO DIE: LIVING WITH OVARIAN CANCER. &LR;  By Liz Tilberis
with Aimee Lee Ball. Avon, $14. The former editor in chief of
Harper's Bazaar chronicled her recurring struggle with ovarian
cancer and her crusade to raise awareness of the disease as well as
her eventful life in the fashion business. Tilberis, who died last
month at the age of 51, ``sounds genuinely likable and down to
earth'' in this ``frank, often moving and surprisingly funny
memoir,'' Katherine Bouton wrote here in 1998.  &UR; CURING CANCER: THE
STORY OF THE MEN AND WOMEN UNLOCKING THE SECRETS OF OUR DEADLIEST
ILLNESS &LR; , by Michael Waldholz (Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14),
focuses on the researchers responsible for the genetic
breakthroughs in cancer research in the last decade and the ethical
dramas that have emerged from their successes. ``The result reads
like an adventure story,'' Andrea Cooper wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A WIDOW FOR ONE YEAR. &LR;  By John Irving. Ballantine, $14.95. The
four main characters in this freewheeling novel are all writers,
but the action is dominated by the youngest of them, Ruth Cole,
whose outrageous adventures feature the author's trademark brew of
sexual farce and sudden brutality. `` `A Widow for One Year' seems
to me the best story John Irving has as yet contrived,'' William H.
Pritchard wrote here in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIN ICE. &LR;  By Bruce McCall. Vintage, $14. In this withering
memoir, a writer and illustrator recalls his dismal youth in
Canada, land of the modest and early to bed, and how his growing
pains drove him to escape to the rowdier nation to the south.
``McCall's revenge on the land that bore (and bored) him is to make
its tedium richly funny,'' Blake Morrison said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AND BOTH SHALL ROW: A NOVELLA AND STORIES. &LR;  By Beth Lordan.
Picador USA, $12. These tales feature unglamorous country folks in
the Midwest whose small moments of intense clarity transcend words
and cannot be named, only described. In 1998 our reviewer, Robert
Houston, called this ``a fine, strong collection, written in a
voice that's utterly assured and utterly distinctive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
