<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, May 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Damp and chilly conditions will cover portions of the Middle
Atlantic and southern New England Coasts Monday as bands of showers
circulate westward around low pressure over the Atlantic Ocean. The
westward migration of the Atlantic moisture will cause clouds and
light sprinkles to reach as far west as the central Appalachians
and interior New England by afternoon. Meanwhile, strong high
pressure over Eastern Canada will thwart the northward advance of
the inclement weather, allowing sunny and warm weather to persist
over northern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly sunny skies will also cover the Southeast and Florida
Monday with comfortable humidity levels. Farther west, however,
southerly breezes from the Gulf of Mexico will fuel numerous
showers and isolated thunderstorms across eastern Texas and the
Mississippi Valley. Another area of showers will develop over the
northern Plains ahead of a cold front approaching from the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will cover the Northwest and northern Rockies
Monday as a fast-moving flow of air from the west imports Pacific
moisture inland. Showers will be generally intermittent though a
period of steadier, heavier rain will occur near the Washington
Coast as a jet stream disturbance passes overhead. Snow will whiten
the Cascades above 5,000 feet as the air is further moistened and
cooled upon ascending the terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny and warm conditions will cover the Southwestern deserts
while southern California stays dry though filaments of cirrus
clouds will dim the sun at times.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Florida Chill
</P>
<P>
   Numerous record low temperatures were established across Florida
this past weekend. Miami and Tampa fell to 60 and 52 degrees
respectively while at Orlando the mercury fell to 54, causing the
city to have its second consecutive day of record cold. Clear
skies, light winds in combination with unusually dry air over the
peninsula has prompted to the records. Humid air, which contains
high amounts of water vapor, cools at a slow rate because the water
vapor molecule is an efficient absorber of energy emitted by the
ground. Since dry air contains less water vapor, it cools at an
accelerated rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
