<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1386 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     05-02 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FRENCH FRY AS METAPHOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Manhattan,  &UR; Firat Yener  &LR; forwards a clipping from the
New York Post, in which supermodel  &UR; Irina Pantaeva &LR;  describes her
``love affair with the American french fry,'' which started when
she arrived in Manhattan, hoping ``that some day I would be able to
afford as many french fries as I wanted. ... They were like my
life: simple and unpretentious, full of struggle and promise.''
</P>
<P>
   As her career took off, writes Pantaeva, she was able to eat in
fancy restaurants ``where I could see the movie stars and
celebrities sitting across the room and enjoying fries just like
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``French fries unify old and young,'' she writes, ``rich and
poor; they are everywhere, shining its (sic) golden light on our
life, making it easy to digest the days, simplify the choices while
extending their welcome to breakfast, lunch and dinner. ... The
mighty french fries! One can only admire them.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Melissa Calavan &LR; , a high school student, writes to say
that when her grandmother gave her and her sister a card last
Christmas from the Heifer Project International ``saying that she
had donated a llama to some hungry person in our name,'' they were
horrified to think that the llama would be eaten. (Its purpose was
to aid in farmwork.) But is there any justice in the avian world?
The Audubon Society is serving grilled chicken at its Mother's Day
Barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Sharon Braz  &LR; overheard a fellow BART passenger speaking on a
cell phone in Chinese, her voice getting louder and angrier as the
conversation continued. ``It became impossible to ignore her,''
writes Braz. ``More and more of the riders began to stare, since
her voice was rather intrusive.'' When she hung up at the end of
the conversation, she noticed the people staring, smiled and said
in English, ``It was my mother.'' The eavesdroppers nodded, writes
Braz, in instant understanding.
</P>
<P>
   - On her TV special last week about great women of the 20th
century,  &UR; Barbara Walters  &LR; asked  &UR; Jane Fonda &LR;  what woman had
influenced her the most. &UR; Coco Chanel &LR; , answered Fonda, who has
metamorphosed from actress to political activist to exercise
dervish to model wife. ``She freed us from the corset. Women don't
pass out today.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Lamar Alexander &LR;  revealed to the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette that
he used peroxide to color his hair orange _ the color of the
Tennessee Vols _ when he was a teen- &LR; ager, but he said his rebel
phase was not serious, and ``I didn't get arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   - If you want to know what good taste is right now, Elle
magazine advises, ``Crunch something. It's not about creamy or
chewy anymore.'' That's one more reason  &UR; Dennis Elliott &LR;  should
have stayed away from that Clover Stornetta chocolate milk he
bought recently that carried an expiration date of May 4, 1959.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Isaac Mizrahi &LR; , who closed his clothing business last year,
is previewing a cabaret show in New York this week. He hopes to
open off-Broadway in the fall, says the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE DRINK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Robert Kennedy Jr. &LR; , environmental lawyer, told New York
magazine that he believes in the Newman's Own brand of bottled
water, sold by  &UR; Paul Newman &LR; , because he thinks that the public has
a right to potable tap water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a political choice to drink bottled water,'' he said.
``We felt that this was the best place to educate the consumer that
we can't turn our backs on the public water supply.'' Selling
bottled water helps save tap water, he explained, sort of. ``It's
like diverting money from private schools back into the public
schools. I drink New York City tap water.''
</P>
<P>
   - Reading the newsletter of Poipu Ocean View Resorts Inc.,
 &UR; Richard O'Lone &LR;  came upon that company's plans to create a $14
million water park in Oahu, bringing to that desolate place
``waterfalls, lagoons and island vegetation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sliding pay scale. It's about putting butts into seats.
... They could have put anybody in `Jurassic Park.' The dinosaurs
were the stars of that one. `Die Hard' is a Bruce Willis vehicle,
and that's cool _ I knew that going in. But it could have been a
run-of-the-mill chase movie. Put people like me and Jeremy Irons in
it, and you have real human beings alongside that superman, John
McClane. So we do bring something to the party.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Samuel L. Jackson &LR;  assessing his roles in the movies, in
Playboy. Jackson has appeared in the '90s in movies that have
earned a total of $1.2 billion, more than any other actor's movies
have earned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
