<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST UPDATE
 &HT;    EDS: Adds: KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY, POW-RETURN
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CoxNet Cox News Service budget
 &HT;    FOR MONDAY, May 3, 1999
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For questions, please call 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Chante LaGon at 404 526-5456
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Elliott Jaspin at 202-887-8346
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton was scheduled
to meet Monday with Russia's Balkan envoy Victor Chernomyrdin over
the search for a diplomatic end to NATO's air war against
Yugoslavia, as Clinton's top Russia hand hinted at U.S. flexibility
on the composition of a Kosovo peacekeeping force, the central area
of disagreement between Moscow and Washington. Even as three
American captives were released in Belgrade Sunday, NATO stepped up
its attacks on military targets and Yugoslav tanks and troops in
the field. (Deans, Cox News Service) 20.
</P>
<P>
   POW-RETURN _ RAMSTEIN, Germany _ The three released POWs are in
good physical condition and say they were well-treated by their
Serb captors. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-WRAPUP _ DENVER _ The mood of the last day of the Star
Wars celebration and an evaluation of the level of enthusiasm for
the upcoming movie. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 15. ETA 4 p.m.
EDT. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   COPYCATS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ SWAT teams and bomb disposal
squads are showing up on school grounds with the regularity of
visiting football teams. Parents are wondering if the school year
is effectively finished. Teachers watch warily for bulging back
packs. Students look over their shoulders. Since the Colorado high
school massacre 13 days ago, more than a dozen Florida middle and
high school students have been questioned by police after making
specific threats to blow up or shoot teachers and students. Several
were suspended, a few arrested. Across the country, hundreds of
bomb threats have been reported at schools. A monotonous litany of
copycat calls and written warnings kept thousands out of class. On
Friday, many schools closed because of rumored violence, some tied
to the anniversary of Hitler's suicide. All of these incidents are
news because they affected families and educators in communities
coast to coast. Still, questions must be asked about how direct a
connection there is between each incident and the shootings at
Columbine High. (Reid, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   with WEBKIDS _ Is the Web really bad for our kids? (Kalaijian,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON-ACCORDS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It seems like ever since war
broke out between NATO and Yugoslavia, the reputation of the Dayton
Peace Accords has deteriorated. Whereas once the word ``Dayton''
was most typically a positive one in the context of international
relations, it now often has a negative vibe. Whereas once it was a
symbol of peace and successful diplomacy, now it is a symbol of
failed hopes, of how not to do things. (Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ This session shows support for
vouchers to be ghostly transparent, and now lawmakers know how
deeply support runs for public schools. (John Young is opinion page
editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ This column will not move today.
(Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
