<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-COX     05-02 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire, hot Tatis start week in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The St. Louis Cardinals bring their history-making
home run hitter to town tonight for a three-game series against the
Braves. But things are different this time.
</P>
<P>
   No one has asked for a pre-game press conference with Fernando
Tatis.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that McGwire guy is still around. But the Cardinal making
headlines now is third baseman Fernando Tatis, who made history a
week ago in Los Angeles by hitting two grand slams in the same
inning.
</P>
<P>
   He's among the National League home run leaders with eight.
McGwire, who set the all-time home run mark with 70 last season,
has a rather ordinary five in the first 22 games this year. No
matter, the Braves still expect huge crowds for Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Already, one fan has called the Braves to find out if the
Cardinals will be taking batting practice. Answer: Yes, the
visitors will hit today and Tuesday at 6:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are still available. Ticket manager Paul Adams said the
Braves are already looking at 36,000 for both Monday and Tuesday
nights and more than 43,000 for Wednesday's 1:10 p.m. business
man's special.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's three-game series in August against St. Louis set an
all-time Atlanta attendance record of 150,096. The first game of
that series ranks as the fifth-largest crowd (50,662) at Turner
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they get here, there'll be a different kind of excitement
because Mac is here,'' said Braves pitcher Tom Glavine, who will
start tonight against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did last year is forever and that'll bring attention
to him wherever he goes,'' Glavine said. ``We expect as players
that there'll be a lot more excitement here and people rooting for
McGwire, that kind of stuff, just like they were last year. But the
fact they're coming here so early probably takes a little bit of
the luster off what it was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the series does have center fielder Brian Jordan's
attention. He played for the Cards last year. ``It'll be nice to
see my old teammates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be seeing an improved Cards team. St. Louis jumped off to
a good start with some surprisingly effective pitching. Kent
Bottenfield is 4-0 with a league-leading 1.53 earned run average.
Jose Jimenez, who pitches against Glavine tonight, is 2-1 despite a
5.40 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Mac, whose homer on opening day did not indicate
he'd struggle through April?
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, Mac will warm up,'' Jordan said. ``He's a
great-enough hitter that he makes adjustments, works really hard.
Mac will be there in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
