<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ELWAY-RETIRES-COX     05-02 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-RETIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elway bows out on top as retirement announced
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Over 16 seasons John Elway performed with the
dispassionate precision of a surgeon, rallying the Denver Broncos
to comeback victories a league-record 47 times either in the fourth
quarter or overtime. When it came time for the final end-game
gambit of his storied career, however, Elway could no longer
control his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   For all his celebrated improvisational abilities, Elway on
Sunday afternoon finally got caught in a pressure situation the
quarterback couldn't calmly scramble beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a bet to Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski over how many
times he would cry during his official retirement announcement, the
future Hall of Fame passer tearfully acknowledged that the
worst-kept secret of the past week certainly represented the
best-case scenario for he and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never want to stop competing, but I just can't compete in
this game anymore at the level I need to,'' said Elway, who fought
back tears right from the start of a 30-minute press conference.
''I just can't do it physically anymore . . . and that's really
hard for me to admit. For 16 years, though, my family has focused
their lives around football. Now it's time for our lives to focus
around them.''
</P>
<P>
   In consummating a decision Elway revealed to close friends two
weeks ago, but which he delayed making public out of deference to
the victims of the masscare at Columbine High School, he opted for
health over the potential of becoming the first quarterback to win
three straight Super Bowl titles. Despite missing only 15 games to
injuries during his career, Elway, who turns 39 next month,
underwent 12 surgeries. While his career is marked by gaudy passing
statistics, a number that cannot be ignored is that he also was
sacked an NFL-record 559 times.
</P>
<P>
   The past two seasons alone, Elway was forced to overcome
shoulder, biceps, ankle, rib and hamstring injuries and several
doctors have advised that he eventually will require knee
replacement surgery. In addition, his wife Janet last summer had
extensive colon surgery and her lengthy recovery was difficult on
the couple and their four children.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife and children, Elway was joined by his mother
and father, owner Pat Bowlen, coach Mike Shanahan and dozens of
teammates past and present for a moment everyone has known was
coming for the past week. For father Jack Elway, who coached his
son at Stanford, the moment was both bittersweet and balanced.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my opinion,'' Jack Elway said, ''he could have played at a
high level for several more years. But to see what he's been
through the last few seasons, this is understandable. Sixteen years
in this league is a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically the retirement came on the 16th anniversary of the
May 2, 1983 trade that sent Elway, the first selection in that
year's draft, from the then-Baltimore Colts to the Broncos. In
attendance Sunday was former Broncos owner Edgar Kaiser, who made
the swap with late Colts owner Robert Irsay, a man personally
angered by Elway's vow that he would never play in Baltimore. In
exchange for Elway, the Colts received career backup quarterback
Mark Herrmann, standout offensive tackle Chris Hinton and Denver's
top pick in the 1984 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trade, the Colts have won just 98 games and never
advanced to a Super Bowl. By comparison, Elway holds the NFL record
for regular-season victories by a starting quarterback (148) and
Super Bowl starts (five). Still, his brilliant tenure was
overshadowed by frustration and his Super Bowl failures until the
last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ''Winning those Super Bowls kind of sprinkled him with
stardust,'' said New York Giants general manager Ernie Accorsi, who
held the same position with Baltimore in 1983 and opposed Irsay on
the trade.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus is Elway ranks among the top six quarterbacks of
the modern era and Hall of Fame coach Sid Gillman, arguably the
father of the sophisticated aerial game, rates him the most
talented athlete at the position. It was trademark competitiveness,
though, which marked Elway's career.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being out there on Sunday afternoons, with the game on the
line and having to make a big play, that's what I'll miss the
most,'' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway through the years
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
