<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TRADEMARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. GROUP SUGGESTS NEW TRADEMARK PROTECTIONS FOR INTERNET
ADDRESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Fla.)  (rk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speculating in the registration and resale of
potentially valuable Internet addresses would effectively be
outlawed under new rules proposed by the intellectual property body
of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would also give companies and people with claims to
famous words or trademarks first claim to certain Internet
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations, issued Friday evening to the Internet Corp.
for Assigned Names and Numbers, are the first attempt by any
official body to draft an international set of rules to combat the
much-maligned practice commonly referred to as cybersquatting.
</P>
<P>
   The report was requested by the Clinton administration last year
when it handed oversight of the Internet's addressing system to the
corporation, an international nonprofit organization known as
Icann.
</P>
<P>
   Icann will take public comment on the recommendations, then
begin reviewing them at its next meeting, May 25, in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing a universal framework for disputes over Internet
addresses, or domains, is a priority for Icann. The group is in the
process of opening the business of registering domain names to
competition, and Icann eventually plans to expand the number of
so-called top-level domains beyond the current ones, which include
.com, .net and .org.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, there have been disputes after domain names like
McDonalds.com, have been registered to parties other than the
trademark holders.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of disputes over coveted names in the .com,
.net and .org registrations are largely believed to have peaked,
companies and trademark holders are worried about a renewed
cyberspace land rush when Icann starts adding new domains.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which is the result of a nearly yearlong process,
recommends that Icann require anyone who registers for an Internet
domain first sign a contract that would define and bar ``abusive''
registration practices and would lay out the principles for
resolving accusations of cybersquatting.
</P>
<P>
   Under that contract, people accused of infringing on trademarks
or trying to peddle names for profit would be subject to a
mandatory arbitration process that could strip them of their
domains and require them to pay any fees incurred in resolving the
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases _ such as those between companies or people with
similar names or claims to the same domains _ would go either to
voluntary arbitration or to courts in the country where the domain
name holder and company that registered it are based.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations are aimed at ``the most egregious problems
between intellectual property and domain names and at obtaining
effective solutions to those problems,'' said the 112-page report,
which the U.N.'s World Intellectual Property Organization posted on
its Web site (www.wipo.org) Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report takes more narrow aim at abusive
registration practices than a first draft issued by the U.N. body
late last year, critics say it still would give wealthy
corporations and trademark holders a new framework for laying claim
to property in what until now has been a free-wheeling arena where
the watchword was first come, first served.
</P>
<P>
   Others are concerned with a provision that recommends that Icann
establish a list of trademarks and other ``famous or well-known
marks'' that would be off limits to registration by the average
Internet user.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is there is no definition of internationally
famous marks,'' said Michael A. Froomkin, a University of Miami law
professor who served on a panel of experts that made
recommendations to the U.N. group.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Oppedahl, a trademark lawyer in Frisco, Colo., described
the exclusionary list as ``WIPO's biggest blunder,'' which he
predicted would ``lead to endless acrimony and struggle as owners
of nonunique, noncoined trademarks manage to get their trademarks
on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, though, Froomkin _ who had been a harsh critic of the
earlier draft of the report _ said Friday's version was ``a good
faith effort to distinguish between what is true cybersquatting and
what is not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
