<SLUG> BC-REVISIONS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IMAGES ASSAIL, BUT ADVENTURE IS STILL AN OPEN BOOK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When people hold forth about the death of literature, I will
recall a series of lovely cemeteries I drove past in Mexico
recently, small fenced-in spaces with white headstones and brightly
colored decorations. They were clearly meant to be part of
everyone's everyday life, and the same is true of literature.
</P>
<P>
   We know that good and great works exist somewhere in the general
consciousness; in this classroom, library or street stall; as tome,
paperback or disk, or in the indiscriminate heap of our memories
where we would sometimes want to express ourselves in nothing but
the words of writers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a practice I find very comforting, especially in grimmer
moments. Self-reproach for instance: ``I was right not to be afraid
of any thief but myself, who will end by leaving me nothing.''
(Katherine Anne Porter.) Self-pity: Elizabeth Bishop's ``Pity
should begin at home.'' Or if that's insufficient, William Cowper's
more florid ``But I beneath a rougher sea/And whelm'd in deeper
gulphs than he.'' And for longing of a nonhuman kind, ``There is in
God (some say)/A deep, but dazzling darkness'' (Henry Vaughan).
</P>
<P>
   I don't worry that we live, as everyone says, in a culture of
images. I loathe plenty of them, but no more than I loathe plenty
of what I read. A little historical distance helps.
</P>
<P>
   Rereading Vachel Lindsay's 1915 book on film, ``The Art of the
Moving Picture'' (portentous but also gloriously smart), it was
useful to be reminded that the United States was still in its
visual infancy when the century began. Compared with the rest of
Europe, Lindsay said, England and the United States were
word-driven cultures. Public libraries were for the masses, museums
for the privileged. But when the movies arrived, masses began to
think in pictures. ``Edison is the new Gutenberg,'' Lindsay
proclaimed. ``He has invented the new printing.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's say then that movies have been as important to America's
artists as the Renaissance was to Europe's and stop brooding so
about the effect of film (and television and video) on literature.
Anyway, our obsession with words is always making itself felt.
Critics imported the highly literary auteur theory from France to
help us start treating film as an art form.
</P>
<P>
   Then we did the same thing with rock music. The first generation
of rock critics tended to be literature graduates who regularly
crowned their favorite performers with mythological and literary
allusions. It is still the ostentatiously verbal that most excites
rock critics and fans; the bardic balladeering of folk rock and the
rhymed rapacities of rap. (Strange, how potent cheap alliteration
is!) We sometimes overlook serious literature, and we certainly
have our struggles with literacy, but we are intensely verbal, and
we are always reading in some form or another.
</P>
<P>
   Part of our anxiety about the future of books and literature
must have to do with the anxieties of living on the technological
edge. Computers, CD-ROM's, E-books. We have to wonder whether they
will change the nature of how we perceive and learn. But again,
history is useful. Pick up a book like Alberto Manguel's ``History
of Reading,'' which is a leisurely ramble through the centuries
with readers and writers, both famous (Alexander the Great, St.
Augustine, Lady Murasaki) and obscure (monks, emancipated slaves,
young ladies sampling sentimental fiction). Then ask yourself if
the changes we are enduring are any greater than the shock of
moving from tablet to scroll to codex, from stone to papyrus,
woodcut block to reusable type and from scribes to printers.
</P>
<P>
   Computer screens, with their moving words and images and
symbols, are the link between our visual and literary cultures. You
sit alone at your screen, the solitary reader or writer. But go
online, visit a Web site, and you have entered a public space where
all kinds of information is being dispensed (as in a documentary or
newsreel), and all sorts of dramas are being enacted. You can't
really spend much time at a computer without knowing you are part
of an invisible multitude: Everything you read or write can be
transmitted and shared within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   There is an urge now to make traditional book reading more
communal. Reading groups are everywhere; public readings
proliferate, and more and more writers see themselves as solo
performers in search of enraptured audiences, whether at poetry
slams or in small, diligently avant-garde spaces. There is a
19th-century quality to much of this: Think of all those young
women (reading groups are still made up largely of women)
exchanging romantic novels and talking about them excitedly. Think
of Ralph Waldo Emerson and Frederick Douglass, knocking them dead
on the Lyceum and Anti-Slavery Society circuits. And maybe because
we are so image saturated, that century-old excitement about
reading as a private and public act is being rediscovered.
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to be a reader in our culture. But it can be hard
to admit how many kinds of readers exist inside you. What about
that magazine with the same title as a famous novel by William
Thackeray, the one so many people claim they read only on airplanes
or in public places? (``I wash my hands afterward,'' a colleague
claims.) Then there is the book (is it by John Grisham? Robert
Ludlam?) that intense mental effort or emotional pressure may drive
you to pick up. (``The prose is horrible, but he can tell a
story,'' a friend in the throes of Ludlam told me. ``I hate
myself.'')
</P>
<P>
   The ever-obsessed and ever-astute D.H. Lawrence was clearly
right when he compared reading with a furtive sexual experience;
his word was onanism, but a trashy pickup will do just as well.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally you have a respectable bourgeois inside you who
responds with high-minded enthusiasm to some of the most important
books from your college reading syllabuses. With luck there is a
passion for some kind of genre writing. For it does what
storytelling used to: Its conventions provide us with deep
nonverbal satisfaction in advance. We know what we need, and we
know we will get it, just as people centuries ago knew what they
would get from ``The Odyssey,'' ``The Arabian Nights'' or any local
fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope we all have a curious iconoclast inside us, a reader
who wanders through fiction and nonfiction looking for worlds
elsewhere, for writing that provides a peculiar blend of the
selfless _ we surrender our imaginative lives to the life of the
book _ and the selfish. Thus we shape every line to our minutest
social and psychological needs. Every book alters this blend. Some
bring out everything mean and competitive in our imaginations. But
with the ones that matter most we transcend our everyday selves and
start to speak a richer, fuller language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
