<SLUG> BC-DIET-DRUG-HMO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGED CARE FIRMS TO RESTRICT COVERAGE FOR NEW DIET DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.) (mk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who hope to slim down with the help of Xenical, a newly
approved weight-loss drug, may have to pay for it themselves. A
number of managed care companies are categorizing Xenical as a
lifestyle product that they will cover only in exceptional cases _
for overweight people at risk for cardiovascular problems, or those
with diabetes, breathing problems or brittle bones.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, analysts said, many people are likely to pay the $4 or
$5 a day themselves needed to buy Xenical, a treatment made by
Roche Holding AG of Switzerland. Analysts projected peak worldwide
sales of the drug at $600 million to as much as $3 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Xenical, which the Food and Drug Administration approved last
Monday, is expected to go on sale in the United States in a few
weeks. It has already earned $100 million in sales in Europe this
year and could reach $3 billion annually in five years, said Samuel
Isaly, an analyst with Orbimed Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Xenical will not be covered as ``a lifestyle drug for someone
who wants to lose 10 pounds for a wedding,'' said Deborah Bohren, a
spokeswoman in New York for Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Sweig, an analyst with Southeast Research Partners, said,
``The slim, thin and lovely crowd will want to abuse this drug.''
Dr. W. Allen Schaffer, chief medical officer at Cigna Healthcare,
said that Cigna specifically excluded diet pills, along with
Rogaine and Propecia to grow hair and Renova, an anti-wrinkle
treatment. But Xenical might be covered, he said, as part of a
behavior modification program that increased its effectiveness, as
happened with smoking-cessation treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In tests, patients lost 5 percent to 10 percent of their weight
after taking Xenical for a year. ``For severely obese patients,
every little bit helps,'' said Viren Mehta, an analyst with Mehta
Partners. ``For the rest of the population, the cost benefit is far
from clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Several insurance executives compared Xenical to Viagra, Pfizer
Inc.'s widely publicized impotence treatment. Typically, these
insurers pay for Viagra only in limited amounts _ six pills each
month _ and only for men who have erectile dysfunction caused by
surgery or other medical causes. On that basis, their costs for
Viagra have been less than had been forecast. Sweig said that less
than half of the Viagra sales of $981 million in its first 12
months were covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Wellpoint Health Networks, which owns Blue Cross of California,
spent less than two-tenths of 1 percent of its $400 million annual
drug budget for Viagra, said Robert Seidman, a Wellpoint vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company would cover Xenical only for people with a
body mass index greater than 35, a technical measure that would
place a person in the severely obese category _ for example, 260
pounds for a person 6 feet tall or 197 pounds for a person 5 feet 3
inches tall. A body mass index of 25 signals a person is overweight
_ 141 pounds for a person 5 foot 3 _ and obesity begins at 30,
meaning a weight of 169 pounds for a person 5 foot 3.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford Health Plans covers weight-loss drugs only for a few
groups that pay extra for the coverage, said Richard Wool, a
spokesman for Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Several managed care companies, including Kaiser Permanente and
Aetna U.S. Healthcare, said their Xenical policies would not be set
for several months, pending reviews of its benefits by committees
of doctors and pharmacists. Doctors at Kaiser could request an
exception ``for a medical necessity,'' said Beverly Hayon, a
spokeswoman for Kaiser, which is based in California.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care executives said side effects of the drug could be a
concern. Schaffer at Cigna said that Xenical worked by lowering fat
intake, affecting vitamins, too. ``People could end up with vitamin
deficiencies, in addition to diarrhea, which is also a side
effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers who developed the drug said that people who
achieved a more biologically acceptable weight would be healthier
and might be less likely to incur diseases that are expensive to
treat. And the drug is now being tested in Scandinavia as a therapy
for diabetic patients, regardless of their weight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
