<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves unaccustomed to rash of errors
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With two more errors Sunday, the Braves have committed
18 errors in their first 24 games. This is not an epidemic.
Montreal has already committed 30.
</P>
<P>
   But for a team that led the league in fielding last season and
committed a franchise record low 91 misplays, the feeling is an
unusual one. With third baseman Chipper Jones making throwing error
in the second inning and letting an Aaron Boone grounder go through
his legs in the fourth, the infield has made seven errors in its
last five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys who have fielding averages of .960, .970 for their career
are going to field .960 and .970,'' said Jones, who fielded a
career-high .971 last year. ``We haven't played that well
defensively for a pretty good stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not a big deal. I'm sure we'll go a period where we
play very good for 20 or 25 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss accounted four three errors in his last four starts and
now has five in 22 games, almost half of the 12 errors he made in
96 games a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think errors are contagious,'' said Weiss, a career
.971 fielder at shortstop. ``Just one of those things. It all evens
out in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Bro'
</P>
<P>
   Sunday marked the first time the Boone brothers ever opposed
each other on any level of competition, dating back all the way
through Little League. Until 1997 when they were united by the
Reds, they had never played on the same team together (Bret Boone
is four years older than Reds third baseman Aaron Boone), though
both played collegiately at the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my brother and I want to see him do well,'' Bret Boone
said. ``I don't him to beat us with a big hit. That's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer ready
</P>
<P>
   Russ Springer finally allowed a run in his sixth re-hab
appearance at Class AAA Richmond, but while he has demonstrated he
is ready to return to the Atlanta pen, the Braves remain
uncommitted to calling him up. He can spend up to 30 days on injury
rehab assignment, which expires for Spring May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Springer has allowed one run and just three hits in seven
innings, striking out six of the 24 batters he has faced while
walking no one.
</P>
<P>
   Marking time
</P>
<P>
   The Reds were aghast at Mark Wohlers' first minor league
appearance Sunday, when he pitched for Class AAA Indianapolis at
Toledo. Wohlers lasted one-third of an innings, allowing a hit,
five walks, four wild pitches and three runs. He left the game with
the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers threw just nine strikes with 13 balls. Toledo batters
swung just three times, all three of those by ex-Brave Luis
Polonia.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Reds centerfielder Mike Cameron, who played baseball and
football at LaGrange High School, did not have the homecoming he
envisioned in his first series in his home state. Camero went
0-for-11 for the series with six strikeouts. He did however make a
superb running catch in the fourth Sunday, taking away an
extra-bases shot by Chipper Jones. . . . For the record, the last
Brave before Chipper Jones Saturday night to hit home runs from
both side of the plate in the same game was Jim Russell, who did it
for Boston on June 7, 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
