<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves sweep Reds in 3-game series
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ History cast its first judgement Sunday upon the trade
that brought Bret Boone to Atlanta and sent Denny Neagle away. The
record notes that Neagle was bleeding from the ears before anyone
could begin to digest brunch.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves concluded a three-game sweep of Cincinnati with a 5-3
victory before 47,097 at Turner Field where the team has won nine
times in its first 13 dates. Rookie Odalis Perez (1-1) won his
first game as a member of the rotation, as all five starters have
now won in five consecutive starts, a first since Sept. 16-20,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams hits a solo homer and Javy Lopez struck two RBI
doubles off his old batterymate. Neagle did not last the third
inning in his shortest starting appearance in six years, retiring
just seven of the 14 men he faced and allowing four runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who you're facing,'' said Neagle, winless in
three starts as a Red with his ERA up to 5.68. ``You make bad
pitches like that, they're going to get you. Even when I made good
pitches, they hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Boone was 2-for-4 while scoring twice, giving
him three runs scored and two RBI in his first series against his
old team. He hit .364 (4-for-11) over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of different,'' he said of the weekend. ``I was just on
the right team today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won their season-high fifth straight and their eighth
game out of nine. Behind 3-0 after the first, the Reds never
recovered against Perez, who allowed five hits and two earned runs
while striking out seven and felt like he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We you have some support from the players, when they score
three or four runs, you might say, `I gotta do it,'' said the
rookie, who had given eight runs in his first 18 innings. ``They're
trying to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds wound up hitting .109 for the series with 25 strikeouts
to go with just 10 hits. Quietly, the bullpen has also contributed,
Braves relievers working seven scoreless innings and allowing just
two singles in the first six games of the homestand. John Rocker
recorded his second save of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our starters are going good and I think our bullpen's doing a
great job too,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``You're not going to hold
`em or pitch great every game but we did our share of good
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
