</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POW-RETURN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAPTURED U.S. SOLDIERS
 &HT;    FREE AT LAST' IN GERMANY
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN, Germany Hospital food probably never tasted so good as
three former POWs celebrated freedom with plates of hamburgers,
chicken and lasagna at an Army hospital here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The three U.S. soldiers, captured by Yugoslav forces and held
for more than a month, arrived Sunday to a heroes' welcome at
Ramstein Air Base, savoring their new freedom at an army hospital
where they are undergoing medical tests and military debriefings.
</P>
<P>
   Army doctors pronounced the three servicemen in reasonably good
health after an initial examination Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers -- Steven Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas;
Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; and Christopher Stone, 25, of
Smiths Creek, Mich. - were expected to be reunited Monday with
family members who were flying to Germany from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The servicemen arrived in Germany after an emotional, daylong
journey from Belgrade. Rev. Jesse Jackson, who negotiated their
release in an unofficial diplomatic mission to Yugoslavia,
accompanied them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not get any better than this!'' read an enormous
banner hung with yellow ribbons at the Ramstein Air Base, where
some 400 well-wishers greeted their military medical-transport jet.
</P>
<P>
   The day began in Belgrade with tearful telephone calls to family
members in the United States as Jackson and Yugoslav officials
signed documents authorizing their release. Later, Ramirez made his
first request, asking for a Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day as they crossed the border from Yugoslavia
into Croatia, the soldiers chanted with Jackson: ``Free at last,
free at last. Thank God almighty, we're free at last.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip by road from Serbia to Croatia and then by air to this
sprawling U.S. base was punctuated with tears, smiles and uneasy
questions about what their release may or may not mean to the
future of NATO's air war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson urged Clinton and other NATO leaders to respond to the
release as a goodwill gesture by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. and NATO officials declared that the soldiers' release
would not help a new diplomatic initiative by Russia's chief
mediator due in Washington today to meet with President Clinton or
prompt a halt in the intensifying NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added a sober note to the celebration over the soldiers'
release with a reminder of the plight of the ethnic Albanians from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we welcome our soldiers home, our thoughts also turn to the
over 1 million Kosovars who are unable to go home because of the
policies of the regime in Belgrade,'' Clinton said in a statement
released by the White House. ``Today we reaffirm our resolve to
persevere until they, too, can return with security and
self-government.''
</P>
<P>
   At Ramstein, Gonzales, Ramirez and Stone stepped off a C-9
military jet into the late afternoon sunshine to the cheers of the
large crowd of servicemen and families. Dressed in their green
camouflage combat fatigues and carrying folded American flags under
their arms, the ex-captives formed a line to salute an honor guard
from their 1st Infantry Division. They were then marched to two
army medical helicopters for the short flight to the Landstuhl
military hospital, where they are expected to remain for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial impression is that they are very happy to be back
and that they are very upbeat,'' said Col. Mack Blanton, chief of
clinical services in Landstuhl medical facility.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence of exposure to any sort of biological
weapons. There is also no evidence they were exposed to pressure
tactics or propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   The three were free from their Yugoslav captors, but not from
questions about the circumstances of their abduction and the
conditions of their confinement.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have insisted that the soldiers were on patrol
well inside the border of Macedonia when Serb forces seized them on
March 31. The following day, they were paraded on Serbian
television showing signs they had been battered on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   In debriefing the servicemen, military officials hope to learn
the details of how their routine border patrol went awry.
</P>
<P>
   Stone had said earlier on Sunday the bruises on his face were
the result of wounds suffered at the time of his capture.
</P>
<P>
   The mistreatment stopped after they were turned over to higher
Yugoslavian authorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the guards who watched them in the solitary-confinement
cells treated them well and earned a measure of respect from the
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaving them it was kind of sad knowing there is this war is
going on and they are left behind,'' said Stone. ``I hope that in
some way our release will lead to negotiations for peace,'' Stone
said to reporters at the airport in Zagreb, adding they had been
treated well in captivity. ``It's sad that this is happening and we
pray for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may meet with the three soldiers during a visit to
Germany on Wednesday. The president is scheduled to tour two U.S.
bases to meet combat pilots taking part in the NATO air campaign
and review humanitarian efforts to aid Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials said the soldiers Monday will undergo further
tests -- including psychological examinations -- and debriefings
before being reunited with their families. Afterward, they will be
offered a rest period in the United States, or can elect to rejoin
their unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are cavalry men and they pride themselves on their
toughness,'' said Col. Michael Sullivan, spokesman for the U.S.
Army in Europe. ``But we pride ourselves on a process that allows
them to depressurize.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
