<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-COX     05-02 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton To Meet Russian Envoy
 &HT;    But Yugoslav Bombing Continues
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON President Clinton agreed to meet here Monday with
Russia's envoy to the Balkans, Victor Chernomyrdin, signaling an
intensification of the search for a diplomatic end to NATO's air
war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Clinton is to meet with civil rights leader Rev.
Jesse Jackson, who called for a halt in the NATO strikes Sunday
after securing the release of three American soldiers from
captivity in Yugoslavia. Jackson said he is carrying a letter to
Clinton from Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, though, Clinton said air strikes would
continue as part of a broader NATO effort to combat a campaign of
repression that has forced an estimated 1.5 million ethnic
Albanians to flee their homes in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we welcome our soldiers home, our thoughts also turn to the
over 1 million Kosovars who are unable to go home because of the
policies of the regime in Belgrade,'' the statement read in part.
``Today we reaffirm our resolve to persevere until they, too, can
return _ with security and self government.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials insisted that Monday's meeting with
Chernomyrdin arranged during a 15-minute telephone conversation
Sunday that Russian President Boris Yeltsin placed to Clinton was
not linked to the release of the Americans in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials spent much of Sunday, in fact, taking
pains to portray the prisoner release as a public relations ploy by
Milosevic to try to erode support within NATO countries for the
allied air strikes, now well into their sixth inconclusive week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a PR stunt,'' Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott
told the NBC television network. ``Milosevic is an absolute master
manipulator in this kind of game.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen said Milosevic earned no points
by releasing the soldiers and would receive no respite from the air
raids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not only not going to stop the bombing, we're going to
intensify the bombing,'' Cohen told NBC. ``We're prepared to wage
this campaign for some months to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the point, NATO pilots worked their way early
Monday through their fourth straight day of the most furious
attacks since the campaign began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of continuing clear skies, pilots pressed
strikes that resulted early Sunday in what Nato officials said was
the most effective assault to date directly on the Serb tanks,
troops and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is straightforward,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea
told reporters in Brussels, ``to cut them off, pin them down and
take them out so that they have no option but to leave Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   As air strikes escalated, so did diplomatic efforts, with
Clinton scheduled to leave Tuesday on a trip that will take him to
U.S. military bases across Germany and to NATO headquarters in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, Russia's former premier, was to meet with Vice
President Al Gore early Monday afternoon and to see Clinton late in
the day, said White House spokesman Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to hear him out,'' said Siewert, ``hear what he has to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting comes a day after Milosevic ordered the release of
three Americans Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths
Creek, Mich; Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; and
Spec. Steven Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas to Jackson, who
visited Belgrade on what the White House described as a personal
mission to try to win the soldiers' release.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation traveled overland from Yugoslavia's main state,
Serbia, to neighboring Croatia, then flew from there aboard a U.S.
C-9 Nightingale military medical plane to an Army base in Germany,
where the former captives were being held overnight for a medical
examination.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Clinton should reward Belgrade by calling a halt to
the NATO bombing and sitting down with Milosevic face to face to
negotiate peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let them go,'' Jackson told the ABC television network.
``Let's celebrate that and let's seize an opportunity to move
toward diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson, ``a diplomatic gesture should get a diplomatic
response.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott, though, made clear that the United States did not
regard Jackson's personal mission as diplomatic and that it would
not result in U.S. reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't characterize what Reverend Jackson did here as
free-lance diplomacy,'' Talbott said. ``He went with one objective
above all others, and that was to get the three servicemen out, and
he succeeded in that.''
</P>
<P>
   He called a meeting between Clinton and Milosevic, ``unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid such talk, there were fresh reminders of the risks the
continuing strikes pose to all parties.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials admitted Sunday that a strike on a bridge at
Lusana, some 12 miles north of Kosovo's capital of Pristina,
destroyed a bus loaded with civilians. The Yugoslav Foreign
Ministry said 47 people - some of them children - were killed and
17 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Conrad Freytag, a NATO military spokesman, said the bridge
``was a legitimate military target,'' as it was used by Serb forces
to resupply units inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The bus was not targeted, Freytag said, but crossed over the
bridge after a NATO pilot had released a bomb aimed for the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any loss of innocent life,'' Freytag said, ``is regretted.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, an American pilot ditched his F-16 fighter inside
Serbian territory early Sunday due to engine failure. The pilot
ejected and was recovered within two hours by a U.S. rescue team,
according to a Pentagon statement, which described the pilot as
being in good condition and said the cause of the malfunction was
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   And a British Harrier attack jet flying what NATO described as a
training mission in support of Operation Allied Force went down in
the Adriatic Sea for reasons that were also under investigation.
The pilot ejected and was rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen cast the release of the American soldiers as an attempt by
Milosevic to change the subject after army and police forces under
his command have gone on a rampage across Kosovo, executing an
estimated 4,000 ethnic Albanians and running another 1.5 million
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has characterized the activity as a crack down on
Albanian terrorists that got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gesture, if one can call it, of good will on his part
cannot obliterate or overcome the stench of evil and death that has
been inflicted in those killing fields in Kosovo,'' said Cohen.
``Under these circumstances, we have to keep our focus on what
Milosevic has done, continues to do, and what he has to do in order
to stop the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO has demanded that Milosevic meet five terms before the
bombing will end:
</P>
<P>
   stop the repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   withdraw Serb forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   permit the introduction of a heavily-armed peacekeeping force
with NATO at its core.
</P>
<P>
   guarantee the safe return of all refugees.
</P>
<P>
   return to Kosovo the political autonomy it enjoyed before
Milosevic stripped the province of that autonomy in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of those demands, the United States has
been working closely with Russia which has close historical and
cultural ties with its Slavic kin, the Serbs to try to hammer out
an arrangement Milosevic might accept.
</P>
<P>
   He has agreed, in principal at least, to withdraw all except
12,000 of his forces from Kosovo a position the U.S. government has
rejected as insufficient but has refused to allow a NATO force into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott, Clinton's top Russia hand, hinted at U.S. flexibility
over the force - the central issue dividing Washington and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott said such a force might be operated under the auspices
of the United Nations, if Russia agrees to allow NATO to lead the
peacekeepers. Russia is one of five permanent veto-wielding members
of the U.N. Security Council, so it's acquiescence would be
required for such a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual modalities can be discussed,'' Talbott told the NBC
television network, ``as long as there will be NATO at the core and
it will have NATO command and control.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
