<HEADLINE>
SOUP AND SALAD FOLLOW GOURMAND CRUISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent meal aboard the Rhine cruise-boat Symphony was planned
and executed by a visiting, three-star French chef named Marc
Haeberlin.
</P>
<P>
   It began with an amuse bouche (literally, an amusement for the
mouth) consisting of snails and broth in a demitasse cup. The meal
also featured cubes of duck and vegetables la glee, a petite salad,
a portion of liver terrine, lobster cubes in a pearl barley soup,
roast lamb with wild mushrooms, Muenster-cheese potatoes and a
black-olive sauce, an assortment of French cheeses, then a spiced
charlotte with fresh fruits and a rich sabayon sauce, followed by
coffee and assorted petit fours.
</P>
<P>
   It recalled to mind the first ``cruise'' undertaken by Your
Obdt. Correspondent, aboard a troop ship headed for Korea. The chef
amused our mouths with a concoction he called ``saute on a
shingle,'' or something like that. His other specialty, served
standing up during North Pacific storms, was Chili Mal de Mer.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way, baby.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 10 Seattle residents recently lived the good life
aboard the Symphony and then _ after an interlude in Nancy and
Munich _ joined 24 others from this area aboard the Mozart for a
seven-day cruise on the Danube.
</P>
<P>
   There were 19 cooks and helpers on the Mozart's kitchen staff.
Soup stocks and sauces were all created from scratch, bread and
desserts were baked daily, there were fresh fruits and vegetables
from South Africa, Israel and Spain, and a changing menu reflected
the boat's progress up the river and through the locks past Vienna,
Budapest, Bratislava and several other ports of call.
</P>
<P>
   One meal began with assorted seafood appetizers and progressed
through duckling soup with mandarins, a lobster-shrimp-salmon
strudel with Nantua sauce and wild rice, a Kir Royal sorbet, slices
of veal with port wine sauce, vegetables and individual potato
souffles, then cheese tartlets, baked Alaska with sabayon sauce, a
cheese course and, finally, coffee with freshly made truffle
chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the kitchen's supply of ``saute on a shingle'' had
been exhausted before we came aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Both river boats also featured buffet breakfasts, four- and
five-course lunches, tea with pastries at 4 p.m., and a midnight
buffet snack. After awhile soup and salad sounded pretty good.
Particularly soups and salads like these.
</P>
<P>
   Soup Budapest
</P>
<P>
   7 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   half-cup rice
</P>
<P>
   1medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 carrots, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 stalks celery, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cabbage, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup green beans
</P>
<P>
   6 leaves fresh minced sage or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half or low-fat evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chopped, cooked chicken or turkey meat
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   half-cup chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   You can substitute your own choice of veggies in place of the
cabbage and green beans. If you prefer zucchini and turnips, that
doesn't necessarily mean you are a bad person. Just misguided.
</P>
<P>
   OK, heat the broth to boiling in a large pot. Add the rice,
cover and simmer 10 minutes. Add the veggies and sage. Simmer
covered until done, maybe another 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan heat the butter or oil. Add the flour and stir
over low heat until smooth. Add a cup of the half-and-half and keep
stirring until you have a thick sauce. Stir this into the soup
along with the rest of the half-and-half.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the chicken chunks and the parsley. Reheat, then add
salt and pepper to taste and serve. This should make six to eight
portions but save room for those homemade truffles.
</P>
<P>
   Salad Vienna
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh or frozen green beans
</P>
<P>
   1 box frozen artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   half-cup sliced black olives
</P>
<P>
   half-cup sliced green olives
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 large tomato, cut in small cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 small green pepper, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   half-pound cheddar or other cheese, cubed
</P>
<P>
   two-thirds cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   Garlic powder to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cook and drain the beans and artichoke hearts, according to
package instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Dump the first eight ingredients in a bowl. Combine the oil and
vinegar and slop this gloop over the veggies as needed, one-quarter
cup at a time, saving the excess dressing for another salad.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the salad a couple of times then taste, and add salt,
pepper and garlic powder as needed. Serves six.
</P>
<P>
   One day, between a five-course lunch and a six-course dinner,
the hostess aboard the Symphony refereed a competition in which
couples tried to bust balloons by bumping their bellies together.
</P>
<P>
   See, that's why we ate so much. Like sumo wrestlers, we were in
training for international competition. It was sort of like a
little Olympics, with crepes and chocolate sauce available on the
sidelines between heats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
