<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-BOMBING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED IN LONDON ATTACKS AIMED AT MINORITIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British police charged a 22-year-old engineer with
murder Sunday after three crude and brutal nail-bomb attacks on
ethnic minorities and gays in recent days that killed three people,
wounded more than 100 and confronted Britons with a violent
challenge to their avowed tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Scotland Yard official, David Veness, said the bombing
suspect, identified as David Copeland, had acted alone and was not
associated with the neo-Nazi White Wolves and Combat 18 groups that
took responsibility for attacks that left Londoners on edge.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland was charged with three counts of murder and three
counts of causing an explosion with the intention of endangering
life.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers closed in on the Hampshire village of Cove,
southwest of London, early Saturday and made the arrest, hours
after a nail bomb exploded at the Admiral Duncan pub, a bar with a
largely gay clientele in London's Soho district.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that ``explosive materials'' had been found in
the modest, three-bedroom home they raided.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no suggestion at this stage that the arrest is linked
in any way to the extreme right-wing groups which have been
reportedly claiming responsibility for these attacks on innocent
people,'' Veness said. He did not go into detail about Copeland's
possible motives, citing legal restrictions on pretrial disclosure
of information that can influence the outcome of court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But Veness left no doubt that the police believe the man they
arrested carried out all three bombing attacks that appeared aimed
at harming Afro-Caribbean residents of Brixton, south London, on
April 17, Asian residents of Brick Lane, east London, one week
later, and gay people in Soho two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appeared, and still appears, to be no trigger event or
specific date which has sparked these attacks, which were clearly
the responsibility of the same person,'' Veness said. He said the
bombs used in all three attacks were ``relatively rudimentary''
devices about the size of a shoe box, made up of a timer, detonator
and explosives packed with nails and other shrapnel. Copeland is
scheduled to appear in court on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He was identified from closed-circuit television footage of a
young white man in a baseball cap recorded at a packed street
market in Brixton shortly before the first attack, on April 17. The
image was widely published in British newspapers in an effort to
identify the bomber.
</P>
<P>
   The police also publicly identified two of the three dead from
Friday night's blast in Soho as Andrea Dykes, 27, who was pregnant,
and John Light, 32, who had been the best man at her wedding two
years ago. Mrs. Dykes' husband, Julian, was critically injured and,
the police said, has not been told of the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The trio had been visiting London to go to the theater and had
stopped at the Admiral Duncan on their way there. Of the 73 people
injured in the blast, eight were said by hospital authorities to be
in critical condition Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is no stranger to far-right-wing organizations, from
pro-Nazi groups in the 1930s to groups such as the National Front
in the postwar era. But the supposition that right-wing extremists
had turned to violence had shaken many people and forced them to
ponder whether there had been a more basic shift in tactics among
far-right militants than had been assumed.
</P>
<P>
   Race relations _ particularly between black Britons and the
white-dominated police officers _ had been strained recently by an
official inquiry's conclusion that the police force had shown
racism in the investigation of the murder of a black teen-ager by a
white gang.
</P>
<P>
   Two thousand people gathered in Soho Sunday to attend a vigil
for the dead in Friday's bombing. Paul Boateng, a black legislator
and a minister in the Home Office, told them, ``I am here to say on
behalf of your government that there is nothing so precious to the
creation of the just, tolerant human society that is our objective
than to preserve by all means its inclusivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair addressed a gathering of Sikhs in
Birmingham, and likened his government's battle against prejudice
to NATO's campaign to stop Serbian authorities from hounding ethnic
Albanians to flee their homes in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one section of our community is under attack, we defend
them in the name of all the community,'' he said. ``When bombs
attack the black and Asian community in Britain, they attack the
whole of Britain. When the gay community is attacked and innocent
people are murdered, all the good people of Britain, whatever their
race, their life style, their class, unite in revulsion and
determination to bring the evil people to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true outcasts today, the true minorities, those truly
excluded are not the different races and religions of Britain, but
the racists, the bombers, the violent criminals who hate that
vision of Britain and try to destroy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
