<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS: RICE TO REMAIN SIDE DISH FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Glen Rice wants a greater role in the Los Angeles
Lakers' offense, but Sunday he was hampered only by his own
shooting woes.
</P>
<P>
   A day after voicing his displeasure with a diminished role in
the offense, Rice scored a season-low five points against the
Sonics. He missed his first seven shots and finished 2 of 10 from
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of finding him when he's open,'' coach Kurt
Rambis said. ``He's getting open, we're just not finding him right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   And when they are finding him, Rice is misfiring.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Rice said the Lakers haven't done enough to provide
him shots off of movement and screens and that it was hurting his
performance. Rambis said he's discussed the situation with Rice,
but said Rice needs to adjust to the Lakers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a two-way street. We have to learn to play with him, and
he has to learn to play within the structure of our team, too,''
Rambis said. ``He's gone from being the major go-to guy, to being
the second or third option sometimes in a lot of our offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna take him awhile to get used to that. It's gonna
take our players a while to get used to what he likes to do. With
the short season, the trade, no practice time, it's just not
conducive to players learning how to play together.''
</P>
<P>
   But this season is nearing a conclusion, and it's possible that
Rice, who said he's ``not OK'' with his situation, might not stick
around into next season to make the relationship work.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis said he ``absolutely, wholeheartedly'' understands Rice's
frustration, but said Rice has to develop a spot-up shooting game
instead of waiting for screens that might never come.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it all comes down to is all the players have to
understand they have to make sacrifices for the benefit of the
ballclub,'' Rambis said. ``If that means giving up part of their
game for the team and improving in areas where they haven't been
asked to perform on past teams or past years, that's something we
all have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange days indeed: Lakers-Sonics on the last Sunday of the
regular season _ normally, that's a battle for Pacific Division
supremacy. Instead, Portland won the division, the Lakers are
battling for the fourth seed and their victory Sunday might have
knocked the Sonics out of the playoffs for the first time in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Strange? ``Nothing's strange for this season,'' Robert Horry
said. ``Everything has been off the whole season _ 50 games, three
games in three nights. It's almost like this season if you thought
something might happen, it wouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Absent: Rookie swingman Ruben Patterson left the team to be with
an ill relative in Ohio and missed Sunday's game. The Lakers hope
he will return in time for tonight's home game against Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
