r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-LADN     05-02 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUKAS GETS A LEG UP IN RIVALRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Charismatic's 31-1 upset Saturday clinched the
Kentucky Derby Trainer of the '90s title for D. Wayne Lukas, who
won his third Derby in the decade as Bob Baffert failed to win a
record third straight.
</P>
<P>
   But the Derby result did nothing to cool the Lukas-Baffert
rivalry _ which is real in fans' eyes if not in the minds of the
two Southern California-based trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt a real rivalry with him,'' Lukas insisted
Sunday morning, calling it a press creation. ``First it was Woody
(Stephens) and I. Then it was Nick (Zito) and I. Now it's Baffert
and I. I've been around long enough to know these things come and
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas credited Charismatic owners Bob and Beverly Lewis of
Newport Beach _ who also won the 1997 Derby with Baffert-trained
Silver Charm _ for preventing animosity by dividing their horses
and attention between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that (rivalry) with Wayne,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   But a rivalry would be natural. Both Lukas, 63, and Baffert, 46,
came up through the quarterhorse ranks. Both are proud and
press-savvy. And, along with two-time Derby winner Zito of New
York, they have dominated America's most famous thoroughbred race
in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, each is intensely conscious of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Lukas, after asking reporters if anybody saw the ABC-TV
Derby coverage: ``Probably `The Bob Baffert Hour.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Here's Lukas on Charismatic's fast improvement after starting
the year in claiming races: ``Did I out-train those guys or what?
... Did that sound like Baffert?''
</P>
<P>
   Here's Baffert on the moment, as the Derby leaders stormed
through the Churchill Downs homestretch, when he realized the
Lewises' colt had a chance: ``First time I ever rooted for a Lukas
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Baffert gave the proper credit to Lukas, who was named to
the racing Hall of Fame earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows he should have been a Hall of Famer a long time
ago,'' Baffert said of Lukas' fourth Derby win. ``They should have
waived the (25-year eligibility) rule _ like (hockey is doing for
Wayne) Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the trainer of the '90s. The guy is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas says he misjudged Charismatic, a son of Summer Squall,
getting away with running him in a claiming race in February. He
also thinks he did one of his best training jobs, waking the
horse's potential with longer, faster workouts starting before his
fourth-place finish in the April 3 Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Before Charismatic's surprise, with jockey Chris Antley, Lukas
won the Kentucky Derby with the filly Winning Colors in '88 and
followed with Thunder Gulch in '95 and Grindstone in '96. The only
trainers with as many victories were Ben Jones (six between '38 and
'52) and Dick Thompson (four between '21 and '33).
</P>
<P>
   Lukas said matching Jones is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why not,'' he said. ``I'm healthy. I like what I'm
doing. I have the client base to get more good horses.''
</P>
<P>
   First things first: Lukas is aiming at the May 15 Preakness
Stakes in Baltimore with Charismatic and third-place Derby finisher
Cat Thief. He'll find that many of the Derby losers, coming out of
the roughly run race with good excuses, will try again in the
second leg of the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Pimlico Race Course officials listed 10 Derby starters as
``probable'' for the Preakness: Charismatic, Cat Thief, Menifee
(second), Prime Timber (fourth), Kimberlite Pipe (sixth), Worldly
Manner (seventh), Lemon Drop Kid (ninth), Stephen Got Even (14th),
Adonis (17th) and Vicar (18th). One Derby starter was ``possible'':
K One King (eighth).
</P>
<P>
   Expected to try to join the series were Kentucky Oaks winner
Silverbulletday, Derby Trial winner Patience Game, Gotham winner
Badge, Flamingo runner-up Forty One Carats, Tesio winner Talk's
Cheap and Maryland-based Millions. The Preakness is limited to 14
horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat everybody that showed up,'' Lukas said when asked if
the best horse won the Derby, in which most of the field ran into
traffic or had to race wide.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic was the 20th consecutive non-favorite to win the
Derby. Now, can he become the first Triple Crown winner since
Affirmed in '78?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to love the mile-and-a-half part,'' Lukas
said, looking ahead to the June 5 Belmont Stakes. ``If he can get
over the next one.'' The Preakness is 1 3/16 miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
