<HEADER>
A1457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-SPIN-670&AMP;ADD     05-02 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-SPIN-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: U.K.)  
 NATO BEEFS UP ITS PUBLIC-INFORMATION STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating for all needing)  
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO has called up reserves of spin in the
information battle over Kosovo, trying to take the initiative after
suffering earlier tactical reverses in news briefings in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The overall commander is still Jamie Shea, the gray-haired,
45-year-old Londoner who has personified the alliance's public face
to the world since the bombing of Yugoslavia began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past two weeks, Shea's original staff of six, tucked
away with support personnel behind the cafeteria, the bank and the
library, has been augmented by a multinational ``information
strategy cell'' of about 20 high-powered public officials.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are P.J. Crowley, a member of the White House
national security staff; Jonathan Prince, one of President
Clinton's speechwriters, and Alastair Campbell, Prime Minister Tony
Blair's spokesman, who commutes occasionally from London to
Brussels. Officials from France, Germany, the Netherlands and other
allied countries are expected to arrive within days.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long he expected to be here, Crowley said, ``My wife
asked me that question, too.'' Nobody knows, apparently, just as
nobody knows how long the war will last, but the information
strategy cell is already pumping out information from a secret war
room situated next to the North Atlantic Council, the
decision-making heart of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've helped enormously,'' said Shea, who became NATO
spokesman in 1993 but stumbled early in the air war, trying to
explain events like the bombing of a railroad bridge as a passenger
train started to cross, and later the mistaken bombing of ethnic
Albanian civilians fleeing Yugoslav military units on a road near
Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   The second attack, in mid-April, posed one of Shea's greatest
problems when precise and timely information proved difficult to
obtain from the NATO military command in Mons, Belgium, which, as
one new information officer remarked Friday, is not exactly joined
at the hip with the policy-making civilian side of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   After first acknowledging that NATO bombs might have killed
civilians north of Djakovica, Shea and an allied military spokesmen
then said for four days that they did not know what had actually
happened, and retracted an earlier statement about a bombing of the
road east of the town, where Serbian television had broadcast
pictures of carnage that it said was caused by allied bombs.
</P>
<P>
   It took until April 19 for Shea's boss, Secretary-General Javier
Solana, and the alliance's top military commander, Gen. Wesley
Clark, to sort out the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Daniel Leaf, of the U.S. Air Force, then took the
stand in Brussels to explain, in copious detail, how allied pilots
had indeed attacked what they thought was a Yugoslav military
convoy southeast of Djakovica and might have hit civilians by
mistake. That ended a daily barrage of reporters' questions about
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to that sequence, when Yugoslav news media reported
this week that NATO had bombed a civilian neighborhood in
Surdulica, the allies' new information machinery swung into
operation quickly. Officials say Campbell personally saw to it that
the military headquarters got an explanation for the bombing to
Shea within 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Shea, later backed up by a military spokesman,
Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Marani, told reporters that at least one
laser-guided bomb aimed at a military garrison had drifted off
target. Though Yugoslav officials said at least 20 people had been
killed at Surdulica, the accident never acquired the prominence of
Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   Shea now talks with Clark daily by telephone, something he had
been unable to do before all his new help arrived. He now holds
morning news briefings on overnight bombing attacks, including
accidents like the missile hit on a residential building in Sofia,
Bulgaria, on Wednesday night, in addition to the televised
briefings at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to get the message across better,'' a NATO
official said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Paris a French Foreign Ministry official said several
information officers with experience in the Balkans would be
dispatched to Brussels soon to help deliver the message of France's
extensive contribution to the bombing to news media besides those
in France.
</P>
<P>
   Shea, who never served a day in uniform because, he said,
Britain abolished compulsory military service when he was a small
boy, is actually a professor who still teaches at five institutions
in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``His students always rate him tops,'' said George Delcoigne, a
fellow professor at the Center of International and Strategic
Studies of the Free University of Brussels. ``He is friendly,
considerate and above all very entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea received a B.A. in modern history and French from Sussex
University in 1977 and a doctorate in modern history from Oxford
University (Lincoln College) in 1981. But he could hardly keep
racing out of NATO headquarters to go off and teach classes in the
middle of a war, so things have changed: Shea now has a small army
of specialists to help him concoct sound bites and focus the
alliance's message on the issues that its political masters want to
get across.
</P>
<P>
   That still sometimes seems to mean more information about what
the Yugoslavs are doing in Kosovo than about what the allies are
doing there, a peculiarity of these briefings since they began.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, for example, the briefing opened with a long
disquisition by Shea on what he said were cracks in the facade of
unity behind President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now over the last few weeks we have had an impression that the
support of President Milosevic is virtually total,'' he said,
``that the whole country is radicalized behind a form of extreme
nationalism, that there is no opposition, that nobody dares to
speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I believe that this unity, based on fear, is beginning to
fragment in Serbia today and that opposition from within the
country to the campaign of `ethnic cleansing' in Kosovo and to the
course of confrontation with the international community, that that
opposition is beginning to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea named Vuk Draskovic, a Yugoslav deputy prime minister; the
mayor of Kacak, Serbia, and the heads of two Serbian political
parties as figures who had dared to dissent, going on to cite
reports that nine Yugoslav generals had been placed under house
arrest and that morale was cracking in the Yugoslav armed forces,
claims that were echoed later the same day at apparently
coordinated news briefings in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But only an hour after Shea spoke, Draskovic was fired, and
later in the week American and NATO officials, speaking on
background, contradicted many of Shea's assertions about weakening
morale.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth in Belgrade, NATO's main public relations job
here, Shea says, is to tell as much as it can about its own
operations, which include not only the air war but also extensive
aid to the hundreds of thousands of refugees who have poured out of
Kosovo since the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   But, acknowledging the battering he has taken, he said the other
day, ``I think after this is all over I'll take a lesson in
humility and go back to teaching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
