<SLUG> BC-GEN-OFFBEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY INSPIRES PROSE, POETRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If John Elway taught us anything, it's how
important it is to read. Especially a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   (All right, so someone paid him to make that commercial. Like he
needed the money. But still, he had to say it).
</P>
<P>
   If Elway's retirement taught us anything, it's how important it
is not to read so much into it.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that Denver and the outlying areas are going
through a lot of pain. Some separation anxiety. Some feeling of
abandonment. But leave that for Columbine, guys.
</P>
<P>
   Here's some of what those who seem to care most deeply _ Denver
newspaper writers _ have tried to convey with their prose this week
about Elway's parting in such sweet ... aw, let 'em tell ya:
</P>
<P>
   _From Woody Paige of the Denver Post:
</P>
<P>
   ``What William Shakespeare could do with a quill pen and a piece
of paper, John Elway could do with a football and a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Let your indulgence set me free,' Shakespeare said, and
Elway proved ...
</P>
<P>
   `` `Let others judge me when I'm through,' (Elway) said. There
has been an occasional lapse on the field and off, a slip of the
ball or a slip of the tongue, but, like Michael Jordan and Wayne
Gretzky, Nobody Has Done It Better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parting, for the Bard and the Duke, is such sweet sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fare thee well, John.''
</P>
<P>
   _From Mark Kiszla of the Denver Post:
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye always comes too soon from somebody you love. And has
any city ever adored an athlete more than Denver cheered John
Elway? ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget all the statistics. The best way to measure Elway? He
left us wanting more ...
</P>
<P>
   ``America will have to find somebody new to root for ...
</P>
<P>
   ``A man must carry on, because life does. And so Elway goes
...''
</P>
<P>
   _From Alex Marvez of the Rocky Mountain News:
</P>
<P>
   ``So what happens next for Elway? ... A career in politics is a
possibility, especially because Elway's popularity would make him a
serious candidate for any office he sought.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all likelihood, Elway isn't entirely done with the Broncos.
Team owner Pat Bowlen plans to discuss an ownership stake with
Elway, who has said he would be receptive to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``And doesn't the new stadium need to be named?''
</P>
<P>
   _From Ralph Routon of the Colorado Springs Gazette:
</P>
<P>
   ``He has led his last comeback. He has thrown his last touchdown
pass. He has won his last game. He has conquered his last
challenge, leaving everyone with a full chest of sweet memories to
treasure forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farewell, No. 7.''
</P>
<P>
   _From John Branch of the Colorado Springs Gazette:
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get a second chance to make a last impression. And
if Broncos fans are finding it difficult to smile knowing their
hero is gone, knowing that Elway's childhood is gone, we should
remember _ in the long run, we'll all be better for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that, more than anyone, includes John Elway.''
</P>
<P>
   _From the Denver Westword, the weekly alternative:
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the continuing Columbine coverage ... the Elway
(retirement) infatuation that once would have commanded the entire
front page (of the Denver Post) received just a demure tease at the
bottom with the major Elway articles consigned to the sports
section.
</P>
<P>
   ``News judgment _ at last.''
</P>
<P>
   _From the Intermountain Jewish News of Denver:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so that's a headline on a feature about Israel's fears over
the approach of the millennium and its potential for religious
unrest. But you get the idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
