<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon rediscovers victory lane
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ After three months of confusion on the
left-hand-turn circuit, things were made right Sunday as Jeff
Gordon restored his dominance in NASCAR's Winston Cup series.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the two-time defending Winston Cup champion, won the
California 500 for the second time in three years, leading 151 of
250 laps and beating points leader Jeff Burton to the finish by
4.49 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gordon's third victory in 10 starts this season, but his
first since winning the Cracker Barrel 500 at Atlanta Motor
Speedway on March 14, a drought of _ gasp! _ five races.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon seemed so relieved to win that he couldn't remember the
way to California Speedway's victory lane, where he celebrated his
win in the inaugural race here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't remember how to get there,'' said Gordon, who won
for the 45th time in 199 career starts. ``The last time, I took the
wrong route, so I just cut across the infield grass to get there
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite leading all but one of the final 87 laps, Gordon didn't
make up much ground on Burton in the points standings. Gordon
erased only 10 points of a 210-point deficit to Burton, who was the
runner-up for the second time in the last three races. Burton
increased his lead to 55 points over Dale Jarrett, who finished
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gibbs Racing teammates Bobby Labonte and Tony Stewart both
finished in the top five for the second race in a row at third and
fourth, respectively. Labonte climbed to third in points, 154
behind Burton, while Stewart, a rookie, is sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended nearly two months of frustration for Gordon,
who didn't finish higher than third in the five events before
California, including DNFs at Texas and Talladega caused by wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels so good,'' he said. ``We've had a little bit of bad
luck here lately. We're human and we're going to have problems.
(But) we've got a better team than we've ever had before. We've had
some rough ones, but I knew we could get back to victory lane and
we proved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also had some luck, which was missing in his recent lull.
After taking the lead from Burton on lap 128, Gordon made his
second green-flag pit stop three laps later. While his No. 24
Chevrolet was still on pit road, however, Ricky Rudd crashed into
the wall in turn 4, bringing out the third caution flag of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and his brother, Ward, and contenders Jarrett, Rusty
Wallace and Jeremy Mayfield made pit stops shortly before Gordon,
so they were left a lap behind leader Mark Martin after the
caution. Gordon's pit crew got him out in 17.6 seconds, enabling
him to beat Martin to the start/finish line under caution and
remain at the rear of the lead lap on the restart at lap 138.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw what was happening, I had my eye on the
leader and I knew that we didn't go a lap down,'' said Ray
Evernham, crew chief for Gordon's Rainbow Warriors. ``We were lucky
enough in that (Burton) and (Mayfield) had pitted earlier than we
did. We had a fairly big lead on Martin, so we were able to make
our pit stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin couldn't pass Gordon on the two-mile oval, and another
caution flag was thrown only two laps later. While the other
leaders made pit stops on lap 142, Gordon and Martin decided to
remain on the track. With 108 laps remaining, the pair would need
at least two more pit stops to have enough fuel to finish the race.
</P>
<P>
   But one of Jarrett's tires blew up only 12 laps later, drawing
the fifth caution of the race because of debris, which gave Gordon
a yellow-flag pit stop on lap 157. Gordon made his final pit stop
on lap 208, and the 15.9-second tuneup allowed him to increase his
lead over Labonte to nearly four seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pit stop is what did it,'' Gordon said. ``When it comes to
crunch time, when the pressure is on and it's time to make a great
pit stop, that's what these guys do. I got to the pits as fast as I
could, got to pit road and they did the rest of the work and got me
out really fast. I had a little bit of breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
