<HEADLINE>
FOR JUNKER, TWO GRAND SLAMS IS VERY DEJA VU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the night Fernando Tatis made major-league
baseball history at Dodger Stadium, Lance Junker had gone out to
dinner with his wife. By the time he returned to his home in
Valencia and turned on the TV to watch what was left of the
Dodgers-Cardinals game, it had already happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that Vin Scully was talking about two grand slams
in one inning,'' Junker admitted to Mike Martinez of the San Jose
Mercury News. ``It didn't dawn on me that it was by one person.''
</P>
<P>
   Junker would know about that. Sixteen years earlier, on June 30,
1983 while playing for the Single-A Redwood Pioneers of the
California League, he did the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember it like it was yesterday,'' said the former
Loyola Marymount University star, drafted by the San Francisco
Giants in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that two grand slams in one inning was
accomplished twice previously _ in 1947 by Ken Myers of the Las
Vegas Wranglers in the Sunset League and in 1952 by Armando Flores
of the Laredo Apaches in the Gulf Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   (And an ironic note: Myers was the pro scout who signed Junker
for the Giants).
</P>
<P>
   As for Junker, 39, his pro career ended when he was released
from the Angels in 1984 a few weeks into spring training. He's now
a vice president of sales for Aero Engineering, a defense
contractor and manufacturer of military spare parts.
</P>
<P>
   But a newspaper clipping of Junker's two-grand-slam inning is in
a collage, framed in the hallway of his home.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if his leg was still in it: A cast worn by Michael
Jordan in 1985 following his only major injury while with the
Chicago Bulls was auctioned last week for close to $9,000 _ the
minimum opening bid was $2,000 _ according to William Mastro, whose
Mastro Fine Sports Auctions had the item among 1,500 lots for bid
via phone and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Jordan's 1991 expired Illinois driver's license went for
nearly $14,000. Minimum bid was $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Elway factor: Last week, Las Vegas bookmakers had the Denver
Broncos as 7-2 favorites to win it all in '99. This week, Minnesota
is the 7-2 favorite; Denver is 5-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-PADRE-PIO-NYT &LR;      05-02 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-PADRE-PIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAINTLY FRIAR GIVES ROME A DRILL FOR 2000 JUBILEE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Padre Pio, an enigmatic friar and mystic who has a vast
following in Italy and throughout the world, was beatified by Pope
John Paul II on Sunday before 300,000 devotees, who had joyfully
flooded into Rome for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials and other Romans, however, reacted somewhat
differently. Rome braced itself for the influx of Padre Pio
worshipers by shuttering itself.
</P>
<P>
   School closings were ordered for Monday, when there will be a
special Mass, and _ perhaps more striking _ the regular Sunday
match of the Roma soccer team was postponed for the first time.
Traffic was rerouted, away from the city center.
</P>
<P>
   Tight security was deployed to keep out Padre Pio worshipers who
failed to reserve a spot in advance at St. Peter's or the auxiliary
site, the Basilica of St. John Lateran, where John Paul traveled by
helicopter after the beatification ceremony to pray before the
overflow crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers' worst fears, which included predictions that there
would be 600,000 pilgrims, proved wrong, however. For an anxious
Italy, the tightly orchestrated beatification served as a drill for
the year 2000 Jubilee, when organizers estimate that more than 30
million people, including at least 2.5 million from the United
States, will visit Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Francesco Rutelli, the mayor of Rome, congratulated the city
Sunday night on a ``brilliant'' success. Earlier last week, he went
on radio and television imploring believers to stay away unless
they had a ticket. ``Padre Pio followers are passionate, generous
and not easily controlled,'' he explained in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he said: ``The most positive success was that we were
able to organize the crowds. If we had not warned people to make
reservations, then there would have been chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Those warnings seemed to have scared many would-be pilgrims into
staying home and watching the event live on state television. Even
some of those who did come said they were nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have faith in Padre Pio, but I don't have a lot of faith in
Italian organization,'' Gina Rescina, a housewife from Noicattaro,
a small town in southern Italy, said after she got off a bus from
Bari to take the subway to St. Peter's Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   She had made a reservation in January and paid $65 for a
round-trip package that included transportation, lunch at a convent
and a Padre Pio commemorative kit. She said her group's bus did not
show up on time in Bari on Saturday night. The pilgrims prayed to
Padre Pio, and a bus arrived an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   Beatification is the last step before sainthood. Padre Pio, a
Capuchin friar who died in 1968, is said by believers to have had
supernatural powers and a gift for healing, and he carried
stigmata, marks believed to represent the crucifixion wounds of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   He was revered by ordinary Catholics long before the Vatican
gave him official recognition. He was unusual among those
identified recently for sainthood in that his popular appeal
combined both medieval piety the ability to inspire a magazine- and
souvenir-selling celebrity cult that in Italy outshines that of
Diana, the late princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   For organizers, however, the ceremony mostly foreshadowed the
kinds of traffic and security hazards that could afflict Rome in
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   City officials expressed relief over the orderly event, which
was preceded on Saturday night by a May Day rock concert that drew
500,000 people. But some critics, who resented the closing of
schools and postponement of the soccer match, saw it as a ominous
sign of how the Jubilee could disrupt normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This confirms that if this is a dress rehearsal for the
Jubilee, Rome can only function under a wartime curfew,''
complained Giovanni Negri, a member of the Lay Observatory of the
Jubilee, a watchdog group that monitors the planning.
</P>
<P>
   An advance-booking-only policy is not generally in the spirit of
religious pilgrimage, but it was one of several experiments the
Vatican allowed as a rehearsal for the Holy Year. The Vatican, in
fact, will soon put on sale Jubilee credit cards, allowing advance
booking for everything from papal audiences to restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican planning for the Jubilee began in earnest in 1994. The
2,000th anniversary of the birth of Christ has special significance
for Christians. But it is also a Jubilee year, which now occurs
every 25 years. The tradition, borrowing from the ancient Jewish
law in which people forgave debts, summons believers to special
prayer and repentance.
</P>
<P>
   The church began inviting pilgrims to Rome on Jubilee years in
1300, when wars made it difficult for them to reach the Holy Land
in Jerusalem. Even 500 years ago, there were security risks. During
the 1450 jubilee, 200 pilgrims leaving a papal blessing mobbed the
only bridge over the Tiber, and 200 people drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the Italian government budgeted $3.7 billion for
Jubilee construction and organization. Officials began sketching
out vast improvement plans, ranging from a new subway line to a
tunnel under Castel Sant'Angelo, near the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Archeologists and engineers blocked the tunnel, and other plans
had to be shelved, many of them because they could not be completed
in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a grandiose plan for the modernization of Rome, which
foresaw the creation of subways, trams and new highways, we have
gone to a modest plan of urban maintenance,'' Negri said grumpily.
Nevertheless, the city says there are now more than 700
construction sites ranging from street repair to building
renovations around Rome. They are all supposed to be finished by
Christmas, when the Holy Year begins.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a giant portrait of Padre Pio was hung from scaffolding
that has covered the facade of St. Peter's for many months.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the tourist season, as many as 900 tour buses
rumble through Rome every day. Plans to ban them from the center of
Rome throughout the Holy Year have enraged many tour operators.
They complain that they will have to park their buses at designated
lots outside the city and rely on city shuttle buses to ferry their
clients to the Vatican, the Colosseum and Piazza Navona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they kidding?'' said Luigi Curcio, a tour guide who
attended a meeting of angry tour operators last week. ``Two hundred
elderly New Jersey tourists are going to have to wait for a city
bus that already gives horrible service to Romans?''
</P>
<P>
   There is not much sympathy among city officials for those who
want to put tourists' needs first. Among tourists, ``we have to
change the hit-and-run attitude,'' said Marcello Fiori, a city hall
planner, who noted that it would not hurt tourists to walk more.
``Rome is not a hamburger.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Vatican officials acknowledged that the beatification
events could offer lessons for the year 2000. ``Yes, it is better
to know today what the dangers and difficulties may be,'' said
Monsignor Crescenzio Sepe, general secretary of the Vatican's
Jubilee planning committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we do rely on faith here,'' he said. ``We believe in
divine providence and that all will go well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
