<HEADLINE>
40 YEARS AGO, L.A. COLISEUM LIGHTS UP FOR CAMPANELLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from
the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   May 3, 1975: With Drake Stadium holding a record 15,069 fans and
2,500 more trying to get in, UCLA freshman Willie Banks takes the
triple jump in a meet-record 55-feet, 1-inch in the last event to
give the Bruins a 75-70 victory over USC. Banks earlier beat
Trojans Olympic champ Randy Williams in the long jump. UCLA coach
Jim Bush, who would later coach at USC, proclaimed: ``This has to
be the greatest dual meet ever.'' (64)
</P>
<P>
   May 5, 1956: Jim Bailey becomes the first runner to break the
four-minute mile in the United States, running a 3:58.5 in Los
Angeles. It is almost two years to the day after Roger Bannister
ran a 3:59.4 in Oxford, England to become the first to break it.
</P>
<P>
   May 5, 1984: UCLA captures its fourth straight NCAA volleyball
title, a 15-11, 15-13, 16-18, 15-12 win over Pepperdine at Pauley
Pavilion to cap a 38-0 season. (69).
</P>
<P>
   May 6, 1961: In his final dual meet as USC track coach, Jess
Mortensen's team takes a 811/3-492/3 victory over UCLA. His team
never lost a dual meet _ he was 79-0.
</P>
<P>
   May 6, 1995: In a much anticipated bout for San Fernando Valley
fight fans, Sylmar's Rafael Ruelas meets Oscar de la Hoya in Las
Vegas. Ruelas loses his IBF lightweight title as he's knocked out
in the second round. On the undercard, brother Gabe Ruelas, the WBC
super featherweight champ, stops Jimmy Garcia in the 11th round.
Garcia collapses in his corner afterward and dies days later.
</P>
<P>
   May 7, 1959: On ``Roy Campanella Night'' at the Coliseum, a
crowd of 93,103 _ still the largest ever to see a baseball game,
and 20,000 were left wanting to get in _ attend an exhibition
between the Dodgers and New York Yankees to honor the former
Dodgers catcher, paralyzed after an automobile accident a year and
a half earlier. Between the fifth and sixth innings, Campanella was
wheeled to home plate by Pee Wee Reese, the Coliseum lights were
turned off and thousands of matches and lighters created a flicker
throughout the stadium. (29)!off
</P>
<P>
   May 7, 1970: Dodgers first baseman Wes Parker hits a 10th-inning
triple against the Mets to complete the cycle (with a single,
double and home run earlier). It's the last time a Dodger has
accomplished the feat.
</P>
<P>
   May 7, 1972: The Lakers stop the New York Knicks 114-100 _ Gail
Goodrich scores 25, Wilt Chamberlain has 24 with a sprained wrist
and Jerry West adds 23 _ to win the NBA title in Game 5 at the
Forum. It's the first league championship for the team since its
move to L.A. from Minneapolis in 1960. (15)
</P>
<P>
   May 7, 1993: Wayne Gretzky becomes the first player to score 100
playoff goals, helping the Kings to a 7-4 win over Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Today: Dodgers pitcher Darren Dreifort (27) and
former Dodgers second baseman Davey Lopes (54). Wednesday: Former
USC basketball star Harold Miner (28). Saturday: Former USC
football star Ronnie Lott (40).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
