<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1473 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARITY-ADS-CRACKDOWN     05-02 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARITY-ADS-CRACKDOWN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES PITCHES TIED TO CHARITIES DRAW STATES' SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn., Wis.)  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nonprofit organizations take in roughly a half-billion dollars a
year for lending their good names to the marketing of everything
from nicotine patches to pain relievers. But consumers are
sometimes confused about whether these are meant to be
endorsements, and regulators are not amused.
</P>
<P>
   Full-page advertisements, for instance, ran last year for
Pravachol, a cholesterol-lowering drug made by Bristol-Myers Squibb
Co., featuring the name and logo of the American Heart Association.
The association, which says the alliance was meant to educate the
public about heart attacks, was paid $600,000 to cooperate. Like
most charities, it insists that it does not make product
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Electrolux LLC, the maker of the new high-end Guardian vacuum
cleaner, sought out an exclusive arrangement with the Asthma and
Allergy Foundation as part of a campaign to persuade consumers that
a cleaner home is a healthier home. As a result, shoppers might be
impressed to see the foundation's logo prominently displayed on the
appliance's cartons and product literature and on the company's
World Wide Web site. Disclaimers, noting that the foundation ``does
not endorse any commercial products or services,'' appear in much
smaller print.
</P>
<P>
   And TV viewers who saw ads for Nicoderm in late 1997 might have
thought the American Cancer Society was vouching for the product.
SmithKline Beecham PLC, which makes Nicoderm, and the American
Cancer Society were described as ``partners in helping you quit,''
and the ads featured the society's name and logo. But the cancer
society, which receives upward of $1 million a year for the use of
its name and logo, says it endorses no commercial products.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they are called, the proliferation of such pitches has
not escaped the attention of state regulators, who are leaning hard
on some of the companies involved.
</P>
<P>
   In December, SmithKline settled with a dozen state attorneys
general who were concerned that the ads involving the cancer
society were misleading. In addition to paying the states a total
of $2.5 million, SmithKline agreed to spell out in its ads that
this was as much a business deal with the cancer society as it was
a joint effort to help people stop smoking. The words ``SB makes an
annual grant to the ACS for cancer research and education for the
use of their seal'' now flash on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Though the charity was not penalized, it acknowledges the perils
of such partnerships. ``Everybody is walking the line here, and we
all know it,'' Steve Dickinson, an American Cancer Society
spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than wage these battles one at a time, 16 attorneys
general, including those of New York, New Jersey and Connecticut,
now want to curb marketing pitches that may leave a misleading
impression of a charity's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   On April 6, the attorneys general, whose responsibilities
include enforcing state consumer protection laws and monitoring
charities, issued a preliminary report about cause-related
marketing, in which companies and charities team up to sell
products or sponsor events or programs. The report _ ``What's in a
Nonprofit's Name?'' _ offers six guidelines that it wants both the
for-profit and not-for-profit sides to adopt voluntarily. Public
hearings are scheduled for May, with final recommendations to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Since American Express Co. learned in the mid-1980s that people
used their charge cards more when it promised to donate a penny
toward the Statue of Liberty restoration for every charged
purchase, corporations have hurried to sign up charities to help
sell their wares. Last year, they paid dozens of nonprofit
institutions an estimated $544 million, according to IEG
Sponsorship Report, a Chicago newsletter that tracks corporate
sponsorship and cause-related marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As advertisers deal with all this clutter out there, having a
cause deal will make a difference,'' said Lance Helgeson, the
newsletter's managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   But when liaisons involve medical devices or health-related
products, regulators worry that consumers might misconstrue a
medical nonprofit group's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling their concern is the decision by many respected
charities, including the American Cancer Society and the American
Heart Association, to lend their names and logos to ads for
specific drugs or devices. The regulators fear that the public will
mistakenly infer that these groups, as experts in given diseases,
are backing certain products over others, said Barbara Tuerkheimer,
a Wisconsin assistant attorney general who is helping to lead the
16-state inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, say the charities, which contend that these joint
campaigns get their message out to more people than the groups
could on their own. The Arthritis Foundation, for example, wanted
to educate people about the different types of arthritis. It
accepted $1 million a year from the McNeil Consumer Products
division of Johnson &AMP; Johnson to let McNeil start using its name to
market over-the-counter pain relievers in late 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, McNeil and the foundation settled with 19
attorneys general, with McNeil agreeing to pay $2 million and stop
making certain claims. Ads could not imply that the foundation had
helped create the pain relievers or that a portion of every
purchase was funding research, when actually a certain threshold
had to be met.
</P>
<P>
   The ads no longer run, and the partnership was not renewed. A
McNeil spokesman said the campaign was just not effective, while
Don Riggin, chief executive of the Arthritis Foundation, said his
organization felt ``very comfortable that this particular program
achieved our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, many charities see these partnerships as an innocuous
way to tap a new source of badly needed revenue. ``I just don't see
the problem,'' said Joseph Bergen, chief operating officer of the
American Lung Association, which was promised $2.5 million in 1997
to lend its name to two years of anti-smoking efforts being
sponsored by McNeil, the maker of the Nicotrol patch.
</P>
<P>
   But charities have had an inkling for some time that these
partnerships could draw scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the American Cancer Society's own research, for
instance, suggests that consumers, who place an extraordinary
amount of trust in charities, assume the charity is standing behind
a product when its name is used. A 1994 study, sponsored by the
Michigan division of the society, concluded after conducting focus
groups and consumer interviews that the use of its logo ``is
considered an `endorsement' by the ACS by nearly all group
participants.''
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors who are members of the American Medical Association
and others were worried about just this type of confusion in August
1997, when a buoyant Sunbeam announced that the AMA had agreed to
affix its name on products ranging from blood pressure monitors to
heating pads. After the association backed off in the face of
intense criticism, it settled a breach-of-contract lawsuit filed by
Sunbeam for nearly $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   What the regulators want, and some charities resist, is more
disclosure _ that if no endorsement is being made, the ad would
make that clear. The attorneys general also want the ads to state
whether the charities are being paid for the use of their names and
whether these arrangements are exclusive. Exclusive deals, the
attorneys general argue, reinforce a false impression that one
product is better than another.
</P>
<P>
   The risk to the charities' bottom lines is that if companies
have to reveal so much, they might not want to bother with the
joint campaigns. ``Companies may decide it is not worth their while
to have all this regulatory language,'' said David Livingston, an
executive vice president of the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Bierig, a Chicago lawyer who represented the AMA in its
dispute with Sunbeam, urged regulators to seek a middle ground.
``In our zeal to get rid of some things,'' he said, ``we ought to
be careful not to discourage very well-motivated associations
between a nonprofit and a company.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is little evidence of a pall. The American Cancer
Society now limits its exclusive arrangement with companies to
specific events, like the Great American Smokeout, with the view
that they can still team up with rival companies on other
occasions. Even with that risk, SmithKline, a corporate sponsor of
the event, was happy to renew its partnership with the charity,
said George Quesnelle, director of medical marketing and sales for
SmithKline Beecham's Consumer Healthcare division.
</P>
<P>
   But if public health is the goal, said Mildred Cho, a researcher
at the Stanford Center for Biomedical Ethics, charities should ask
themselves whether there really is a difference between allowing
their names to be used in marketing and an all-out endorsement.
``If they are not endorsing it, why are they putting their name on
it?'' she asked. ``If the goal is to educate generally about
smoking cessation or nutrition, you don't need to mention a
specific product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
