<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1483 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-RELEASE-BO     05-02 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-RELEASE-BOS </SLUG>
  
 MILOSEVIC TO FREE THREE US SERVICEMEN
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic said Saturday
he would release three US serviceman held captive for more than a
month, apparently hoping his good-will gesture might pave the way
to a negotiated end to NATO's punishing bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers are expected to be handed over Sunday to the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, who arrived in Belgrade Friday on a mission,
conducted without the Clinton administration's blessing, to win
their freedom. The three will probably go to nearby Croatia, and
from there to a US military base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   There were no conditions attached to the release, but Jackson
issued a plea to NATO for a pause that would give Serbs ``a night
of peace from bombs'' and allow for some kind of diplomatic effort
to take root.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who met with the three soldiers Friday and held prayers
and talks with Milosevic Saturday, said he would carry a letter to
President Clinton from the Serbian leader with a plea to end the
bombing, an outline of Milosevic's ideas on ending the crisis, and
an offer to meet with Clinton to discuss a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Serbian state television channel RTS reported that
a NATO attack killed between 34 and 60 people Saturday when a
missile hit a bus on a bridge north of Pristina, Kosovo's capital.
</P>
<P>
   RTS showed pictures of the destroyed bus on a bridge and bodies
scattered nearby. RTS said four people survived the attack. Half
the vehicle plunged off the bridge while passengers in the other
half burned to death.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent confirmation. In Brussels, NATO
officials said they were checking the report. An alliance military
source said the bridge was not on NATO's target list, but added:
``This doesn't mean it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO conducted the heaviest bombing of Yugoslavia Saturday since
the campaign began six weeks ago, with 600 sorties for the second
day running.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes were aimed at attacking the ``nervous system'' of
Yugoslavia's armed forces, as well as signaling the Western
alliance's continued resolve to press ahead following a legislative
blow to the campaign Wednesday from the US House of
Representatives, which rejected a motion to support sending in
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has not officially responded to Jackson's request for a
pause in the bombing campaign. But Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright reportedly told Jackson that while Washington welcomes the
release of the prisoners, its position ``remains unchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   --Tanjug, Yugoslavia's state news agency, reported that NATO
missiles damaged a maternity hospital and police station in
Pancevo, north of Belgrade, as well as a bridge leading from the
Yugoslav province of Montenegro into Kosovo. The attack, according
to Tanjug, killed four, including two ethnic Albanian children.
</P>
<P>
   --The UN high commissioner for human rights, Mary Robinson, said
the Yugoslav government estimated that 500 civilians have died as a
result of the NATO bombings. So far, NATO has acknowledged only 112
deaths caused by at least three errant bombings.
</P>
<P>
   --The European Union's ban on oil shipments, designed to starve
the Milosevic military machine of fuel, took effect Saturday as the
White House announced additional sweeping unilateral sanctions
against Yugoslavia. The US sanctions, which exempt the republic of
Montenegro, are designed to strengthen the embargo by banning
imports and exports of all ``goods, software, technology and
services,'' except medicine and food.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO forces have captured a second Yugoslav soldier and are
holding him in Germany, the Pentagon said Saturday. Pentagon
spokesman Lt. Col. Lane Van de Steeg said he did not know the rank
of the Yugoslav officer or the circumstances of his capture.
</P>
<P>
   --Fresh violence broke out along the Kosovo-Albanian border in
the town of Letaj, in an area where hundreds of thousands of
refugees have crossed. The area is also increasingly being used by
the Kosovo Liberation Army as a staging ground for raids against
Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   --Refugees continued to spill over the Albanian border following
exodus of 12,000 Kosovar Albanians on Friday alone. Thousands more
were expected over the weekend, according to the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   --There were repeated, but unconfirmed reports that Serb
military forces were pulling males of all ages off Kosovo refugee
convoys making their way to the border. One report said men were
picked from their vehicles and forcibly put on a bus holding more
than 100 male Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   --The Pentagon designated Fort Dix, N.J., as the processing
point for 20,000 Albanian refugees who are being flown into the
United States for temporary shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Balkans envoy Viktor S. Chernomyrdin returned from his
mission to Bonn, Rome, and Belgrade with a pessimistic view on the
prospects for peace, saying the chances of arriving at a political
settlement were slim following the West's dismissal of a seven
point Russian-Yugoslav proposal for peace.
</P>
<P>
   The former prime minister, however, said he would press on with
his mission to sell the plan to Western leaders this week.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has said he would withdraw troops from Kosovo to a
``pre-war'' level but only if NATO halted the bombing campaign and
removed its forces from Yugoslavia's frontiers. He has refused,
however, to bow to the alliance's demand that an armed
international presence be allowed into Kosovo to ensure the safe
return of almost 1 million ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   US officials dismissed the plan as long as it did not call for a
larger withdrawal of Serb military, police and paramilitary forces
from the region, as well as an armed peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana told the German magazine
Der Spiegel that the alliance's campaign was achieving its goals
and with the imminent deployment of US Apache helicopters, moving
into its ``final phase.''
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing in Brussels Saturday, NATO announced its jets and
missiles had struck an untold number of tanks, command posts,
armored vehicles and mortar positions, as well as military
airfields in the cities of Sombor and Ponikve, and an oil refinery
in Novi Sad.
</P>
<P>
   Also hit were transmission towers and control buildings for the
Yugoslav radio relay network in seven locations, what Peter Daniel,
a NATO spokesman, called the ``nervous system that keeps the
Milosevic machine informed and in touch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press and Reuters was used in this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
