<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1484 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONDON-BOMB-BOS &LR;      05-02 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-BOMB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON GRIPPED BY FEAR OF RACIST BOMBINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Golders Green, the heart of this city's Jewish
community, usually is quiet on Saturdays as Orthodox Jews observe
the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, it was less crowded than usual. Even secular Jews
stayed out of the shops, and the gentiles who often take advantage
of a quiet day to shop stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   That's because many people think Golders Green, or some place
like it, is the next target of a bomber believed to be a racist who
has struck three times in London in 14 days, killing two and
wounding more than 100.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why a group of Orthodox men, dressed in traditional
black garb, stopped a stranger who was asking questions along the
Finchley Road Saturday. The stranger was a newspaper reporter, and
so there were handshakes and good wishes all around. But in a city
of 7 million, all strangers are now suspect.
</P>
<P>
   London, no stranger to bombs, is in the grip of a smoldering
panic. The nail bombs that have raised tensions all over London
have been left in gym bags in crowded areas and have followed a
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   First it was Brixton, the symbolic capital of London's black
community. Thirty-nine people were injured in the April 17
explosion, five of them seriously, including a baby who had to have
a 4-inch nail removed from his head.
</P>
<P>
   The second bomb exploded a week ago Saturday on Brick Lane in
the East End, the heart of the Bangladeshi community. Six people
were injured but none seriously because a passerby had found the
bag and had left it in the trunk of his car to find police when it
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday evening, a gay pub in the middle of Soho, the most
tolerant neighborhood in London, was blown up. Two people were
killed, more than 70 wounded, 23 of them seriously. Several had
limbs blown off.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Police, well-trained in counterterrorism after
30 years of dealing with Irish Republican Army bombs, have launched
a massive criminal investigation but have not found the bomber.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are focusing on extreme right-wing, Neo-Nazi groups,
some of which have claimed responsibility for the bombs. While
several anonymous callers claiming to represent these groups have
said they carried out the bombings, police say they don't know who
is behind the attacks. However, they say they are certain that a
hatred of minority groups is at the core of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Police have arrested and questioned three men before releasing
them. One man remained under arrest Saturday &UR;  &LR; night for
questioning. But charges related to the bombings were not imminent,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police and government officials are worried about panic
spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an attack on all of us,'' said Paul Condon, chief of
the Metropolitan Police. ``It's a time for calm. It's a time for
vigilance. It's a time for the community to work together to defeat
these cowards.''
</P>
<P>
   With the police unable to say for sure who is behind the
attacks, minority communities are taking matters into their own
hands. Michael Whine, head of the British Board of Jewish Deputies,
said Jewish groups across the city are patrolling their
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to inciting fear, the bombings also have tapped
Londoners' traditional defiance. In the wake of the bombings,
thousands of Londoners have donated blood. Many say they refuse to
be threatened off their streets.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Watson, a leader of Stonewall, a gay-rights group, said his
organization spent Saturday appealing to gay men to return to Old
Compton Street, center of the gay bar scene in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be intimidated off our streets,'' said Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Bombings are nothing new to Londoners. The Nazis blitzed them in
the 1940s. The IRA killed dozens of people with no-warning bombs in
the 1970s and 1980s. More recently, bombs have been used by animal
rights extremists and even someone with a grudge against a
supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it has been about 15 years since the IRA abandoned its
no-warning bombs that indiscriminately killed civilians. And
Londoners always have taken comfort in the fact that the diversity
of their city, home to so many different colors and cultures, would
deter extremists, lest they kill some of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But now it is that very diversity that has become the target,
creating fear and uncertainty in one of the world's biggest cities.
</P>
<P>
   Because John Murphy's name adorns his North London pub, the bar
is a potential target. The racist groups that have claimed
responsibility for the bombs say that Jews and Irish are on their
hit list.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Murphy followed a young man he didn't know into the
pub's bathroom to make sure he didn't leave anything in the
toilets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible thing to say, but if someone I don't know
comes in here, I've got to expect the worst,'' said Murphy, shaking
his head. ``If you look where the bombs have been already, you'd
see that the Jews and the Irish are next. It's dreadful.''
</P>
<P>
   While whoever is planting the bombs wants to kill and maim
minorities, the attacks inevitably are hitting civilians from all
walks of life. The Brixton market that was bombed is patronized by
as many whites as blacks. Whites far outnumber minorities in the
restaurants around Brick Lane that had their windows blown out last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And although Old Compton Street is popular with gays, not unlike
Bay Village in Boston, area restaurants are frequented by
straights, and its narrow lanes are used by pedestrians on the way
to Chinatown and the theaters in Covent Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Gray, 33, had delivered a package on Brewer Street, just
beyond Old Compton Street, and had just walked past the Admiral
Duncan pub before it exploded Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty seconds earlier, and I would have been walking right in
front of the pub,'' he said Saturday, driving his taxi in Highgate,
a North London neighborhood. ``That's what so crazy about this. The
people who are planting the bombs want to kill minorities, but
we're all minorities now. We're all vulnerable now. We're all
targets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
