<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1487 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NRA-DENVER-BOS &LR;      05-02 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-DENVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HESTON REBUTS CRITICS OF RIFLE ASSOCIATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Undaunted by thousands of gun-control activists who
formed a human chain outside, the National Rifle Association held a
brief but defiant annual meeting here Saturday. Leaders defended
gun owners' rights and lashed out at criminals, political
opportunists, the media, and the loss of values.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual right to bear arms is freedom's insurance
policy, not just for your children, but for infinite generations to
come,'' NRA president and actor Charlton Heston told several
thousand cheering members, praising their ``courage'' to attend.
``We must not let human tragedy lay waste to the most rare and
hard-won human right in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Heston struck back at criticisms of the NRA that flourished in
the days after the Columbine High School massacre, which took place
just 10 miles away. Wearing a blue-and-silver ribbon on his lapel
to honor the victims, he derisively quoted a statement praising gun
control by Adolf Hitler, whose birth date was chosen by the gunmen
for their April 20 killing spree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dirty secret of this day and age is political gain and
media ratings all too often bloom on fresh graves,'' Heston said.
``We're often cast as the villain. That is not our role in American
society, and we will not be forced to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Heston reserved some of his harshest comments for the media. He
called coverage of the killings ``pornography'' and accused
reporters of perching ``like vultures on the balconies of hotels
for a hundred miles around.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the NRA meeting at a downtown hotel, about 4,000
gun-control demonstrators gathered five blocks away on the steps of
the gold-domed Colorado State House. Among them was Thomas Mauser,
whose son Daniel was among the 12 students and one teacher murdered
at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA deserves credit as a promoter of gun safety and
representative of hunters,'' said Mauser, who carried a sign with a
photo of his smiling, towheaded son. ``But it and other gun
organizations deserve our condemnation for their relentless
promotion of gun proliferation and protection of all types of guns,
regardless of their dangerousness.''
</P>
<P>
   His voice cracking, Mauser described how his son was fatally
shot in the face with a TEC-DC9, a 9mm semiautomatic handgun with a
30-bullet clip. He said the only purpose for such a gun was as a
``killing machine,'' and asked: ``Can you relate to that pain, Mr.
Heston?''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the crowd was a statue of a Civil War-era
soldier bearing a rifle. To cheers and whistles, a man climbed the
10-foot pedestal and placed a bright-pink sign in the soldier's
arms reading, ``Let's cradle children, not Uzis.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA convention originally was expected to attract 22,000
members. In the end, all but about 3,000 stayed away when the
organization cut the session from three days to one, and canceled
all planned events except the two-hour business meeting. NRA
officials abandoned the traditional introduction of its oldest and
youngest members, an apparent concession to the recent uproar about
children and guns.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's mayor had asked the group to cancel the convention
altogether to give the community time to heal, but NRA officials
said they were required by law to hold an annual meeting and there
was no reason they should be blamed for the actions of Columbine
gunmen Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in absolutely gun-free, zero-tolerance, totally
safe schools,'' said Wayne LaPierre, the NRA's executive vice
president. He said the real problem is failure to prosecute
criminals who gain illegal access to guns, saying there were only
13 prosecutions of the 6,000 students caught with guns at school in
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre also criticized proposals that have gained ground in
the past 11 days to impose new restrictions on weapon sales at gun
shows, which now can take place among unlicensed sellers without
background checks or compliance with other gun-control measures.
Investigators have said three of the four weapons used at Columbine
were bought by Klebold's girlfriend at a gun show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will consider instant checks at gun shows when, and only
when, this administration stops demanding new gun taxes and stops
illegally compiling the records of millions of lawful gun buyers,''
LaPierre said.
</P>
<P>
   While Heston and LaPierre won rousing ovations, both were
upstaged by Colorado Secretary of State Vikki Buckley, who brought
the crowd to its feet by declaring: ``Welcome to Colorado, a state
where some of us believe strongly in the entire Constitution of the
United States, including the Second Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, who is black, spoke passionately to a nearly all-white
audience about racism, her own experience as a shooting victim, a
loss of family values, irresponsible sex, and what she called
``new-age hate crimes'' _ a phrase she used in speaking at the
funeral last week of Columbine High senior Isaiah Shoels, the only
black person killed in the rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Rank-and-file NRA members defended their right to attend the
meeting. ``Who's running this country? The criminals or the
law-abiding people?'' asked Albert Tierney, a lawyer from Norwell,
Mass., who said he has been an NRA member on and off for more than
50 years. ``The NRA is being treated as a scapegoat.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, NRA member Connie Truax of Golden, Colo., sold
dozens of blue-and-silver ribbons for $1 each. She said the
proceeds would go to a student relief fund at Columbine.
``Murderers killed these 12 students and one teacher. Blaming the
guns they used is missing the point,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, more than 2,000 of the gun-control advocates
marched from the Statehouse to the site of the NRA meeting, forming
a human chain and ringing bells in an otherwise silent protest.
There was a heavy police presence for the peaceful march. No
arrests were reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just think the NRA's agenda is irresponsible,'' said Ted
Pascoe, executive director of the Colorado Coalition Against Gun
Violence, which organized the protest. ``We hope this has a lasting
effect by sending a message that the NRA is not welcome in our
city, particularly at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-gun activists in Colorado claimed partial victory after the
Columbine shootings; three bills they opposed that were heading
toward passage _ including one lifting a state ban on concealed
weapons _ were withdrawn, their prospects now in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was young and old, with a heavy dose of high school
students. ``I'm here because I don't like the fact that I don't
feel safe at school,'' said Beth Diebert, 17, a high school senior
from Boulder. ``It's become personal. People my age are the ones
who got killed.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest drew the attention of members of a tour group from
Holland, where gun violence is a rarity. They stood near the
Statehouse and gaped at the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible for us to think that the gun lobby here is so
strong,'' said Lenie Ruigrok of Utrecht, Holland. ``We can't
imagine the need for so many people to protest this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
