<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-JACKSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC SENDS JACKSON BACK TO US WITH AN OLIVE BRANCH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his stunning decision Saturday to free three
captive American soldiers, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
raised the stakes in the diplomatic struggle for peace in the
Balkans amid signs of wavering public support in the United States
for the NATO siege of Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, in freeing the prisoners even as his troops control
the Kosovo province they have purged of many ethnic Albanian
civilians, was seen by foreign policy specialists as seizing an
opportunity to shake President Clinton's resolve and to step up his
urgent quest for an end to the NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   With the surprise move, Milosevic sends the Rev. Jesse Jackson
back to Washington with an olive branch and a message that, Jackson
said, ``cannot be ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first step of peace and reconciliation,'' Jackson
told reporters in Belgrade. ``We should miss no opportunity to
choose peace with dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, who suffered a public relations setback last week
when the House refused to endorse his Kosovo policy, the
development presents another obstacle to building support for
pushing ahead with the massive US military role in the NATO
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have shown growing public concern about Clinton's
handling of the crisis. And the House's refusal to officially back
the US role in the NATO campaign reflected increasing wariness in
Congress about the direction the conflict is taking. The House
debate even raised ghosts of Vietnam-era rhetoric, as several
lawmakers urged the administration to ``give peace a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's move was seen in part as an attempt to exploit the
antiwar feeling that emerged in the House. ``It's interesting that
this release comes shortly after that vote,'' said Lee Hamilton,
former chairman of the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   For Milosevic, the time for peace seems ripe, analysts said. He
has fulfilled his goal of controlling most of Kosovo. But the
economic capacity of his Serbian republic is being decimated by
escalating NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to get any better than this for him,'' said
Richard N. Haass, director of foreign policy studies at the
Brookings Institution and a former special assistant to President
Bush for national security affairs. ``It makes sense that he is
thinking about what he can do to get the bombing to stop so he
might hold on to his presidency and at least claim victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Haass said Milosevic's move reflects his increasing diplomatic
attempts to extricate himself from the NATO siege. Milosevic
decided to free the prisoners the day after the United States and
NATO rejected his six-point plan for a war settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been in regular contact with Russia's envoy to the
Balkans, Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, who is trying to mediate a
resolution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Milosevic is throwing out ideas and pushing buttons
that may weaken American resolve or NATO resolve or both,'' Haass
said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the effort, Milosevic is expected to give Jackson a
new settlement plan to deliver personally to Clinton. Jackson said
the letter will include an offer by Milosevic to meet face-to-face
with Clinton ``and to take this matter to resolution through
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was golfing Saturday with his friend Vernon E.
Jordan Jr. when Milosevic's decision was announced, is expected to
have little appetite for appearing publicly with the Yugoslav
president.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and NATO also were poised to rebuff Jackson's
plea to suspend the airstrikes to give Yugoslavia ``a night of
peace from bombs'' before the expected release of the prisoners
Sunday. The appeal came shortly after Clinton announced plans to
tighten US economic sanctions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Milosevic's image could be bolstered in NATO
countries by photographs of him praying with Jackson and a
delegation of US religious leaders shortly before he decided to
release the prisoners. In a stark juxtaposition, Milosevic, who
faces possible war-crime charges for presiding over a campaign of
killing, rape, and gunpoint expulsion that has driven 1.4 million
ethnic Albanians from their homes in Kosovo and created refugee
crises throughout the Balkans, is shown praying for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's public approval ratings are expected to soar, just
weeks after he announced he would not seek the Democratic
nomination for president. He also has given Clinton little choice
other than to praise him for his diplomatic coup, even though
Jackson's triumph has complicated Clinton's challenge in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's success came despite the White House's refusal to
sanction his mission, which the administration warned could be
exploited by Milosevic for propaganda purposes. Yet if Milosevic
makes good on his pledge to free the soldiers, the Clinton
administration would be left to criticize Jackson's efforts at its
own political peril.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
