u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STADIUM-KRAFT-BOS &LR;      05-02 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-KRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW KRAFT MADE DECISION TO KEEP PATRIOTS IN MASSACHUSETTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The beginning of the end of Robert Kraft's partnership with
Connecticut can be traced to last Thursday morning, when a team of
consultants to his New England Patriots assembled in a conference
room on the 34th floor of the Kraft Group headquarters in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   After a month of sifting through all the data, the experts hired
by the Patriots were ready to give Kraft and his son Jonathan a
bleak assessment: Connecticut was unlikely to have a stadium, to be
built for the Patriots on a polluted site, ready by the 2002
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts and team vice president Andy Wasynczuk had known for
months that Connecticut was struggling with the site. But the
consultants left little doubt that Connecticut would miss the 2002
timetable specific in its contract with the team. And the Krafts
faced a deadline set for Sunday under which they could pull out of
the deal without penalty.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a firm decision right then, according to people
familiar with the meeting and on whose accounts this article is
based. Just a growing sense of the inevitable. But there was one
last chance the deal might be saved. Coincidentally, the Krafts
were scheduled to meet with Connecticut Governor John G. Rowland
that afternoon. Perhaps if he agreed to extend the penalty-free
exit clause in the contract for another 30 to 60 days, the team
could then see if more encouraging news was available from state
officials feverishly working to prepare the site.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Krafts heard their consultants' discouraging
report, the team's Connecticut lobbyist, Jay Malcynski arrived at
the One Boston Place office. A close personal and professional
friend of Rowland, Malcynski has enormous clout and access in the
Connecticut capital. He was hired to help the Patriots get their
new home in Hartford built as planned. Now, more than ever, that
plan was in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting with the governor had originally been set for the
week before, but Rowland had asked to reschedule it for Thursday
afternoon. For the next hour or so, the Krafts discussed the
consultants' critical assessment with Malcynski and explored
whether Rowland might be willing to extend the penalty-free
deadline. ``It was a chance for the team to show good faith by
giving Connecticut more time to wipe away the doubts,'' said one
person close to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts made it clear they were discouraged by the
consultants' analysis. But Malcynski didn't beliee Rowland would
agree to an extension, especially since Massachusetts was
fast-tracking a counteroffer to keep the Patriots. The Krafts were
told Rowland feared that giving the team more time would simply
encourage the Bay State to up its ante. At the very least, it would
give Massachusetts lawmakers and the National Football League more
time to kill Connecticut's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Over a lunch of takeout burritos, the Patriots and their
lobbyist continued to talk about the team's options. Malcynski
pressed the Krafts not to back out of the deal, even if the stadium
opening slipped to 2003. The Krafts made it clear they were not
willing to add yet another year to the deadline, especially since
their original agreement with Connecticut had promised a 2001
completion date.
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts, sensing they would not be able to negotiate with
Rowland, wondered aloud whether there was any point in flying to
Hartford for the meeting with the governor. In the end, they
decided it would be more respectful to keep the appointment and
discuss their reservations face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   The two Krafts, Wasnyczuk, and Malcynski drove to Logan Airport
after lunch, intending to fly to Hartford for a 4 p.m. meeting with
the governor. But upon arriving at the terminal, they discovered
the small plane they had chartered was not available. It took
several hours to find one, during which time the men cooled their
heels at a private airport lounge. Rowland was not happy about the
delay and offered to meet the Kraft contingent halfway. Instead,
the two sides agreed to postpone the meeting until after 8 p.m. so
Rowland could attend his daughter's violin concert before returning
to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts had been assured their meeting with Rowland would be
private, but after a call from the Patriots' spokesman, they
discovered the news media had been alerted to the meeting. When
they arrived at the State House around 6 that evening, the Krafts
were greeted by a crush of cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay at the airport had given the press time to swarm the
Capitol, and after hours of waiting they were hungry,'' said one
source at the scene. Feeling ambushed, the Krafts entered the
governor's office without addressing reporters and waited for
Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   The Kraft party was seated in a relatively dark room just off
the governor's office known as ``the cave.'' As they waited, they
watched sports on TV and ate pepperoni pizzas supplied by the
governor's office. The governor arrived sometime after 7 and the
meeting between Kraft and Rowland began.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft outlined his concerns about the state's ability to finish
the stadium by 2002. Connecticut officials, including some
overseeing the project, continued to insist they could meet the
deadline. Kraft then offered to wait a month before deciding, if
the state would extend Sunday's penalty-free exit date for one
month.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland refused.
</P>
<P>
   The governor pressed Kraft to explain why he would even consider
walking away from such a lucrative deal _ estimated to be worth up
to $1 billion over 30 years _ over a one-year delay.
</P>
<P>
   People close to both sides tell basically the same story up
until this point. Now, their accounts diverge. The Patriots say
they detailed their concerns and made clear they were not willing
to accept a 2003 season opening for the stadium. Patriots sources
say Kraft's message was unambiguous: The pact was in peril.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut officials say Kraft held out hope that the 2002
deadline could still be met, and was willing to keep the deal
alive. At one point, a clearly frustrated Rowland told the Krafts
it was time to ``fish or cut bait,'' people from both sides
confirm.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kraft then told Connecticut officials he would get them an
answer within 24 hours, Rowland's side says. They were confident
that the team would stick with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 98 percent sure the Patriots were going to go
forward,'' said Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani. ``They had presented
no rational arguments for pulling out.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting ended. Each side drafted press statements, but
Rowland objected to Kraft's wording, calling it a ``death watch.''
Connecticut officials edited the remarks, and Rowland and Kraft
went to face reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure is not an option,'' Rowland told reporters at 11:25,
saying he and the team would spend the next five weeks trying to
win NFL approval of the move. Kraft was noncommital, saying only
that his ``goal'' remained to play in Hartford in 2002. The two men
took no questions and shook hands briefly before exiting from
different doors.
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts flew back to Boston, arriving after midnight. Father
and son spoke only briefly in front of their parked cars. They knew
that with no extra time from Connecticut to further study the site,
the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   It was already Friday morning. By that afternoon the deal would
be dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
