<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HARD DAY'S NIGHT WELL WORTH IT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The game started in April but didn't end
until May. Ray Bourque skated for 53 1/2 minutes, including a short
stint in goal. The Bruins won after midnight, in double overtime,
as the Greensboro Coliseum PA piped, ``Let's Spend the Night
Together.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it feels like the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, they say a playoff series hasn't really begun until
the road team wins a game. In Boston, we know the playoffs haven't
officially started until Harry Sinden blows a gasket complaining
about the officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins filed a protest Saturday in an attempt to get
Carolina winger Gary Roberts suspended before Game 6 (Sunday) of
this suddenly spicy first-round playoff series. Roberts
cross-checked Boston center Tim Taylor into the boards in the first
minute of the third period of Boston's 4-3 sudden-death victory
Friday/Saturday. Taylor suffered a separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be suspended,'' Sinden said of Roberts. ``It's a
cross-check from behind into the boards. The last thing we want in
our league is that check. There's no defense for it. The player who
is hit is most vulnerable and we can't allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins may not get satisfaction from the league office, but
Boston fans are sure to send a message to the Hurricanes at the
Vault.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns, making light of the bogus black curtain
that hides 10,000 Greensboro seats and allows the Hurricanes to
claim phony sellouts, said, ``We have the same curtain at home.
We're going to pull it up and there'll be another 10,000 fans
there. You think it's loud here? You haven't heard nothing yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In Greensboro, watching hockey is something you do between those
satisfying cigarette breaks between periods. Carolina fans practice
their ``Boston sucks'' while sucking on every kind of Winston and
Salem.
</P>
<P>
   Burns believes the Boston fandom will return the favor Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll bring it back to Boston,'' said the coach. ``There'll be
a lot of noise and a lot of fun. Both teams have proven they want
it. Nothing means nothing now. Once the puck hits the ice Sunday,
it'll be a battle. Somebody's going to come out of this playoff
series awfully sore.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the survivor of this first-rounder might not have much
left for Round 2. The Friday night/Saturday morning special was
grueling, even for the heroic Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for everybody,'' said the exhausted captain.
``Especially a 38-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   He was so tired he didn't see Anson Carter's winning goal in the
15th minute of the second overtime just after midnight. Bourque was
on the bench, catching his breath with his head down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt relief,'' he said. ``I didn't want to go out for
another shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking around the room, the veteran blue liner added, ``It's a
huge game. This is the first time these guys have won a
double-overtime game. It's important for the younger guys in the
room. They're learning how to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns provided some spark of his own after the Bruins fell
behind, 2-0. He told his team they might as well warm up the
airplane and get out of town if they kept playing so passively. The
Bruins responded by potting three of their first six shots in the
third (better than Antoine Walker at the line most nights), scoring
three goals in 1:52. Boston has outscored Carolina by an aggregate
9-3 in the third periods.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had plenty of opportunities in overtime, none better
than Martin Gelinas's botched attempt from in front of the crease.
Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe had been taken out of the play and it was
left to Bourque to stand in front of the net while Gelinas fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``He double-hit it,'' said Bourque. ``He just missed it. I've
done that on the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gelinas will probably have a hard time sleeping tonight,''
added Burns. ``He certainly missed that one, but that's what
overtime's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Overtime was long and the players and fans were tired. Scores of
Carolina fans carried sleeping children out of the arena before
Carter banged home the winner.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Bruins have a chance to end one of our city's
longest droughts. No Boston team has won a playoff series since the
Brian Sutter Bruins topped Montreal in seven games in the spring of
1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
