<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-A'S-BOS &LR;      05-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACE BANDAGE FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-A'S-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ He is the first pitcher in the major leagues
to win five games this spring. He struck out 13 batters in seven
innings Saturday, matching his most dominant outing in a Red Sox
uniform, even though his fastball was the only pitch he trusted.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, he will end _ by Mother's Day _ any debate on who
should start the All-Star Game in Fenway Park in July.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite a 7-2 win over the Oakland A's that elevated a
team that couldn't have looked more bedraggled than it had one
night before, Pedro Martinez finds himself under siege. Again.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was one of 125 pitches he threw _ the fastball he
planted between the numbers on Olmedo Saenz's back in the seventh
inning _ to resurrect accusations that the Dominican is as
diabolical as he is dandy. That he throws his 95-mile-an-hour
fastball not only past people, but at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy with what he did,'' A's manager Art Howe said
after the game. ``He has a history of that. What's going to happen
is he's going to get somebody hurt over there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was them, I'd start policing him a little better. He's
too good a pitcher for that BS.''
</P>
<P>
   Saenz is a Panamanian version of Brian Daubach, a career minor
leaguer who hit plenty of homers in the bushes but is just now
getting his first taste of the big leagues. On Friday night, he
pinch hit against Sox reliever Jim Corsi and was hit by a pitch
with the bases loaded, a pitch that Corsi said Saenz made no
attempt to elude.
</P>
<P>
   Saenz remained in the game, then hit a three-run home run off
another Sox reliever, Derek Lowe, to break a 9-9 tie in a 13-9 win.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Saenz pinch hit again with the Sox ahead, 5-1, with
one out and nobody on in the seventh. One pitch later, he was
wincing in pain as he walked down to first base. He believes, as
did Howe, that Martinez had committed a deliberate act of
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his (expletive) approach,'' said Saenz, still
steaming afterward. ``To hit me right on my (expletive) back. I
didn't do anything to show anybody up. I was just doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, A's reliever Buddy Groom threw a pitch over the
head of Nomar Garciaparra, which elicited no response from either
Garciaparra or plate umpire Joe Brinkman. But when Tim Worrell, the
A's fourth pitcher, threw a ball at Jose Offerman's belt buckle in
the ninth _ Offerman stepped back from harm's way _ Scott issued a
cease-and-desist warning to Worrell.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Martinez not only professed his innocence in the
strongest possible terms, he also pleaded ignorance of the events
of the night before. Martinez said he left the game early to return
to the hotel for a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was (Saenz) the one who hit the home run?'' Martinez said,
looking unblinkingly at his questioners. ``I wasn't watching the
game. I don't know him. I have no idea who he is. I don't think I
ever faced him. I had no reason to hit him. Just because my team
gave it up (a home run), that's no reason to hit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you get fresh with me, or if you show me up, I'll drill
your ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanley, who has trumped last week's 0-for-22 slump with an
11-for-22 outburst, had three hits on a day the Sox had 15 _ a
season high. John Valentin also registered three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's 13 strikeouts matched his previous high with the Sox
and fell one short of his career best.
</P>
<P>
   He limited the A's to just five hits and a run, which came after
the Sox had taken a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary opened the scoring with his seventh home run of the
season to start the second, and the Sox made A's starter Gil
Heredia disappear in a flurry of base hits in a four-run fourth
that featured four doubles and two singles, all hit with authority.
Even the outs that inning were loud. A's centerfielder Jason
McDonald took a home run away from Jason Varitek with a leaping
catch at the wall, and he also overtook O'Leary's drive over his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been swinging the bats better,'' said Varitek, who had
two hits. ``We just haven't pitched well and hit well at the same
time. Those days are going to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
