<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett takes fifth the hard way
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Dale Jarrett has been NASCAR's most consistent
driver for nearly two months, with top-five finishes in the last
seven races.
</P>
<P>
   None was as tough as his fifth-place outing in Sunday's
California 500 at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where to start with what happened,'' Jarrett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who started second behind race winner Jeff Gordon, led
the first lap and was running fifth 60 laps into the 250-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   Then things took a turn for the worse. Jarrett's pit crew took
19.4 seconds on his first green-flag pit stop on lap 77, nearly
three seconds longer than Mark Martin's 16.2-second stop.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be the least of Jarrett's problems. He made
his third pit stop on lap 126 and got caught a lap down to Martin
when Ricky Rudd crashed in turn 4. After another caution on lap
140, Jarrett tried to pit, but pit road wasn't open yet because of
an accident.
</P>
<P>
   On lap 153, one of Jarrett's tires blew up. Fortunately, the
mishap left debris on the track, so he wasn't forced to make an
unscheduled stop after nearly pulling onto pit road. Still, he was
running 12th five laps later.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Jarrett rebounded to finish fifth. As a result, points
leader Jeff Burton widened his lead over Jarrett by just 15 points,
for a lead of 55 after 10 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until 20 laps to go, I would have never figured we could
finish in the top five,'' Jarrett said. ``I was hoping we could
finish in the top 15 and not lose too many points. With everything
that happened to us, we could have lost a lot of points.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of gas
</P>
<P>
   How do you go from winning a race to running out of gas? Ask
Dale Earnhardt. That's what happened on lap 86 after Earnhardt
didn't pit with the lead-lap cars six or seven laps earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's crew apparently saw Ted Musgrave's No. 75 Ford
slowing on the track and thought a caution flag might be thrown.
What they didn't know was that Musgrave had run out of gas.
Earnhardt ran out of gas and had to coast into the pits.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt lost a lap to the leaders. He regained it two laps
later, but still finished 12th, one lap behind the top nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a fair day,'' he said. ``We were mediocre on the
race track and mediocre in the pits.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's hot _ literally
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Tony Stewart hasn't made many mistakes in his first 10
Winston Cup events, but he made one before Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who climbed to sixth in points with his second straight
top-5, forgot to wear his heat-resistant boots, which go over his
driving shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out about 50 laps into the race,'' Stewart said. ``I
paid for it the rest of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   On lap 147, Stewart tried to pass Rusty Wallace, but he got
loose and nearly spun out. He fell from fifth to 11th, but
eventually made his way back to the front pack.$20 million Bill
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott's 19th-place finish earned the Dawsonville native
$48,325, pushing him past $20 million in career earnings. Elliott
joins Earnhardt and Gordon as the only drivers to surpass that
mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did it all go?'' Elliott said earlier. ``It's sure a
long way
</P>
<P>
   from the $640 I earned at my first race (at Rockingham, N.C., in
1976).''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
