<HEADLINE>
NATO ADMITS MISSILE HIT BUS BUT CALLS BRIDGE A VALID TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO acknowledged Sunday that one of its missiles
had accidentally hit a bus in Kosovo on Saturday but insisted that
the bridge the bus was crossing had been a legitimate military
target.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Foreign Ministry said the attack on the bridge,
about 10 miles north of Pristina, the Kosovo capital, killed 47
passengers on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesmen said the bus began to cross the concrete bridge
only after the pilot had fired the missile, and that the pilot had
not seen the vehicle. The nationality of the pilot and the type of
plane involved in the attack were not immediately revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not target the bus and there was no intention to harm
civilians, and any loss of innocent life is regretted,'' said Col.
Konrad Freytag, a NATO spokesman. ``This was a legitimate military
target on a key north-south resupply route for the federal Republic
of Yugoslavia military and special police operations.''
</P>
<P>
   During a day of intensive airstrikes on Yugoslavia, NATO and the
Pentagon also reported the loss Sunday of two American warplanes.
An F-16 fighter went down over Yugoslavia near the Bosnian border
and a Harrier jump-jet crashed into the Adriatic Sea during a
training exercise. Both pilots were rescued.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said the F-16 pilot ejected from his plane at about 2:20
a.m. after the engine failed for reasons that have not been
determined. He was rescued about two hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is safely back at his operating base, where he is receiving
medical attention and being debriefed,'' said Jamie Shea, the NATO
spokesman in Brussels, Belgium. NATO and Pentagon officials said
they had no evidence to support news reports in Yugoslavia that the
plane, which was returning from a combat mission over Yugoslavia,
had been shot down.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy said the Harrier lost power and crashed into the sea
about 25 miles east of Brindisi, Italy, during a training flight,
and that the pilot was recovered by a rescue helicopter after
spending about five minutes in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav television repeatedly showed grisly footage of the
charred hulk of the bus destroyed Saturday and the bodies of the
people who had been trapped inside. The attack left NATO spokesmen
on the defensive during a briefing at the alliance headquarters in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to underline that we did not bomb the bus,'' Freytag
said, noting that he had seen video displays of the attack from the
cockpit of the fighter. ``We did not target the bus. I have seen
the video and on that video it shows much earlier another vehicle
passing the bridge and not being harmed at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
