<SLUG> BC-RAC-KENTUCKY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30-1 SHOT CHARISMATIC HITS PAYDIRT 
</HEADLINE>
 DERBY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ When the horses charged into the stretch, Cat
Thief taking the lead at the quarter-pole from Worldly Manner, Cat
Thief's trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, began cheering wildly: `C'mon, Cat
Thief. Cat Thief, c'mon! We got it! Cat Thief, c'mon! We've got
it!''
</P>
<P>
   Some 100 yards from the wire, though, despite Lukas's pleadings
and urgings, another horse came up to Cat Thief and passed him. For
a moment, Lukas seemed stunned, stunned into silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charismatic!'' he then shouted. The new leader, the horse
charging home to win the 125th Kentucky Derby, was none other than
Lukas's other horse, the forgotten former claiming horse,
Charismatic, stunning one and all, especially the bettors, who had
him 30-1.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic paid a whopping $64.60, the third-highest payoff in
Derby history behind Donerail's $184.90 in 1913 and the $72.40 paid
to the backers of Gallahadion in 1940. The 7-1 Menifee finished
second Saturday, closing stoutly to miss by a neck, while the 7-1
Cat Thief was third.
</P>
<P>
   Rich men and rich women, sheikhs and princes, horse fanciers and
experts, pay hundreds of thousands of dollars, even millions, to
buy young horses who just might deliver the thrill that Charismatic
brought to Lukas and owners Bob and Beverly Lewis Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But on Feb. 11, in the sixth race at Santa Anita, Charismatic
was entered into a claiming race and could have been bought by any
horseman for $62,500. Charismatic had been bought as a yearling for
$200,000 but had become more and more ordinary ``and I thought we'd
maybe get sixty-two fifty if somebody claimed him and pay some of
the bills,'' said Bob Lewis. Charismatic couldn't even win that
race ``but we took a calculated risk with him,'' said Lukas, ``just
so we could build up his confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic became the first horse to have run in a claiming
race and win the Derby since Dust Commander did it in 1970.
Saturday's winning time of 2:03 1/5 was most ordinary, the slowest
winning Derby time on a fast track since Cannonade plodded home in
2:04 in the 100th edition in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Charismatic went unclaimed, as claiming races most
often are for ordinary and inferior horses. And when Charismatic
escaped the claiming box unscathed, said Lukas, ``I told Bob
(Lewis) that we'd never do that again. We breathed a sigh of
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Derby was so wide open that the 151,051 fans at
Churchill Downs were as confused as no Derby crowd in the 125 years
of the classic had been confused. Only once in Derby history had a
favorite ever gone off as high as 4-1 (Prairie Bayou, $4.40 to 1 in
1993), and Saturday's favorite was the highest in history. The Bob
Baffert entry of General Challenge and Excellent Meeting was sent
off at $4.80 to 1. (His Prime Timber finished fourth).
</P>
<P>
   And it was clear from that tote board that something was amiss
with Baffert's entry, which had been the morning line favorite at
5-1. The backstretch grapevine at Churchill Downs is so finely
tuned that when Baffert's entry went up in odds, rather than down,
it was clear they would not be winning the third Derby in a row for
Baffert. Excellent Meeting finished fifth and General Challenge
finished 11th.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief instant, at the top of the stretch, Sheikh Mohammed
al Maktoum's Worldly Manner took the lead, shocking all who had
belittled the Godolphin Stable's approach toward training for this
Derby. But then Cat Thief passed Worldly Manner and Charismatic
swooped by them all.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was vindication for Lukas, who had been under
criticism in recent years for entering so many horses in the Derby
(34), but his fourth Derby silenced all. It was vindication also
for jockey Chris Antley, beset by weight and substance abuse
problems since winning the 1991 Derby with Strike The Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the name `Forrest Gump' in South Carolina,'' said a
tearful Antley of his running many miles a day on his comeback
attempt and not giving up despite many telling him he could not
make it back after a year away from the sport. ``I was in South
Carolina for about a year and for the last eight months I was
trying to get my wieght down. I didn't think I would be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Antley's father, Les, advised his 33-year-old son to give
it up. ``My day said, `Start another business,' '' said Antley.
`You don't need to ride . . . it's dangerous.' But I told my father
that I had a goal in life and I would get to that goal. I will be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Tears still flowed from Antley, who now weighs 114 pounds, but
had seen his weight balloon up to 147. ``Last November,'' he said,
``I told my dad, `The Derby's coming up and wouldn't it be neat if
I rode in it.' I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley was so wrapped in the emotion of winning the race that he
removed his left hand from the reins in the final yards, nearly
costing him the race to the fast-closing Menifee, who missed
winning by a neck (Cat Thief finished three-quarters of a length
behind Menifee). ``Yes,'' said Antley, ``I pointed my finger. I
looked up and thanked God.''
</P>
<P>
   The win by Charismatic also was vindication for Secretariat, who
still holds the Derby record for fastest time, set in 1973. In the
last 25 years, no horse with Secretariat blood in his veins ever
had won the Derby. Saturday, all three of the top finishers _
Charismatic, Menifee, and Cat Thief _ were descendants of
Secretariat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DODGERS-CUBA-BOS &LR;      05-02 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-CUBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID LA STEP OVER LINE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Two minor league players have told baseball
officials an astonishing tale of international intrigue, accusing
the Los Angeles Dodgers of holding secret tryouts in Cuba,
orchestrating the players' escape from the communist-ruled island,
then ordering them to lie about the elaborate scheme.
</P>
<P>
   If true, the allegations would place the Dodgers in violation of
Major League Baseball rules that prohibit teams from scouting in
Cuba, and possibly the longstanding US trade embargo. They also
would represent the most brazen effort yet to strip Cuba of one of
its greatest natural resources: the talented ballplayers who have
been defecting from the country in droves.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-odd defections, the latest of which occurred last month
at a junior tournament in Caracas, have created tension between the
government of Fidel Castro and Major League Baseball, tension that
has been eased recently by home-and-home exhibition games between
the Cuban national team and the Baltimore Orioles. The second game
is scheduled for Monday night at Baltimore's Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Avila, a Dodgers senior vice president, angrily denied the
latest accusations, which were outlined in a letter sent last month
to Major League Baseball officials in New York. First baseman Juan
Carlos Diaz, 23, and outfielder Josue Perez, 21, have asked to be
declared free agents on grounds that they were signed illegally and
at less than market value.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that nobody should go to Cuba,'' said Avila, who
once led troops into Havana with Castro's 26th of July Movement,
then returned to try to overthrow him at the Bay of Pigs. ``Look, I
don't work for the immigration. I don't work for the State
Department. I don't work for the police department. If somebody
went to Cuba, it's not my business.''
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Peguero, the scout alleged to have arranged the
defections, also denied the reports. In an interview from Santo
Domingo, Peguero said he had not been in Cuba in more than 10 years
and suggested that the players were trying to blackmail the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They invent many things when money's involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz and Perez, he said, ``arrived on their own, like millions
and millions of others have arrived in Miami and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Diaz, who slugged 30 homers last year at Single A and Double
A, and Perez, a whippet-fast spray hitter who is with the Dodgers'
Single A club at Vero Beach, Fla., told nearly identical stories
during separate interviews recently at the Dodgers' spring training
facility here.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said he was first approached in December 1995 by Peguero
after a developmental league game in Havana. He said the scout
identified himself as a Dodger representative, asked for his
address, and invited him to a tryout the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Peguero appeared at his home around 9 a.m. the next day with
bats, balls, and a video camera, Diaz said. He said Peguero took
him to a nearby field, pitched batting practice to him, timed him
running the 60-yard dash, and had him field errant throws at first
base. He said Peguero taped most of the workout and called him
later to say that Dodger officials were pleased with his tryout and
wanted to bring him to the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after their first meeting, Diaz said, Peguero
returned to Cuba with a woman he introduced as a cousin and told
Diaz that she was having surgery. Diaz said Peguero's cousin then
fabricated the story that enabled him to obtain a visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told the authorities that I was a friend, that my family
had helped find a Cuban doctor for her surgery, and that she wanted
to invite me to the Dominican Republic as a sign of her
gratitude,'' said Diaz, adding that the woman paid all of his
travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Once he was in the Dominican Republic, the Dodgers placed Diaz
in their training academy at Campo Las Palmas outside Santo
Domingo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they paid off people or what, but I
immediately got my provisional residency papers, which enabled me
to sign,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was called into Avila's office and told he would
receive a signing bonus of $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything,'' he said. ``Look, I was in the
Dominican Republic. The (other) players were getting $2,000,
$2,500, $4,000 bonuses to sign. I saw $65,000 and thought this was
super. Now I realize that what they did was abusive. I have
demonstrated that I was worth more than $65,000.''
</P>
<P>
   After he signed, Diaz said, Peguero and Avila told him to lie if
he ever was asked how he escaped to the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They warned me against speaking with reporters,'' he said,
``that if anyone asked to say I was invited to the Dominican
Republic by a girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said the Dodgers initially listed him as a Dominican native
on team rosters.
</P>
<P>
   Peguero insisted that Diaz had, in fact, come to the Dominican
Republic with a woman, but not the Dodger scout's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He arrived with a girlfriend,'' Peguero said. ``He said he was
in love or something like that. We didn't sign him until he got his
Dominican residency.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Diaz, in turn, recommended Perez, who was signed under
the same circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that teams have been sending scouts into Cuba have
circulated for years, but the allegations against the Dodgers are
by far the most specific. Stunning in their sheer audacity, the
stories, if confirmed, would raise to a new level the risk that
teams seem willing to take in their insatiable quest for fresh
talent.
</P>
<P>
   In the only documented case of scouting in Cuba, a
Cuban-American agent from Miami, Juan Ignacio Hernandez, was
arrested in 1996 for allegedly trying to persuade players at a
junior tournament in the city of Sancti Spiritus to defect.
Hernandez also had made contact with pitcher Orlando ``El Duque''
Hernandez (no relation), who later defected and has become a star
with the Yankees. Cuban authorities sentenced the agent to 15 years
in prison and shortly thereafter banned El Duque from Cuban
baseball for life.
</P>
<P>
   A scout with an American League team said the Commissioner's
Office has repeatedly warned teams against going into Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've sent e-mails to each office that you're not allowed to
go down there,'' said the scout. ``They've made it very clear that
you can't negotiate with any Cuban players even if you're out of
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Courtney, a spokesman for Major League Baseball,
declined comment on the reports. Sandy Alderson of the
Commissioner's Office confirmed that he received the aformentioned
letter but otherwise declined comment. In the past, the
Commissioner's Office has said that teams could face fines,
suspensions, or loss of draft choices if found in violation of the
rules against scouting in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Dodgers also would have violated the 36-year trade
embargo, which prohibits American companies from conducting
business on the island, is unclear. According to the Treasury
Department, which enforces the embargo, teams are prohibited from
visiting Cuba to scout or recruit. A Treasury official said the
embargo permits only humanitarian and cultural exchanges, such as
the Orioles series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting ballplayers is not part of that,'' said the
official.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals can be fined up to $55,000 for violations. The
maximum corporate fine is $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The chilling effect of Juan Ignacio Hernandez's arrest was
believed to have deterred most scouts from entering Cuba. But
Perez, the outfielder, said Peguero helped him defect on Feb. 23,
1997, after a courtship that began in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Peguero held another tryout for him in 1996, Perez said, then
came to Havana at the end of the year to arrange the escape. He
introduced Perez to a young woman, who he said would arrange the
formal invitation for him to leave. Perez said he was given a
30-day tourist visa, traveled with the woman to the Dominican
Republic, then never saw her again.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said the Dodgers forbade him from seeing an agent after
placing him in Campo Las Palmas. After several months, Avila and
Peguero signed him for a $40,000 bonus, but told him not to tell
anyone how he had gotten to the Dominican.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `It's $40,000, sign here,' '' said Perez. ``If I
didn't sign, what was I going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Perez eventually retained an agent, Los Angeles-based Gus
Dominguez, who was also Diaz's agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He began to open my eyes,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez, reached in Los Angeles, confirmed that the two
players had filed a grievance but declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he feared that he might be found out before he left
Cuba, Perez, seated at a restaurant in Vero Beach, said, ``If
you're fearful, you won't get anywhere in life. I wouldn't be
sitting here talking to you if I was fearful. Pablo said he would
take care of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said Peguero told him that after one trip to Cuba his plane
was held up by Cuban security agents and he was escorted from the
plane and interrogated. The agents eventually allowed him to leave,
Diaz said the scout told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He vowed never to set foot in Cuba again,'' Diaz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
