<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-RAPIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION GO DOWN FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution finally lost a game in
regulation time Saturday night. And a 2-1 defeat against the
Colorado Rapids cost the Revolution a chance to move into first
place in the Eastern Conference of MLS.
</P>
<P>
   In their first five games, the Revolution had two
regulation-time victories, and had trailed for a total of only 21
minutes. But they presented a makeshift defense in their sixth
game, and the Rapids capitalized on the Revolution's
disorganization in the first half, and scored a disputed goal in
the second half as the Revolution pressed for the winner while
playing an offside trap.
</P>
<P>
   Even player-coach Walter Zenga, whose goalkeeping had
compensated for defensive mistakes in previous matches, could not
prevent a defeat. Panamanian striker Jorge Dely Valdes of Colorado
finished a move started by Wolde Harris for the first goal in the
seventh minute. Dely Valdes was kept onside by Manny Motajo, who
was making his first start as a replacement for Richard Goulooze
(calf strain) in central defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Colorado had several other chances in the first half as the
Revolution defenders never seemed settled. Brian Dunseth, who is
better suited for the middle, struggled with his passing on the
right side as Mike Burns (hamstring pull) missed his first match.
Motajo was benched after halftime. And the Revolution, with only 13
field players available, had few answers.
</P>
<P>
   Joe-Max Moore tied the score with a powerful, bouncing free kick
from outside 25 yards in the 20th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Ivan McKinley-Dan Calichman combination solidified the
central defense in the second half and gave the Revolution a chance
to win. They went to a three-defender scheme and depended more on
the offside trap, which seemed to be well executed.
</P>
<P>
   But Harris scored the game-winner in the 81st minute after a
David Vaudreuil pass to Joey DiGiamarino was allowed. DiGiamarino
had difficulty with his first touch, but had so much room that he
had time to settle and cross for Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a ton of offsides that weren't called,'' Calichman
said. ``But just because they don't call it doesn't mean we can't
stop the play. We played poorly and were beaten by the better team.
The loss of concentration for a minute, actually for a second, cost
us a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the slow start, the Revolution had chances in the first
half as Colorado failed to control the tempo and made several
appalling giveaways. Paulo Dos Santos, an original member of the
Revolution who was starting for the first time, slammed a shot off
the crossbar in the 13th minute.
</P>
<P>
   By the second half, the Revolution pressed forward, searching
for the winner. The three Revolution substitutes in the second half
were all attackers. Jamar Beasley pressured the Rapids with his
speed after replacing Motajo. But Johnny Torres and Tony Kuhn
failed to add to the attack, and Kuhn's giveaway set up Colorado's
winning counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's frustration became apparent late in the match
as McKinley was ejected by referee Ruben Rodhas after a clash with
Colorado goalkeeper Marcus Hahnemann. Zenga and assistant coach
Giuseppe Galderisi pursued the refereeing crew after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play our game and I didn't play well,'' Jair said.
``They scored early and got their confidence, but we believed we
could win in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose, you get a little down. But it's still the
beginning of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
