<HEADER>
A1510 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OWNERS-B     05-02 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OWNERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNERS OF ONE WILD LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Patrick Sullivan reacted like a fan when he heard the
Patriots' stadium deal in Hartford had fallen through and they were
staying in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great news. I was one of those people not necessarily
fearing a move to Hartford, but one who feared they might move to
Houston,'' said Sullivan, the team's former general manager and son
of William Sullivan, the founder and longtime owner of the Patriots
who died Feb. 23, 1998, at 82.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Sullivan is a private citizen these days, although he
still is linked to the league by his television production
business. He still lives in the area and is a season ticket-holder.
</P>
<P>
   There are many things Sullivan misses about the game, but there
are many things he's glad he never will have to deal with again.
</P>
<P>
   No more lawsuits. No more failed attempts to build stadiums,
lucrative deals that would have made life a little easier for his
father. No more dealing with player agents, whose influence began
to rise at an alarming rate toward the end of his reign. Best of
all, no more controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In commenting on what now may be the final chapter of Patriots
stadium follies, he was taken by the great interest shown by the
Boston business community in the team, which many believe spurred
Massachusetts lawmakers to finally agree on a $70 million
infrastructure package for the Patriots, now owned by Robert Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan wished this interest was as loud and strong back in the
1960s and '70s, when the Patriots had a chance to stay in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the support of the business leaders, I said, `Wow,
this happened about 30 years too late,' '' Sullivan said.
``Obviously it's great that it happened now so the team can open a
state-of-the-art stadium in Foxborough and keep the team in this
area, but if that commitment had been shown by the business leaders
years ago, I think the Patriots would have been in Boston. To me,
the real tragedy in all of this is that nothing could be worked out
in Boston. The Patriots should have been in Boston and my father
really dedicated himself to keeping them there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan remembers a 1964 plan that was approved by the city and
state to build a $98 million retractable-roof stadium at the end of
the Massachusetts Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a 55,000-seat stadium, with parking
garages, a hotel,'' recalled Sullivan. ``It was way ahead of its
time. The state was going to build it but it called for all four
sports teams to commit to 20-year leases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox and Tom Yawkey wanted out of Fenway Park. The
Celtics wanted out of the Garden. But what killed the deal was the
Bruins. They controlled all of the concessions at the Garden and
they wanted to keep that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Sullivan said a football-only stadium across from the
Keystone plant at Neponset eventually was crushed by ``a lot of
political mumbo-jumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until a few months later, when E.M. Lowe was convinced
by Prescott Hobson to donate land at the racetrack in Foxborough to
Stadium Reality Trust, that the deal there became a reality. At the
time there was also the possibility the Patriots would move to the
Rockingham Park area in Salem, N.H., but that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was Foxborough. Schaefer Stadium, with concrete slabs
and aluminum seats that made a warm fall day seem wintry, was built
at a cost of $6.8 million, giving the Patriots a home for the last
28 years after opening Aug. 15, 1971, amid chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Massive traffic jams on Route 1, bad plumbing, locker room
urinals mistakenly placed too high, and incidents of bad behavior
by fans on Monday nights all had Boston-area fans wondering whether
it was a good idea after all.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the problems at the stadium were corrected little by
little over the years by Foxborough officials and ultimately by
Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been plenty of problems with the team overall,
most the result of ownership inadequacies and financial problems
that, in part, were because of the increasingly inadequate stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Victor Kiam, owner of the Remington company, owned the team from
1988-92 after a proposed deal between Billy Sullivan and Kraft fell
through. While Kiam bought the team for a song, his efforts to
purchase the stadium failed because Kraft outbid him. That left
Kiam holding on to a team that couldn't generate enough revenue
from the luxury boxes, parking, and concessions, much of which
belonged to Kraft, with another entity owning some parking.
</P>
<P>
   There were failed attempts by Kiam to sell the team to groups in
Memphis, Jacksonville, and Baltimore, and Kiam's own financial
downfall and the bad publicity created by the sexual harassment
suit principally involving Zeke Mowatt and former Herald writer
Lisa Olson made Kiam's tenure a circus.
</P>
<P>
   Not more than two months after he bought the team, he told then
Boston Mayor Ray Flynn he needed a new stadium or he'd be forced to
sell out of New England. Kiam never got his stadium and he never
recovered from his bad business deal.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kiam there was Fran Murray, a bright, articulate man from
Philadelphia who in 1986 saved the Sullivans from bankruptcy by
borrowing $21 million (which gave him 49 percent ownership) to
become a partner with an option to purchase the team. That was,
only to find on the day he was supposed to exercise his right to
buy the team along with Reebok head Paul Fireman, the Sullivans had
made a deal with Kiam. Murray never had met Kiam, but he was now
his reluctant partner.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was also the first to attempt to orchestrate a deal with
Hartford, dealing with former Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker Jr.
on a $130 million stadium plan that also fell through.
</P>
<P>
   When Kiam finally sold to James Orthwein in May of 1992, Murray
remained minority owner. He eventually sold his interest to
Orthwein in November of '92 and concentrated his efforts in St.
Louis to get what became the RCA Dome built.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis businessman Orthwein always was seen as a temporary
owner, one who wanted a pro football team in his hometown and tried
to move the Patriots there.
</P>
<P>
   Orthwein and his business partners were unable to crack a
determined Kraft, who owned the stadium after purchasing it out of
bankruptcy court for $50 million. Kraft had an iron-clad lease that
the Patriots had to play their home games at Foxboro Stadium for
the length of the lease. Any attempt to move the team would result
in a lawsuit that Kraft would win easily. The lease was Kraft's key
to finally purchasing the team.
</P>
<P>
   Orthwein pushed hard for the megaplex deal in Boston in 1993,
but that also never came to fruition. Unable to get his hands on
Kraft's stadium, he sold the team to Kraft for a reported $168
million, a deal that became official Feb. 25, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   During his ownership, Orthwein hired Bill Parcells as coach, and
the team made Drew Bledsoe the No. 1 pick in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Sullivan, Murray, and Kiam all wound up suing the NFL.
Sullivan retrieved about $11.5 million after some wins and losses;
he had claimed the NFL essentially forced him to sell the team by
not letting him make a public stock offering. Murray had his suit
in federal court thrown out when a judge ruled the league had not
acted improperly in arbitrating his dispute with Kiam or in its
handling of Murray's application for an expansion team in St.
Louis. Kiam, claiming the NFL wouldn't allow him to move the team,
lost a $150 million antitrust suit.
</P>
<P>
   Orthwein went off to St. Louis, where he has a minority
ownership interest in the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sale to Kraft began the most stable period of ownership the
Patriots ever had had. The day after Kraft bought the team, 5,958
season tickets were sold, and by April 29, 1995, every game was
sold out before the season for the first time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers, including former Gov. William Weld, promised
Kraft would be taken care of with a new football facility. A
promise one might say finally was kept, but not after much
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Sullivan, meanwhile, had his ups and downs with the
owners after his father. During the sexual harassment incident and
a 1-15 season in 1990, Kiam suspended Sullivan. A year later Sam
Jankovich was brought in and Sullivan was under his control. That
marriage didn't last long, and Sullivan left his role of football
executive for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that problem with Victor, but hey, that goes with the
territory,'' said Sullivan. ``It's over. There's nothing more to be
said about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan never knew Orthwein, but was certainly familiar with
the Krafts. ``My dad had known them because they had been season
ticket-holders for years and they had owned the Boston Lobsters,''
said Sullivan. ``We tried to sell them the team, but Bob had an
adviser who we called `Dr. No.' Anything we proposed he would say
no. So we called him `Dr. No.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some disagreements, but the Krafts have been great
owners of the team. Bob and Myra Kraft are two of the most generous
people you'll ever find in the Boston area. They have done so much
good for so many people. And now Bob has stepped up and turned down
a lot of money to keep the team where he feels it belongs. That's
great. It really shows his commitment to the people of this area
and I think dad had that commitment as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a true home and stable ownership. It's only taken 39
years to get to this point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
