</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT ELWAY, BRONCOS MAY NOT MAKE RUN FOR IT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As of Sunday, the Jacksonville Jaguars are the team to
beat in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   That simple fact says as much about John Elway as the NFL-record
148 regular-season and 47 come-from-behind victories he led the
Denver Broncos to during a 16-year career that officially comes to
an end with his retirement announcement.
</P>
<P>
   For as much as people have insisted that the Broncos of late
were Terrell Davis's team, another man drove the bus in Denver and
he is gone now and the Broncos will pay a price for that next fall.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement of Elway is not like the 49ers letting Joe
Montana go to Kansas City when he was past his prime, as Elway also
is. There is no Steve Young behind Elway as there was behind
Montana in San Francisco. There is Bubby Brister, and that
eventually will show those who called the Broncos Davis's team that
it never really was.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is a great runner, perhaps the best in the game today
(although for my money Barry Sanders is still unbeatable). But
great runners seldom can carry their team to the Super Bowl.
Quarterbacks do that, as no less a fan of the running game than
Bill Parcells knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quarterbacks, like coaches, are judged by their jewelry,''
Parcells loves to say, and Elway is proof of that, being the only
quarterback to lead a team to five Super Bowls while playing with
33 running backs and 22 receivers during his career.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot often go the distance without a great defense or a
great quarterback or both in the NFL. A great runner is a weapon of
supreme significance, but he alone cannot often affect a season the
way a great quarterback can. If that were so, Walter Payton, Eric
Dickerson, Earl Campbell, Jim Brown, Tony Dorsett, O.J. Simpson,
and Sanders would have more than three world championship rings
among them, for they were among the game's greatest runners, far
greater for far longer than Davis has been.
</P>
<P>
   So the loss of Elway cannot be minimized for the Broncos, who
have averaged 13 wins a season the past three years while winning
back-to-back Super Bowls. The presence of Brister, who at 37 has
not started more than eight games in a season since 1990, or Chris
Miller, a 34-year-old returning pensioner who retired four years
ago because of repeated concussions, will cost the Broncos a game
or two next season. Not because of their own failures, but simply
because they are not Elway. And that will cost Denver the chance to
three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing Davis can do about that. After rushing for
2,008 yards last season, there is simply nothing more he can do for
his team that he's already done.
</P>
<P>
   That is not meant to imply he's washed up, it is just to make
clear that whether he rushes for 1,700 or 1,800 or 2,000 yards he
cannot replace what Elway brought to the Broncos, even in his
declining years, because Elway brought fear to the stadium with him
on the opponent's bus. Fear and the clear understanding of every
defensive coordinator in the game that you could not stack your
defense to simply stop Davis even if this was now his team, nor
could you safely assume you had the Broncos beaten as long as Elway
had the ball and enough time to produce a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling is gone now and a quarterback named Bubby cannot
bring it back. It leaves Sunday when Elway walks out of his last
press conference in Denver and into the sunset of his athletic
life. The respect will remain for the Broncos because Mike Shanahan
has built a solid team around a star runner and a talented
offensive line, but respect is not the same as fear. Fear leads
opponents to limit what they'll try to do. Fear freezes opponents
for a fatal moment _ all the time a quarterback like Elway needs to
beat them. Fear is far more debilitating to an opponent than
respect.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no fear of Davis's Broncos this year because no
one will fear the man who hands him the ball. That's what the
retirement of Elway has taken away from Denver.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years Shanahan has been considered a genius for
the multiheaded offensive system he has designed for the Broncos,
and he may well be a genius of design, the Bill Gates of offensive
football. But a programmer eventually has to turn his program over
to an operator, and if that operator pushes the wrong buttons at
the wrong moments errors result, and eventually the system shuts
down. The Broncos' system seldom shut down when Elway was running
it and often exceeded its capabilities in the years Dan Reeves was
giving him one that included an undersized defense and no running
back at all. Shanahan did better by Elway and consequently he did
slightly better by the Broncos, twice winning the season's final
game.
</P>
<P>
   Now Shanahan will to try to do it the other way _ with a great
running back but a far less resourceful operator running his
system. He will have a chance now that he never really wanted.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have a chance to prove he really is a genius, because
he'll have to be the one to win it all without John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't hold your breath waiting for the multimillion-dollar fines
and temporary loss of services of the players in question that some
predicted the Cowboys faced for allegedly reaching agreements with
free agents Rocket Ismail, Mark Stepnoski, and Quentin Coryatt
without officially signing them because it would endanger the
team's salary cap compliance. While the league is looking into the
matter at the insistence of several Cowboys opponents, the fact is
no team or free agent has to sign a contract the moment a
settlement is reached. Second, if the Cowboys don't sign them, both
sides remain at risk, gambling that injury or another offer won't
conspire to break their oral contract, if there is such a thing in
professional sports. If a player, or a team, is willing to gamble
by waiting for the papers to be signed, there is little the NFL can
do about it but fume. That this violates the spirit of the salary
cap is obvious, but such actions go all the way back to the cap's
earliest days and, in fact, are commonplace. Onetime Bengals
lineman Max Montoya, for example, agreed to a contract in
Cincinnati the first year of free agency but didn't sign it and 10
days later jumped to the Raiders because he got an unexpected
bigger offer. The Bengals were irate but had no recourse. That is
the gamble Dallas owner Jerry Jones took when he reportedly reached
agreements with all three players that took them off the market but
had not cleared enough salary cap room to officially sign them. The
NFL can do nothing about this until it changes its cap regulations
to give a team X amount of time to file a signed contract after an
agreement is reached . . . Time and his waistline caught up with
quotable Nate Newton Thursday when Jones announced that he did not
plan to re-sign the six-time All-Pro who has played 13 years in
Dallas. The Cowboys are planning to move their best lineman, Larry
Allen, into Newton's left guard spot from left tackle and are
hoping No. 2 draft choice Solomon Page can handle one of the tackle
jobs . . . Gil Brandt, one of the originators of the computerized
information-gathering that now passes for scouting in the NFL, has
to laugh at the way his ideas are now being used. ``We started all
that in Dallas to find a way to break the tie when you have six
guys who are about identical in ability and all look alike,''
Brandt explained. ``It was never really supposed to be the main
deciding factor. Last year only two offensive linemen ran the 40
under 5 flat: Kyle Turley and Steve McKinney. They both ended up
starting every game at New Orleans and Indianapolis. But the two
strongest guys got cut. Next year it could be the opposite.
Sometimes things change. The more I scouted over the years, the
more I began to believe that if you can find a way to see who will
really work hard at being good after they sign, you'll have the key
factor to success. When Calvin Hill came to us, his goal was to
make more money every year. Because of that he was always working.
Do you think Terry Glenn has worked hard to get better? Joey
Galloway (Glenn's former Ohio State teammate) was always in the
workout room if you went to Ohio State and looked for him. Others
aren't.'' . . . According to Brandt, all you have to do is watch
film of Saints No. 1-and-only draft choice Ricky Williams against
Nebraska last season to understand the kind of player he is. ``He
runs 50 yards to tackle a guy from behind and he makes a pickup
block on a blitz that was beautiful to watch,'' Brandt said. ``You
already know he can run the ball but you get the Nebraska tape and
you know he's a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During rookie minicamp last week, University of Maine wide
receiver Drew O'Connor made a good first impression on Tampa Bay
coach Tony Dungy, which is what an unknown free agent has to do.
The 6-foot-3 1/2-inch O'Connor, who had 71 receptions for 1,027
yards in Orono, was signed after the draft because his size and
hands caught the eye of area scout Joe DiMarzo, who twice went to
Orono to work O'Connor out. The Bucs have four sure-shot receivers
on their roster but Dungy may keep seven and is looking for size in
several of them. If O'Connor can show he has the speed to get off
the line, he has a shot at a job . . . Seattle coach Mike Holmgren
is wasting little time letting the Seahawks know it's a new day. He
already has conducted two minicamps and ripped several veterans for
missing much of the second one with injuries. Although he did not
single out running back Ricky Watters and defensive tackle Cortez
Kennedy, who claimed hamstring and back problems, he says,
``There's a handful of fellas that are going to have to learn how
we do things. They are good football players but they have to learn
how we practice.'' What he meant by that was every day. Holmgren
has another minicamp next month and two more planned for June . . .
The Bengals will bring in veteran cornerback Cris Dishman this week
for a look, and so will Kansas City. The 34-year-old Dishman was
released by the Redskins after they drafted Champ Bailey last
month, allowing them to avoid paying Dishman $2.7 million this
year. The Bengals are looking for a veteran backup to play behind
rookie Charles Fisher, and Dishman could be the man if his contract
demands are low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ELWAY-RETIRES-NYT     05-02 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-RETIRES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ELWAY FINDS IT HARD TO SAY GOODBYE  (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGLEWOOD, Colo. _ It is something most athletes, especially
great competitors like John Elway, find incredibly hard to say:
that their bodies, after years of pounding, can no longer perform
at a top level.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks Elway has stared at his ailing knees, remembered
the pain-killing shots he took for his injured ribs and tired of
the rigorous physical therapy sessions he endured just to attend
practice for the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, 38, knew what was happening. Age had caught him in the
way no defensive lineman ever could. That is why Sunday at a
suburban Denver hotel he officially announced his retirement from
the NFL after 16 marvelous seasons, including two Super Bowl
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Elway will go down as one of the best quarterbacks in history,
but even he could not overcome the toll football took on his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard,'' said an emotional Elway, who cried several
times during his nearly one-hour news conference before his family,
members of the Broncos and more than 100 members of the news media.
``There's an over-under in the locker room on how many times I'm
going to cry. It's been great. It was a tough decision to make. I
really don't look at it like it's a retirement. It's a graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for me to move on. I can't do it physically anymore,
and that's really hard for me to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway missed just 15 starts in 16 seasons because of illness or
injury, but he was one of the strongest _ and toughest _
quarterbacks ever, despite being sacked an NFL-record 559 times in
256 games. He played through broken bones, pulled muscles and
several severe knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Elway will most likely have his arthritic left knee
replaced in the coming years. Recently, Elway has had to spend
increasing time with Steve Antonopulos, the team's athletic
trainer, who patched up the future Hall of Famer like a rag doll
before and after games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had to go through so many things just to get ready for
practice,'' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's retirement was known for a week but was delayed because
of the shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. His
news conference began with a moment of silence for the victims and
Elway wore a blue-and-silver ribbon on his suit jacket in memory of
the slain students and teacher. Elway was joined on the stage by
the Broncos' owner, Pat Bowlen, and coach Mike Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   Elway leaves as the NFL's winningest quarterback with 148
victories. It is likely that Miami's Dan Marino, who has 142, will
pass him next season. But Marino would probably trade all of those
victories for a Super Bowl championship, something that had eluded
and haunted Elway for years.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his career, Elway was viewed as a spoiled brat, the
son of a coach who demanded a trade from the Baltimore Colts when
they took him as the first pick in the 1983 draft and a quarterback
who got into arguments with his former coach, Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   What truly angered and later motivated Elway was how he was
viewed as the quarterback who could not win a championship. Earlier
in his career, Elway had lost three Super Bowls by a total score of
136-40, and his critics, like former Pittsburgh Steelers
quarterback Terry Bradshaw, often ripped him for not being able to
win the big one.
</P>
<P>
   Elway would later call those losses, combined with his rift with
Reeves, among the saddest days of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed when Shanahan was named coach of the Broncos
in 1995. The first thing Shanahan did was give Elway more control
of the offense, including more freedom to call his own plays.
Shanahan also opened the offense up, allowing Elway to fully
utilize his strong arm and athletic gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, Shanahan drafted a little-known running
back from Georgia named Terrell Davis in the sixth round in 1995.
Elway and Davis would prove to be a potent combination.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his career, Elway had a franchise running
back. Teams could no longer focus all of their efforts on him; they
had to account for Davis, a slashing, powerful runner.
</P>
<P>
   The combination proved dangerous two seasons ago, with Davis
rushing for 1,750 yards and 15 touchdowns during the regular season
to help the Broncos to a 12-4 record. Then, behind Elway's powerful
arm and Davis' legs, the Broncos gained one of the biggest upsets
in championship history by beating a heavily favored Green Bay team
in Super Bowl XXXII, 31-24.
</P>
<P>
   It was Elway who made the critical play, leaping over three
Packers and scrambling for 6 yards and a first down near the Green
Bay goal line. Elway, running on those creaky knees, was hit in
midair and spun like a top.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos made it back to the Super Bowl last season, and
Elway faced Reeves, the coach he had not liked playing for. (Of the
dozens of people Elway thanked Sunday, Reeves was not one of them.)
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons dared Elway to beat them by often lining up seven
men near the line of scrimmage, and Elway did, throwing for 336
yards. He was named the most valuable player as Denver beat
Atlanta, 34-19. The only thing sweeter for Elway than beating
Reeves was hoisting the Lombardi trophy over his head with Bradshaw
watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that impressed me about John was the poise,''
Shanahan said, ``the performance under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who was a nine-time Pro Bowl quarterback, provided some
of the most incredible moments in football history. Perhaps the
most memorable was the 1986 AFC championship game against
Cleveland. Denver began a drive at its 2-yard line, trailing the
Browns by 20-13 late in the game. Elway led the Broncos on a
15-play, 98-yard drive that ended in a touchdown pass with 37
seconds left. Denver won, 23-20, in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The record book is spiced with Elway's name. He finishes with
51,475 passing yards (second), 4,123 completions (second), 300
touchdown passes (third), 7,250 passing attempts (second), and 12
3,000-yard passing seasons (second).
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe that John was the greatest to play the game,''
Bowlen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
