<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHING IN, POUND FOR POUND 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Having grown weary of hearing about how open scoring is
going to save boxing, and realizing that things are kind of slow in
the ring at the moment, this seems to me like the right time to get
into an argument instead of a fight, and what better way to do that
than to reopen the debate over who is boxing's pound-for-pound
champion?
</P>
<P>
   That title has for all intents and purposes been vacant since
the fall of Pernell Whitaker, who for many years held it so firmly
that the editors of Ring magazine finally went so far as to award
him a belt. But time and a fast-lane lifestyle finally eroded
Whitaker's skills, and since his loss to Oscar De La Hoya two years
ago the debate over his heir has raged without conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a clear-cut pound-for-pound champion and the
likelihood that none of those at the top of the list will ever meet
only add to the debate. Here is one man's learned opinion of
today's Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   1. Oscar De La Hoya (30-0, 24 KOs, World Boxing Council
welterweight champion).
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has faced consistently better competition than Roy
Jones or any of the world's other top fighters and showed his
mettle in a recent victory over previously undefeated Ike Quartey.
That night he passed his first big test, coming on in the final
three rounds to beat an opponent as tough as he is but apparently
not as determined.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's critics believed The Golden Boy would fold under
such pressure but the fact is he's been coming through whenever
he's been in the spotlight since the 1992 Olympics. Until something
_ or someone _ changes that, De La Hoya should be considered the
best.
</P>
<P>
   2. Roy Jones (39-1, 33 KOs, World Boxing Association-WBC light
heavyweight champion).
</P>
<P>
   Jones may have more talent, speed, and pure artistry than anyone
in boxing, including De La Hoya, but his reluctance to fight the
best of a sad lot of available middleweight, super middleweight,
and light heavyweight opponents is a problem. It is not that Jones
fears anyone, but his insistence on purses that exceed his fights'
value has caused him to miss several opportunities to cement his
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Until he answers a stiff challenge, a question will remain
unanswered. Such a test may come next month when he tries to unify
the 175-pound title by taking on International Boxing Federation
champion Reggie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   3. Shane Mosley (32-0, 30 KOs, IBF lightweight champion).
</P>
<P>
   Mosley was the Boxing Writers' Association 1998 Fighter of the
Year, and for good reason. He is the dominant 135-pounder in the
world and no one else is close. He can box or punch, and his talent
seems as limitless as Jones's and De La Hoya's.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley may stay at 135 to try to unify the title _ especially
now that Stevie Johnson is back in the picture _ but he continues
to struggle to make weight. For his latest title defense, he gained
16 pounds in one day after the weigh-in, and entered the ring at
151 to face John Brown. Those struggles may lead him to move up to
junior welterweight, but if he does, there's no one at 140 who will
beat him either.
</P>
<P>
   4. Mark Johnson (37-1, 26 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tired of having no challenger at flyweight so he vacated
the IBF title and moved up to junior bantamweight. As a flyweight
he was the best in the world at 112 pounds and last weekend he
easily outpointed Thailand's Ratanachai Vorapin to win the vacant
IBF 115-pound championship.
</P>
<P>
   5. Johnny Tapia (46-0-2, 25 KOs, WBA bantamweight champion).
</P>
<P>
   Tapia goes unnoticed by many but he's 20-0-1 in world title
fights, took apart Danny Romero when many thought he would
struggle, and has always answered the bell. Until that changes, he
deserves this slot or maybe even a higher one.
</P>
<P>
   6. Felix Trinidad (34-0, 29 KOs, IBF welterweight champion).
</P>
<P>
   The belief is that Trinidad has greatness inside him, and
perhaps he does, but his list of opponents is less impressive than
even Jones's. For as often as De La Hoya has been criticized in
some corners for ducking tough fights, who has Trinidad fought?
</P>
<P>
   There is no Quartey or anyone close to him on Trinidad's resume,
and by the time he got to Whitaker, De La Hoya had already unmasked
the former champion.
</P>
<P>
   Until Trinidad gets into the ring with someone who can bring the
best out of him, as Quartey did for De La Hoya, you have to wonder
why his handlers are holding him back. Is it his chin, which has
been heard to sound like cracking glass several times?
</P>
<P>
   If not, why doesn't promoter Don King match him with
hard-punching but vulnerable WBA champion James Page to get
Trinidad two belts, instead of matching him with the likes of
Vincent Pettway?
</P>
<P>
   7. Tim Austin (19-0-1, 18 KOs, IBF bantamweight champion).
</P>
<P>
   Austin gets less publicity than any top-drawer champion around
but he showed guts and boxing ability in winning the title from
Mbulelo Botile two years ago despite breaking his jaw. He is a
power puncher who also can box, and if he were a bigger man in a
more high-profile division, fight fans would think more of him.
</P>
<P>
   8. Bernard Hopkins (35-2-1, 27 KOs, IBF middleweight champion).
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins loves to talk but he also loves to fight. He is the
dominant middleweight in the world today, and even though it's a
thin division, there's no one in his class that Hopkins can't
handle.
</P>
<P>
   People forget that he fought a close fight with Jones when the
two met several years back as middleweights and Jones didn't
exactly beat the door down to give him a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   9. Ricardo Lopez (47-0-1, 35 KOs, WBA strawweight champion).
</P>
<P>
   You win as many title fights in a row as this guy, and I don't
care if you weigh eight pounds, you can fight.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez has struggled some of late and may be reaching the point
where it's taking too much out of him to continue boxing at 108
pounds, but whatever weight class he fights in, he'll be one of the
best.
</P>
<P>
   10. Ike Quartey (34-1-1, 29 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   How do you drop him out of the top 10 for losing a close
decision to De La Hoya? Quartey seemed to fade at the end of that
fight, as he has in other bouts lately, but he can still punch with
power and do damage with his jab, as De La Hoya's face showed.
</P>
<P>
   Many considered him one of the top five fighters in the world
before his loss to De La Hoya, and his late fade that night doesn't
drop him much. He would be a stiff challenge for Trinidad, which is
one reason they haven't fought, and he may end up with a chance to
redeem himself in a rematch with De La Hoya before the year is out.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you may wonder where Floyd Mayweather Jr., Fernando
Vargas, and Prince Naseem Hamed are, but they are where they
belong. Not on this list. Mayweather is a talent and he has the
arrogance of a great champion, but he is too young now to break
into the pound-for-pound rankings. The same is true for Vargas,
although within a year both could make it.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hamed, this is not a list of pound-for-pound biggest
punchers _ which he would be at or near the top of _ nor is it a
list of pound-for-pound most irksome showmen. Although Hamed has
the gift of power, he is a completely off-balance fighter who one
day will pay for that vulnerability. And, by the way, when is he
going to fight somebody?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
