<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALCAVECCHIA SHOT WAS OUT OF BOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Even if we could award him a mulligan, it would not
help. The damage has been done. Mark Calcavecchia said something
that angered an awful lot of people, and the comments will haunt
him forever. Three weeks after he said Arnold Palmer should stop
playing in the Masters, the mention of Calcavecchia's name is met
with disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was he thinking?'' asked a gentleman the other day after
our group had completed a round of golf. The man, whom I had never
met, had a fluid swing and a strong passion for the game, which I
guessed he had been playing for parts of five decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be real curious to find out what was behind his remarks,''
said James Dodson, who worked with Palmer to produce ``A Golfer's
Life,'' a wonderful book that tells the story of arguably our most
cherished sports hero, a man who earned adulation not because he
won major championships but because he lost them with dignity and
never forgot to thank people for the chance to play.
</P>
<P>
   That is the thing about Palmer, said Dodson: ``He always knew
how to say thank you to the public. There'll never be anyone as
beloved as Palmer, and perhaps some players resent his success.''
</P>
<P>
   People want Palmer to play at Augusta every April, and he should
for as long as he wants. The Masters is like no other tournament;
it is about tradition, something we carelessly toss aside far too
often. Palmer is not taking up anyone's spot. He earned the right
to be there. Calcavecchia and too many players like him are too
busy having things given to them to understand what that means. Too
busy worrying about the endorsement deals of tomorrow to respect
the sacrifices of yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   To many others, Palmer stands for integrity and honor.
</P>
<P>
   Advised of Calcavecchia's comments, Palmer said only, ``That's
his opinion, and he's welcomed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because Arnold Palmer understood public relations
better than anyone,'' said Dodson. ``He knew when to open his mouth
and when to say nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad we can't say the same about Calcavecchia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You just know that US captain Ben Crenshaw will have no shortage
of volunteers asking to step up against Jarmo Sandelin should the
Swede continue his fine play and make the European Ryder Cup team.
Sandelin won last week's Spanish Open and is fifth in the Ryder Cup
point standings. He is mentioned first by many players, however,
when they are asked if anyone out there disturbs them. Sandelin did
what was generally thought impossible _ upset Phil Mickelson _ in
the 1996 Dunhill Cup and is the guy who rubbed it in to Mark
O'Meara with the ugly ball-marking incident at the Lancome Trophy
in 1997. Months after O'Meara had won the event, a film clip of the
tournament showed that he had placed his ball an inch or two closer
to the hole than where he marked it. O'Meara said it was
unintentional, and only Sandelin expressed outrage. The Swede, who
finished second, called on O'Meara to relinquish the title and
referred to him as ``Mark O'Nearer.'' So last year's Masters champ
may be first in line to request that Crenshaw put him up against
the guy with the snakeskin golf boots. Sandelin may be the zaniest
of the three Swedes who could spice up the Ryder Cup. Jesper
Parnevik (keeps hat flipped up, eats volcanic sand, wears pants
three sizes too small) and Per-Ulrik Johansson (is it a beret or is
his cap on backwards?) are the others. Sandelin was introduced to
the sport through miniature golf, and he wields a 52-inch driver.
Unfortunately for him _ and the European team that would have to
take him _ Sandelin quite often hasn't a clue as to where his drive
is going. He is long, but he can be very, very crooked. Not the
type of game you bring to The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, Tom Lehman has moved up in the Ryder Cup standings.
He's 20th after a solid performance at Greensboro (69-68-69-69),
and sometimes lost in all the talk about David Duval and Tiger
Woods is the notion that Lehman may be the best Ryder Cup player
the US has. He didn't get rattled when Seve Ballesteros tried to
fluster him in 1995 (Lehman won, 4 and 3) and he put a 7-and-6
beating on Ignacio Garrido at Valderrama in 1997. Lehman is 3-2-2
in his two Ryder Cup appearances . . . Business is brisk for those
trying to move Ryder Cup tickets. One broker said he is selling
them for $3,000. He is getting his tickets, he said, from people
chosen in the PGA of America's drawing (5,000 entrants won the
right to buy two tickets for $275 each). ``They probably didn't
intend to sell them,'' said the broker, ``but when they found out
they could get $2,000 each, they remembered they could see it on
NBC.'' How does the Ryder Cup ticket compare with an All-Star Game
ticket for Fenway Park July 13? The latter is going for about
$1,500. But when you consider that the Brookline spectacle is a
three-day event, baseball is the higher sell . . . Not a bad start
to last week's Spanish Open for Juan Carlos Aguero:
eagle-birdie-birdie-birdie-birdie. But he played the next 67 holes
in just 10 under and finished in a tie for fifth . . . Ireland's
Christy O'Connor Jr., who closed with a 65 to tie for fourth at
last week's Home Depot Invitational, has another Senior Tour
exemption into next week's Nationwide event in Atlanta . . . On the
heels of Sergio Garcia's solid debut as a professional (9 under,
T-25 at the Spanish Open) comes this statistical update: Justin
Rose remains perfect since turning pro after his stunning
performance at last summer's British Open. He has missed 17 cuts in
17 starts. Garcia, by the way, makes his US pro debut at the Byron
Nelson May 13-16 . . . Another amateur star who has found the pro
life less than rewarding is Scotland's Gordon Sherry. He is playing
on the Challenge Tour, Europe's equivalent to the Nike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
