</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER BULLS SEE ANOTHER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last year at this time, they were the defending world
champions, en route to a sixth title in eight years. Then came the
diaspora and now the Chicago Bulls are almost unrecognizable to
those who once wore the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   We know what happened. The Big Guy retired and Big Chief
Triangle took a year off _ at least _ from coaching. Then the
dominoes fell. Scottie Pippen went to Houston. Luc Longley and Joe
Kleine went to Phoenix. Jud Buechler went to Detroit. Steve Kerr
went to San Antonio. Dennis Rodman went to Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   All but Rodman should be in the postseason again. All could go
home ringless for the first time in years.
</P>
<P>
   They've kept in touch. They've watched the disintegration from
afar. They've reminisced about the glory years. They know it will
never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that all of us left made it easier, I think,'' Kerr
was saying from Vancouver this past week. ``If I had been the only
one, it would have been harder. But they really broke up that team
and the core has gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Chicago general manager Jerry Krause knows what he has in
mind for the Bulls and, based on what we see, he must know
something no one else does. The Bulls didn't want to become the
Celtics. They didn't. They became the Clippers. Or worse. We all
expected a dropoff, but did we think they'd be this bad?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to believe that this is what they wanted; I
refuse to believe that,'' Kleine said. ``It's kind of shocking. I
was in Boston when they started to go down, but they had a reason _
injuries. Without those injuries, they'd have competed in the '90s.
That's a gamble they took and I think it was the right thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Bulls used to be a joy. Now it's eye pollution. The
Bulls are en route to becoming the lowest-scoring team since the
advent of the shot clock in 1954. They're averaging about 5 points
a game less than anyone else and threatening to become the first
team since the 1961 Celtics to shoot less than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But statistics reveal only what's happening on the court. To the
ex-Bulls, the parting was also the end of a lifestyle. They've had
to become normal NBA players again, if there is such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all living in a fantasy in Chicago,'' said Buechler,
who told of how he would call a restaurant when the team was on the
road and ask the manager if a table could be set aside so the Bulls
could eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're thinking Michael, Scotty, and Dennis,'' said Buechler.
``Meanwhile, it's me, Steve Kerr and the trainer. They're like,
`Anybody else?' But we always had a great table.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on, ``It was a great thing to be a part of, the whole
experience of being on that team. Those memories are the most
important thing. I have great feelings about Chicago. My last game,
we won the world championship. That's something I'm always going to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something they'll all have.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ballots for league awards are due Sunday. For the first time
since 1985-86, we won't have a Bull winning a single postseason
honor. As always, there is plenty of room for debate on just about
every choice. Here's my ballot and the reasons for the choices.
</P>
<P>
   Most Valuable Player: Tim Duncan, San Antonio. ``I would vote
for him, too, if I had a vote, but maybe I'm a little biased,''
Kerr says. ``He's awesome.'' This was basically a three-man race
among Duncan, Karl Malone, and Alonzo Mourning, all of whom are
worthy. They're 1-2-3 on my ballot, with Allen Iverson and Chris
Webber rounding out the top five. Duncan has become the leader and
conscience of a very good San Antonio team. Sure, he has help, but
so do the others. In a couple of years, this could be his league
and you might even see him on national television when the Lakers
aren't busy.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year: Jason Williams, Sacramento. This also is a
three-man race, with Paul Pierce and the likely winner, Vince
Carter. Williams, however, plays the toughest position of the
three, has had more responsibility, and likely has taken his team
into the postseason. That's good enough for me. Plus, he's done the
impossible: He's made the Kings a must-see team. Eventually, cable
got the message. NBC still prefers the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year: Jerry Sloan, Utah. When is this guy going to
get his due? All he does is win. Pat Riley was my original choice,
but how can you vote for a guy who goes 0-3 against the Celtics?
Mike Dunleavy is another good choice, but he had a young, intact
team and the best schedule. I say it's time to reward Sloan, who,
heading into the final weekend, again had the team with the best
record.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth Man Award: Rasheed Wallace, Portland. Someone on this team
has to be rewarded; why not this guy? It speaks to the main reasons
for the Blazers' success this season: depth, unselfishness, and
versatility. Wallace didn't pout when he was removed from the
starting lineup. He became an incendiary force off the bench.
That's what sixth men are supposed to do. Darrell Armstrong (see
below) and Jalen Rose should also get serious support.
</P>
<P>
   Most Improved Player: Darrell Armstrong, Orlando. He'll get a
lot of votes for sixth man, but he's also back in the starting
lineup. What he's really done is elevate his game exponentially,
and that's the kind of thing that gets you this award. Alas, he
should be wary. Of the last 11 winners, only one is still with the
team for which he played in his coming-out season (last year's
winner, Alan Henderson) and a handful are either out of the game or
were injured and didn't play this season, including Pervis Ellison
and Gheorghe Muresan.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive Player of the Year: Alonzo Mourning, Miami. He keeps
it in the Georgetown family, taking it from two-time defender
Dikembe Mutombo. 'Zo has finally put it all together this season at
both ends. He's a big reason why the Heat are one of the best
defensive teams of the season when they play anyone other than the
Celtics. Miami has been at or near the top all season for fewest
points allowed and defensive field goal percentage. That's 'Zo's
turf.
</P>
<P>
   All-NBA teams. There are obvious choices here, but one criterion
I try to use is whether the player's numbers mean anything if his
team stinks. This is known as the Antoine Walker Rule. As this was
written, all 15 players were either guaranteed to be in the
playoffs or were close.
</P>
<P>
   First team: Tim Duncan, Karl Malone, Alonzo Mourning, Jason
Kidd, Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Second team: Grant Hill, Chris Webber, Shaquille O'Neal, Allen
Iverson, Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Third team: Kevin Garnett, Brian Grant, Hakeem Olajuwon, John
Stockton, Anfernee Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning is overdue for an appearance on any All-NBA team; he's
never made one. Ditto for Kidd. There were some tough omissions
(Antonio McDyess, Tim Hardaway, Ray Allen), but what's striking is
the number of future Hall of Famers/Dream Teamers who aren't here.
Scottie Pippen, Patrick Ewing, Charles Barkley, David Robinson, and
Mitch Richmond are all out. Pippen has made one of the teams every
year since 1992 and Richmond has been a staple since 1994. Ewing,
however, has made only one All-NBA team since 1993 (the second in
1997) while Barkley hasn't been on any All-NBA team since 1996.
Grant was a sentimental pick; someone from Portland deserves a
selection and he epitomizes what the Trail Blazers are all about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Casey isn't campaigning to have the ``interim'' dropped from
his job title, but he wouldn't mind if the Nets just went out and
did it on their own. Unless the Nets can get Phil Jackson, who
sounds happy matching guitar riffs with Robbie Robertson at
Woodstock, why not keep Case? The players like him, he's the
anti-Calipari and he knows the drill. Casey also says he has had no
problems with Stephon Marbury or, even more important, any of the
Marbury entourage, which can be considerable. ``I like him,'' Casey
said of Marbury. ``I think when he first came here, he was
bewildered. First, he got traded. Then, there was a coaching
change. He didn't know me. I didn't know him. But he's been great.
He has won over the older guys. He's a talented kid and he does a
number of good things on offense and defense.'' Casey said Marbury
has been under more pressure lately because the offense goes
through him now almost exclusively . . . Rick Pitino says he has a
budget for next year that will approximate the salary cap plus the
veteran exception. That adds up to around $36 million. The Celtics
already are committed to spending more than $40 million and then
will have to make decisions on Tony Battie (unless he's traded) and
Ron Mercer (unless he goes elsewhere). The Celtics' cap figure for
next year is around $44 million because Dino Radja's money is still
on the books and not all of Dwayne Schintzius's $1.5 million (yup,
that's right) is guaranteed . . . The Western Conference is in for
a doozy of a finish for the final three playoff spots. A .500
record might not be good enough. The team that looks to be in
trouble is the Timberwolves, who finish on the road at Houston and
Phoenix. Seattle has two of its three at home and closes with games
against Dallas and the Clippers. Sacramento has it even better:
home games with Phoenix and Vancouver and a roadie at Denver. As
for Phoenix, it has a biggie Sunday in Arco Arena, its only visit
to Sacramento . . . Kerr almost has disappeared in San Antonio. He,
Buechler, Longley, and Pippen are discovering that the Bulls play
one way, and the rest of the NBA plays another way. Chicago still
uses the triangle offense, which is almost antithetical, some
coaches would say heretical, to the boring, dump-it-in, post-up,
reverse the ball, stand-around style that everyone else uses.
``It's a unique way to play, that's for sure,'' Kerr said . . .
Jerry West nearly quit the Lakers last year, or threatened to, and
was rewarded with a huge contract extension that kicks in next
season. However, several NBA people say West is so fed up with what
has gone on this season that he'll resign and leave Jerry Buss's
money on the table. Buss ignored West's pleas to extend or fire Del
Harris last summer. Then, when it was clear Harris had to go, he
turned to someone with no head coaching experience, Kurt Rambis, to
oversee the circus. The Rodman fiasco was all Buss's doing; West
stayed away from that as if it were the Ebola virus. He then made a
trade that, in the short run, has totally backfired. West has not
been visible at a Lakers game for almost a month, and when he ran
into reporters last week, he said simply, ``Blame me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
