<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BUCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCKS STAY ON ROAD TO PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ No Glenn Robinson. No Dell Curry. No problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Bucks, minus their top rebounder and scorer in
Robinson and the league's best 3-point shooter in Curry, rallied
from a 16-point deficit in the first quarter to knock off the
Celtics, 88-79, at the FleetCenter Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The victory before a crowd of 18,089 ended Milwaukee's
seven-game road losing streak, enabled the Bucks to sweep a season
series from Boston for the first time since 1970-71, and, most
important, solidify their already strong hold on a playoff
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big thing is to get to the playoffs, and the door to them
is still open,'' said Bucks coach George Karl. ``It's not over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, who play Monday in New York then wind up their
season Wednesday at home against Charlotte, were up, 49-43, at the
break, but came out cold in the third quarter and stayed that way.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino's boys scored 30 points in the first quarter, which
equaled their entire output in the second half; a half in which the
Bucks turned up the defensive pressure and turned over the
basketball just twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half, we were real sloppy,'' said the Bucks' Armon
Gilliam. ``I don't want to make any excuses, but we got in at 4
a.m. I think that had to do with part of our slow start.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the way they finished that counted.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Allen's 3-pointer put the Bucks ahead for good, 55-52, and
Chris Gatling punished the Celtics under the offensive glass for a
crucial stretch of the third quarter. The visitors held a 71-65
lead after three, thanks in large part to the Celtics shooting 5
for 15 from the field and the Bucks 12 for 25. The Celtics not only
had trouble shooting in the quarter, but also in holding on to it _
seven turnovers for 10 Bucks points.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a great victory (in Miami Thursday), this is a
disappointing loss,'' said Pitino. ``Their half-court trap hurt us
a little bit. We didn't do what we did against Miami _ reverse the
basketball, make the extra pass, and get good, strong moves to the
basket. But we forced 14 turnovers at halftime and ended up with
only 16 and that's extremely disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Cassell, just off the injured list, took Marlon Garnett into
the paint and hit a jumper for a 67-61 lead. He then closed out the
quarter with a 15-foot jumper after Dana Barros coughed the ball up
at midcourt. Paul Pierce's 3-pointer early in the fourth quarter
cut the deficit to 71-68, but Ron Mercer's turnover was followed by
an Allen jumper and a 5-point Bucks lead.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who had a game-high 26 points, wouldn't let the Bucks
wilt: When Barros canned a 3-pointer, he came right back with a
rainbow for a 75-71 lead midway through the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam's free throws upped it to 77-71 and after a Celtics
miss, Michael Curry converted two more freebies for 79-71 lead with
4:52 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Curry's slam with 3:36 to go gave Milwaukee its first
double-digit lead and the Celtics drought continued. They scored
just 8 points in the first nine minutes of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we weren't scoring it was hard to step up our press,''
said Mercer, who led the Celtics with 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were clearly more energized early in the game. The
Bucks clutched and grabbed their way to passing the personal foul
limit with five minutes to play in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Pierce freebies made it 18-10 and when Barros hit two
3-pointers, sandwiched around a Pierce steal at midcourt, it was a
24-10 Celtics lead with 3:22 to go. Time out, Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   A Pair of Mercer hoops made it 28-12 _ the Celtics' high-water
mark _ before Allen answered with a long 3-pointer and top of the
key jumper.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Mercer baskets kept the lead respectable, but a
Cassell 3-point play got the Bucks to within 34-28 and when Vinny
Del Negro swished a trey, the Celtics lead was down to 36-31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
