<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON CASTAWAY GORING TURNS UP ON ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ His trademark, beyond that flimsy toy helmet, was his
relentless skating, not to mention an accurate pair of hands that
were good for 888 career points.
</P>
<P>
   But Butch Goring was accomplished in the back end of the ice,
too, which for years made him the defensive dose of reality in that
Points 'R Us lineup in Los Angeles, and then made him the
stabilizing, two-way pivot who helped the Islanders to their four
Stanley Cup championships in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen years after getting sacked as coach of the
Bruins, the 49-year-old Goring returned to the NHL Friday as the
new boss behind the Islander bench. Given the Isles' woes of late
(five straight seasons, no playoffs), he may want to find a thicker
helmet for his new endeavor. Either way, it's good to see another
good head back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dream come true,'' Goring said at his news
conference on Long Island. ``I'm going to coach this team the way I
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Goring's sentiments were similar when he followed Gerry Cheevers
and Harry Sinden to the throne here in the Hub in the fall of '85.
Claimed on waivers by the Bruins that January, when Cheevers was
still coach, Goring was behind the bench come September, another
ex-Bruin immediately made head coach without so much as a moment's
worth of coaching experience. Imagine what would play on the silver
screen if Hollywood chose its directors so cavalierly. He was
willing, but unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Goring was fired early in his second season in Boston and has
spent the better part of a decade-plus coaching in the minors,
relentlessly pursuing a return to the bigs. Rumored as a possible
candidate for the vacant Los Angeles coaching job, he was in
Edmonton scouting the NHL playoffs last week when Islander GM Mike
Milbury called him for an interview on Long Island. By Thursday
night, Goring had a three-year deal worth $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butch,'' said Milbury, the former Bruin
defenseman/coach/assistant GM, ex-Boston College coach, and former
broadcaster, ``has Islander blood.''
</P>
<P>
   That orange-and-blue hemoglobin and hype aside, Goring, more
importantly, was twice named the International Hockey League's
coach of the year _ after directing the Utah Grizzlies to
championships in '95 and '96. He knows what he's doing. He'll no
doubt run efficient practices and keep that controlled effective
distance between bench and player that was so much Al Arbour's
stamp when ``Radar'' was masterminding the Islander bench in their
glory years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' Goring said Nov. 6, 1986, the day after he
was fired by the Bruins immediately following a loss in Buffalo.
``I'm mad. Hockey's certainly not fair and this is not fair. This
is no easy pill to swallow. And I don't think gassing me is the
answer. But we'll never know, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers sometimes call in David Scott, a sports psychologist,
to help flex their cerebral muscles. The good doc likes to inject
some wit. He recently held a team viewing of the '70s favorite,
``Monty Python and the Holy Grail,'' in which a battling knight
utters, ``It's only a flesh wound!'' as his limbs are hacked off,
one by one . . . Ex-Sabre Matthew Barnaby, now with the Penguins,
traded some verbal shots with Devils tough guy Lyle Odelein early
in the Pittsburgh-New Jersey series. It began when Barnaby referred
to Odelein as ``Cornelius,'' a reference to one of the lead
characters in ``Planet of the Apes.'' Odelein returned fire with
disparaging words about Barnaby's wife, saying she is ``God-awful
to look at.'' Wonder what page of the NHLPA Good Vibes &AMP;
Brotherhood Handbook covers those kinds of salutations . . .
Vancouver GM Brian Burke disagrees with the suggestion here to
disallow icing the puck during penalty-killing situations, a rule
change that would result in an immediate whistle and a faceoff in
the defensive end _ all aimed at increasing scoring via more
power-play goals. ``Too drastic,'' said Burke. ``It would kill the
balance of power in the game, and give far too much of an advantage
to teams with strong power plays.'' Burke doesn't believe the game
needs more scoring. Case in point: the Bruins-Hurricanes series.
Burke: ``What tremendous entertainment _ lots of hitting, great
scoring chances _ and no one cares that the goals are down. It's
just great hockey. It just goes to show, once more, that the best
playoffs in all pro sports are in the NHL. This is my feeling about
more goal scoring: If it ain't broke, don't fix it.'' . . . Jaromir
Jagr exited the Penguins-Devils series with what was reported as a
groin pull after Game 1. But Devils forward Bobby Holik has learned
not to trust injury reports during the playoffs. ``Unless a guy has
a broken arm,'' said Holik, ``and you can see it hanging off his
body.'' Yeah, just a flesh wound. Jagr, by the way, tried to hurry
back to Pittsburgh to visit an acupuncturist, but returned to the
team hotel after spending nine hours at Newark Airport, unable to
catch a flight . . . The Oilers were swept out of the first round
by Dallas, prompting Edmonton boss Glen Sather to ask coach Ron Low
if he wanted to come back next season _ not exactly a vote of
confidence. If Low gets the gate, look for ex-Oiler defenseman
Kevin Lowe to land the job. Lowe on such a prospect: ``I don't even
want to touch that. My hopes are, quite frankly, to keep working
with Ron next season.'' . . . Mike Smith made it known in Toronto
that he'll give the front office two weeks after the Leafs' season
ends to decide whether they want him as GM.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ABC/Disney/ESPN wants to hire the recently retired Wayne Gretzky
as a broadcast commentator for next season. The Great One's dad,
Walter, said the day his son retired that he doubted Wayne would
find a liking for mike work: ``He'd have to be at a certain place
at a certain time to do that. Wayne's never played the game that
way.'' . . . No surprise, of course, that the Hockey Hall of Fame
took another step toward adding Gretzky this summer, far ahead of
the standard three-year waiting period. As for what sweater he'll
be depicted in when enshrined, the suggestion here is to place the
NHL shield on his chest, and festoon it with the smaller logos of
Edmonton, Los Angeles, St. Louis, and New York. The league as much
as invited that when it proclaimed the afternoon of his last game
that Gretzky's No. 99 would never be worn again in the NHL . . .
Gotta like the Kansas City Blades running a ``Toothless Night''
promotion. Anyone who sported the gapped look got in for free. In
all, 269 walked through the wickets at no charge and 49 got in at
half-price. The 50 percent discount went to those who only had a
chipped tooth or two. Must have been a big night, too, at the
candy-apple counter . . . Will NHL players be seen at the 2002
Olympics in Salt Lake City? USA Hockey was hoping to hear from the
NHL about now, but the International Ice Hockey Federation recently
told the NHL it could wait on its decision until August . . . Race
relations took another hit in the NHL last week when Flyer tough
guy Sandy McCarthy, his father black and his mother a Native
American, accused Leafs pugilist Tie Domi of ``dropping the
n-word'' on him. Domi denied using the racial slur. The blend of
the league is such, said Flyer netminder John Vanbiesbrouck, that
``people are always picking on you . . . you are the Russian or the
Czech, or you are the Indian or the Chief. We are living in a
stereotyped world, when nicknames come before names, and that
sometimes leads to other things.'' . . . The Flyers haven't suited
up defenseman Luke Richardson in the Toronto series. Two years ago,
he was playing 28 minutes a night for the Oilers in their
postseason series with the Stars. From 28 to zero in two years. And
remember, the Flyers wooed him away from Edmonton with a five-year
deal worth $12.5 million. Ouch . . . Word around Chicago is that
the Hawks will part with 33-year-old Bob Probert, once the most
fearsome dude on double-runners before falling into the addiction
abyss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senators had, and still have, a talented team. But their
four-game sweep by the Sabres in Round 1 proved once more that
skill is only part of the postseason equation. They'll have to
improve on both size and grit over the summer if they're going to
think about making a serious run. When it was clear in Game 1 that
their top gun, Alexei Yashin, couldn't shake superchecker Michael
Peca, the series was effectively placed in Dominik Hasek's pocket.
``They don't have any physical defensemen or other people (i.e.
enforcers) in their lineup,'' said Peca. The good news for the
Senators: It's a whole lot easier to stock grit and muscle than to
go out and find a half-dozen or so skilled shooters . . . There was
nothing in the Red Wings-Ducks series, a 4-0 Detroit sweep, that
would make anyone think the Wings will be deterred from a third
straight Cup (the first threepeat since the Islanders won four
straight, 1980-83). One big key to their success has been the
defensive pairing of Nicklas Lidstrom and Chris Chelios, perhaps
the most menacing blue line tandem in the game (Lidstrom had been
with Larry Murphy). It takes a lot of the sting out of losing Uwe
Krupp to a back injury. Signed to a four-year, $16 million free
agent deal last summer, Krupp collected all of 5 points this season
_ only 2 more than Red Wings goalie Chris Osgood . . . Eric Lindros
is back on skates, joining the Flyers in noncontact drills. His
blood level is still down by 10 percent (he lost three liters when
his lung collapsed) and his weight is around 227 pounds (10 under
his playing level), but he remains hopeful of playing in Round 2 if
the Flyers advance . . . Flyer coach Roger Neilson, amid claims
that Philly was roughing up Toronto netminder Curtis Joseph,
reminisced last week about his days as Vancouver coach when Canucks
tough guy Tiger Williams took on Islander netminder Battlin' Billy
Smith in the '82 Cup finals. ``I'm going to get him,'' said
Williams, tired of Smith's repeated slashes. ``Just watch.''
Neilson picks up the story: ``The next thing, I look over, and
Tiger's on top of him. Billy wore a chain around his neck and Tiger
grabbed it and just started choking him.'' Ah, whatever happened to
old time hockey . . . USA Hockey, located in Colorado Springs, will
hire a public relations/marketing intern this summer, a spot opened
up in memory of Brian Fishman, a 28-year-old staff member who died
in January of carbon monoxide poisoning. The ideal candidate would
be a graduating college senior interested in the sports
PR/marketing field. If interested, write Brian Fishman Internship
Program, USA Hockey, 1775 Bob Johnson Drive, Colorado Springs, CO
80906.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
