u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUISIANA-POLITICS-NY     05-02 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID DUKE MISSES LOUISIANA RUNOFF BUT HAS STRONG SHOWING 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   METAIRIE, La. _ Despite having five viable and conservative
alternatives, one of every five voters in Louisiana's 1st
Congressional District voted on Saturday for David E. Duke, a
former Ku Klux Klan leader and self-styled defender of the rights
of European-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, a Republican, fell just short of qualifying for a May 29
runoff for the seat vacated by Robert L. Livingston, who stunned
his constituents late last year by acknowledging extramarital
affairs and resigning just as he was about to become speaker of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   David C. Treen, a former governor and congressman, and state
Rep. David Vitter finished atop the nine-person field but neither
won the majority needed to avoid a runoff. Both are Republicans,
insuring that the party will regain the 12-seat majority it held in
the House before Livingston's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Treen finished with 25 percent, followed by Vitter with 22
percent and Duke with 19 percent. Polls had shown Duke with about
half that amount, and the result vindicated his assertion that he
flies under the radar of conventional public opinion research.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's surprisingly strong showing caused some anxiety during
the night for establishment Republican leaders who feared that a
Duke victory, or even a place in the runoff, would deeply embarrass
a party that is trying to broaden its appeal, particularly with
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sweating bullets,'' said Ken Johnson, an aide to Rep.
W.J. (Billy) Tauzin, the Republican dean of Louisiana's
congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Following Duke was Monica L. Monica, a Republican
ophthalmologist, who finished fourth with 16 percent, despite
spending more than $1.2 million, most of it her own. State Rep.
Bill Strain, a conservative Democrat who seemed to take votes from
Duke, finished fifth with 11 percent and Rob Couhig, a Republican
lawyer and the owner of New Orleans' minor league baseball team,
had 6 percent. Three fringe candidates shared the rest of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana has an unusual open primary system that allows
Republicans and Democrats to run against one another in a first
primary. If no candidate wins a majority, the top two finishers
compete in a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The runoff will highlight the stylistic differences between
Treen, 70, the first Republican since Reconstruction to represent
this state in Congress or as governor, and Vitter, a 37-year-old
lawyer, Harvard graduate and Rhodes Scholar who has served for
eight years in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Treen cites his experience and relationships with congressional
leaders. He has been endorsed by Livingston and Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, the majority leader. Vitter counters that Treen's age
may limit his ability to amass power in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The district, which begins in the northern suburbs of New
Orleans and stretches across Lake Pontchartrain to the farms and
timberland along the Mississippi border, is considered the most
conservative and reliably Republican district in the state.
Eighty-five percent of the registered voters in the district are
white, and many have fled what they consider to be high crime and
inadequate schools in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Duke finished first in Tangipahoa Parish and a close second to
Strain in Washington Parish, both rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Duke won a legislative seat in 1989 and won more than half of
the white vote in losing races for the U.S. Senate in 1990 and for
governor in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Saturday night, Duke asserted that he would
have made the runoff if Strain had not been in the race. Susan E.
Howell, a political scientist at the University of New Orleans,
agreed. ``That Democrat saved the Republicans a significant
embarrassment,'' Ms. Howell said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Howell, like other analysts of the race, said she was
surprised by Duke's showing because of the many other choices on
the ballot for conservative Republican voters. ``People over the
years have asked me what percentage of the vote in Louisiana or in
a district like the 1st is hard-core racist, and I never knew what
to say,'' Ms. Howell said. ``Now we know, and it's one out of
five.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke, who calls in a new book for an Aryan resurgence and
voluntary homelands for minorities, said that his supporters were
aware of his past and his views. ``This has got to say something
very powerful about the issues I represent,'' he said. ``These
people did not go into this unaware.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that while he had no immediate plans to wage another
campaign, he was ``absolutely committed to spending the rest of my
life as a spokesman for the rights of European-Americans.'' Phil
Baum, the executive director of the American Jewish Congress, said
he was particularly disturbed that Louisiana's Republican leaders,
including Gov. Mike Foster and state Republican Chairman Mike
Francis, had refused to join the party's national leadership in
denouncing Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Treen nor Vitter publicly repudiated Duke during the
campaign, although both criticized his views in interviews. Now
both must seek the votes of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Vitter, who hopes to paint Treen as a go-along Republican, said
Sunday that many voters supported Duke out of an ``underlying
frustration with the current congressional leadership that we're
not moving boldly on real tax reform and ending affirmative
action.''
</P>
<P>
   Treen commended Duke as a vigorous campaigner and maintained
that he won support by muting his views in this campaign. But in
fact, it is hard to imagine that Duke, who ran television
advertisements denouncing Kwanzaa and Malcolm X postage stamps,
could have been much more pointed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
