<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1520 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-MCLAREN-BO     05-02 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MCLAREN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 McLAREN ASSISTED BY DIVINE INTERVENTION  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He was going to be on his own. He was adamant about
that. Harry Sinden couldn't dissuade him, try as he did. The Bruins
president/general manager admired the kid's independent sense while
at the same time doubting his common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle McLaren was, after all, barely 18 _ old enough to risk a
face full of stitches in the National Hockey League but not
necessarily capable of crossing the street in a strange city on his
own. There are certain NHL traditions, and one is that a teen
tenderfoot be billeted with a host family for a year or two, the
better to ease his transition to adulthood off the ice even as he's
being thrust into a man's job on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that age,'' says Sinden, ``they're learning about life in
the NHL _ the travel, living in the big city, getting the proper
rest and diet. We suggested that he live with a family.''
</P>
<P>
   But McLaren, the Bruins' first draft pick (ninth overall) in
1995 and an instant revelation who had cracked the Boston defense
corps in his first camp, would have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I'd like the challenge of being my own boss, taking
care of myself, getting to know the city,'' he recalls now, four
years later. ``And it was a huge adjustment _ the cooking, the
cleaning . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   But while the Bruins were willing to let McLaren burn the
occasional roast or overflow the washing machine a few times, they
have another tradition on which there is no room for compromise.
First-year defensemen generally are given a chaperone on the ice to
facilitate their education in the game's toughest position, like it
or not. And since McLaren's escort was Boston's defensive icon, Ray
Bourque, what wasn't to like?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the biggest influence in my hockey career,'' says
McLaren. ``I had the chance to play with him, learn from him, watch
him. He showed me what it takes to compete in games, to belong at
this level.''
</P>
<P>
   So well has Bourque advised and McLaren adhered that the protege
looms as the heir apparent to the father confessor.
</P>
<P>
   No one is planning a farewell tour for Bourque, 38, the 20-year
veteran who is under contract through next season and still is
performing like a thoroughbred while logging pack mule playing
time. The latest evidence was his 53 1/2-minute epic in Friday's
4-3 double-overtime win that gave the Bruins a 3-2 lead over the
Carolina Hurricanes in their best-of-seven Eastern Conference
quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   But pure chronological inevitability indicates that Bourque will
be gone sooner rather than later, and it stands to reason that the
6-foot-4-inch, 219-pound MacLaren, now an old-timer of 21, will
inherit the defensive mantle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that,'' says McLaren, who has graduated to a
defense pairing with Don Sweeney the past two seasons while Bourque
initiates Hal Gill. ``But I don't think I'm going to replace Ray by
myself. Here's a guy who's been around so long and done so much _
we'll need six guys to replace him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden feels comfortable with the probable chain of succession,
mindful that Boston's winning percentage this year was about .600
with McLaren in the lineup, and while he was missing 30 games
because of a contract holdout and later a shoulder injury, the
Bruins stumbled along at a .400 clip.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was impossible to foresee this impact four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 18, they're pretty raw,'' Sinden says. ``It's really a
lottery. But Kyle was picked out by our chief scout at the time,
Bart Bradley, as the best player out there. And based on the
progress he's made the last two years, he's headed that way _ he
has all the capabilities to be the leader of the defense corps.
He's a real heavy hitter, and that sets a tone. He's good with the
puck, can make plays, and takes care of our end.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very popular with his teammates, too. By example was the
way Ray led. In the last five years, he's become more of a
locker-room example. I can see Kyle assuming that role more quickly
than Ray did. He's more outgoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque himself endorses the eventual elevation of McLaren, of
whom he has been a fan and confidant from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rookie, I saw a player who had a lot of poise,'' says
Bourque. ``He's a big presence, a big guy, who plays good, strong
defense, makes big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren was born with the size. But developing into a true
presence was a slow evolution, and it was in this area that Bourque
proved indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he felt comfortable that he could ask me anything and
I'd listen,'' says Bourque, who was in the same situation as
McLaren at age 18. ``Here was a kid who was being asked to step in
and play regular minutes. There's a lot of pressure on you to play
as a veteran right away. I tried to emphasize consistency to him,
that he had to come out the same way every night. I told him to
relax, let the game come to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand that McLaren may be Bourque's successor but he won't
be Bourque. He lacks the veteran's offensive flair _ ``I'm not an
80- or 90-point scorer,'' he says _ and nothing about his game hits
you over the head, except perhaps one of his frequent concussive
checks.
</P>
<P>
   McLaren works in the shadows, tending to the details that don't
make it to billboards but form the foundation of dependable
defense. This series has been no exception. Though McLaren was
partially culpable on Sami Kapanen's goal with 1:45 left in
regulation Friday that necessitated overtime _ and Bourque's
marathon _ he has been an invaluable contributor in subtle ways.
Whether he's thumping the likes of Carolina strong man Keith
Primeau or keeping the area around Byron Dafoe's net clear of
debris and danger or serving as an adjunct to Bourque on the
power-play point, he has been a model of reliability.
</P>
<P>
   It's the basics on which he prides himself. Given the choice
between flash and substance, McLaren says, ``I'd take solid. I love
hitting guys in the corner, playing defense. I'm not going to go on
offense like Ray or Paul Coffey. Maybe I'll make the occasional
great play. But if I can be a 30-point scorer and play great
defense, I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true stay-at-home defenseman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
