u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BO     05-02 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE TOOK LONG ROAD DOWN MEMORY LANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He thought about drawing a parallel, using a
nine-year-old example to help his teammates understand the wonder
of the situation they were in. He thought about dipping back into
his past, hard as it may have been, to make them realize that what
they were feeling at this moment was special. He thought about 1990
and all the emotions, the drama, the history.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Bruins captain Ray Bourque decided not to
mention the triple-overtime game against the Edmonton Oilers in
Game 1 of the 1990 Stanley Cup finals while his current teammates
were embroiled in an overtime contest of their own, against the
Carolina Hurricanes, in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference
quarterfinals Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bourque did what he's done for 20 years. He led by
example. When the Bruins looked in danger of being run over after
falling behind, 2-0, through two periods, it was Bourque who helped
bring them back. He scored 34 seconds into the third period to cut
the deficit in half. Darren Van Impe, assisted by Bourque, tied it
up at 1:59, and P.J. Axelsson gave Boston its first lead at 2:26.
</P>
<P>
   Sami Kapanen tied it with 1:45 left in regulation, but then it
was Bourque who assisted on Anson Carter's winning goal at 14:45 of
the second overtime. The Bruins are now up, three games to two,
with the series switching back to the FleetCenter, where they can
close it out Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If you look back at that remarkable Edmonton game, it was
Bourque who brought the Bruins back to life then, too, scoring a
pair of third-period goals to send the game into extras. That game,
the longest in Stanley Cup finals history, lasted 115 minutes, 13
seconds and Bourque played a whopping 58:26 on that steamy May
night at Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday against the Hurricanes, Bourque, nine years older,
played 53:26.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go out there for another shift,'' said
Bourque, who had 57 tours of duty and was trying to recover from
one when the winning goal went in. ``I didn't see it. I just had my
head down and I was trying to rest for my next shift. I got my head
up and I see A.C. going for a dive. It was a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the triple-overtime loss was the worst feeling.
That night, battling both exhaustion and dehydration from the
scorching heat and humidity inside the arena, Bourque felt fine
despite his workload _ at least until he had a chance to relax at
home. Then he began cramping everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was downstairs and I was trying to yell at my wife to help
me,'' he said, smiling at the memory. ``I couldn't get up the
stairs. It was like I was paralyzed. That was painful.''
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's game, Bourque said he felt fine again, for the
most part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good up until the second overtime,'' he said. ``It was
tough but I think it was tough for a lot of people, not only for a
38-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's agenda was rest, a lot of water, even more massage,
and more rest to recover for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque understated his role in Friday's win. Both coaches had a
difficult time finding the praise for the job he did.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina's Paul Maurice was most impressed by Bourque's breaking
up of Martin Gelinas's bid on an open net at 5:14 of overtime No.
2. Goalie Byron Dafoe was out of the net, and Gelinas was staring
at an empty cage. Bourque got back first. Gelinas hit the puck, it
popped up, Bourque tried to whack Gelinas's stick, Gelinas hit the
puck again, and it bounced out of harm's way. It appeared that
Bourque had saved it with the shaft of his stick but Bourque said
he actually missed the puck as Gelinas hit it the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He double-hit it,'' said Bourque. ``He hit it forward and then
he hit it backward. We caught a huge break. I couldn't believe it.
I've done that on the golf course and then you look around and say,
`Did I just do that?' He couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice tipped his cap to the veteran who is six years the
coach's senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are star players, then there are the handful of special
players,'' said Maurice. ``Either he makes them happen or they
happen to (him) or it's the right person playing the right sport.
If you're from Boston, you're bored of it by now, you see it happen
enough. Those of us who get to enjoy something like that, we only
see it once in a while, thank God.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston coach Pat Burns found Bourque's yeoman duty ``completely
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's game was not the Stanley Cup finals, nor was it a
series clincher, but it was clearly something special for Bourque,
and it reminded him of that wonderful, horrible game in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to mention that between periods,'' he said. ``I
didn't, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of funny to consider where some of his current
teammates were then.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle McLaren was 12 years old. Sergei Samsonov was 11. Joe
Thornton was, yikes, 10. Dmitri Khristich was playing his second
full year for Sokol Kiev of the Russian League.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, too, remembers that year well. He was coaching the
Montreal Canadiens, who had been steamrolled by Boston in five
games in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   An eerie coincidence comes in the form of defenseman Glen
Wesley. It was Wesley who missed an open net for Boston in the
second overtime in that Edmonton game. On Friday night, Wesley, who
is now playing for Carolina, hit the crossbar 2:21 into the first
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The only Bruins player other than Bourque who remains from the
1990 game is defenseman Don Sweeney, who was just 23 then. One of
the enduring images in the aftermath of that game was a photo of
Sweeney, sitting on the ice, legs outstretched, his back against
the boards, his tongue sticking out in exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   That triple-OT win was the springboard Edmonton used to win the
Stanley Cup, which they skated around the Garden a few nights
later. Mark Messier, the Oilers captain, carried the hardware
around Bourque's rink and soon was presented with the Hart Trophy
as the league's MVP, an honor many felt Bourque deserved. Bruins
president/general manager Harry Sinden was one of those who thought
Bourque was robbed.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's dream is still to win that Cup, and Friday's victory
is another step toward that goal. As long as they are still
playing, there is always a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge win for us,'' he said. ``It's the first time some
of these guys won a double-overtime game. It puts us in the
driver's seat. I've been saying the whole series, this is so
important for the young guys in this room just to get a taste of
how you have to battle to get through a series and it's so tough
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now, Bourque's teammates will want to ask him about that
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
