<HEADER>
A1523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-B     05-02 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST HEROICS SHOW TEAM MAKING A DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At the risk of playing the race card _ gotcha reading
hockey now, don't I? _ the fact that Anson Carter is black has
absolutely nothing to do with his heroics Friday night in
Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   But the added fact that no one from around here has done
anything bigger on ice since maybe Mike Eruzione or Nancy Kerrigan
makes the fact that he is black worth talking about only because it
fits the crazy mosaic that's going on here in the Hub of Hockey
right now.
</P>
<P>
   It's just different. That's all I'm saying. It's all very
different.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, what could be more upside-down, inside-out and contrary
to the way hockey usually goes around here _ contrary to the way
all sports go around and around and around here _ than looking up
after midnight and seeing a black kid in a Boston uniform score a
huge goal in overtime at Greensboro, N.C., and all but clinch a
playoff series? Whew. Pause here and use that sentence to catch
your breath. Here in the land of let's be individuals, let's be
new, refreshing, and out of the ordinary, you're telling me you've
got better than that? No you don't.
</P>
<P>
   We in the sports department have an overused habit of
highlighting key words in italic print when we want to drive a
point home. In the above paragraph, that would mean putting the
italics to just about every word.
</P>
<P>
   The hour was late.
</P>
<P>
   The locale was not exactly Original Six stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is obviously not what you'd call cut from the same ol'
bolt of cloth. In case you didn't notice, No. 33 in the Black 'n
Gold looks a lot more like Bill Russell than Billy O'Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone worth the spoked B on his or her needlepointed pillow
knows that the Bruins, the playoffs, and overtime fit together like
Harry Sinden and the chapter chairman of the Up With Spending
Society.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you don't understand all that, here's what I want you
do. Put down this paper, find a Bruins fan, and count the time
between saying, ``Petr Klima,'' and he or she begins spewing
invectives the way Linda Blair went projectile in ``The Exorcist.''
It just hasn't been a pretty sight around here in the spring once
the hockey clock goes beyond 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But with 5:15 remaining in the second overtime Friday night,
Carter put a chink in our thick Calvinist flak jacket. With help
from Ray Bourque (there, some things remain the same), and Jumbo
Joe Thornton, Carter swooped in on goaltender Arturs Irbe (hey,
find a name like that in a Toronto-Montreal summary, circa 1957)
and stepped through the looking glass into a fairytale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not my best move,'' Carter would say after lifting the Bruins
to a 4-3 victory with his neat little backhand tuck at the left
post. ``I've got something even a little better than that in my bag
of tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Carter's got better than that? I'm getting woozy.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody better give this guy a Billy Buckner reality check. How
'bout we get Mike Torrez to swing by the Vault Sunday night prior
to the Bruins facing Carolina in Game 6, and remind Mr. Carter that
things are just never that good. Not here in the Hub of Horror. If
you've got something better, and you're keeping it hidden under the
table, up your sleeve, or tucked away in the barn rafters with your
'63 Mantle card, you go with it and go with it now, baby.
</P>
<P>
   What are you saying, tomorrow? Tomorrow around here is used for
explaining what went wrong yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know about having something better. What we know,
Chicken Little, is that the sky always falls with a thud in our
ballparks and arenas. After the crash, we shovel, we plant, we talk
about next year. As sure as Carl Yastrzemski and Luis Aparicio once
turned base-running into bumper cars, we know that's true. As sure
as Don Cherry could have used a Hooked on Numerals crash course, we
know that the feeling of control is just a Satanic deception, so
much straw over the trap door to hell.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, we knew that Babe Ruth had an OK swing. But who wanted to
take the big fella out of the rotation? No one around here.
</P>
<P>
   But that's Carter. He's different, for reasons as obvious as the
way he looks and as subtle as the way he talks. He's a decent
player, not great, with shooting, passing, and skating skills that
range from middle of the pack to slightly better in the NHL. His
greatest single attribute thus far, in his 26 months as a Bruins
employee, is that his learning curve keeps meandering upward. It's
not something you see shift to shift, but it seems like in six- to
eight-week chunks he keeps getting a little bit better. One minute
his shot doesn't look like it can break tissue paper. The next
minute, he's potting the winner with the finesse of Jean Ratelle.
</P>
<P>
   He's just that kind of athlete that, if he took up pole vaulting
tomorrow, he'd barely be able to clear the counter at Pizza Hut. A
month later, he'd be springing over the Leaning Tower of Pisa and
landing with a theory on how to make the thing stand straight.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is cocky, self-assured, but not boastful. He's probably
got it in his head that he can be another Mike Bossy. I don't think
he's got that kind of skill, but I am the same guy who figured the
Senators and Avalanche would battle it out in the Cup final this
year. The Senators now are golfing. The Avalanche, like their name,
are rolling downhill fast.
</P>
<P>
   Carter talks in a soft voice and dresses like a baseball player
on offdays, with ballcap turned around backward and oversized chain
swinging freely across a T-shirt. Parkie, Cheesie, and Doakie never
saw such a sight. He puts on his sunglasses and you'd swear he took
the wrong exit off Storrow Drive and is running late for batting
practice at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins can clinch a playoff series Sunday, something they
haven't done since 1994. That's different. And they're in this
position, in large part, because they've got this black kid from
Toronto skating the wing, having a blast, sometimes looking like
the most out-of-place person you've ever seen in a Bruins uniform,
other times looking as normal as Springsteen drooped on a mike with
guitar slung over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   It's different. Most of all, it's fun. And we don't get to say
that all that often around here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
