<HEADLINE>
THIRD TIME ISN'T CHARM FOR BAFFERT 
</HEADLINE>
 DERBY-BAFFERT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Three was one too many.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bob Baffert flirted with history Saturday as he sent out
three starters in an attempt to become the first to train three
consecutive winners of the Kentucky Derby. But for a man who talks
often about believing in fate, it wasn't meant be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was trouble on the first turn, there were too many
horses,'' said Baffert. ``The first turn is tough, but, what can
you do? You can't keep horses out of the Derby. My horses tried to
run late, but it wasn't enough. I'm just glad the Lewises won. You
can't win them all. We'll just regroup and come back for the next
one. That's all you can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how to act. We're sort of lost souls. We didn't
have any luck, three horses and so much traffic. Prime Timber ran a
good race, but Excellent Meeting ran the best of all my horses. She
was dead last and she was coming best at the end. General Challenge
had a horrible trip, just a horrible trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Beverly Lewis have two trainers, D. Wayne Lukas, who
trained Charismatic to victory Saturday, and Baffert, who trained
their Silver Charm to a Derby win in 1997. While Charismatic, a
former claimer, ran into the winner's circle, Baffert's entrants
ran fourth (Prime Timber); fifth (the filly Excellent Meeting), and
11th (General Challenge). While there wasn't a pebble in Baffert's
path when Silver Charm and Real Quiet (1998) captured the Run for
The Roses, his horses had some problems Saturday and their jockeys
told a tale of woe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a horrible trip,'' said Kent Desormeaux, who rode
Excellent Meeting. ``We got pinched back leaving the gate, and then
the horses in front were getting shuffled back, and I ended up last
when she wants to go. I literally galloped her to the three-eighths
pole. The horse on my outside finally turned me loose, and she went
under the wire full of run. She never took a deep breath.''
</P>
<P>
   As bad as the trip was for Excellent Meeting, it was worse for
General Challenge, the other member of the Golden Eagle Farm entry
that was coupled as the 7-2 favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my worst trip ever in horse racing,'' said Gary
Stevens, who was aboard General Challenge. ``We got away from the
gate not too bad, I did get bumped out of there but not too bad.
Then when I went up into the first turn, I was down there between
Charismatic and Prime Timber and they put the squeeze on me. They
picked me up and carried me about four strides. I don't know how I
didn't fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when I was over on the far turn, I got hit again. I
finally got him out and made a little late run, but by then it
didn't much matter. Today, we got a nightmare trip. You had people
running over each other trying to get positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a horse like mine, who is hard to contain back off the
pace, it just turned into a disaster. That was the roughest Derby
I've ever ridden. But it was nobody's fault. It's just racing.''
</P>
<P>
   David Flores, aboard Prime Timber, had the least trouble of the
Baffert contingent, but it was no stroll in the park for him
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little tough there, but I was feeling good about my
chances,'' said Flores. ``I had to use him to get into position,
then they ran away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber will go to the Preakness at Pimlico May 15, and
Silverbulletday, who won the Kentucky Oaks on Friday in grand
style, may go to the Preakness, as well. ``Excellent Meeting and
General Challenge go back to California,'' said Baffert. ``Prime
Timber goes to the Preakness, and I'm considering Silvebulletday,
as well. I'm just disappointed my horses didn't get the chance to
run in the Derby. I knew we were dead at the first turn. Now, I
won't have to worry about the Triple Crown this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
