<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: RUSSIA STAKES ITS PRESTIGE ON BALKAN DIPLOMACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ By dispatching his special envoy to
Washington for talks on ending the Yugoslav conflict, President
Boris Yeltsin has put Russia at the center of international
diplomacy, reviving relations with Washington and NATO. Perhaps
more to the point for Yeltsin, it also plays well at home.
</P>
<P>
   The move has quieted the hard-line critics who have lamented
Moscow's dwindling influence, and has even enabled the president to
settle a few scores with some of his political rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that it remains unclear whether the Kremlin has
real influence over Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
whether it is willing to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians have been knocking at the door and demanding to
be treated as an important player,'' said Toby T. Gati, a former
senior State Department official. ``Now they have got the biggest
welcome they can have: the welcome at the White House. But this is
a high-stakes game. The question is whether they can deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   An initial answer may come Monday afternoon when Viktor
Chernomyrdin _ the former prime minister whom Yeltsin fired last
year and then tried unsuccessfully to rehire _ meets with President
Clinton. Yeltsin suggested the meeting in a 15-minute telephone
call to Clinton on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Yeltsin had compelling reasons to plunge into Balkan
diplomacy. Since NATO's bombs first started raining down on
Yugoslavia more than five weeks ago, the Kremlin has been on the
political defensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists have charged that the NATO raids show how weak
and marginalized Russia has become on Yeltsin's watch. Hard-liners
have demanded that the Kremlin provide military assistance to
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Such a step would frustrate Yeltsin's longstanding policy of
maintaining a good working relationship with the West, no small
consideration for a nation still sorely in need of billions of
dollars in credits from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Yeltsin sought to fend off his critics by turning up
the anti-NATO rhetoric. Russian officials denounced the allied air
strikes in vitriolic terms, warning that the military campaign
might even spark a third world war. When it came to deeds, however,
the Kremlin was careful to stay clear of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, that approach merely reinforced the
perception that Russia was powerless to end the fighting. Neither
NATO nor Belgrade seemed to care very much what Moscow thought.
</P>
<P>
   So Yeltsin switched his strategy. He appointed Chernomyrdin
special envoy on the Yugoslav conflict and sent him to Belgrade in
search of a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In a cut-throat world of Russian politics, the Chernomyrdin
appointment also served another purpose. It enabled Yeltsin to
diminish the political role of Yevgeni Primakov, Yeltsin's current
prime minister and a former foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has become increasingly unhappy with the ambitious
Primakov, who has done little to pull Russia out of its economic
morass while seeking to position himself as a potential successor
to the ailing president.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Chernomyrdin's diplomacy is simply a
matter of political theater. Russia has a genuine stake in
brokering a settlement on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's air strikes have dragged on, there has been increasing
talk in allied capitals of a possible land offensive. A NATO ground
assault to seize Kosovo would further inflame anti-Western opinion
in Moscow and renew the bitter criticism at home of Yeltsin's
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Brokering an agreement, however, is the hard part. As Russian
officials see it, Chernomyrdin has several important strengths,
including a good working relationship with Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiating a settlement might also help Chernomyrdin revive his
moribund political career, though almost certainly not to the point
where it would make him a plausible presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chernomyrdin's mission is heavy with political risks.
Having claimed the world spotlight, Russia has staked its prestige
on diplomacy. If it fails to make headway, Russia may soon find
itself back on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the issues are still formidable. NATO and
Belgrade have been far apart on the main issues, including the
alliance's demand that NATO troops be deployed in Kosovo to protect
ethnic Albanians and that all Serb forces be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Another divisive question concerns the final political status of
the Kosovo region. NATO is proposing that it be an
``internationally protected area'' that is only nominally within
Yugoslavia. Belgrade wants clearer administrative responsibility
over the region.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear that Moscow and Washington agree on how Russia
should go about its mediating role. Russia has tended to cast
itself as a sort of marriage counselor that expects concessions
from NATO, as well as Belgrade. The United States, however, insists
that NATO's demands are firm and that it is the Milosevic regime
that will have to make the major concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, for his part, met on Friday with Milosevic. He
left without declaring a breakthrough and was careful not to
promise one on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider the situation to be far from simple,''
Chernomyrdin said. ``But it gives us hope that efforts which Russia
has taken and will take are significant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
