<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES ROUT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Philadelphia's Curt Schilling did what Kevin
Brown was expected to do and because of it the Los Angeles Dodgers'
five-game winning streak is over.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling pitched out of a bases-loaded, none-out jam in the
sixth inning. In the bottom of the inning, Dodgers second baseman
Eric Young couldn't come up with a line drive with the bases
loaded. It led to three runs and the Phillies went on to beat the
Dodgers 12-3 Sunday in the finale of a three-game series at
Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The score got out of hand when reliever Jeff Kubenka allowed six
runs in the eighth, but the line drive was where the game turned.
It set up a broken-bat single by Philadelphia's Doug Glanville that
scored two runs and gave the Phillies a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have days when you can't buy a break,'' Brown said. `` I
had a chance to keep the game (close) and it didn't happen. You
make a pitch down the middle of the plate and he lines it at
somebody and everyone says, `Hip, hip, hooray. You got out of it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You make a good pitch and the guy breaks his bat and two runs
score.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time Young, who's played well in the field,
had an opportunity to make a play on a ball but couldn't get the
handle.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dodgers tied it in the top of the fourth on Todd
Hundley's two-run homer, Philadelphia's Bobby Abreu led off the
bottom of the inning with a triple. With one out and the infield
in, Rob Ducey hit a sharp grounder to Young at second. Young
couldn't get a grip on it to throw home, but he did get Ducey at
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one, ground ball hit hard, either I come up with it
or I don't,'' Young said. ``The line drive kind of knuckled at me.
Those are plays you either come up with or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who lasted six innings in his shortest stint since
opening day, put himself in trouble with uncharacteristic wildness.
He walked four for the second consecutive game, including three
straight with one out in the sixth. It set up Desi Relaford's liner
Young couldn't handle.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said the 20 mph winds blowing in
the face of the pitchers hurt Brown's and Schilling's control.
Brown didn't go that far, but he didn't deny the wind's impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't make a judgment on that,'' said Brown, who fell to
2-2. ``Obviously, I didn't do a good job adjusting to it. It's not
a reason I didn't win. I didn't get balls where I wanted them. It
was one of those days. I didn't think anything went right.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling also scuffled with his control with a season-high four
walks. But he was able to take a few deep breaths behind the
pitcher's mound before pitching out of similar trouble in the top
of the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Gary Sheffield, Raul Mondesi and Dave Hansen to load
the bases with none out, and the Dodgers had their left-handers in
order.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling fell behind in the count 3-0 to the switch-hitting
Hundley, but battled back to strike him out. Ditto with lefty Todd
Hollandsworth for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him do it before and that's what makes him great,''
Hansen said. ``He regrouped, tied his shoes and went after it. He
went to the back of the mound, did his Al Hrabosky imitation and
came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, who threw an insane 134 pitches in 71/3 innings, got
out of the sixth inning by getting hot-hitting Adrian Beltre to
ground into a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Schilling credit,'' Johnson said. ``Bases
loaded, 3-0 on a couple of good hitters and getting out of it
without a run. We could have broken the game open right there and
didn't. Schilling made the pitches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
