<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-WRAPUP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Highlights from the star Wars convention
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Two distinct kinds of fans attended the Star Wars
Celebration here this weekend: those who wanted to know what's
going to happen in Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace, and
those who absolutely did not.
</P>
<P>
   And the fans who wanted to avoid spoiling the surprise
outnumbered the ones looking for definitive answers about five to
one.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan MacKnight of Athens, Ohio, said he'll buy the
novelization of the Phantom Menace as soon as it goes on sale.
``But I won't even open it until I've seen the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The desire to preserve the surprise didn't stop MacKnight and
others from speculating about Episode I and the planned Episodes II
and III. And much of the speculation centered around how Anakin
Skywalker, a 9-year-old boy in Episode I, becomes the menacing
Darth Vader introduced in 1977's Episode IV.
</P>
<P>
   Max Clark of Beavercreek, Ohio, expects a battle between young
Anakin and his mentor Obi-Wan Kenobi. ``It's going to end with
Anakin falling into acid or molten metal,'' Clark said. ``His body
will be so badly damaged that he won't be able to survive without
the helmet and breathing equipment Darth Vader uses.''
</P>
<P>
   Another area of discussion on the last day of the celebration
was the probable impact Episode I will have on pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Carla Beth Perry of Longmont, Colo., came to the
celebration Sunday wearing makeup inspired by the character Queen
Amidala.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up wanting to be Princess Leia,'' she said, ``and now
we'll have a new generation of little girls wanting to be Queen
Amidala.''
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't immersed yourself in Episode I lore yet, here are
some of the Star Wars images that are most likely to spillover from
the world of hard-core fans into the wider culture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Darth Maul: Even before the fan event in Denver, the
red-and-black wasp pattern face of super villain Darth Maul has
popped up on the covers of popular magazines. His malevolent sneer
and double-bladed light saber were highlights of the first Episode
I advertising trailer. At the celebration, Darth Maul and Ray Park,
the actor who portrayed him, emerged as superstars. Walking among
the displays were short, tall, fat, skinny, old and young versions
of Darth Maul in homemade costumes of varying quality. Expect to
see the same at Halloween parties and science-fiction conventions
for the next couple years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Desert chic: Many of the characters in Episode I will be
dressed in loose fitting tunics in desert shades of beige, tan and
brown. The simple shapes and rough woven fabrics could easily find
their way into fall fashion lines. And the hairstyle sported in the
movie by Liar Neeson _ shoulder-length hair with a portion gathered
into a pony tail in back _ was the dominant look for men with the
required locks at the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   _ Amidala and Anakin: Just as Darth Maul was a major hit with
adults, children at the celebration identified with young Queen
Amidala and Anakin Skywalker. Anakin in helmet and goggles promises
to be the No. 1 boy's costume this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toys: Some toys went on sale today, and an early hit is likely
to be small action figures with electronic dog tags. The dog tags
have voice and sound implanted that can be downloaded and replayed
with a device called the Comm Tech chip reader, available for about
$20 to $25. The must-have toy for Christmas, however, will be Queen
Amidala's Royal Star Ship. This bright silver, highly detailed ship
is large enough to hold about six of the action figures and comes
with its own detachable landing yacht. It won't be available until
October and will sell for about $100.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
