<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBKIDS-COX     05-02 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBKIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet - maligned since Littleton - also comforts youths
 &HT;    (EDS: Sidebar top COPYCATS-COX.)
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Angry, hurt or overwhelmed by fear after
the high school shootings in Colorado, thousands of young people
across the country are seeking comfort in the familiar glow of
their computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   The Littleton tragedy quickly became the dominant topic in
Internet chat rooms and discussion groups geared to teens. Shielded
behind screen names, many assumed the role of analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Others simply cried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel unhappy,'' one girl wrote. ``Can I get a hug?
Anyone?''
</P>
<P>
   Cyberhugs flowed back. So did advice to demand a ``REAL one,
from your folks!''
</P>
<P>
   The strongest reaction has come from self-labeled geeks, Goths
and assorted outsiders _ kids who identify with the killers' image
as oddballs who were shunned and perhaps bullied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet that the people that were killed had provoked the
killers in the past,'' wrote Andrew. ``I'm not saying it's right
either, but what goes around comes around.''
</P>
<P>
   A Web site called Slashdot (www.slashdot.org), which serves
high-tech and computer-game fans, published an attack on ``geek
profiling.'' The article criticized attempts by schools and the
media to identify potentially violent kids by singling out those
who dress differently or prefer video games to traditional school
activities.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the site received more than 2,000 e-mail messages
from teenagers. Some expressed resentment at being even vaguely
identified with the horror. ``How dare you glorify these scum? They
were Nazi thugs, nothing more, nothing less,'' one wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Killer's page part of story
</P>
<P>
   The Internet's connection to the story became inseparable with
the revelation that one of the killers built and maintained a Web
page with a violent theme.
</P>
<P>
   Among the postings by Eric Harris were lyrics by an obscure
German band (``Chaos-panic /No resistance/ Detonations in a
distance'') and bomb-building instructions. Harris and Dylan
Klebold, the other gunman, also both posted personal profiles on
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The profile of Harris reportedly included provocative notes such
as, ``Personal Quote: it's fun being schizophrenic,'' and, ``Kill
Em AALLLL!!!!''
</P>
<P>
   The postings were expunged within a day or two of the killings,
but not before they were copied and posted elsewhere by others _
including a Broward County high school student, who quickly came
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   There are now numerous sites that claim to offer the words and
artwork or both killers.
</P>
<P>
   Web pages, the Internet equivalent of highway billboards, have
become easy to make and cheap or even free to post for anyone with
an Internet account. Many contain hate speech, obscenities, threats
and revolting images. Most are quickly submerged in the
ever-expanding sea of more than 100 million other Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Profiles aim to shock
</P>
<P>
   Users' self profiles are often clearly written for shock value:
One America Online member currently lists his marital status as ``3
dead girls'' and his hobby as ``killin red necks.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL won't comment on postings by the Colorado teens, saying it
has been asked not to discuss the case by the FBI. But the on-line
service does review member profiles periodically for profanity and
threats, said AOL spokeswoman Kim McCreery. The Internet is so vast
that few topics are unaddressed. For example, Harris' bomb
instructions added little to the voluminous advice available on
incendiary destruction.
</P>
<P>
   A brief Web search turned up several do-it-yourself manuals on
homemade weapons and bombs. Included are diagrams and ingredients
for pipe bombs, fire bombs and flame throwers.
</P>
<P>
   The search also turned up instructions for making school bomb
threats more realistic by planting fake bombs and using chemicals
to create a burning smell in the halls and bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   For the more ambitious, or destructive, there are even plans for
atomic devices. Diagrams for nuclear weapons are posted by the
physics department of the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   A disclaimer at that site warns: ``We here at UC Berkeley do not
recommend using this file beyond the realm of casual or academic
curiosity.'' Any attempt to build an A-bomb at home would likely
result in death from radiation poisoning, it concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to maim?
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely a teen could scrounge up the fissionable material
to get that far, but the consequences could be just as deadly for
anyone who tried to follow other Internet bomb-making recipes.
There is no way of knowing whether they are reliable, or perhaps
designed to maim the people who try them.
</P>
<P>
   The same caution about verity applies to other Internet advice,
such as the seemingly sober thoughts of a Connecticut teen who
created an ``unofficial'' Web site for his high school.
</P>
<P>
   It includes instructions under the heading, ``What to do if an
intruder comes into your school.'' The first steps follow common
sense: Find a place to hide, find a phone to call 911, lie on the
floor, pull down the shades.
</P>
<P>
   The last may be a sign of what's on many minds: ``Call CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
