<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SONICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS GET KOBE'D
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Someday it will be blacktop lingo: ``He went Kobe on
me.'' A heavy sigh will follow. And you'll know just what the
neighborhood kid meant by the expression. And you'll probably pity
him.
</P>
<P>
   To wit, ``going Kobe'' will be loosely defined as an unworldly,
unstoppable outburst of offense, crammed into a brief window of 10
or so minutes. It is a sight to behold. And it is devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the Seattle SuperSonics, whose playoff hopes probably
died Sunday in a third-quarter Kobefest, as young Kobe Bryant
scored 19 points in a 9-minute, 44-second span to lead the Los
Angeles Lakers to a 91-84 victory at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   With that sizzling run, Bryant helped the Lakers win their
second straight, strengthen their grip on the fourth seed in the
West and make the Sonics mathematical long shots to make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal did the rest with a 33-point, 12-rebound
performance, including a 21-point first half that set up Bryant's
third-quarter extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Shaq, `You can line 'em up, and I'll shoot them down,'
'' Bryant said. ``When I caught the ball, I noticed they were
backing off. I just figured why not shoot it?''
</P>
<P>
   He did, and made 9 of 10 in the quarter _ on fadeaways, on
pull-up jumpers, on a 3-pointer, on layups, and, at the end of the
run, on a breakaway one-handed jam for emphasis. He scored nine
straight points in one burst and eight straight in another for a
17-2 run that was all Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Final score in the third quarter: Kobe 19, Sonics 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets it going, he makes a couple, you can tell that he
starts getting `geeked,''' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``He just plays
stronger, he plays harder, he plays more confident. You can see
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers emerged from the third with a 70-57 lead. Turned out,
it almost wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   After O'Neal dominated two quarters and Bryant the next, no
Laker could get going in a fourth quarter that saw the team shoot
27.8 percent. O'Neal missed 4 of 5 shots, and Gary Payton replaced
Hersey Hawkins in defending Bryant, holding him to three points in
the final frame.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice's 3-pointer, his first field goal of the night, pushed
the Lakers' lead to a game-high 16 points to open the fourth. Then
Payton took over, scoring nine points in a 16-3 Sonics run that cut
the lead to 76-73.
</P>
<P>
   Payton scored 14 of his 29 points in the fourth, but the Lakers
rediscovered their defense, which held Seattle to 37.5 percent
shooting for the game. The Sonics never got closer than three
points.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that was failed strategy. With three minutes left,
Seattle coach Paul Westphal, desperate and and watching his team's
playoff hopes fade, put Dale Ellis on O'Neal with orders to foul;
almost every Lakers possession became an O'Neal trip to the foul
line, and Ellis committed all six of his fouls in the quarter,
three against O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, coming off a 14-for-17 free-throw performance three days
prior, delivered just enough this time. He hit 5 of 9 fouls shots
in the last three minutes, and the Lakers scored nine of their
final 13 points on free throws to hold on.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, a 53 percent career free-throw shooter, was unoffended
by the early intentional fouling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys probably don't believe this, but I sit around the
house ... and dream of my team down by one, they foul and put me at
the line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he vowed to make teams pay for the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna always make one. I'm gonna start making two at a
time. I ain't missing no more. I'm ticked off at myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For once, though, the Lakers are generally happy with
themselves, having parlayed last week's team meeting into two solid
wins and something resembling momentum heading into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to see,'' Robert Horry said. ``It's good to go out
and play one good game. But when you carry it over that's the more
important thing. So we carried it over today, which is great for
us. There's still some things we gotta work on. We see the things
we need to work on, we get it done _ that's the sign of us growing
as a team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
