A1548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORRESPONDENTS-DINNER     05-02 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRESPONDENTS-DINNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MELDING OF EXTREMES AT CORRESPONDENTS' DINNER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fellini could not have directed the scene better.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House Correspondents Association Dinner, the annual
roast at which the Washington press corps honors the president,
mingles with government sources and _ in recent years _ gawks at
Hollywood celebrities, the level of surrealism was high.
</P>
<P>
   At a cocktail party before Saturday night's dinner, hosted by
George magazine, Susan McDougal, who went to prison rather than
testify against President Clinton in the Whitewater affair, stooped
over in her lavender evening gown to embrace Larry Flynt, the
Hustler magazine publisher who offered money to women who could
reveal the sexual transgressions of politicians.
</P>
<P>
   A guest of George's editor in chief, John F. Kennedy Jr., Flynt
sat in his trademark gold wheelchair, wearing a satin kelly-green
dinner jacket with embroidered lapels. As the crowd stared, Ms.
McDougal eased herself into Flynt's lap, whispered in his ear,
stood up and announced, ``It's so good to be outside'' _ a
reference to the end of her prison term.
</P>
<P>
   A huddle of photographers sprang to life to photograph the pair.
Kennedy beamed. Despite the fact that one of his invited guests,
Richard Mellon Scaife, the conservative multimillionaire who has
been critical of Clinton, did not show up for the dinner, Kennedy
was still able to host six tables of guests that included Flynt,
actor Sean Penn and actress Claire Danes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was afraid of the press coverage,'' Kennedy said of
Scaife.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, however, is not. A provocative guest list is standard
equipment for the dinner, which has become an opportunity for
magazine publishers to show off prize celebrity catches and
generate some publicity for their publications.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy defended his guest list, saying that ``this event, and
the culture of our magazine, is about the melding of extremes.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, the dinner has increasingly melded those
extremes, attracting the famous and infamous each year, from Fawn
Hall in 1987 to Paula Jones in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Warren Beatty publicized his political movie
``Bulworth,'' and seven camera crews trailed Paula Jones wherever
she went. For the last six years Vanity Fair magazine has held an
after-dinner party that has been monitored by camera crews from
``Entertainment Tonight'' and ``Access Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, George magazine upheld the level of notoriety with
Flynt, but, in general, the star power was less blinding, and the
connections linking stars to the dinner were more tenuous. Vanity
Fair invited actor Val Kilmer. Clinton's personal secretary, Betty
Currie, was a guest of Newsweek magazine. People magazine brought
Camryn Manheim, the actress who plays a lawyer on the television
series ``The Practice'' _ and who is not starring in a political
movie but was happy to talk about her new book, ``Wake Up, I'm
Fat.''
</P>
<P>
   In a scenario that perhaps best exemplified the transition from
the old-style correspondents' dinner, when the most famous faces
belonged to Cabinet members, Ben Bradlee, the editor who shepherded
The Washington Post through Watergate, was the dinner guest of In
Style, the monthly magazine devoted to celebrity fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that movie stars regularly appear at a dinner intended
for political writers was emphasized by Brian Williams, the MSNBC
anchor who delivered the evening's opening remarks. He thanked the
``Hollywood celebrities for inviting the Washington press corps to
dinner.'' And hundreds of autograph-seekers gathered at the rope
line cordoning off the entrance to the dinner, which was held in
the Washington Hilton, the only hotel with a banquet room large
enough to hold the 2,700 guests.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Stewart Powell, the acting president of the
correspondents' association, arranged a dinner that insured that
the president would avoid embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than relying on a comedian who might make rancorous fun
of the president and first lady, Powell hired Aretha Franklin to
perform _ at a cost of $55,000 _ and the only person who might have
been embarrassed was Helen Thomas, the veteran Washington
correspondent, who danced a seated rendition of the Funky Chicken
on stage while Ms. Franklin sang ``Freeway of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Isikoff, the Newsweek reporter whose reporting ushered
in the Monica Lewinsky story, received an award, but Williams
presented it, and the president, who in past years has stood with
award recipients for a handshake and a photo opportunity, arrived
at the dinner late enough to miss Isikoff's award and any possibly
awkward moment.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Oreskes, the Washington bureau chief of The New York
Times, expressed his concerns about the tone of the dinner, and the
newspaper did not buy a table this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dinner had gotten out of hand even before last night,''
Oreskes said. ``I hope that all the journalists there had a good
time because the profession is paying a price for this evening
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Donaldson, the White House reporter for ABC News, said that
when he first attended the dinner in the early 1960s, he was ``in
awe of the secretary of defense, the secretary of state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then when the president came in,'' Donaldson added, ``I was
just a puddle. Now it's the Hollywood stars. As we were leaving
last night, at the rope line, there was such a crush of cameras and
people squealing. I couldn't tell who it was but it was not the
secretary of defense, I assure you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
