A1554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RESIDENTS-NYT &LR;      05-02 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RESIDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TRAVELERS IN SERBIA, DANGER AND DIFFICULTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ At night in Kosovo, the only light is
that thrown by burning tires, set aflame by police apparently to
alert the very few drivers that they are approaching a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Police and soldiers keep a low profile, and _ with gasoline
rationed and life constrained by constant air raids _ their
vehicles are almost the only ones on any roads in Serbia. Those who
man checkpoints along the road exude an air of calm correctness
when checking drivers' documents. Where bridges are down, police
block the roads with mounds of earth and divert traffic through
bumpy side roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not concerned for ourselves. We are soldiers or police,
it is our job to risk our lives,'' said one policeman on the road.
``But we care about the children, the civilians and the old people.
For them, it is terrifying with the bombs and the sirens going on
every day and night.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters who were escorted into Kosovo by Yugoslav Defense
Ministry officials after a NATO missile slammed into a bus,
reportedly killing 47 people, at Luzane, just 12 miles north of
Kosovo's capital, Pristina, gained a fleeting impression of how
police are working there.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian police seem to be surviving and coping with the NATO
attacks and emerging unfazed. One policeman, just back from a
40-day shift in Kosovo, made light of his tour of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Looking healthy and well fed, he said his unit had never lacked
supplies. They had based themselves in an abandoned Albanian
village, near Djakovica in western Kosovo, and had been able to
cook for themselves. They even had time to make themselves cookies,
he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Police and soldiers are said by NATO officials, refugees and the
few foreigners who have traveled the province since NATO started
bombing to be using the cover of civilian villages all over Kosovo
to avoid airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   The policeman suggested that the threat from the air was
limiting the security forces' ability to move, or at least making
them think twice about doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main danger from NATO is when we are traveling from one
position to another,'' said the policeman, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had come under attack from planes when on the road
several times. Each time the planes had seemed to fire a warning
shot at the head of the column, giving the men in the convoy a
split second to jump clear of their cars, before the missiles
struck methodically along the column of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The policeman said that the guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation
Army were using mines to ambush police convoys on the roads more
now than in the past. He indicated that they present little threat,
attacking only sporadically and usually in pairs or even alone.
</P>
<P>
   Civilians boarding buses in Belgrade Sunday for Kosovo or
southern Serbia displayed similar acceptance that danger was simply
a part of life right now.
</P>
<P>
   Tanya, who had come from Bosnia to visit her parents in
Belgrade, was one of many passengers buying daily newspapers that
bore graphic pictures of the mangled wreck of the Nis-Pristina bus
hit by NATO's missile. ``I have lived through seven years of
that,'' she said, alluding to the years of war, hardship and
lawlessness in Bosnia since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their fears, Serbs were continuing Sunday to travel.
Several buses left for Pristina in the morning. Many passengers had
little option but to take them. At 2 p.m. Steva Nikolic and his
family were waiting to travel home to Mitrovica in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me the creeps,'' he said, folding up his newspaper.
``What do you mean, am I scared? I have four children, a wife who
is expecting and my parents-in-law with me.''
</P>
<P>
   A refugee from Tuzla in Bosnia, Nikolic has lived in Kosovo for
the last three years in a former barracks, along with 150 other
Serb refugees. Just 500 yards away is a military barracks that had
been hit by NATO bombs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day my table moved right across the room when a bomb
exploded. The whole building lifted and shook. We are very
scared,'' he said. He had brought his family up to Belgrade for a
few days to escape the bombing, but they had nowhere to stay and
had to return home. ``What can I do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
