<DOCNO> NYT19990502.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     05-02 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The lingering, day-after-the-Derby question
Sunday was whether Charismatic made more history than he prevented.
</P>
<P>
   The full-bodied chestnut colt recorded the third-biggest upset
the Kentucky Derby has ever known, a glorious way to say goodbye to
the 1900s. But here is the heartache by the numbers: no favorite,
no California horse, no gelding and no filly has won this race in
21, 38, 71 and 13 years, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Topping off a week that saw him elected to the Racing Hall of
Fame, D. Wayne Lukas tried to tell us that Charismatic had the
right stuff, but hardly anyone was listening. ``This horse can be
my Villanova,'' said Lukas, referring to the unsung team that
knocked off seemingly invincible Georgetown in the 1985 college
basketball final. An old high school coach, Lukas is fond of
dropping a hoops reference into his turf talk.
</P>
<P>
   True to his school, the school of hard knocks, hard work and
hard cash, the Gray Fox won his fourth Derby, adding this year's
trophy to those captured by Winning Colors (1988), Thunder Gulch
(1995) and Grindstone (1996). He did it with a colt who had run 14
times with only a single victory in a stakes race, who was almost a
discard, and who went to the post at odds of 30-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have ever misread a colt so badly as I did
this one early on,'' said Lukas, who believed Charismatic needed to
go on a diet. ``I made up my mind to burn the fat off him and see
if there was anything there. The more I drilled him, the better he
got.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding the horse was just big, not blubbery, he took a closer
look and saw an emerging star. This was after Lukas and owners Bob
and Beverly Lewis had twice entered him in claiming races, where he
could have been bought by anyone for $62,500. The Lewises had
purchased the son of Summer Squall for $210,000 right off the
breeding farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you go along and nothing happens,'' said Bob Lewis,
``and you feel like you need to cut your losses.'' In February at
Santa Anita, the colt went unclaimed after finishing second _ and
moved up to first when the winner was disqualified. ``I was sitting
in the box with Bob,'' recalled Lukas. ``I said, `Whew, we're not
doing this again.'''
</P>
<P>
   If he can deceive his trainer, what chance did the rest of us
have? The more likely Lukas entry was thought to be Cat Thief _ who
led briefly and finished third. Charismatic received a sure and
well-timed ride from Chris Antley but was the beneficiary of the
horse hockey game going on around him. He still had to hold off
Menifee, who lost by a neck.
</P>
<P>
   More than one jockey argued that the best colt did not win. The
125th Kentucky Derby drew the second-largest crowd and the
second-largest betting pool, but few of the riders in the field of
19 actually saw much of the race because they were busy getting
bumped, bounced or clipped, while others pinballed their way around
the track.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic will go for the second jewel of the Triple Crown,
the Preakness, on May 15 at Baltimore, and you doubt he will be
favored. Lukas concedes the Belmont will be more to his liking, a
long-distance test for a colt that ``can run all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert will try to rebound from his failed effort to win a
third straight Kentucky Derby by sending Prime Timber and Excellent
Meeting, who finished fourth and fifth, to the Preakness. They will
be joined by his superstar filly, Silverbulletday, who ran away
with the Kentucky Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenger, the colt Baffert prized the most, wound up a
wobbly 11th and is going home to California. This is a rough
league. One loss and you're off the team.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic paid a bountiful $64.60 to win. He may have once
looked like something out of the five-and-dime store, but he's a
million-dollar baby now.
</P>
<P>
   Between a colt regarded as too pudgy and a jockey who had to
battle his own bulge, this was a race Weight Watchers could have
endorsed. Antley, who won the 1991 Derby on Strike the Gold, had to
overcome a larger handicap. He was out of racing for 18 months
while he struggled with a recurring drug problem. As he fought to
get clean and sober, he had to run his own marathons to get rid of
34 unwanted pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Making Antley's success more poignant was a message from Pat
Valenzuela, who is in California trying to get his life together
after 10 years of alcohol and drug abuse. The jockey who rode
Sunday Silence to victory in the 1986 Derby and Preakness sent
good-luck wishes to his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Day, who gave Menifee a terrific ride, is another who had to
get himself off drugs and up from the pits. Their stories are not
unique, which may be a reflection of the pressure to make the
weight and the money and temptations that come with winning.
</P>
<P>
   No, the race isn't always to the swift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
