<HEADER>
A1560 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     05-02 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONE MAY KNOW NUNN STILL AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Nunn is no longer considered one of the
best fighters in the world. At 36, it's too late for him to realize
the greatness so many had predicted. And, it appears, he won't be
retiring as the multimillionaire he might've been.
</P>
<P>
   He won't leave boxing without an impressive body of work.
</P>
<P>
   The native of Davenport, Iowa, who has long trained in Van Nuys
has remained at or near the top of every weight division in which
he has fought for almost 15 years, a remarkable run of consistency
that lives on.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time world champion, now a light heavyweight, faces
once-beaten William Guthrie on Sunday in North Dakota with the
winner expected to be in line for a world-title shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through all that,'' said Nunn, referring to the
pound-for-pound debate. ``It's OK if my name doesn't come up. It's
nothing I dwell on. I dwell on getting out there and performing on
a high level.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I continue to go to the gym every day, run, fight
and beat the best, I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunn was once as feared as any fighter.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid- and late '80s, his combination of immense boxing
skills and speed was too much for his first 36 opponents. Among his
victims: Frank Tate (for the IBF middleweight championship), Juan
Roldan, Sumbu Kalambay, Iran Barkley, Marlon Starling and Donald
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   He had created an ominous illusion of invincibility against some
the sport's biggest names.
</P>
<P>
   However, it didn't last long: Nunn ran into trouble and out of
luck beginning in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   _He lost three big fights _ to James Toney, Steve Little and
Frank Liles _ within a 3{-year period.
</P>
<P>
   _He had personal problems _ a few run-ins with the law and a
self-destructive tendency to lose focus on boxing. An adviser of
Nunn once blamed it on distractive elements in Davenport, which he
called ``a black hole.''
</P>
<P>
   _And Nunn abandoned those who had guided him to the top _ Van
Nuys-based Dan and Jo Goossen _ in favor of Don King shortly before
the Toney fight in hopes of earning more money. Instead, his career
went downhill and would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he's as good as any light heavyweight in the world this
side of Roy Jones Jr. His skills remain sharp and he insists his
vast experience compensates for any physical deficiencies that
might come with age.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to prove it in his latest championship bout but lost
what many believe was a bad decision to then-WBC champ Graciano
Rocchigiani in the German's home country last year. It was Nunn's
15th world-title fight and would've been his third championship.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a 36-year-old who now has had 57 pro fights (53-4,
with 34 knockouts).
</P>
<P>
   However, few noticed: He is largely anonymous these days in
relation to fighters like Jones, Oscar De La Hoya and several
heavyweights. Mention his name and you're likely to hear, ``Oh,
he's still around?''
</P>
<P>
   Nunn admits if he had Evander Holyfield-like commitment, things
might've been different. At the same time, he has come to terms
with any lost opportunities. He likes the person he has become _ he
says he has settled down _ and is grateful he can still fight at a
championship level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone ever really (realizes his or her
potential),'' Nunn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a learning experience. There are things I've done I
realize I can't do now. It's something I had to go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me a better individual. And, hey, I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Goossen, now the head of America Presents, will always
bemoan Nunn's fate to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others, he saw a lot of Sugar Ray Leonard in Nunn _
the ability, an engaging personality, a great smile. That Nunn
never created a Leonard-like legend saddens Goossen.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Goossen has to give Nunn his admiration. After
all, how many fighters remain on top in this roughest of games as
long as Nunn has?
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel bad when a person doesn't reach goals that you
know are attainable,'' Goossen said. ``From that standpoint, I'll
always be disappointed that Mike didn't become one of the greatest
fighters who ever laced up gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, considering the bumps in the road, he kept
himself on top for a very long time. You have to hand it to him for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ruelases: Dan Goossen said he has tentatively set a July
date for the comeback fights of former world champions Gabriel and
Rafael Ruelas, who are expected to appear on the same card.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen, who has been with the Sylmar products their entire
careers, said he supports their decisions to fight again _ to a
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel ... they deserve the opportunity to show that they
still have the ability to become a champion again,'' he said.
``That's the only agreement we have. Then we'll make an evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they show they're correct, if they still have the ability
to win a world title, we're all behind them. If they show
deterioration, if they show a skill level that would make it
virtually impossible to reach a championship, we've agreed to sit
down and speak man to man, honestly about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Goossen said he wouldn't feel right if someone else promoted the
Ruelases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is they're going to fight,'' he said. ``I'd
rather be in a position to watch over them rather than someone use
them for their names.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales defense: Erik Morales will defend his WBC super
bantamweight title against Juan Carlos Ramirez _ a replacement for
Wayne McCullough _ on Saturday in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, one of the top young fighters in the world, needs a
meaningful challenge if he's going to take the next step in his
career, something neither McCullough nor Ramirez are capable of
giving him.
</P>
<P>
   Who could? There are many fighters in and around his weight
class who would make for an interesting fight: Naseem Hamed,
Luisito Espinosa, Marco Antonio Barrera, Tim Austin and Johnny
Tapia, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Forum update: Juan Manuel Marquez, the mandatory challenger for
Hamed's WBO featherweight title since 1997, is scheduled to face
former contender Wilfredo Vargas next Monday at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed, who is more hype than substance, has refused to fight
Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamed claims he will fight anyone, any place,'' said John
Jackson, Forum Boxing vice president. ``It's time for him to put
his fists where his mouth is and fight the man he's supposed to
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Marquez has won 28 straight fights since losing in his pro
debut. He has 22 knockouts.
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight fight: Former IBF cruiserweight champion Al Cole is
scheduled to face Willie Williams in a 10-round heavyweight bout
Thursday in St. Paul, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   The fight will be televised on USSB.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
