<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC WILL LEAD FIELD OF CONTENDERS INTO PREAKNESS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Ten of the 19 horses who ran in the Kentucky
Derby were booked Sunday into the Preakness, the second race in the
Triple Crown, including the top four finishers led by Charismatic,
the 31-1 long shot who won the Derby in the final strides.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic, who was a forgotten claimer in the barn of D. Wayne
Lukas last winter, not only scored a dramatic upset in the Derby
but also restored Lukas to the highest rank of Triple Crown
trainers by outrunning all three horses entered by Bob Baffert and
preventing Baffert from winning his third straight Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The colt now will try to become something of an iron horse: two
weeks ago, he won the Lexington Stakes at Keeneland. Then, the
Kentucky Derby before a crowd of 151,051 at Churchill Downs. Next,
in two weeks, he will try the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who has won the Derby four times _ three times in the
past five years _ strongly discounted any suggestion that his
victory might have been diminished by the wide open race down to
the finish. And at the finish, Charismatic was separated from
Menifee only by the length of his neck and from Cat Thief by less
than a length, and only 10 lengths separated the top 15 horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't put together the field,'' Lukas said Sunday morning.
``You only beat the ones that show up. You go over in the 125th
year, and you beat the ones that show up. The race had 19 horses in
it, and we beat everybody that showed up.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the horses who showed up apparently were victimized
by the size of the field and by the rough traffic jams that
resulted. Baffert reported that his star colt General Challenge,
the race time favorite with his entry mate, the filly Excellent
Meeting, had felt the stings and arrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Challenge's eyes were full of dirt and stuff,''
Baffert said. ``The poor guy, he probably took the worst of it of
all of them. He's all right today, but he looked like he was
dragging his hind leg a little bit yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard for me to get into the Derby this year because of
the 20 horses,'' Baffert said, meaning the 20-horse limit. ``It
becomes a crap shoot. You still need a good horse, but you need so
much luck. I couldn't get the trip with any of them yesterday.
Excellent Meeting ran unbelievable. She was dead last and she came
10-wide, and she only gets beat about two and a half or three
lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Timber was pretty tired after the race,'' Baffert said.
``He had a little bit of a rough trip, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert salvaged one prize from the weekend: his star filly
Silverbulletday won the Kentucky Oaks the day before the Derby for
her 10th victory in 11 starts. The trainer said he might enter her
in both the Black-Eyed Susan and the Preakness the following day.
But he said that he had no regrets about his decision to run her in
the Oaks instead of the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to run her in a 20-horse field,'' he said.
``She could have been in there getting knocked around. That's when
they get hurt and get clobbered. The Oaks was like a nice breeze
for her. It didn't knock her out.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said he would go to the Preakness with Prime Timber, who
ran fourth in the Derby, but not with Excellent Meeting (fifth) or
General Challenge (11th).
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't run in the Preakness,'' he said. ``I don't know
what we'll do with them. We'll just freshen them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Another rough Derby trip was suffered by Three Ring, the other
filly in the race, who finished 19th and last (Ajabr was
scratched). She was bumped repeatedly and her trainer, Eddie Plesa,
said: ``If I could have waved a magic wand the first time she went
by, I would have pulled her out.''
</P>
<P>
   John Velazquez, who rode Three Ring, said that he had another
problem: The saddle slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all the problems,'' Velazquez said. ``The saddle went
over her neck. I was like riding on her head.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, who nearly caught Charismatic at the wire with an
electrifying dash in the late homestretch, will go on to the
Preakness. But his stablemate, Ecton Park, will not.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Walden, who trains both colts, said that ``Ecton Park
hasn't run that well two races in a row.'' But he was philosophical
about Menifee, who ran second just as his star Victory Gallop did
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran a beautiful race,'' Walden said. ``At least, we were in
the position to have that opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Derby field of 19, these were the horses reported most
likely to start in the 1 3-16-mile Preakness, which will be run on
May 15 at Pimlico Race Course in Baltimore : Charismatic, Menifee,
Cat Thief, Prime Timber, Kimberlite Pipe, Worldly Manner, Lemon
Drop Kid, Stephen Got Even, Adonis and Vicar. Listed as possible
starters: K One King, who ran eighth, and Forty One Carats;
Millions and Talk's Cheap who did not run in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner, the ``mystery horse'' from Dubai, who challenged
for the lead in the stretch but then faded to seventh, will stay at
Churchill Downs for a few days before his Preakness trip is
confirmed. But he gave a strong performance after traveling halfway
round the world on an experimental training regimen with no prep
races.
</P>
<P>
   Would a prep race have helped?
</P>
<P>
   His rider, Jerry Bailey, said with unassailable logic: ``We'll
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
