<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-CORSICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH ANTI-TERRORIST OFFICERS SUSPECTED IN EXPLOSION IN CORSICA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Bombs and fires have long been common tools for
Corsica's separatists, but a recent explosion at a beach restaurant
on the Mediterranean island has come with an unusual twist:
Evidence has appeared that the blast may have been the work of the
very crack police squad that was created to stem the guerrilla
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the elite anti-terrorist squad, including the
chief of the national police on the island, were placed under
investigation and imprisoned in Paris last week on charges of
``voluntary destruction'' caused ``by an organized gang.'' Among
the burned-out remains of chez Francis, which was bombed on April
20, local residents found a ski mask as well as a police-issued
walkie-talkie and combat knife.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassed government in Paris quickly ordered
investigations and pledged to disclose the truth about the police
actions while the prime minister and the minister of interior faced
a storm of questions in Parliament. Corsican nationalist groups
declared that Paris was trying to destabilize the island and had
ordered the fire to pin the blame on the separatist groups.
</P>
<P>
   The four police officers, all of them members of the national
police force known as gendarmes, have denied setting the fire at
the beach restaurant, just south of the Corsican capital of
Ajaccio. They said that three of the men had been at the scene as
part of a routine patrol, but no explanation has been offered for
why one of the men suffered burns.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the restaurant and politicians in Paris have
demanded to know whose orders the squad were following when they
appeared at the restaurant during the night in a small boat.
Francois Leotard, the former minister of defense, said, ``In all my
life, I have never seen a gendarme acting on his own, and certainly
not in this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians and newspapers have seized on the
incident to embarrass the Socialist government of Lionel Jospin.
While Corsica has seen its portion of political bombs and fires for
the past two decades, this particular bomb threatens to turn into
the first serious scandal affecting the Jospin government.
</P>
<P>
   For one, it undermines the government's campaign to restore
order on the volatile island in the Mediterranean. Separatist
guerrillas have targeted public buildings and tourist sites for
more than two decades in their campaign to gain more autonomy from
Paris. Rivals regularly shoot each other. But the most audacious
strike came last year when gunmen killed the highest official on
the island, Prefect Claude Erignac. His killing, like many on the
island, has not been solved.
</P>
<P>
   Following the prefect's death, France sent an elite squad to the
island to stem not only the political violence but also to crack
down on the notorious corruption in the Corsican administration.
</P>
<P>
   The group's investigations have annoyed many Corsicans because
it has interfered in cozy local habits from tax dodging to illegal
construction permits.
</P>
<P>
   The three men implicated in the restaurant fire belong to this
group, a body of 85 men, known as the Security Squad. Politicians
in Ajaccio have demanded that the squad be disbanded and sent back
to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious that these events are a blow to the policy of
re-establishing a state of law'' in Corsica, the minister of
interior, Jean-Pierre Chevenement, told the Senate. ``At this
stage, no hypothesis can be or should be excluded.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative newspaper Le Figaro, in a front-page editorial,
mocked the ``pitiful adventure'' of the police and called it a
stunt worthy of Inspector Clouseau in ``The Pink Panther.''
</P>
<P>
   It added that this action had wiped out the government's
law-and-order efforts in Corsica of the past year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
