<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/02/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 2, 1999 -- SANG-PARALYZED-GYMNAST, 5-02
-- Sang Lan, the Chinese gymnast who was paralyzed in a warm-up
vault at the Goodwill Games last summer, with an interpreter at a
recent awards dinner. Sang, who turns 18 on June 11, is set to
return home to China on June 2. If any major surgery needs to be
done, Sang will return to the United States, where she is insured
for up to $10 million in medical expenses. (Vic DeLucia/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 2, 1999 -- INTERNET-PHONE-IPO, 5-02 --
Itzhak Fisher, chief executive of RSL Communications Ltd. In what
would apparently be the first initial public offering of stock in a
company that focuses exclusively on transmitting phone calls using
Internet technology, RSL Communications Ltd. plans to announce
Monday that it intends to sell stock in its Delta 3 subsidiary.
``In order to attract eyeballs and to provide more products and
services, we decided to give Delta 3 the ability to do financing on
their own,'' he says. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHIJARASI, India -- May 2, 1999 --
INDIA-WOMEN-POLITICS-4, 5-02 -- In the small village of Chijarasi,
Rani who is head of the village council, is illiterate. Her son
Vikram read her a document. Rani, who like many lower-caste women
in India goes by only one name, is one of almost a million women
who have been elected to village governing councils since India
adopted a constitutional amendment in 1993. (Celia W. Dugger/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KHODA, India -- May 2, 1999 -- INDIA-WOMEN-POLITICS-3,
5-02 -- In Khoda, Bir Bal Singh Yadav, center, still acts as
village head even though his wife, Munni, 40, was elected to the
post. The only woman present, as councilors met recently, was there
to pour tea. ``My lady is illiterate,'' he says. ``She has to
attend the meetings, but besides that, I do all the work and I
explain matters to the authorities.'' (Celia W. Dugger/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) KHODA, India -- May 2, 1999 -- INDIA-WOMEN-POLITICS-2,
5-02 -- In Khoda, Munni Yadav, 40, is the pradhan, or elected
village head, but her husband carries out most of her functions.
``I'm not an educated woman,'' says Mrs. Yadav, who won election in
a field of a dozen women candidates. ``I am a village woman. So
most of the work is done by my husband. We village women are not
supposed to come out of the house and speak with strangers.''
(Celia W. Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CHIJARASI, India -- May 2, 1999 --
INDIA-WOMEN-POLITICS-1, 5-02 -- Rani, 30, an illiterate woman from
the washermen's caste, is now head of the Chijarasi village
council. Rani, who like many lower-caste women in India goes by
only one name, is one of almost a million women who have been
elected to village governing councils since India adopted a
constitutional amendment in 1993. ``I am the boss,'' she says
boldly. (Celia W. Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- May 2, 1999 -- SOCSEC-BALL-PROFILE,
5-02 -- Robert M. Ball, 85, a regular source of advice for leading
Congressional Democrats on the issue of Social Security. Ball is an
irreplaceable link with 60 years of history. He went to work for
Social Security in 1939, ran the program as Commissioner from 1962
to 1973, and has since played a principal role on some of the
important advisory commissions, and, yes, is a Social Security
beneficiary himself. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MILL VALLEY, Calif. -- May 2, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-INTERNET, 5-02 -- Deanna Miller of Mill Valley, Calif.,
and her husband, Richard, have forbidden their son Max, 9, to play
the computer game Battlenet. After the massacre in Littleton,
Colorado., ``we're paying more attention,'' says Ms. Miller. Many
parents feel the current soul-searching, prompted in part by the
Littleton news, may herald more active parental monitoring of their
children's use of the Internet. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DENTON, Texas -- May 2, 1999 -- Y2K-REFORMS, 5-02 --
Prof. Leon Kappelman, an associate professor of business computer
information systems at the University of North Texas and
co-chairman of the Society for Information Management's Year 2000
working group, considers computing's year 2000 bug an ethical
lapse. Few programmers feel pangs of conscience about Y2K in the
way that some nuclear physicists rue having brought the world the
bomb. (Mark Graham/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 2, 1999 -- NEW-FOUNDATION-2, 5-02 --
Jeffrey Soros, nephew of George Soros, the billionaire financier,
and one of the new benefactors of a new foundation called Creative
Capital Foundation, that hopes to support artists who challenge
convention. The new nonprofit organization has already made it
clear that it will not shy away from the kind of innovative art
that incited protests by religious and political conservatives.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 2, 1999 -- NEW-FOUNDATION-1-B&AMP;W, 5-02 --
Archibald L. Gillies, president of the Andy Warhol Foundation for
the Visual Arts and benefactor of a new foundation called Creative
Capital Foundation, that hopes to support artists who challenge
convention. ``This is a boisterous, diverse country, and we have
always had art that upsets people,'' says Gillies. ``Controversy,''
he adds, ``won't bother us at all.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ANGELES -- May 2, 1999 -- KINGSLEY-PROFILE, 5-02 --
Pat Kingsley, 66, one of Hollywood's top publicists, tends to
minimize her role in Hollywood. But no one else does. As a founder
of PMK, the most powerful public relations company in
entertainment, she ranks as the doyenne of Hollywood publicity and
an extraordinarily potent force in the movie industry. ``We prefer
to be buffers,'' alluding to her role as the gatekeeper limiting
access to the stars. (Monica Almedia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- May 2, 1999 -- ONLINE-BOOKSELLING, 5-02 --
Workers set up a booth at the Los Angeles Convention Center for
Book Expo America, the annual and sometimes uneasy business reunion
of independent booksellers and their suppliers. A new industry
study indicates that the popular market for literature declined,
with the number of purchases dropping for the first time in seven
years despite the growing presence of electronic bookstores and the
easy availability of titles. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LITTLETON, Colo. -- May 2, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-MEDIA,
5-02 -- A student talked with a television interviewer near
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., the site of the shooting
rampage by two students on April 20. The three major broadcast
networks devoted far more time to the Columbine massacre, on their
evening and morning news programs and prime-time news magazines,
than they had ever allocated to any similar shooting rampage.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOLLYWOOD -- May 2, 1999 -- VARIETY-REPORTER, 5-02 --
Anita Busch, left, editor of The Hollywood Reporter, is challenging
Peter Bart, editor of Variety, to dominate Hollywood's information
marketplace. Their trade papers are the battleground in the
industry's 'spin' wars. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
