<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUISIANA-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      05-02 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID DUKE FAILS TO MAKE GOP RUNOFF FOR HOUSE SEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Two figures from the Republican establishment,
former Governor David Treen and state Representative David Vitter,
will face each other in a May 29 runoff after leading a fractious
field of nine candidates jousting for a congressional seat
abandoned by the House speaker-designate, Bob Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   A strong third-place finish by David Duke in Saturday's open
primary also demonstrated that the former Ku Klux Klan leader may
continue to play an active role in Louisiana politics. Although the
48-year-old Duke said earlier that this would be his last race if
he lost, he seemed to reverse himself over the weekend after
claiming nearly 20 percent of the vote. ``I didn't say I wouldn't
run for the rest of my life,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Preelection surveys put Duke, a Republican, in single digits,
but he again drew on the support of followers unwilling to openly
declare their preference for the champion of ``white civil
rights,'' just as he had in races for senator and governor. A
former state representative, Duke has run for office six times in
10 years and mounted a feeble campaign for president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Treen, who is 70 and served nearly four terms in Congress before
his election as a one-term governor in 1979, led all contenders
with 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old Vitter won 22 percent of the turnout to secure a
place in the run-off. He has represented a suburban district in the
state legislature for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Monica, a Republican ophthalmologist who spent $1 million
of her money to fuel an insurgent campaign, finished fourth with 16
percent. Her ads against liberals _ who are virtually nonexistent
in the district _ made her unusual name known throughout the area,
but her attacks on Vitter, who renounced his belief in term limits,
injected a negative note into the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Though Treen led in Saturday's voting, he is not necessarily the
favorite in the run-off, according to John Maginnis, one of the
state's leading political analysts. ``I think Vitter has momentum,
and the people may want to go with a younger guy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Duke was ``helped by the negative tone of the race,'' Maginnis
said, which undercut other candidates and apparently turned
disgruntled voters to Duke. He may seek the seat again, the analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Treen and Vitter vowed to conduct dignified campaigns over
the next four weeks. ``I'm going to run a campaign like I did
before: positive,'' Treen told supporters at a rally Saturday
night. ``David Vitter is a gentleman and I'm pleased to have that
kind of person to run off with.''
</P>
<P>
   Vitter also pledged to run ``a strong, positive campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The two finalists live in Metairie, a suburb of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The 1st Congressional District is composed of a couple of white
neighborhoods in New Orleans, suburban Jefferson Parish, and three
predominantly rural parishes across Lake Pontchartrain from the
city. The district has relatively few black residents and holds a
reputation for staunch conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Duke carried one of the rural parishes, Tangipahoa, and came
within 100 votes of winning Washington, another parish along the
Mississippi border.
</P>
<P>
   The only well-known Democrat in the race, state Representative
Bill Strain from the town of Abita Springs, ran as a supporter of
the right to bear arms. He finished fifth with 11 percent, followed
by Rob Couhig, the owner of New Orleans' Triple-A baseball
franchise, the Zephyrs.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Landry, a self-proclaimed 33-year-old virgin, won 324 of
the 146,000 votes cast. All candidates run in the one open primary,
regardless of party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Sex was a subtext of the election after Livingston resigned
following disclosures that he had carried on extramarital affairs.
As the lion of the Louisiana congressional delegation, Livingston
had spent years loading the district with government contracts. His
announcement, days before Christmas, that he would give up his seat
and his prospective post as House speaker in the midst of the
impeachment crisis stunned his constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Treen offered to step into the breach with the endorsement of
many prominent Republicans and a promise from House Speaker Dennis
Hastert that he would restore seven years of Treen's seniority if
he won back his old seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Vitter and the candidates eliminated Saturday night were
unwilling to let Treen win the job without a challenge, and the
special election turned into a costly, rancorous struggle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
