</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-KRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT SAYS PATRIOTS WILL REMAIN IN MASSACHUSETTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two days after New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft
terminated his record-breaking stadium agreement with Connecticut,
team officials Sunday did something they have not done since the
tug-of-war between the Nutmeg State and Massachusetts began: Say
the Patriots will stay in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to a long future in Massachusetts,'' Patriots
spokesman Stacey James said Sunday, adding: ``The New England
Patriots are not for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement marks the first time since negotiations with
Connecticut began last year that the Patriots have publicly stated
they want to remain here.
</P>
<P>
   Following Kraft's decision Friday to walk away from
Connecticut's stadium package, which sports financing experts
estimated could be worth up to $1 billion over 30 years, angry
Connecticut officials publicly speculated that Kraft was planning
to sell the team.
</P>
<P>
   Because Kraft declined to comment immediately on a counteroffer
by Massachusetts when he terminated his agreement with Connecticut
on Friday, some Bay State fans also worried he was weighing
publicly funded stadium proposals from other states.
</P>
<P>
   The news that Kraft intends to keep the team in Massachusetts
comes as Beacon Hill lawmakers are drafting a bill that would
provide $70 million in state funds for infrastructure at a new
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, who has quarterbacked
efforts to keep the team in Massachusetts, said Senate lawyers are
currently drafting the bill, and he was confident it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``What some thought was a Hail Mary Pass was completed for a
touchdown,'' Birmingham said Sunday night. ``I expect the Senate
will adopt it soon because we passed a virtually identical bill
last year. And since we all negotiated in good faith, I expect we
will all keep our word.''
</P>
<P>
   Both House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran and Governor Paul Cellucci
said last week that they expect the bill will become law before the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Birmingham, Cellucci, and Finneran agreed on a plan
to try to keep the Patriots in Massachusetts. Under the plan, the
state will provide $70 million in improvements to roads, sewers,
walkways, and lighting. Local business leaders and officials of the
National Football League have hailed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's deal was far richer. It gave Kraft a $374 million
stadium package and included other valuable perks such as luxury
and club seat guarantees, making it the most lucrative stadium deal
offered to an owner in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Massachusetts deal requires Kraft to pay up to
$250 million to build a new stadium on land he owns in Foxborough.
He will also pay the state up to $1 million a year to help repay
infrastrucure costs.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Connecticut were stunned by Kraft's decision to pull out
of his deal there. Not only did the Nutmeg State have far more cash
on the table, but the plan had already been adopted by the
Connecticut Legislature, and Governor John Rowland had signed the
contract with Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston deal is still an agreement in principle that has not
been turned into law.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford stadium site was polluted and there were many
delays in preparing it. After consultants hired by the Patriots
told Kraft it was unlikely the state would be able to deliver a new
stadium for the 2002 season, Kraft called Rowland and terminated
his agreement, orally and via fax, on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After the Patriots' decision to pull out of Connecticut, Rowland
threatened that Connecticut would sue both the Krafts and the NFL.
However the governor has since acknowledged Kraft had the right to
cancel the contract without penalty if, in the team's ``sole and
absolute discretion,'' it believed the 2002 deadline could not be
met.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut's case against the NFL is different. As
previously reported, the state is exploring a case based on the
claim that the NFL wrongly interfered by promoting an alternative
offer in Massachusetts. On Friday, NFL officials denied the charge,
noting the decision to leave Connecticut was Kraft's and not the
league's.
</P>
<P>
   Working with members of the Massachusetts business community,
NFL officials helped develop the Bay State's counteroffer last
week. The NFL is also assisting with the marketing of luxury suites
and club seats at a new Foxboro Stadium. To encourage Kraft to stay
in Foxborough, business leaders last week pledged to sell up to $15
million in premium seats over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials are concerned about the downsizing of the league
as teams move from large media markets to smaller cities that offer
more lucrative stadium deals to owners. Since national broadcast
revenues are the lifeblood of the NFL, the league was loth to
exchange Boston's media market, the sixth-largest in the nation,
for Hartford's 27th-largest.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' public statement Sunday appears to undercut a
story in Sunday's Hartford Courant, which quoted an unamed
``Patriots official'' criticizing the Massachusetts deal and saying
the team's management did not know what the future holds.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots Sunday adamantly denied that team officials made
the disparaging remarks about the Massachusetts plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with the tough talks between Rowland and Kraft
Thursday night suggested the critical remarks might have come from
the Patriots' Connecticut lobbyist, Jay Malcynsky, who has close
ties with Rowland. Malcynsky could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
