<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA STAYS ON A ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It would take a miracle for the UCLA baseball team
to win the Pacific-10 championship.
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA playoffs? That is now a possibility. The unranked
Bruins beat rival USC for the second day in a row Sunday, 8-5 in
front of a season-high 1,605 fans at Dedeaux Field.
</P>
<P>
   With seven games left in the regular season, UCLA is 26-26, 10-8
in the Pac-10. No. 15 USC dropped to 30-22 and 15-7 in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins could make an argument for an at-large bid to the
field of 64 with a strong finish, especially with a three-game
series at home against No.5 Stanford on May 14-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our goal, to get to the playoffs,'' said UCLA catcher
Jason Green, who went 3 for 4 with three RBI. ``We have to win them
all, basically. Our backs are against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA won four of six against the Trojans this year. USC lost
despite the return of All-America catcher Eric Munson, who has been
out of action since breaking a bone in his right hand on March 27.
Munson went 0 for 2 with a sacrifice fly as the designated hitter.
He was cleared to play an hour before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have (Munson) in the lineup, we got a little boost,'' USC
shortstop Seth Davidson said. ``But it takes more than one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans needed more than Munson to keep up with the Bruins'
firepower. The middle of UCLA's lineup _ which had been ineffective
the first two games of the series _ came alive Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Scott, Garrett Atkins and Jason Green combined for eight
hits and five RBI against four USC pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, the former Alemany High slugger, hit his team-leading
19th home run in the first inning against USC starter Steve Immel.
</P>
<P>
   When the Trojans rallied with three runs in the fourth to tie
the game at four, Green came back in the fifth with an RBI single
that gave UCLA a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, with the Bruins leading 6-5, Green hit a
bases-empty homer off reliever Steve Smyth over the right-field
fence, his fifth of the season. Atkins had a run-scoring double in
the ninth that completed the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Green was a triple shy of hitting for the cycle for the first
time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first two years here, you would have never thought (Green)
could play college baseball,'' UCLA head coach Gary Adams said.
``He has made himself into a great player. He is the glue to this
ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Green and shortstop Jack Santora are the only seniors on the
roster. Scott and Atkins, who went 3 for 5 with an RBI and two runs
scored, are both sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Roe, a 6-foot-5 left-hander who went eight innings for
UCLA to improve to 3-3, is also a sophomore. As is Chad Cislak, who
came out of the bullpen in the ninth when Roe left the game with
numbness in his pitching hand. He retired the side in order for his
fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Bruins) have grown up,'' USC head coach Mike Gillespie
said. ``They were a young team with a great future and the future
seems to have arrived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
