r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBLICANS-NEWHAMPSH     05-02 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-NEWHAMPSHIRE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFULS KICK OFF CAMPAIGN SEASON IN NEW
HAMPSHIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHSTER, N.H. _ The front-runner was half a continent away in
Texas, but other Republican presidential contenders met for the
first time in Campaign 2000 Sunday night at a kickoff event for the
New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who has dominated early presidential polls,
didn't make it to Manchester, where about 1,500 Republican
loyalists took an early look at the GOP field in a hotel ballroom.
But eight of the 11 hopefuls who have acknowledged White House
ambitions gathered for the first time in the campaign season _ nine
months before New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush maintained a presence without even being there. In a veiled
reference to the front-runner, former Vice President Dan Quayle
urged Republicans to withhold judgment on the GOP field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over,'' Quayle said. ``Take a look at us, size us up
and then ask the tough questions. ... Go with your hearts, not with
the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander told the crowd: ``Our
nomination can't be bought, can't be inherited. It has to be
earned.''
</P>
<P>
   The other speakers were former Transportation and Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole, conservative activist Gary Bauer, Rep.
John Kasich of Ohio, Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire, publisher
Steve Forbes of New Jersey and anti-abortion activist Alan Keyes of
Maryland. Sen. John McCain of Arizona and conservative commentator
Pat Buchanan skipped the event.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who stuck to her habit of roaming into the audience during
her remarks, drew a tepid response by endorsing a handful of
gun-control measures. She said she favors the current bans on
assault weapons and armor-piercing bullets, and would like to see
safety locks for triggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' one man shouted in response.
</P>
<P>
   Although the candidates differed on the details, they were
united in calling for lower taxes. Most also cited the recent
school shootings in Littleton, Colo., as evidence of a moral and
societal decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me begin by asking you a question: Do you believe in
God?'' Bauer ask before recounting the fate of a Colorado student
who was shot after she acknowledged her faith. ``If we do not
remember that America was built on God, that he is the author of
our liberty ... nothing else will matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The dinner's rule prohibited stand-in speakers, but Bush got
some help from Sen. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, who welcomed the
guests to his home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not to be any surrogates, so I won't mention my man,
George W. Bush. He's a good man,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters passed out bags of popcorn at a pre-dinner
reception and dined at tables decorated with Texas-style
centerpieces. Small bales of hay were adorned with fake yellow
roses, a small plastic cowboy hat and the Texas flag, alongside the
flags of New Hampshire and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Russell, one of the leaders of Bush's New Hampshire
campaign, said his decision to stay in Texas until the end of the
legislative session has not dampened enthusiasm for his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to him coming,'' she said of Bush's
planned visit next month. ``They want to see him and hear him and
touch him.''
</P>
<P>
   All the candidates did their best to show grass-roots support,
with varying degrees of success.
</P>
<P>
   A group of young Quayle volunteers stood on a street corner
outside the hotel with a large banner touting the former vice
president. Their enthusiasm began to wane after about a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the potato joke twice already,'' one said glumly.
``That's pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no mistaking the overall mood of Republican
optimisim. A rack of bumper stickers outside the dinner captured
the feeling among Republicans as well as any of the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Miss Barbara Bush,'' one said. Another looked even further
back for a GOP role model: ``Nixon 2000. He's Not As Stiff As Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
