</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.H.-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STAYING AWAY, BUSH IS THE TALK OF NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Maybe he was home washing his hair. Maybe he
was up late with his foreign affairs coaches, refining his position
on Kosovo. Or maybe the governor of Texas was just fixin' to play
possum a little bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his reasons, the only sign of George W. Bush, the early
Republican favorite, at the first formal New Hampshire gathering on
Sunday night of presidential contenders was a booth with bags of
fresh popcorn and a faux marquee that promised: ``Coming
attractions: Governor George W. Bush. Coming this summer to a
neighborhood near you.'' Bush has vowed not to venture far beyond
Austin, Texas, until after the Legislature adjourns on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Like a play that begins with everyone obsessively talking about
a character that has not yet appeared, the cocktail party chatter
under a big tent revolved around the candidate who was not at the
state Republican Party's extravaganza. Instead of peddling their
own positions, Bush's rivals in this state that traditionally holds
the first primary were forced to compete over who could give the
snappiest, or snarkiest, answer about the meaning of the governor's
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to hear that Texas is in such difficult shape that
the Legislature has to convene on Sunday night,'' said former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the publisher, said, ``If you don't show up for a
baseball game, the other side is not going to shed any tears.''
</P>
<P>
   One candidate who did not make light of Bush's absence was Gary
Bauer, the social conservative, who said, ``It is sort of an
unusual phenomenon when the front-runner continues to avoid all
these important events.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the big draw, the dinner night marked the first
time that (almost) all the Republican contenders appeared
side-by-side. Others who showed were Elizabeth Dole, the former
president of the American Red Cross; former Vice President Dan
Quayle; Rep. John R. Kasich of Ohio; Sen. Robert C. Smith of New
Hampshire, and Alan Keyes, a talk show host and former diplomat.
Two others besides Bush did not appear, citing previous
commitments: Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Patrick J. Buchanan,
the conservative commentator.
</P>
<P>
   In their speeches, rationed to seven minutes each, the
candidates did their best to try to stand out _ and persuade the
audience of 1,200 of the party faithful that they were presidential
timber.
</P>
<P>
   Several spoke about the killings two weeks ago of 14 high school
students and one teacher in Littleton, Colo. Mrs. Dole, wading into
the audience with a microphone, risked offending gun owners _ and
drew scattered boos on Sunday night _ by calling for tougher
regulations in the wake of the deaths. She called for retaining the
ban on assault weapons, something her husband, former Sen. Bob
Dole, opposed in his bid for president in 1996. Mrs. Dole also said
she would favor banning armor-piercing bullets, would support
safety locks on guns and the financing to enforce instant
background checks on gun sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you need an AK-47 to defend your family,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, linking the killings to his crusade for values, asked,
``Who has been fighting for your values and for your families for
over 20 years?'' He went on: ``Littleton, Colo., reminds us once
again that values matter most. You ever feel that perhaps we are
slipping away from being a God-fearing nation to a nation that
fears the next killing at our local school? My friends, this
country needs a spiritual renewal.''
</P>
<P>
   Imploring the audience to look beyond Bush's high poll numbers,
Quayle added, ``Go with your hearts _ not the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander recalled that in his childhood children carried
pocketknives for whittling, not to harm each other. ``We had
parents and other adults deeply involved in our lives as
children,'' he said. ``It's time to put our government and culture
back on the side of parents raising children.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer pledged to ``devote every waking hour of my presidency to
make sure that every American child is welcome into the world and
protected by the law.'' Children, he said, ``will never have to die
for their faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the attention given to Littleton, most of the
behind-the-scenes talk on Sunday night was about the man who was
not on stage but who leads his closest rival, Mrs. Dole, by at
least two-to-one in most polls: Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the degree to which Bush was overwhelming the early
field, Jim Nicholson, the national party chairman, said, ``The
front-runner is probably a matter of interpretation.'' But
Nicholson was perhaps the only person here who was not ready to
concede Bush's dominance.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner, besides an important vehicle for the state party to
raise money at $150 a head (the gross take was roughly $170,000),
was a way for the candidates to draw precious notice from the
press, and therefore persuade donors of their viability.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the ballroom in the Holiday Inn in downtown
Manchester, Mike Murphy, a Republican strategist who is not
formally backing any candidate, noted how all candidates were
positioning themselves should Bush falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would call this a meeting of the upset caucus,'' Murphy
said.
</P>
<P>
   But even Murphy conceded that the wisest course _ at least for
now _ was for Bush to sit on his lead as long as he could. ``The
people with something to gain are here,'' Murphy said. ``The person
with something to lose is not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
