<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SHUT OUT GIANTS, 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Masato Yoshii glanced down to his black shoes once,
then twice, and only then began his windup. He repeated this
several times on Sunday, a new ritual that yielded tremendous
results.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after Mets Manager Bobby Valentine gave Yoshii
videotape proof that a move toward the first-base side of the
pitching rubber _ a move Valentine had recommended in spring
training _ had caused Yoshii's pitches, especially his sinker, to
move too much, Yoshii inched back to his more natural spot on
Sunday, the one from which he had pitched all of his career.
</P>
<P>
   With the shift back toward third base, Yoshii slid into his
comfort zone, pitching six shutout innings in a taut 2-0 defeat of
the San Francisco Giants that came on two unearned runs in the
eighth. And he gave the Mets a boost in what had been a
deteriorating spot in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days ago, Mets front-office personnel suggested that
Yoshii, who was 1-3 with a 7.52 earned run average, could land in
the minor leagues with a poor start on Sunday. Instead, relying
more on his fastball than usual, Yoshii threw 68 pitches, 43 for
strikes, and allowed just three hits and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, Dennis Cook (who got the victory to go 5-0) and John
Franco combined for a seven-hit shutout, although Franco injected a
dose of angst by loading the bases in the ninth before picking up
his ninth save with a game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yoshii was what we were hoping for,'' Valentine said. ``He
made quality pitches, and he pitched in an extremely
pressure-filled situation. He knew exactly what was on the line. A
lot of people were waiting to cut off his head, and I'm extremely
proud of him. His pitches were down in the zone. Rather than
kicking myself because of something I did in the past, we said,
`Let's not worry about it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii said, ``The bottom line is I was able to throw the ball
in the lower half of the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   While Yoshii stymied the Giants, San Francisco's starter, Kirk
Rueter, was baffling the Mets; through five innings, they had just
one hit. That forced Valentine to pinch-hit for Yoshii to lead off
the bottom of the sixth. Roger Cedeno led off with a single but was
stranded. The seventh yielded nothing, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, the Mets came close to wasting Yoshii's effort.
With Cook on the mound, Rich Aurilia hit a ground single into left
center and took second when it was mishandled by Rickey Henderson,
who had earlier dropped a Stan Javier high fly that was caught in
the gusty winds. As Henderson tried to recover, his left foot
slipped and he went down hard on his right knee. Valentine said
later it was just a slight strain of a knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   With Shawn Estes pinch-running for Aurilia, Ramon Martinez
pinch-hit for Rueter. He struck out, and Cook got Marvin Benard to
pop up to end the inning. But Giants Manager Dusty Baker's decision
to replace Aurilia with Martinez at shortstop would haunt him
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Giants reliever John Johnstone, who entered the eighth coming
off 12 straight scoreless innings, had two outs when Matt Franco,
hitting for Cook, singled to left. Henderson, who arrived at the
plate to scattered boos, sent a high fly to short left field. With
the outfield playing deep, Martinez backed up while Javier and
Benard closed in. The wind _ whipping enough to remind the Giants
of their notorious home field _ sent the ball away from Martinez as
he reached for it. It bounced off his glove for an error, and
Franco, running hard, scored from first.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball gets above the stadium, it doesn't end up where
it started off,'' Franco said. ``When you see major league players
struggling like that, you know the conditions are rough.''
</P>
<P>
   After Johnstone walked Edgardo Alfonzo on four pitches, he was
replaced by Rich Rodriguez to face John Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud got his second hit of the day, a single to left field
that scored Henderson. Mike Piazza then hit with two out and
runners at the corners and provided a momentary thrill with a high,
deep blast. But the wind, blowing straight in toward home plate
most of the day, kept the ball on the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   Even John Franco's scare _ he loaded the bases with one out but
got Charlie Hayes to hit into a double play to end the game _ could
not obscure the impressive play of the Mets (16-9) in this series.
With their fifth victory in a row, they swept a team that had come
in with a six-game winning streak and the best record in the
National League even without Barry Bonds. Now, however, the Giants
are 16-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were struggling to get the big hit, but now the bats are
coming around,'' Matt Franco said. ``We got lucky to win, but we'll
take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
