<SLUG> BC-SALMON-RECOVERY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEUD ARISES OVER WHO WILL OVERSEE, DISPENSE STATE SALMON FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, Wash. _ Just a few hundred yards from the fury of the
swollen Skykomish River, John Sayre waded easily through the quiet
water of a back channel, checking the contents of an
hourglass-shaped fish trap.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year ago, the channel was a weed-choked ditch, cut off
from the Skykomish for 60 years by a man-made dike. Now it teems
with young salmon _ coho, chum, pink. Sayre dipped a net into the
trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the fuss is all about,'' he said, pulling out a
tiny, silver fish no bigger than his smallest finger. ``A wild
chinook.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebirth of this channel, called the Haskell Slough, is the
work of a coalition of community and tribal groups, landowners and
volunteers. By any measure, it seems an undisputed success. But it
is, in fact, at the heart of an intense dispute over the state's
salmon recovery strategy.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is who will control the tens of millions of dollars in
salmon money and where it will be spent. Sayre, director of
Northwest Chinook Recovery, and others active in grassroots efforts
to save the salmon say the administration of Gov. Gary Locke has
pushed them aside, directing money to the natural resources
bureaucracy and away from projects like the Haskell Slough.
</P>
<P>
   County, local and tribal governments have raised concerns that
they, too, may be left out. So have lawmakers. Sen. Ken Jacobsen,
chairman of the Senate Natural Resources Committee, says too much
power is concentrated in executive agencies _ and ultimately Locke
_ and too many decisions are made in closed Cabinet meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor wants us to be a rubber stamp for his plans,''
said Jacobsen, a Democrat from Seattle. ``We need to get something
so people can say, `We're part of the deal.'''
</P>
<P>
   What that deal might be remains unclear. But unless the governor
and lawmakers can reach agreement on who will oversee $112 million
for restoring salmon habitat, the entire grant program could be in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers on whether to leave funding decisions in the
hands of natural resources and transportation officials, known as
the Interagency Review Team, or give that authority to an
independent citizens board. Locke and the House favor the agencies;
the Senate wants an independent board.
</P>
<P>
   The issue wasn't resolved before the Legislature adjourned.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem:
</P>
<P>
   - The Legislature failed to pass authorizing legislation
establishing an independent board to oversee salmon restoration
projects.
</P>
<P>
   - The capital budget, however, includes a section creating a
salmon recovery fund and an independent board to manage it.
</P>
<P>
   - Locke says he will veto the independent board provision.
</P>
<P>
   - If he vetoes that section, he also would kill the salmon
fund's $112 million appropriation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the risk, Locke plans to go through with the veto in the
hope of finding a compromise during next week's special legislative
session, said Sandi Snell, spokeswoman for the Governor's Salmon
Recovery Office. One proposal would keep decision-making in an
interagency review team, but create an advisory board to represent
the many interests at stake in salmon recovery policy.
</P>
<P>
   Locke, Snell said, believes the agencies have the statewide
perspective and technical support needed to make sure money goes
where it can do the most good. Science, not clout, population or
connections, should determine spending, Snell said.
</P>
<P>
   Locke, in a recent session with the Seattle Post-Intelligencer's
editorial board, said he worries that an independent board would be
insufficiently accountable, and too susceptible to political
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got concerns,'' Locke said. ``I've never believed in pork
barrel politics. I've never believed we should distribute the
dollars based on per capita, or based on the number of miles of
streams.''
</P>
<P>
   But many question whether agency officials can be honest
brokers. More often than not, critics say, state agencies will
choose to put money into state programs and staff, instead of
local, tribal or volunteer efforts.
</P>
<P>
   An independent board would be accountable in ways bureaucratic
decision-makers are not, Jacobsen said. Its members would be
subject to Senate confirmation, and its proceedings subject to the
state's open meeting law, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of (an independent) board,'' said Bill Clarke, a
lobbyist for the Washington Association of Realtors, ``is you have
a neutral party to look at where the money is being spent, and
whether it's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer and community groups are particularly concerned. They
have, at times, had adversarial relations with state agencies. And
they worry they'll have difficulty competing for salmon money,
regardless of who makes the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike cities, counties or state agencies, the groups have
neither the money nor staff to complete complex, technical
applications, said Robert Anderson, chairman of the Citizens
Advisory Board for Regional Fisheries Enhancement Groups. Volunteer
groups have called _ so far unsuccessfully _ for more money and a
bigger role for the state's 12 Regional Fisheries Enhancement
Groups, which coordinate community-based salmon restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me five days notice, and I can put 200 people on the
ground any place in the state,'' Anderson said. ``But large, highly
staffed entities are going to be much better able to put together
applications. How can little, community-based programs compete with
King County?''
</P>
<P>
   Snell, the Locke spokeswoman, said the agency review process has
been fair, open and based on science. Rep. Debbie Regala, co-chair
of the House Natural Resources Committee, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have criteria about what type of projects should be funded,
and they have been nominated at the local level,'' said Regala,
D-Tacoma, cautioning against making big changes in the process.
``We need to take a deep breath, and really think how we want to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The process delivered about $200,000 in state money to the
Haskell Slough project in Monroe. But the key, said Sayre, of
Northwest Chinook Recovery, was the community groups' ability to
mobilize volunteers and persuade landowners to go along with the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The channel stretches some three-and-a-half miles, meandering
along country road and pasture, through a series of ponds and
properties, including Dale Reiner's 300-acre cattle ranch. Reiner,
whose great-grandfather settled the homestead, recalled crossing
the channel recently, when the sun hit the water just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a big school of fish, as big as the hood of (a
pickup) truck,'' Reiner said, his voice rising with enthusiasm.
``It's exciting to have these fish in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayre listened to Reiner with special satisfaction. Sayre has
spent the past 13 years working to save the salmon, measuring
success in the contents of fish traps, and the reactions of people
like Reiner.
</P>
<P>
   He thought a moment about the debate in Olympia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis,'' he said, ``no matter what the
process, you have to end up with a bucket-full of fish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
