<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES GET RELIEF FROM UNLIKELY SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Don Zimmer is an equal opportunity manager. If you
do the job, he's going to use you, and it doesn't matter if you
have a multiyear contract or you are established with the Yankees,
or, like reliever Jason Grimsley, you are a journeyman.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley went to spring training nearly three years removed from
his last appearance in the major leagues, guessing he would open
the season in the minors. Because he has pitched well, and Jeff
Nelson and Mike Stanton have struggled, however, Zimmer is relying
on Grimsley more. He pitched two scoreless and pivotal innings on
Sunday in the Yankees' 9-8 victory over Kansas City, a crazy game
nearly given away by Hideki Irabu in the early innings and taken
back when Bernie Williams smashed a two-run home run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it,'' said Zimmer, acknowledging the ragged play in
a contest that lasted 3 hours 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The path that has led Grimsley to the Yankees has zigged and
zagged: When he was 12, he lost the big toe of his left foot while
running a motorcycle over a stump, and because of a broken wrist
and a sore shoulder, he was unable to play baseball in his last two
years of high school. He impressed the Philadelphia Phillies in a
tryout camp and signed his first professional contract _ as a
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   But Grimsley became a pitcher, and as a hard thrower he
repeatedly got chances to establish himself as a starter for the
Phillies and then the Cleveland Indians and California Angels, and
repeatedly, his control failed him. He walked 74 batters in 1301/3
innings with California in 1996 and did not pitch in the majors
again until this year.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley spent the '97 and '98 seasons in the minors, developing
his skills as a reliever; maybe, he suggested on Sunday, it just
took him a long time to find his niche, in the bullpen. He could
enter a game and stalk hitters with his hard, sinking fastball,
rather than refining three or four pitches. Grimsley had a 3.76
earned run average last year for Class AAA Buffalo, and one day,
Billy Connors _ the Yankees' director of player personnel _ saw him
pitch and was impressed with his stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So Grimsley signed with the Yankees in January, with a subtle
strategy: He figured the Yankees' bullpen was so good and so
established that he would be sent to Class AAA out of spring
training and would get an extended opportunity to prove himself in
the minors.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees' bullpen has been unstable: Darren Holmes,
unreliable in pressure situations last season, was traded at the
end of spring training, and Grimsley made the team. Now Nelson (11
walks in 101/3 innings) and Stanton (12 base runners in five and
one-third innings) are struggling. So Zimmer has turned to
Grimsley: For example, the right-hander assumed an 8-4 lead in the
eighth Saturday and pitched one and two-thirds scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Irabu was horrible, giving up six runs in four and
one-third innings, and he was relieved by Dan Naulty with the
Yankees losing, 6-2. But as is their habit, the Yankees roared
back, scoring five runs in the sixth to take a 7-6 edge.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson took over in the bottom half of that inning, walking two
with two out, and he escaped with the lead only when Chuck
Knoblauch charged a ground ball hit near second and, using only his
glove, flipped the ball to shortstop Derek Jeter for an
inning-ending force. ``Just instincts, really,'' Knoblauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer jumped up off the bench on his two bad knees to
congratulate Knoblauch coming off the field. Nelson, however,
descended into further trouble in the seventh, walking the leadoff
hitter Mike Sweeney and giving up a single to Larry Sutton. First
and third and nobody out, and Zimmer turned to Grimsley, hoping for
a ground ball and a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley, firing hard sinkers inside, got the first out on a
foul pop _ he has retired the first hitter he has faced in all
seven of his appearances _ and then struck out Chad Kreuter. He
jammed Carlos Febles with a fastball, but Febles managed to roll
the ball through the left side of the infield, a game-tying single.
Zimmer shrugged while recalling the hit later: unlucky.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley shut out the Royals in the eighth inning, however, and
in the ninth, Paul O'Neill beat out an infield hit. Williams was
next, fighting an odd slump. He is getting his share of hits, but
because his swing is out of sorts _ he has been rushing at the ball
and pulling out his front shoulder too soon _ he has not been
hitting with any power. He had hit only one home run.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Williams stayed back and waited. Jose Santiago threw
a high fastball, and Williams whacked it to dead center field, the
ball carrying far and landing on the grassy bank beyond the fence,
sinking into the hillside like a golf ball buried in a sand trap.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the game, Williams had slid headlong into first base
and hit the bag with his midsection, and it was all he could do to
stand and smile at his distress. But the lingering pain went away
as soon as the ball carried over the wall in the ninth inning, and
Williams pranced around the bases on his toes, joyfully.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley was the winning pitcher to move to 2-0, and he will get
more chances, Zimmer said. ``You get a guy hot in the bullpen,''
Zimmer said, ``and that's who you go to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
