</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JAGR `SMELLED A CHANCE' FOR THE WINNING GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS) 
(rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Two weeks ago, Wayne Gretzky passed the torch to
Jaromir Jagr, and Sunday Jagr burned the Devils with it.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbled by a pulled groin muscle, Jagr had missed the past four
games of this opening round Stanley Cup playoff, but with the
Penguins one defeat from elimination, he returned for Sunday's
sixth game. And with the Devils leading, 2-1, the Penguins were
less than three minutes from elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Jagr scored the tying goal, then in the overtime he
scored the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we think we've run out of things that he's done that are
pretty incredible,'' said Kevin Constantine, the Penguins' coach,
``he does something incredible again.''
</P>
<P>
   But in any sport, that's what great players do. That's why they
are great players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys, he can be out and come back and play
great,'' defenseman Bobby Dollas was saying now in the Penguins
dressing room. ``I've played with Paul Kariya, Teemu Selanne, Steve
Yzerman, Sergei Fedorov, but he's the best player in the league.
Hands down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils agree. So does just about everybody else in the NHL.
With 127 points, including 44 goals, the 6-foot-2-inch Jagr led the
league in scoring during the recent season, and he is expected to
be voted the Hart trophy as its most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Gretzky passed him the torch.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Jaromir Jagr did Sunday what other great hockey
players such as Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard, Gordie Howe, Bobby Orr,
Wayne Gretzky, Mark Messier and Mario Lemieux often did in the
playoffs _ score a theatrical goal (or two) when their teams needed
that goal (or two).
</P>
<P>
   And with those two goals, the 27-year-old right wing from the
Czech Republic created Tuesday night's decisive seventh game at the
Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tying goal,'' Jagr, in a Penguins warm-up suit, was saying
now, ``German Titov made a good play and beat the guy outside, then
he threw it to the net and I just hit the puck, and it was kind of
a lucky goal that just went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, Jagr had seemed to be skating carefully,
tenderly so as not to aggravate his groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `I cannot skate very well up and down,''' he
said. ``I asked my teammates to just dump it in and try to play it
in the corners. That's where I can play and it doesn't hurt me at
all. But if I go long strides, it kind of hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   During his 29 minutes 35 seconds on the ice, had he skated full
speed at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the last play,'' Jagr replied, smiling, ``because I
smelled a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He drilled a point-blank shot past goaltender Martin Brodeur for
the third overtime playoff goal of his career. Two weeks earlier,
he had scored the overtime goal in the season finale against the
Rangers that momentarily silenced Gretzky's great goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won a lot of games during the season in overtime,'' Jagr
said, alluding to a Penguins-record seven overtime victories.
``That's what we said in the room before the overtime. Play a smart
game and skate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagr, however, couldn't skate with the sudden bursts of speed
that have terrified goaltenders throughout his career. He was
wearing what he called ``new pants to hold my leg a little
tighter.'' And when he was asked to evaluate his skating ability on
a scale of 100 percent, he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the corners 90, skating back and forth 60,'' he said. ``But
there are days when 60 is better than 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was one of those days in what, if the Devils win Sunday
night, could have been the Penguins' last game in Civic Arena for
this bankrupt franchise. Lemieux is hoping to obtain the franchise,
but a bankruptcy court judge will make that decision. If Lemieux's
bid fails, the franchise may be dissolved or go elsewhere, perhaps
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this game is going to save the team,'' Jagr
said, ``but the city and the people owe Mario a lot. He was the guy
that made hockey here.''
</P>
<P>
   But the possibility of Sunday's game being the last for the
Penguins in what is known here as the Igloo contributed to Jagr's
decision to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I wanted to play the game,'' he said. ``I wanted to
hear the fans. I knew they would be crazy like they always are. I
wanted to hear them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe for the last time. And if it was the last time, all those
Penguins fans will always remember how Jaromir Jagr's torch burned
the Devils.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
