<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-N     05-02 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGR PLAYS WITH AN INJURY, BUT IT'S THE DEVILS WHO FEEL HIS PAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (See also HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN) 
(rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH, Pa. _ On the brink of capturing their opening round
Stanley Cup playoff series, the New Jersey Devils were victimized
by the Pittsburgh Penguins' star Jaromir Jagr Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Making an electrifying return from a groin injury that had kept
him out of four previous games, Jagr tied the score with a goal
late in the third period and sent the Devils to a 3-2 defeat with
another goal in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr took advantage of the Devils' conservative play after they
had a one-goal lead and enabled the Penguins to force a seventh and
deciding game in New Jersey Tuesday night. The loss was the sixth
overtime setback in a row in playoff action for the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little stunned and shocked,'' Devils defenseman Brad
Bombardir said, ``but this is playoff hockey and things like this
happen when you have the best player in the league playing. We can
take the blame, though, because we became a little conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik and Brian Rolston were the severest critics of the
Devils' strategy after they took a 2-1 lead at 4 minutes 34 seconds
of the third period on Scott Niedermayer's first goal in the
playoffs. The Devils kept banging the puck out of their defensive
zone instead maintaining control through the neutral zone. As a
result, most of the action took place near goalie Martin Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got the lead,'' Holik said, ``we didn't keep playing
the way we gained the lead. This team is not good when it sits back
like this. Our game is to control the puck and forecheck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, we held back too early,'' Rolston said. ``Now
we're in a do-or-die situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils paid tribute to Jagr, the NHL's leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best player in the league, and you have to respect
him,'' Holik said.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr's presence lifted the Penguins and the crowd at Civic
Arena, which was rocking when it learned that Jagr had not been
scratched.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr tied the game with 2:12 left in regulation when he pounced
on a loose puck from a shot by German Titov and jammed it into the
net from Brodeur's left doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely my responsibility to not let that guy beat me
to the net,'' said Niedermayer, who slipped on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr's winner came at 8:49 of overtime, from near the bottom of
the right circle, when he one-timed Martin Straka's pass from the
other side after Straka got around Niedermayer, who had fallen
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just unbelievable,'' his teammate Brad Werenka said of
Jagr's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr was hobbled so badly that he could barely stand up on
skates before the Devils' 4-3 victory Friday in Game 5. He talked
pessimistically Saturday of playing in Sunday's game, but became
more encouraged after being fitted with some scuba-diver's pants
that provided more support and partly eased the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good,'' Jagr said. ``The new pants held my leg a
little tighter and I felt much better when I skated. That's when I
decided to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Brylin opened the scoring at 12:04 of the first period,
scoring on a backhander from the lower slot off Holik's one-handed
pass from behind the net. But Straka tied it for Pittsburgh when he
was left alone at the side of the net and directed Alexei Kovalev's
pass by Brodeur at 6:44 of the second.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer broke the tie when Jason Arnott's shot hit him in
the right leg and bounced in past Tom Barrasso.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur faced 28 shots, four in the overtime, and could not be
blamed for Jagr's goals. Brodeur's best moments came in the third
period while the Devils were protecting their lead.
</P>
<P>
   Devils coach Robbie Ftorek said that he was pleased with
Brodeur's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with emotion,'' Ftorek said, ``but we also iced the
puck an awful lot. We like to control the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' captain, Scott Stevens, admitted that his team did
not always get the matchup it wanted against Jagr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them the opportunities to make plays,'' Stevens said.
``I think we started too early in the third to sit back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston, Ftorek and the rest of the Devils, said that they were
not surprised that Jagr made his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were facing elimination,'' Rolston said. ``I think he had
to play. Every time he plays against us, he does well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we didn't take advantage of our chance,''
Devils defenseman Ken Daneyko said. ``Jagr came up with some big
plays for them, but I like the fact that we play the last game at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's Game 7,'' Ftorek said of Tuesday's
deciding game. ``It's now Game 1.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
