<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT     05-02 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS GIVE KNICKS A RUDE AWAKENING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The New York Knicks spent the past week flirting
with everyone, winking and smiling and crooking their finger. But
after all the attention Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell had
attracted for their recent flash of style, after all the Knicks had
done to pitch themselves as a fun night out, they were exposed by
the Indiana Pacers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As undisciplined as toddlers, the Knicks thumbed their nose at
their coach's strategy, ignored their assignments and reverted to
the kind of lazy defense that left Indiana's Chris Mullin drifting
alone in 3-point territory.
</P>
<P>
   This carelessness when they were trying to seal a playoff spot
was as surprising as the ease with which the Pacers overwhelmed
them in a 94-71 loss at Market Square Arena. The Knicks (25-23) did
move closer to clinching the final Eastern Conference playoff spot,
but only because the Charlotte Hornets lost later Sunday night in
Miami. The Knicks, who hold the tie breaker against the Hornets,
lead them by one game with two games to play and can clinch the
playoff spot with a victory against Boston on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continually forget who we are as a team,'' Coach Jeff Van
Gundy said. ``When we play well, we're a defensive team first. And
we pass as the first option and not as a last option. We were
trying to hit home runs by ourselves. And we were making it up
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a departure from the kind of unselfish offense and
buttoned-down defense they had played to win four of their previous
five games. Throwing away their map, the Knicks lost Mullin while
he made three 3-pointers in the third quarter. When Charlie Ward
was slow to find him twice, Mullin hit back-to-back 3-pointers to
help turn the Pacers' 14-point halftime lead into a gaudy 22-point
lead just three minutes into the third quarter. A timeout was
called by a furious Van Gundy, but he made no substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than take out all five of them, which you could do,''
Van Gundy said, then paused. ``You can't just pinpoint one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end, an assortment of Knicks, from Larry Johnson to
Sprewell, had left the Pacers open to hit 8 of 16 3-pointers. Amid
the flurry, Mullin hit all four of his attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Mullin is a great shooter, and we left him open,'' Van
Gundy said. ``It was like target practice for him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullin aimed and scored a game-high 20 points, so Reggie Miller
did not have to. The pinstripe-thin Miller is usually the one who
wiggles free and dashes the Knicks' hopes, but he scored just 6
points on 2-for-8 shooting. His sluggish counterpart, Houston,
could not take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   The pixie dust on the duo of Houston and Sprewell _ who had
seemed to get over their awkward partnership and synchronize
themselves this past week _ was brushed off by a more physical
Pacers defense. After finding each other over the last week and
setting off the kind of ball movement that leads to open shots,
Sprewell finished Sunday's game with two assists and Houston had
one for a team that had just 11 for the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was an example of how fragile and unpredictable the Knicks'
success this season has been. One glitch in the system, and the
Knicks ended the game shooting 33.7 percent while the Pacers shot
50 percent. Those crazy, unorthodox runners by Sprewell were not
falling over the windmill arms of Derrick McKey, and Houston's
drives were going nowhere with Dale Davis and Rik Smits patrolling
the paint. There was no one to bail Houston and Sprewell out while
they combined to make just 11 of 34 shots from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never found a rhythm as a whole,'' Houston said. ``When
we're moving and passing, we shoot well. We didn't today. I don't
know if that has anything to do with Patrick being there or not.''
</P>
<P>
   As a futile fourth quarter unfolded, Patrick Ewing had cut off
the thick ankle tape around his left Achilles' tendon and was
sitting on the bench in his socks. He had been lifted by Van Gundy
with the Knicks trailing by 22 points eight minutes into the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised he took me out,'' Ewing said. ``But that's
part of the game, I guess. I didn't say anything. You have to wait
until your number is called.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was best to save Ewing for the Knicks' increasingly
important game against Boston on Monday night at Madison Square
Garden. Maybe it was best to save him from himself. Although he
unearthed enough jumpers to score 15 points on 6-of-14 shooting
from the field, he was practically helpless on defense. Twice in
the first half, the lumbering Smits drove right by an immobile
Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   At times, he seemed like a ball and chain for the kind of
fast-paced style Sprewell and company had been able to show of late
in his absence. Not knowing when and if Ewing will be able to play
from game to game is also something that toys with the team's
mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   But Ewing's 24 minutes of floor time was hardly the reason for
the Knicks' inexplicable lack of discipline in a game in which they
needed to focus more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why this happened,'' Sprewell said. ``No one can
put a finger on it. We didn't execute as well as we should have. I
thought we tried to stick to what was drawn up, but we missed
coverages and blew assignments. It was disappointing, not
surprising, but more disappointing. We needed this game, and we
couldn't get it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
