<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-02 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE KNICKS' PROBLEM WILL NOT JUST GO AWAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ No less a legend than Larry Bird knows how it
feels to be Patrick Ewing. Bird has been there, the center of
attention who is accomplished but aging, injured and anxious,
determined yet tentative.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of his own brilliant career, Bird was exactly where
Ewing is now, day to day, in and out, the sometimes star. As
painful as this was for the Boston Celtics, Bird said it was worse
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're off for a week, without really practicing,
everything feels different,'' Bird said Sunday after his Indiana
Pacers toyed with Ewing and the Knicks, 94-71, at Market Square
Arena. ``You're fighting the game instead of it being fluid. Your
legs aren't there. You're hands aren't there. The lighting feels
brighter.''
</P>
<P>
   When the arena lights blind your star, the result can be a messy
crash and a multiplayer pileup. After Ewing informed his coach,
Jeff Van Gundy, that he was ready to go on his aching left
Achilles' tendon, the Knicks went out and collectively looked very
much like the eighth-seeded playoff team they still have an
excellent chance of being. They shot 33 percent from the field.
They had 11 assists to the Pacers' 24. The Pacers, never
threatened, needed not a single jump shot from Reggie Miller, their
own leading man.
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair to blame this on Ewing, but beyond this
particular game it would also be naive to ignore the crimp that his
uncertain availability puts into the most modest of the Knicks'
post-season plans. With the `A' game they brought Sunday, the
Pacers are better than the Knicks, but with Ewing back as an
offensive hub, as their leading scorer, the Knicks were simply not
the best team they can be.
</P>
<P>
   After 80 points in three games, Latrell Sprewell cooled off.
Allan Houston missed 12 of 17 shots. Marcus Camby and Chris Dudley
did little defensive intimidating with their reduced minutes. The
power forward, Kurt Thomas, shot 1 for 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing had a statistically rewarding first half, including 13 of
his 15 points. The Knicks also finished the half with the grand
total of 32, discombobulated and down by 14. Late in the half, on
successive possessions, Rik Smits blew by an immobile Ewing for
dunks _ first from the right baseline, then straight out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to settle for the jump shot, but I saw him coming out
at me,'' Smits said. ``I've been in the same boat as him with bad
feet, and I know how tough it is to run out at a guy and recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Checketts, the acting team president, should be terrified
to know that the typically glacial Smits added that Ewing looked
``a little slow.'' Ewing was benched after he missed his first four
shots of the third quarter as the Knicks fell behind by 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the early 1990s, Bird's status was more closely
scrutinized than the Celtics' daily price on the New York Stock
Exchange. He had aching feet, a cranky back and Michael Jordan
coming fast to take over the sport. Bird desperately hung on for
``one more'' and played when he could. Psychologically, young
players like Dee Brown and Reggie Lewis had no choice but to share
his pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, 'cause you know Patrick wants to do his best,''
Bird said. ``The other guys have got to make the adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   This is easy for Bird to say. For one thing, not a soul in
Boston, where he had won three championships, would dare to
question him slipping in and out of his rightful role. For another,
Bird, a visionary passer, made everyone better by just showing up.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, when Sprewell first entered the game Sunday, Chris
Mullin was guarding him, a flagrant mismatch. Good teams invariably
seize such chances to punish a coach for trying to get away with
even one possession. Ewing, catching the ball on the left side,
turned and faced Smits, offered a series of head and shoulder
fakes, drove the lane and missed.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, itching to get active after almost eight minutes on
the bench, shook his head and ran downcourt.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks would have lost Sunday no matter how they played it,
but the Ewing Watch is wearing on them. Van Gundy, the most
passionate of Ewing loyalists, had to admit as much. Before the
game, he started to call the situation ``disruptive,'' stopped
himself at ``disrupt'' and changed it to ``a little disruptive.''
Then he talked about how much Ewing's lack of practice, as much as
his injury, has an impact on his play and affects potential
matchups and players' minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more for them to think about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a touchy subject, Ewing as the go-to player who may not go,
more so than last season, with the explosive Sprewell around. It is
a minefield the organization has never made much effort to defuse.
At this point, still believing he is in position to make the calls,
even on who coaches, it is unlikely that Ewing is going to take a
more realistic look at himself.
</P>
<P>
   This problem does not go away if the Knicks make the playoffs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
