<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ORIOLES-CUBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: CASTRO TAKES BREAK FROM DAY JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Cubans were not in the building at the time they
were originally advertised to be there, so the most compelling
issue of the day was moot. The Cuban national baseball team was
delayed in arriving here, so the evening workout that was to be
closed to everyone else was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The burning question had been whether the Cubans' leader and
chief strategist would be at Camden Yards, overseeing the secret
workout.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro, who apparently has harbored a long latent,
deep-seated desire to be the Latin George Steinbrenner, was
instrumental in preparing the Cubans for their game against the
Baltimore Orioles Monday night. A report out of Cuba last week said
that Castro had been attending the Cubans' daily workouts and had
been involved in ``all aspects of the team's tactical and
logistical preparations'' for the second game of the two-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first game, in Havana on March 28, Castro had limited
himself to a pregame visit to the team's dugout, where all the
players gathered around and heard his words of encouragement. They
were not quite enough, however, because as well as they played, the
Cubans lost to the Orioles, 3-2, in 11 innings. Castro obviously
decided more of his input was needed to gain a split of the
controversial series.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, however, might have overplayed his hand. When the
Orioles played in Havana, they had not yet begun the season and
were an unknown quantity apart from the fact that they were one of
the highest-paid teams in the major leagues. They completed their
fourth week of the season Sunday and boy, are they known now. They
have by far the worst record in the American League, making them,
for now, the worst overpaid team in baseball history. If this is
capitalism, the Cubans really don't need it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Havana game was a bad omen for the Orioles (Scott
Erickson was the starting pitcher in that game and hasn't won yet
in five decisions) and laid the groundwork for their disastrous
start that apparently has the general manager, Frank Wren, as well
as the manager, Ray Miller, in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Angelos, the owner, said recently that Miller wasn't going
to be fired, though how much time and how many games that position
will cover Angelos didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening cannot be attributed to his lack of
managerial competence,'' is what Angelos did say. Because Angelos
handpicked Miller to replace Davy Johnson, who was forced out after
the 1997 season, the owner's wrath may settle on Wren, the team's
first-year general manager, whom Angelos can blame for putting this
mess together. An executive of another team said Sunday that word
was circulating along the baseball grapevine that Wren might soon
be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Castro did not fire his manager for losing the game in Havana.
Alfonso Urquiola will be in Cuba's dugout again Monday night.
However, nine of the players he had for the first game will not be
there with him. Neither will German Mesa, who is arguably the best
shortstop in Cuban history.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa's absence from the 25-man roster is not surprising. When he
was reinstated this past Cuban league season from suspension, which
he shared with the Yankees' Orlando Hernandez, it was said that he
would not be allowed to play games in other countries. That status
either was extended punishment for the thoughts of defecting that
he was suspected of harboring or a guarantee against his defection
now.
</P>
<P>
   Defection has been a hot topic of speculation. Some of the
players who have defected in the past few years, such as Rey
Ordonez, the Mets' shortstop, escaped the grasp of the Castro
regime when the national team was playing in practice games or
international tournaments in the United States or other countries.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, the Orioles and the Clinton administration
would be in an embarrassing position if any players were to defect
because the Orioles worked hard to get the game here and
administration officials helped facilitate it.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable additions to the Cuban roster are first baseman
Orestes Kindelan and second baseman Antonio Pacheco, who missed the
Havana game because their team was playing in the championship
round of the Cuban league playoffs. Kindelan is the career leading
home run hitter in Cuban history, but his production has dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Omar Linares, one of the greatest players Cuba has
had, is on the roster again. His two-out single in the eighth
inning tied the first game, 2-2, but when he had a chance to win it
in the 10th, he popped up for the third out with runners at first
and second.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Contreras is on the roster again, too. The Orioles may not
want to see him. He relieved Jose Ibar, the starter, in the third
inning and baffled the Orioles for the next eight innings, allowing
two hits and striking out 10. He fanned Albert Belle twice and
induced him to ground into an inning-ending double play after
walking Will Clark intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans have not said whether Contreras will start. They may
have to await last-minute word from their chief strategist.
Contreras or Ibar, Irabu or Mendoza. Same thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
