<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANG-PARALYZED-GYMNAS     05-02 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANG-PARALYZED-GYMNAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REHABILITATING A BODY AND A BOND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sang Lan, the Chinese gymnast who was paralyzed in a warm-up
vault at the Goodwill Games last summer, and her mother, Chen
Xiufeng, were looking at an anatomy chart recently at the Burke
Rehabilitation Institute in White Plains, N.Y. The mother ran her
hand along the chart's gray-colored regions, where her daughter
will probably never regain feeling, and the two spoke in Mandarin
for a few seconds before retreating into a familiar silence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most difficult adjustment Sang will have to make
upon her return to China on June 2 is sharing a life with a mother
she hardly knows. It will be a relationship more intertwined than
either could have imagined, since Sang requires constant care.
</P>
<P>
   Sang's mother has been living with her for months in the Armonk,
N.Y., home of K.S. Liu, and his wife, Gina, who are Sang's
guardians here. While Chen has performed most of the intimate
caregiving tasks, the Lius have provided a welcome buffer between
mother and daughter, who spent 11 years apart while Sang trained to
become a champion. That buffer will come down now that Sang's visa
is about to expire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she and her mother will be able to bridge their
long separation, Sang answered through Gina Liu's translation,
``It's difficult to tell.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sang's mother, also through Liu, said, ``We're together every
day and our feelings will be closer.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sang and Chen plan to settle in a Beijing apartment near the
China Rehabilitation and Research Center, the nation's best
neurological hospital. Sang's father, a housing official, will
remain in the family's hometown of Ningbo, south of Shanghai. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there's difficulty for the family, but I will face
it,'' Chen said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If any major surgery needs to be done, Sang will return to the
United States, where she is insured for up to $10 million in
medical expenses. Everyday life in China, however, will test a bond
that turned awkward through the years. On a recent Monday afternoon
at the Lius' home, an outgoing Sang chatted with Gina Liu and a
Chinese television crew while the reserved Chen receded into the
background. Their lack of communication was normal, the Lius said,
because they have nothing to talk about. Chen said she had to get
used to Sang's constant talking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the Chinese government, Sang left home against her
mother's wish at age 6 to attend a gymnastics academy in Beijing.
She eventually became the Chinese national champion in the vault
and an Olympic hopeful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last July 21, during a routine practice vault at Nassau Coliseum
in Uniondale, N.Y., Sang's momentum carried her an extra revolution
on a flip. Unable to complete the flip, she landed headfirst onto
the mat, the impact causing a frightening crack. Sang had crushed
her spine, leaving her paralyzed from the chest down. She has some
movement in her shoulders and wrists, but cannot flex her fingers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept that I won't be able to walk again,'' Sang said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sang has improved her motor skills to the point that she can
feed herself with a spoon that is attached to her left wrist with
Velcro. Her therapists said she is the model patient, pushing
through 20 repetitions of an exercise when asked to do 10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a gymnast,'' Sang said. ``I used to do a very difficult
action, but now I can't do anything myself, even a simple thing
like getting water. That has made me upset, discouraged, because
there's not much progress.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sang, usually smiling and babbling, grimaced into a picture of
concentration when she tried to squirm from a table into her
wheelchair. No sensation in her triceps makes applying leverage
difficult. Chen rarely took her eyes off Sang during the 90 minutes
of upper-body drills, stretching done by the therapists, and light
weight lifting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chen said she is prepared to devote her life to her daughter,
although still angry at Sang for leaving home. ``If we stay more
time together, that will be forgotten,'' Chen said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sang, who turns 18 on June 11, has assured her mother privately
that she will someday be self-sufficient, and has asked her not to
cry so much. Gina Liu said that Chen has put up a positive front to
mask her devastation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Chen's admiration for her daughter is genuine. Chen recalled
a spoiled little girl who cried when she did not get her way. Now
she is getting to know a courageous young woman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't imagine she could deal with this,'' Chen said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
