<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS MARVEL AT ELWAY'S TALENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also FBN-ELWAY-RETIRES) 
(rk) 
 By BUDDY MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER, _ For Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe, quarterback John
Elway was like Halley's comet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only comes along every 77 years,'' Sharpe said, ``and I got
an opportunity to play with him. That's what it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who had delayed his retirement announcement for more than
a week out of respect for the victims of the shooting at Columbine
High School in nearby Littleton and their families, made it
official Sunday at a news conference. It was a scene filled with
laughter, tears and memories of Elway's illustrious career.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 members of the media, family, friends, coaches,
teammates and the Broncos owner' crammed into a hotel conference
room as Elway stepped away from the mike on several occasions to
regain his composure.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Elway's wife, Janet, rushed to the podium with a
box of tissues and a glass of water from the front row, where she
sat with their four children. Elway gasped and apologized, then he
kept trying to insert humor into the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's time to retire,'' Elway said, ``because I'm
getting to the point where people are asking me to trace over old
autographs.''
</P>
<P>
   One surprise attendee Sunday was the former Broncos owner Edgar
Kaiser, who clandestinely engineered a trade for Elway with the
Baltimore Colts. Kaiser said that he hadn't even informed his
coach, Dan Reeves, of the trade on May 2, 1983, until Elway, the
No. 1 pick in the NF L draft, was a Bronco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember flying up to the Northwest to pick John up and
riding down on the airplane together,'' Kaiser said. ``John and I
were both nervous. John was really nervous as a kid. So we got him
in the jump seat in the cockpit so he could relax a little bit. And
I said, `John, you're not going to believe this, but there's going
to be quite a scrum at the Bronco headquarters.' And indeed there
was.''
</P>
<P>
   And Elway created another scene Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough day for him,'' Sharpe said, ``walking away from
football after nearly 30 years of playing the game. I knew it would
be. But if it had been me, I'd have still been crying. I have to
admit it was tough for me to watch. He's so big, so strong _ it's
almost enough to make you break down. I had to hold back a couple
of times.''
</P>
<P>
   After 16 years, it's going to be tough on Denver sports fans to
not see their greatest sports legend in his No. 7 jersey. And what
will Elway miss most?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss the huddle, and telling Sharpe to be quiet,'' Elway
said, drawing the biggest laugh of the day at the expense of the
tight end. ``I know you're open, I know you're open, I know you're
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those there to pay respects was Elway's close friend and
coach Gary Kubiak, who backed up Elway for more than a decade and
returned under Mike Shanahan as quarterback coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the greatest improviser ever to play the game,'' Kubiak
said. ``As a coach, you draw up all these plays that look good on
paper, but in all honesty, 5 or 10 of them never go the way they're
planned. At that time, an athlete takes over. And when it was time
to take over, he was the greatest ever to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
