<HEADER>
A1694 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-CALSIDE-LADN     05-02 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CALSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON BACK ON TRACK WITH HELP FROM CREW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ So much for the demise of Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion, who had suffered
through several racing misfortunes in recent weeks, proved he still
has a dominating team Sunday by easily winning the third California
500 before an estimated 117,000 at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt like we've been out of contention,'' said
Gordon. ``We've always known what we're made of. I've been saying
all year long that our team is better then they've ever been. I
think (Sunday) certainly proved it. (Crew chief Ray Evernham) and
the guys set up the race car just perfect. The horsepower
underneath the hood was just incredible, and we had great pit
stops.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gordon credited the latter with being the difference Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That last pit stop was the key,'' said Gordon, who went from a
two-second lead to a four-second advantage following a pit on lap
208. ``When it comes to crunch time, when the pressure is on and
it's time to make a great pit stop, that's what these guys do. I
got to the pits as fast as I could, got to pit road and they did
the rest of the work and got me out really fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham, though, said the driver deserves some credit as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make up seconds in the pits anymore,'' he said. ``A
lot of that is how fast you get to pit road. Jeff did a good job
keeping the car clean and getting it to pit road. He actually made
up more for us there than the guys had in the pits.''
</P>
<P>
   After the stop, Gordon increased his advantage to 7.3 seconds
before Jeff Burton made a futile charge over the final 30 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know that (Gordon) was running as hard as he could,''
said Burton, who trimmed the deficit to as little as 3.01 seconds
before losing by 4.492. I suspect that he wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Gordon, who saw his lead shrink by nearly two
seconds between Laps 230 and 234.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took off real hard on new tires,'' Gordon said. ``I couldn't
give up too much time on new tires. I was running real, real hard,
trying to pull away and get through traffic as quick as I could. I
think I sort of used up the right rear tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Burton) was coming on strong, and I felt like I used it up a
little bit. When he started closing in, I was definitely trying to
make sure I hit all my marks just right and not make any
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the race was Gordon's or Burton's to lose. They traded
leads several times and held as much as a 20-car length advantage
at one point during the first half of the 250-lap event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We swapped leads quite a few times,'' Gordon said. ``If I got
the lead and he got behind me it would loosen me up and I would
have to give him that position. It's very hard to lead here if
you've got somebody right behind you. I really wanted to ride
behind him and tighten the car up and wait for the (tire) pressures
to build up and then try to get the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Gordon slipped by Burton on lap 127, then took
advantage of that famous Gordon luck that he has converted into
three points titles.
</P>
<P>
   It began when Gordon pitted from the lead on lap 131, giving the
edge to Mark Martin. Veteran Rick Rudd then blew his engine and
struck the outside wall between turns 3 and 4, bringing out the
caution. Gordon was able to exit the pits before the pace car
brought the field around, allowing him to continue on the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw what was happening, I kept my eyes on the
leader,'' Evernham said. ``You always try to pick a pit stall past
the start-finish line. That's one of the reasons we do that. We had
a fairly big lead (on Martin) when we pitted. The (crew) once again
had a good pit stop. I knew that once Jeff got off the jack and
rolling, Mark just then crossed the start-finish line, so we
weren't a lap down. The anxious moments came after we realized
weren't a lap down and realized we could have been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
