<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-02 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1696 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-GORDON-LADN     05-02 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-GORDON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON, PIT CREW TEAM UP FOR VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Cancel those thoughts about Jeff Gordon having
used up all his luck in NASCAR Winston Cup competition. The rainbow
that appeared over the California Speedway on Friday must have been
an omen for Sunday as Gordon and his Rainbow Warriors pit crew put
together a dominating effort to win the NAPA California 500.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's victory was his second in the pair of Winston Cup races
run at the Fontana track. ``This was really special,'' said Gordon,
who beat Jeff Burton's Ford to the finish line by 4.492 seconds
after 250 laps before an estimated 117,000. Bobby Labonte and Joe
Gibbs' Pontiac teammate Tony Stewart, a rookie, were next, followed
by another Ford driver, Dale Jarrett. Ward Burton, Jeremy Mayfield,
Wally Dallenbach and Terry Labonte also finished on the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the race, Gordon had crashed in three of the last four
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put Texas and Talladega behind us,'' said Gordon,
who failed to finish both races after being involved in crashes and
prompted talk about his bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time defending Winston Cup champion was last in a 43-car
field at Fort Worth and 38th last week in Alabama. But there was
none of that on Sunday. Gordon's crew, led by Ray Evernham, turned
in two pit stops that were more than luck. One allowed the DuPont
Chevrolet driver to remain on the lead lap and the last one
solidified the run to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pit stop (on lap 208) is what did it,'' said Gordon, the
lone driver to score top-five finishes in all three races at the
two-mile, D-shaped speedway. ``When it comes to crunch time, when
the pressure is on and it's time to make a great pit stop, that's
what these guys do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who was leading by 2.5 seconds when he came in,
surrendered the lead to Stewart. However, Gordon, who re-entered
the fray just 4.5 seconds behind the leader, regained the point on
the next lap and was never seriously threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make up seconds in the pits any more,'' said
Evernham. ``It's how fast you get to pit row. Jeff did a good job
of keeping the car clean and getting to pit row. He can actually
make up more time for us there than the guys in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things when the choreography is
perfect, and you hit all the lug nuts perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   That couldn't be said for Burton, who increased his points lead
to 55 over Jarrett. He was caught in the pits when one of five
caution laps came out, putting him nearly a lap down. But Burton
battled back and attempted to challenge Gordon, who led 151 laps,
including the final 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the thing that hurt us the most, obviously getting a
lap down hurt us a great deal, was when we made our lap up, on the
next-to-last set of tires I asked to take two rounds of bite out
and make a change to make it looser,'' said Burton, who sat on the
pole by virtue of his points lead when qualifying was rained out
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got it too loose; the 24 (Gordon) and the 18 (Bobby Labonte)
drove away from us because I got it too loose.'' said Burton. ``The
24 drove away from us, and we never had a caution again to move us
back up.''
</P>
<P>
   While the yellow flags slowed the average speed to 150.890 mph,
nearly 5 mph slower than Gordon's race record in the inaugural 1997
race, it did create close racing. There were 28 lead changes among
13 drivers. Jeff Burton led 57 laps while Labonte was in front 10
times. Defending champion Mark Martin led 10 laps and was
competitive until his Roush Racing Ford engine blew on lap 196.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we dropped a valve,'' said Martin, who dropped two
places to sixth in the points race after a 38th place finish. ``We
were starting to get up there pretty good, but that last set of
tires we got weren't competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner was also in the hunt but dropped back in the last 100
miles of the race that took 3:19.38 to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened to the car,'' Skinner said of his
Lowe's Chevrolet that led once for a single lap. ``At one point, we
thought we could win it. Then it went from the best car on the race
track to the worst car in one pit stop.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a similar story for Terry Labonte, whose run of top-five
finishes at Fontana in the Kellogg's Chevrolet ended. He led once
for three laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car fell off quite a bit in the second half of the race,''
said the older Labonte brother and Gordon's Rick Hendrick
Motorsports teammate. ``I wished we hadn't passed on taking tires
on one pit stop (lap 205). In hindsight, I think we would have been
better off coming in and taking on four tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Labonte were joined in the top 10 by teammate Wally
Dallenbach. In addition to his pit crew, Gordon covered the field
with a car that ran best while in front, with little traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get out there in clean air and that made a
difference,'' said the 27-year-old driver, who earned $155,890 for
the win. ``The car was handling great all day long if we got clean
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be leading and that's the key when you're out in
front.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the five Roush entries, only Jeff Burton finished in the lead
lap. Kevin Lepage was 18th and Chad Little, who gained five bonus
points for leading the race was 22nd. Joining Martin in the lower
portion was Johnny Benson, who crashed on the third lap. It was
nearly a crash-free race. In addition to Benson, only Ricky Rudd
and Joe Nemechek managed contact with the walls. But there was no
managing any kind of contact with Gordon, winner of 45 Winston Cup
races in 199 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never felt like we were out of contention (for the
championship). We knew what we were made up,'' said the Vallejo,
Calif., native. ``Anytime you win the Daytona 500, you're not
having a bad year. Then you put Atlanta and California in on it, I
don't see how we can have a bad year from here on out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do want to be a factor in the championship when it comes
down to the end of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
