<SLUG> BC-ARK-BOAT-SINKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13TH VICTIM FOUND IN SINKING OF BOAT IN ARKANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change ``20 passengers'' to ``21 people on board'' in 18th
graf, beginning: Although there were ...) (mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOT SPRINGS, Ark. _ Returning to the bottom of the serene lake
where a tourist boat slipped below the surface on Saturday, a team
of divers found a 13th victim Sunday but failed to shed light on
what caused the boat to sink so swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   The latest victim was identified by local authorities as Jim
Patton, 48, of Russellville, Ark., who had been missed by divers
when they recovered the bodies of the other victims on Saturday
afternoon. Sheriff Larry Selig of Garland County said the man's
15-year-old son, James Jr., who survived the accident, realized on
Saturday night that his father was not accounted for. Divers found
the body about 30 yards from the sunken boat.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours earlier, Patton's wife, Floy, had died after
spending the night on life support, the sheriff said. The couple's
daughter, Jennifer, 20, also died on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Other victims included a brother and sister, both under 5 years
old, and their father, all from Keithville, La.; and a 3-year-old
boy and his mother from Dyersburg, Tenn. Many of the victims were
trapped under a canopy when the amphibious boat began taking on
water several minutes into the aquatic leg of its journey.
</P>
<P>
   The accident seemed to startle but not benumb this leisurely
tourist region an hour southwest of Little Rock. Pleasure craft
sped blithely around a small buoy marking the site Sunday
afternoon, 300 feet from the shore of Lake Hamilton, and fishermen
returned to the surrounding docks.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had a few theories Sunday for how the boat could
have taken on water, but said they would have no definite answers
until after the boat could be raised, possibly on Monday. The
vessel, which had passed Coast Guard inspection on Feb. 23,
officials said, is submerged in 51 feet of water. Its owner, Land
and Lake Tours, is to return it to the surface using flotation
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the victims were from out of town, the sinking
struck at the heart of the city's major industry. For four decades
the ungainly amphibious vehicles known as ``ducks'' have been a
familiar if curious sight around town, picking up passengers in
downtown Hot Springs, rolling on rubber tires down Highway 7 to
Lake Hamilton, and then slicing into the water for a $9 sightseeing
tour of the man-made lake and the old resort area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this where that duck went down?'' asked Webb Crouse, a
local fisherman who, like many residents, stopped by the lakeshore
Sunday, searching the calm waters in vain for the site of the
accident. ``It just doesn't make sense that one of those big old
things would just disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange as they looked, the fleet of World War II surplus army
vessels had an exemplary safety record, never before suffering a
fatality. With their yellow and white hulls and candy-striped
canopies, the boats are a popular staple of the local tourist
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ride on the amphibious duck is an unforgettable
experience,'' promises brochures that were still prominently
displayed Sunday in every hotel lobby. A cartoon-like map showed a
drawing of a boat making a big splash in precisely the spot of the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the Coast Guard and the National
Transportation Safety Board stood scratching their heads at the
shore like everyone else, baffled at the sinking. Many of the eight
survivors had said on Saturday that the boat took only 30 seconds
to go down in sunny, windy weather after taking on water in the
stern, descending to the bottom stern-first. But no one reported
how the water had entered the hull, made of quarter-inch steel and
built to handle 5,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Robert Bowen, chief of the Coast Guard's merchant vessel
safety division, said it was conceivable that water had come in
around the propeller or rudder shafts. Or the hull could have
suffered some kind of structural failure. But he said the boat had
easily passed its inspection in February, just as have all the
other ducks in the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the transportation safety board, John Hammerschmidt,
said Sunday that investigators had interviewed the operator of the
boat, Beth Hambrick, who told them that she had recently taken it
in for a repair to the rubber boot that surrounds the drive shaft
and prevents water from leaking in. The boot had been leaking, she
told board investigators, but had been repaired; Saturday's voyage
was the first since the boat returned from the repair shop.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard ordered that the dozen or so ducks operated by
two companies on Lake Hamilton cease operation until the cause of
Saturday's accident is determined, Bowen said. The Coast Guard is
weighing whether to impose a similar order on other amphibious
boats that operate elsewhere in the country, including Branson,
Mo., Galveston, Texas, Chicago and Washington, D.C. The 31-foot
boats, each weighing 7.5 tons, are part of a group of 21,000 built
by General Motors in 1943 as landing craft for allied troops
invading Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Land and Lake, Q. Bryum Hurst Jr., said on Saturday
that Ms. Hambrick, the boat's operator, had all the credentials
required by the Coast Guard to be captain of the vessel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The boat went down so suddenly that there was little for
survivors and witnesses to describe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't believe how fast that thing sank,'' said Gary Ledin,
a survivor from Oakdale, Calif., who told The Hot Springs
Sentinel-Record on Saturday that he and his wife had less than 30
seconds to swim away from the boat and up to the surface. His wife,
Diane, managed to push her way through one of the windows, but many
other passengers were trapped beneath the red-and-white canopy.
Bowen said nine of the 13 victims were found beneath the canopy on
the boat; the survivors seemed to have been sitting in front of and
behind the canopy.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were 38 life jackets on the boat, which seats 30,
none of the 21 people on board _ including the five children under
15 who died _ was wearing one. Federal and state laws require that
the jackets be on the boat, but not that passengers wear them.
Arkansas law requires children under 12 to wear a life jacket on
recreational vessels, but the sheriff said it was not clear whether
the law applied to a commercial boat operating on a waterway under
Coast Guard jurisdiction, like Lake Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Selig added that even if everyone had worn a jacket, it would
not necessarily have saved any lives. By making each person
bulkier, the jackets might have prevented people from escaping the
canopy and swimming away from the sinking boat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the survivors were rescued by other boaters and nearby
residents, but the job of lifesaving requires training. Danny
Harris, 16, said he was staying with friends at a nearby
condominium complex when he heard people screaming in the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all ran down there,'' he said. ``I jumped in the water,
grabbed one of the guys who was trying to float, but he was
drowning me. So I had to swim back.'' He did not know if the man
whom he tried to rescue was later saved.
</P>
<P>
   The divers, who included sheriff's employees and local
enthusiasts, described visibility at the bottom as essentially
zero, and said they found the bodies mostly by touch, about 40
minutes after the boat sank. When ambulances ran out of space,
divers had to place the bodies on nearby docks, and the sight
stunned nearby residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to stop looking after a while,'' said Rhett Smith, a
computer operator living nearby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
