<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-CHINA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON SEATTLE VISIT, PAT BUCHANAN BLASTS CHINA'S WTO BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ China is ``not remotely qualified'' to become a member
of the World Trade Organization and the United States should not
yield to ``bribes'' such as those offered by Premier Zhu Rongji on
his recent visit to the United States, Republican presidential
candidate Patrick Buchanan said Sunday in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Describing U.S. trade negotiators as ``too weak and wimpish,''
Buchanan pledged that if elected president, he would ``demand
complete access to Chinese markets'' as the trade-off for China's
continuing to sell its products here.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan will appear at Port of Seattle docks on Monday as a way
of dramatizing the United States' $58 billion trade deficit with
China, and what he said is a decline of U.S. exports and lack of
vigor in dealing with U.S. trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is making his case in a corner of the United States
that has been a bastion of support for U.S.-China trade.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Jiang Zemin once dramatized the importance of his
country to Boeing jet sales by visiting a Boeing worker's home in
Marysville, Wash. A key inducement to WTO membership, recently
offered by Zhu, was a lifting of China's ban on imports of wheat
from the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan said Sunday that as a Republican president, he
would not hesitate to challenge the GOP's traditional corporate
allies.
</P>
<P>
   He even personalized the argument with a reference to Boeing
Chairman Phil Condit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transnational corporations, which are entirely correct
calling themselves that, have a right to make their case and defend
their interests,'' Buchanan argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when they shut down factories, lay off American employees,
kill jobs _ and make their parts in China _ it is the duty of the
American president to look after American workers, not Mr. Condit
and his executives.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a television commentator and former aide to Presidents
Nixon and Reagan, is making his third try for the White House. Both
Reagan and Bob Dole captured the GOP nominations on their third
attempt. But despite his surprise early victories in 1996 _
including upsetting Dole in the New Hampshire primary _ Buchanan is
still considered a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, what Reagan once called a ``conviction
politician,'' a robust conservative at the onset of a political
season in which some fellow Republican presidential candidates are
proposing to soft-pedal positions on which the party has been
identified.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday, Buchanan also:
</P>
<P>
   - Decried the loss of 350,000 American manufacturing jobs last
year and warned that the country's status as a superpower is in
jeopardy if its ability to make things continues to decline;
</P>
<P>
   - Claimed President Clinton is ``scapegoating gun owners and
sportsmen'' for the Littleton, Colo., school massacre. Clinton has
proposed reinstatement of the Brady Bill's three-day wait on
handgun purchases, to require trigger locks on gun purchases and to
ban ownership of handguns by those under 21.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of expanding gun control, Clinton should focus on ``the
cultural polluters of the entertainment industry who put these
ideas in children's heads,'' Buchanan argued. He acidly noted that
some of the alleged polluters have been among Clinton's most
generous contributors.
</P>
<P>
   - Warned that the Republican Party would ``lose its soul'' as
well as its most dedicated volunteers if it ``turns a deaf ear on
the silent screams of the unborn.'' Any abandonment of the GOP's
opposition to abortion would simply be designed ``to appease people
who never voted for us in the beginning,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also warned that the GOP cannot count on the pro-life
movement to stay in the fold if its cause is soft-pedaled. If
opposition to abortion is modified or abandoned, ``the Republican
Party will demean itself and call into being a new party,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   - Buchanan also declared himself opposed to any dismantling of
the Northwest's hydroelectric system to save or restore salmon
runs. He was asked about proposals to breach four dams on the lower
Snake River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, salmon are important, but people come first,'' he
added. ``I adhere to the biblical idea that good things were put
here by the Lord for the wise use of mankind, which is required to
be a good steward of what has been bestowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think the good steward needs hydroelectricity more
than a few more salmon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is a candidate who does not hesitate to tell you which
side he is on. For instance, he decried what he called ``the
demeaning, mocking and demonizing'' of traditional American values
in popular entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional Catholics and fundamentalist Christians, in
particular, are targets of these outrages,'' he added. ``It is time
for decent people to fight back with boycotts, and by using the
political process. The president of the United States has a bully
pulpit. It should be deployed on the side of decent people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
