<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-02 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY JUST ABOUT LETTER-PERFECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From Z to A, it's all Elway:
</P>
<P>
   Z is for ``Zen and the Art of the Two-Minute Offense,'' a title
we submit for John Elway's memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Y is for the Yankees, for whom Elway was a .318-batting right
fielder with a team-leading 24 RBI in single-A Oneonta (N.Y.) in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   X is for XXXII and XXXIII, the two Super Bowls that didn't get
away.
</P>
<P>
   W is for Walker, Herschel, the running back from Georgia who
beat out Elway for the 1982 Heisman Trophy. Elway, whose Stanford
squad finished 5-6, was second in the voting, just ahead of SMU
running back (and onetime L.A. Ram) Eric Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   V is for Elway's 105 victories in 139 starts at Mile High
Stadium, a superlative 75.5 percent winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   U is for the ubiquity of Elway's celebrity, which once prompted
him to say, ``Sometimes I wonder what it'd be like to be somebody
who wasn't noticed.... I don't like to stick out.''
</P>
<P>
   T is for ``The Drive'', a 98-yard classic that Elway conjured up
out of the frigid air (minus-5 with wind chill) in the January 1987
AFC Championship Game in Cleveland. He scrambled for 11 yards on
one down, 9 yards on another and completed passes of 22, 12, 20 and
14 yards before knotting the game at 20 with 37 seconds left on a
5-yard pass to Mark Jackson and an extra point by Rich Karlis, who
kicked the game-winning field goal in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   S is for Simms, Phil, the winning quarterback and MVP in Elway's
first Super Bowl appearance, in Pasadena in January 1987. Elway
passed for 304 yards, but the Giants, behind Simms' 22 of 25
passing (for 268 yards) scored 24 unanswered points in the third
quarter to obliterate Denver's 10-9 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   R is for running backs. Elway knew a few before finally hooking
up with The One. Before Terrell Davis there was Sammy Winder,
Gerald Willhite, Tony Dorsett, Bobby Humphrey, Gaston Green, Rod
Bernstine and Leonard Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Q is for Queen City of the Plains, which is what Denver was
called before John Elway came and conquered it. Or delivered it, if
you believe Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe, who was quoted as
saying, ``When you think of Denver you think John Elway.... John
Elway is Denver's Moses. He has led Denver out of obscurity and
into the land of milk and honey.''
</P>
<P>
   P is for Pittsburgh, site of Elway's NFL regular-season debut in
the Broncos' 1983 season opener. ``Welcome to the NFL, now go back
to baseball'' seemed to be the message hand-delivered by the
Steelers defense, which sacked Elway four times. He completed just
1 of 8 passes in a 14-10 loss.
</P>
<P>
   O is for the Ohio State-Stanford game in 1982, which provided a
hint of what was to come. The Cardinal trailed 20-16 with 1:32 to
play when Elway drove his team 80 yards for the winning score, the
decisive touchdown coming on a pinpoint pass from a scrambling
Elway to Emile Harry.
</P>
<P>
   N is for the No.1 pick in the NFL draft. Elway was it in 1983,
going against his stated wishes to the Baltimore Colts. Elway
didn't want to be owned by Robert Irsay or ordered around by coach
Frank Kush and in the end he got his way; on May 2, 1983, he was
traded to Denver for quarterback Mark Hermann, offensive tackle
Chris Hinton and a first-round draft pick that turned out to be Ron
Solt. After the Broncos' win in Super Bowl XXXII in San Diego,
somebody heard Sharpe scream, ``I'd like to thank the Colts for
making that stupid trade!''
</P>
<P>
   M is for Most Valuable Player, the award Elway took home after
becoming the oldest person in Super Bowl history to score a
touchdown, in Denver's 34-19 win over Atlanta in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   L is for Elway's left knee, which has given him fits since his
senior year at Granada Hills High in 1978, when he underwent
surgery for torn cartilage. He has played without an anterior
cruciate ligament in the joint ever since.
</P>
<P>
   K is for the Kansas City Royals, who drafted Elway out of high
school, after he had signed a letter-of-intent to attend Stanford
to play football and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   J is for Jana, Elway's twin sister, who was born a few minutes
after John on June 28, 1960.
</P>
<P>
   I is for the improvisation that was Elway's signature on the
gridiron. He was the Jerry Seinfeld of football, always ready with
a quick comeback. Who else could score a go-ahead touchdown on a
4-yard scramble late in a game against rival Kansas City with only
10 Broncos on the field?
</P>
<P>
   H is for history. Elway is the first quarterback to appear as a
starter in five Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   G is for Granada Hills High, where Elway completed 60 percent of
his passes for 5,711 yards and 49 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   F is for fourth-quarter comebacks, 47 in all (nine alone against
Kansas City). The Broncos were a patient the doctor, who looked
like he could have been lifted straight from the set of ``General
Hospital,'' was forever having to revive, especially in the Dan
Reeves years. Good thing Elway's specialty was miracles.
</P>
<P>
   E is for eyes wide open, the expression Elway wore when a
first-down marker or goal line was in his sights.
</P>
<P>
   D is for DeBerg, Steve, whom Elway replaced as a starter in the
first regular-season game of Elway's rookie year and who fittingly
graced the roster of rival Atlanta in Elway's final game, Super
Bowl XXXIII in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   C is for charity. For Elway, it truly does begin at home. With
the help of wife Janet he started a foundation that has raised more
than $1 million for the prevention and treatment of child abuse.
Then there are all the $1,000 fines he gladly paid for the game
balls he tossed to fans in the stands at Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   B is for Bradshaw, Terry, a former Pittsburgh quarterback who
blistered Elway for refusing to play for Baltimore and blasted him
after his performance in Super Bowl XXIV (San Francisco 55, Denver
10) and then heaped praise upon him in large shovelfuls in a
network interview after Elway was named MVP in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   A is for antacids. The Broncos cornered the market on them for
much of Elway's career and we're not just talking about the fans.
Elway's insides would churn so before games, he'd be seeing pink.
Thus, the joke from a Broncos trainer that Elway ought to be called
the ``Pepto-Bismol King.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hoped Elway will be able to retire all those bottles now
that he is finished. It wouldn't be a joke to call him, simply, the
King.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
