<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prisoners
</P>
<P>
   _ Three American soldiers captured by Yugoslavia 31 days ago
arrived in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Combat
</P>
<P>
   _ Belgrade and other parts of Serbia were plunged into darkness
when NATO warplanes hit a major hydroelectric power station.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two American planes were lost, one reportedly with engine
problems and the other in a training accident. Both pilots were
rescued.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO said that one of its missiles had accidentally hit a bus
in Kosovo on Saturday but that the bridge it was crossing was a
legitimate target. Yugoslavia said 47 people died.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy
</P>
<P>
   _ The White House said that President Clinton plans to meet
Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy for the Balkans, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Administration officials remained resolute in their
determination to continue the bombing campaign despite calls by the
Rev. Jesse Jackson, who negotiated the prisoners' release, to end
it.
</P>
<P>
   _ An 11-member bipartisan delegation from Congress, after
meeting in Vienna with a group of Russian lawmakers and a
representative of Milosevic, offered ideas for a peace framework,
but NATO said it was not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees
</P>
<P>
   _ Refugees continued to stream out of Kosovo by the thousands.
Some entering Albania said Serb police had prevented women and
children from Kosovo's second-largest city, Prizren, from crossing
the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
