<HEADER>
A1709 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SHO-HNS &LR;      05-02 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE WOODLANDS _ They make movies about stuff like this. One was
called Angels in the Outfield.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing Hollywood could pump out can compare to the Angel in
the Fairway who was riding shotgun with Stuart Appleby on Sunday at
the Tournament Players Course.
</P>
<P>
   With the memory of his wife, Renay, giving him inner strength
and his timely putter doing the rest of the work, Appleby overcame
a two-stroke deficit in the final three holes to edge Hal Sutton
and John Cook and win the Shell Houston Open.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Australian's first PGA Tour win since Renay died in
London last July when a taxi backed up and pinned her against
another vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave me the strength,'' Appleby said. ``I felt strong.
She's going to be with me forever, no doubt, in anything I do. And
she'll be there to help.''
</P>
<P>
   In a big way, Renay's memory drove Appleby to victory Sunday. He
started the day three strokes behind Sutton. He shot a final-round
71. Only one player on the leader board, Cook, had a better round
during a tough, windy afternoon of golf. Appleby's 72-hole total of
9-under 279 was the highest winning score at the TPC since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby's 12-foot birdie at the par-4 17th, which Sutton would
bogey minutes later, was the decisive hole. It was the culmination
of a lot of mental teamwork Appleby said he did with thoughts of
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, What do you have to do to play well?'' Appleby
said. ``And to do that, I needed to stay calm and stay positive and
believe that everything I do is going to pay off. You'd better
stick to your guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Renay was always telling me to do. She was always
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to try to be Renay and talk to myself about what I had
to do to win. And she knew what it was, and I knew what it was. The
answer was to get your act together, stay positive on the course,
believe in yourself and believe that it's all going to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to do when you lose someone you love so much.
But you've got to turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby began turning it around when he won the Coolum Classic
in Australia in December, although he admitted the level of
competition wasn't nearly as strong in that tournament as it was at
the SHO.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby also said he has tried to get past the mindset of
winning for his wife since then. But it hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Australia, that victory was a historic event for Renay and
I,'' he said. ``It was an event that I played for her. It was our
tournament. We went there because she always had a great time. I
didn't go there because I wanted to play and win so much. I went
there because she had a good time there. It was a week off for her,
and she could do whatever she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go back there felt a little funny. I didn't really want to
go back. It was a little emotional for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this tournament, I was a bit hungrier. This was work, real
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby's third PGA Tour win was nothing if not a hard-earned
piece of work. He weathered two front-nine bogeys that left him at
7-under for the tournament and as much as three strokes behind
Sutton. Cook had mounted a nice charge with birdies at Nos. 16 and
17 to get to the clubhouse at 8-under 280.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton was coasting along with a two-stroke lead over several
players when he stepped up to the 16th tee. The par-3 was playing
175 yards into the wind, and Sutton's tee shot came up short on the
left fringe. His first putt stopped three feet short, and he then
pushed the par effort enough to ring off of the right lip.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Appleby was stabbing a 12-foot birdie putt on
the 17th, drawing into a tie with Sutton. Appleby had missed three
putts inside six feet that could have given him breathing room
earlier in the round. But he had a premonition about the one at the
17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew I was going to make that putt,'' Appleby said. ``I
just knew it would drop. I told myself that this is what it's all
about. This is something you should just eat up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton then had an 8-iron approach shot knocked down by the wind
and end up just a foot over the lake guarding the 17th green. His
chip ran 12 feet by the hole, and he missed the comebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby, playing two groups ahead of Sutton, parred the 18th,
then waited for Sutton to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton knew as he looked at his second shot on the finishing
hole that he needed a birdie to force a playoff. His shot came to
rest about 25 feet left of the hole, which was tucked on the right
edge of the green with water just five yards in front and to the
right.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton hit a good putt, but it slid by on the left edge of the
cup, giving the win to Appleby.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody had to beat me, I was happy it was Stuart,''
Sutton said. ``He has been through a lot. And I can certainly
understand how much meaning this has to him. I'm sure there's
somebody smiling on him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby knew as he waited for Sutton to finish play that he had
done all he could by getting to 9 under par. Nos. 17 and 18 were
the two hardest holes on the TPC on Sunday, with only four birdies
on the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Par is your friend on 18, definitely,'' Appleby said. ``Hal
obviously struggled down the stretch with the nerves and the
condition. I knew I had to make that putt on 17 because 18 wasn't
yielding any birdies.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby's win was worth $450,000 and means that he now has a win
in each of the last three years on tour. And it was another step
forward in the rest of his life, a life that, like golf, is getting
easier for Appleby nearly a year after his wife's death. ``Time
goes on,'' he said. ``I've learned that trying to win a golf
tournament is nothing to be scared of. But, obviously, not having
Renay here makes it a different feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling at the start of the day I was going to win
this tournament. I'm very excited that I won. It was a great week
for me. I stayed strong mentally and just did the right things.''
</P>
<P>
   After his victory, Appleby ran an endless gauntlet of autograph
promotions for the Houston Golf Association, then he finally was
ready to exhale and seek a quiet moment when he could have a
private audience with his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   And with that angel who will never stray from his heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
